<TEXT>
<BODY>
<HEAD>THE BUKE OF JOHN MAUNDEUILL.</HEAD>
<DIV1 TYPE="prologue" ID="Eg.Prol" CORRESP="Cot.Prol">
<PB N="1">
<HEAD TYPE="MS">HERE BEGYNNEZ &THORN;E BUKE OF JOHN MAUNDEUILL</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.1.1" CORRESP="Cot.1.1">SEN yt es so &thorn;at &thorn;e land be&yogh;ond &thorn;e see, &thorn;at es to say &thorn;e land of repromission, &thorn;at men calles &thorn;e Haly
Land, amanges all o&thorn;er landes es &thorn;e maste worthy land and souerayne of all o&thorn;er, and es blissed and
sacred and halowed of &thorn;e preciouse blude of oure Lorde Ihesu Criste; in &thorn;e whilk land it lyked
him to take lief and blude of oure Lady Saint Marie and to enuirun &thorn;at land with his blissed fete.&mdash;And &thorn;are
he didd many miracles and preched and teched &thorn;e faithe and &thorn;e lawe of vs Cristen men, as vnto his childer;
and &thorn;are he sufferd many reprufes and scornes by vs. And he &thorn;at was King
<NOTE N="1">King, om. <ABBR>E</ABBR>.</NOTE> of heuen and of erthe, of &thorn;e aer
and of &thorn;e see, and of all thingz &thorn;at er contened in &thorn;am, wald be called all anely king of &thorn;at land, as &thorn;e
prophete saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Noli timere, filia Syon: ecce, rex tuus venit tibi mansuetus</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">This quotation, made up of John xii. 15 and Matt. xxi. 5, only in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> follows the French texts.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "&thorn;ou doghter of
Syon, drede &thorn;ou no&yogh;t; for, lo, &thorn;i kyng commes to &thorn;e, dulye mylde and meke"; and &thorn;at land he chose before
all o&thorn;er landes as &thorn;e best and &thorn;e maste worthy of &thorn;e werld; for, as &thorn;e philosophere saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Virtus rerum in
medio consistit</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "&thorn;e vertu of thingez es in &thorn;e myddes." And in &thorn;at land he wald lede his lyf and
suffer hard passioun and dede of &thorn;e Iews for vs synfull wormes, to by and delyuer vs fra deed withouten end,
whilk was ordeyned til vs for &thorn;e synne of oure forme fader Adam and for oure awen also. For, as for
himself, he desserued neuer nane euill; for he did neuer euill, ne thoght neuer euill. And he &thorn;at was king
of glory and of ioy, mightiest and best,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">myghte best in that place suffre, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> wald in &thorn;at place suffer &thorn;e deed titter &thorn;an in ano&thorn;er. For he &thorn;at will

<PB N="2">
<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="folio">do any thing &thorn;at he will be knawen openly til all men, he will ger crie it openly in &thorn;e middell of a toune or of
a citee, so &thorn;at it may be knawen til all &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e citee. On &thorn;e same wyse he &thorn;at was kyng of all the
werld wald suffer deed at Ierusalem, &thorn;at es in middes of &thorn;e werld, so &thorn;at it might be knawen to men of all &thorn;e
parties of &thorn;e werld how dere he boght man &thorn;at he had made til his awen liknes for &thorn;e grete luffe &thorn;at he had
til him. For mare worthie catell myght he no&yogh;t hafe sett for vs &thorn;an his awen blissed body and his precious
blude, &thorn;e whilk he sufferd be schedd for vs. A, dere Godd! what lufe he had til his sugets, when he &thorn;at
neuer didd trespas wald for trespassours suffer ded! Right wele aght men to lufe and serue swilk a lorde,
and wirschepe and praise swilk a haly land, &thorn;at bro&yogh;t furthe swilk fruyte, thurgh whilk ilk man es saued, bot
if it be his awen defaute. &THORN;is es &thorn;e land &thorn;at es hight til vs in heritage; and in &thorn;at land he wald die and sesse
&thorn;are in, to leefe it to his childer. For &thorn;e whilk land ilke a gude Cristen man &thorn;at may, and has wharoff, suld
enforce him for to conquere oure right heritage and chace oute &thorn;erof &thorn;aim &thorn;at er mistrowand. For we er
called Cristen men of Criste oure fader; and if we be ri&yogh;t childer of Criste, we awe for to chalange &thorn;e
heritage &thorn;at oure fader left to vs, and for to do it oute of straunge men handes. Bot now pride enuy and
couetise has so enflaumbed &thorn;e hertes of lordes of &thorn;e werld &thorn;at &thorn;ai er mare bisie for to disherite &thorn;aire neghbours
&thorn;an for to chalange or conquere &thorn;aire right heritage before said. And &thorn;e common pople, &thorn;at wald putte
&thorn;aire bodys and &thorn;aire catell in iupardy for to conquere oure heritage, &thorn;ai may na thing do withouten lordes.
<MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="folio">For assemblee of &thorn;e pople withouten lordes &thorn;at may gouerne &thorn;am es as a flokk of schepe &thorn;at has na
schepehird, &thorn;e whilk departes sunder and wate neuer whider &thorn;ai schuld ga. But wald Godd &thorn;at &thorn;ir werldly
lordes ware at gude accorde and, with o&thorn;er of &thorn;aire common pople, wald take &thorn;is haly viage ouer &thorn;e see, I
trowe wele &thorn;at within a lytill tyme oure ri&yogh;t heritage before said schuld be recounsailed and putte in to &thorn;e
handes of &thorn;e right heyers of Ihesu Criste.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.2.22" CORRESP="Cot.3.13">And for als mykill as it es lang tyme passed sen &thorn;are was any general passage ouer &thorn;e see in to &thorn;e haly
land, and men coueytes to here speke of &thorn;at land and of diuerse cuntreez &thorn;er aboute, and &thorn;eroff &thorn;ai hafe grete
solace and comforthe, I JOHN MAWNDEVYLE, Kny&yogh;t, &thorn;of all I be vnworthy, &thorn;at was borne in Ingeland in &thorn;e

<PB N="3">
toune of Saynt Albanes, and passed &thorn;e see &thorn;e &yogh;ere of oure Lorde Ihesu Criste m<HI REND="sup">l</HI>cccxxxij,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">So in four English manuscripts in the British Museum, viz. Harley MSS. 2386, 3954, and Royal MSS. 17 B. xliii., 17 C. xxxviii. All the French and Latin manuscripts have 1322, as well as the English version in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on Myghelmesday,
and seyne hiderward has bene lang tyme ouer &thorn;e see, and has sene and gane thurgh many kingdomes,
landes and prouincez and iles, and hase passed thurgh Turkye, Ermony &thorn;e lesse and &thorn;e mare, Tartarye,
Perse, Sirie, Araby, Egipte &thorn;e hie and &thorn;e lawe, Liby, Caldee, and a grete party of Ethiope, Amazon, Inde
&thorn;e lesse and &thorn;e mare a grete party, and thurgh many o&thorn;er iles &thorn;at er aboute Inde, whare dwelles many
diuerse maners of folke of diuerse lawes and schappes&mdash;of whilke landes and iles I schall speke mare
playnely, and I schall diuyse a party of &thorn;a thinges what &thorn;ai er, when tyme commes, after &thorn;at it may comme to
my mynde, and specially for &thorn;aim &thorn;at wil and er in purpose to visit &thorn;e haly citee of Ierusalem and the haly
<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio">placez &thorn;at er &thorn;are aboute; and I schall tell &thorn;e way &thorn;at &thorn;ai schall hald &thorn;ider, for I hafe many tymes passed and
riden it in gude company of lordes.
<NOTE N="2" RESP="DR">A passage about the language of the work, present in the French texts, is not found in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>. A unique version of the passage, not precisely following the French but on the issue of language, occurs in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.1" N="1" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.1">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER I</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[To teche &yogh;ou the weye out of Englond to Constantynoble.]</HEAD>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">The text in Egerton MS. 1982 not being divided into chapters, the headings are taken from <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. They closely follow the headings in the French version in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR> and <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Royal 20 B. x">R</ABBR>.</NOTE>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.3.13" CORRESP="Cot.4.13">IN &thorn;e name of Godd allmyghty, he &thorn;at wil passe ouer &thorn;e see to Ierusalem, he may wende many ways, bathe
on &thorn;e see and on &thorn;e land after &thorn;e cuntreez &thorn;at he commes fra, and many of &thorn;am commes all to ane end.
Bot troues no&yogh;t &thorn;at I will tell all &thorn;e tounes and citeez and castelles &thorn;at men schall ga by; for &thorn;an me
must make to lang tale. Bot all anely sum cuntreez and maste principal stedes &thorn;at men schall ga thurgh to ga

<PB N="4">
&thorn;e ri&yogh;t way, schortly I think for to touche. For, if a man come fro &thorn;e west partys of &thorn;e werld, as Ingland, Ireland,
Wales, Scotland or Norway, he may, if he will, wende thurgh Almayne and thurgh &thorn;e kyngdom of Hungary,
&thorn;at marchez to &thorn;e land of Poialme
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Poland.</NOTE> and to &thorn;e land of Pannony and of Alleseye.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Silesia.</NOTE> And &yogh;e schall vnderstand
&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of Hungary es a full grete lord and a myghty, and haldes grete and mykill land. For he
haldes &thorn;e land of Hungary, Sauoy,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Slavonia.</NOTE> Comany, a grete party of Bulgary, &thorn;at men calles &thorn;e land of Bulgers,
and a grete party of &thorn;e kyngdom of Ruscy, and &thorn;at lastes to &thorn;e land of Nyfeland
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Lifland, Livonia.</NOTE> and marchez apon
Pruysse. And thurgh &thorn;e land of Hungary men gase to a cytee &thorn;at es called Chippron
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Cyperon, or Sempronium, now Oedenburg.</NOTE> and thurgh &thorn;e
castell of Newhurgh,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6"><ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> adds, "and be the evylle town, &thorn;at sytt toward the ende of Hungarye" (<HI REND="i">Cf.</HI> the French text, and see [commentary]).</NOTE> and men passez by &thorn;e ryuer of Danuby. &THORN;is es a full grete ryuer and gase in to
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">gothe into, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. A misreading by the translator of "uaist (vait, va) en" for "naist en" (Vogels, <HI REND="i">Die ungedrukten Lat. Versionen Mandeville's</HI>, 1886, p. 12).</NOTE>
<MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="folio">Almayne vnder &thorn;e hilles of Lumbardy, and it takes in to him xl. o&thorn;er ryuers; and it rynnes thurgh Hungary
and Cresses
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">Greece (as in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>) and Thrace.</NOTE> and Tracy and gase in to &thorn;e see so stalworthely and with so grete strenth &thorn;at &thorn;e water es fresch xx.
myle within &thorn;e see. And efterward men gase to Bulgary and enters in to &thorn;e land of Bulgers, and &thorn;are passez
men a brigg of stane &thorn;at es ouer &thorn;e ryuer of Marrok.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">River Morava.</NOTE> And &thorn;an men passez thurgh &thorn;e land of Pynceras
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">The Pincenati, or Petschenegs.</NOTE> and
commes to Grece to &thorn;e citee of Sternes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="11">Hesternit, now Sofia.</NOTE> and to &thorn;e citee of Affynpayn
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="12">Philippopolis.</NOTE> and seyne to &thorn;e citee of Bradrenople
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="13">Adrianople.</NOTE>
and seyne to &thorn;e citee of Constantynople, &thorn;e whilk was sum tyme called Bethsamaron,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="14">Byzantium.</NOTE> and &thorn;are dwelles
commonly &thorn;e emperour of Grece. &THORN;are es &thorn;e best kirk of &thorn;e werld and &thorn;e fairest, and it es of saynt Sophie.
And before &thorn;e kirk of saynt Sophie es ane ymage of Justinyane &thorn;e emperour, wele ouergilted; and it es made
sittand apon a hors and coround. &THORN;is ymage was wont to hald in his hand a rounde appel of gold; bot it es
lang sen it fell oute of &thorn;e hand. And men saise &thorn;are &thorn;at &thorn;e fallyng oute of &thorn;e apple es a token &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour
has lost a grete party of his lordschepe. For he was wont to be emperour of Romany, of Grece, of Asie &thorn;e
lesse, of Surry, of &thorn;e land of Iudee, in &thorn;e whilk es Ierusalem, of &thorn;e land of Egipte, of Perse and of Araby;
bot he has lost all, oute taken Greece, and &thorn;at land anely he haldes. Men wald meny tyme hafe putte &thorn;e
appel in to &thorn;e ymage hand, bot it will no&yogh;t habyde &thorn;erin. &THORN;is apple betakens &thorn;e lordschepe &thorn;at he had ouer

<PB N="5">
all &thorn;e werld. &THORN;e to&thorn;er hand he haldes lift vppe agaynes &thorn;e west,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">the east; a&yogh;enst the est, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in taken for to menace mysdoers. &THORN;is
ymage standes on a piler of marble.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.2" N="2" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.2">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER II</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the crosse and croune of oure Lord Ihesu Crist.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.5.5" CORRESP="Cot.6.1">AT Constantynople es &thorn;e spounge
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">is the cros of oure Lord Ihesu Crist and his cote withouten semes, that is clept <HI REND="i">Tunica inconsutilis</HI>, and the sponge, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;e rede of whilk &thorn;e Iewes gafe oure Lord to drynke, when he hang
on &thorn;e crosse. Sum men trowes &thorn;at halfe &thorn;e crosse of Criste be in Cypre in ane abbay of munkes
<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at men calles &thorn;e Hill of &thorn;e Haly Crosse; bot it es no&yogh;t so. For &thorn;at crosse &thorn;at es in Cypre es &thorn;e
crosse on whilk Dismas &thorn;e gude theeffe was hynged. Bot all men wate no&yogh;t &thorn;at; and &thorn;at es ill done. For by
cause of getyng of offerandes &thorn;ai say &thorn;at it es &thorn;e crosse of oure Lorde Ihesu Criste.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.5.9" CORRESP="Cot.6.12">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e crosse of oure Lord was made of foure maner of treesse, as it <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">es</SUPPLIED> contende
in &thorn;is werse, whilk es here writen, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">In cruce fit palma, cedrus, cypressus, oliua</Q>. For &thorn;e pece &thorn;at went vprightes
fra &thorn;e erthe vnto &thorn;e heued was of cypresse; and &thorn;at pece &thorn;at went ouerthwert, to &thorn;e whilk his hend ware nailed,
was of palme; and &thorn;e stock &thorn;at stude in &thorn;e erthe, in &thorn;e whilk was made a mortas, was of cedre; and &thorn;e table
abouen his heued was a fote and a halfe lang, on &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e tytle was writen in Hebrew, in Grew and in Latyne,
and it was of olyue. Of &thorn;ise foure maner of treesz &thorn;e Iews made Cristes crosse for &thorn;ai trowed &thorn;at he schuld hafe
bene hingand apon &thorn;at crosse als lang as &thorn;at crosse myght last. And &thorn;erfore made &thorn;ai &thorn;e fote of cedre; for
cedre may no&yogh;t rote in erthe ne in water. For &thorn;ai wald &thorn;at it schuld hafe lang lasted. And for &thorn;ai trowed &thorn;at
Cristez body schuld hafe stynked, &thorn;ai made &thorn;at pece &thorn;at went fra &thorn;e erthe vpward, on whilk his body hang, of
cypresse, for it es wele smelland, so &thorn;at &thorn;e smell of his body schuld not greue to men &thorn;at come forby. And &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="folio">pece &thorn;at went ouerthwert, to whilk his hend ware nayled, was of palme; for in &thorn;e alde testament was it ordaynd
&thorn;at, when any man had &thorn;e victory of his enmy, he schuld be cround with palme. And for &thorn;ai trowed &thorn;at &thorn;ai

<PB N="6">
had &thorn;e victory of Criste, &thorn;ai made &thorn;e ouerthwert pece of palme. And &thorn;e table of &thorn;e tytle was made of olyue;
for olyue betakens pees, as &thorn;e story of Noe beres witness, whare &thorn;e doufe broght &thorn;e braunche of olyue in hir
beek, whilk betakned pees made betwix Godd and man. And so trowed &thorn;e Iewes to hafe pees, when Criste was
deed; for &thorn;ai said &thorn;at he made stryffe amang &thorn;am. And ye schall vnderstand &thorn;at oure Lorde was nailed to
&thorn;e crosse liggand, and &thorn;erfore he sufferd &thorn;e mare payne.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.6.6" CORRESP="Cot.7.10">Men of Grece and o&thorn;er Christen men also &thorn;at dwelles be&yogh;ond &thorn;e see saise &thorn;at &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e crosse &thorn;at we
call cypresse was of &thorn;at tree &thorn;at Adam ete &thorn;e appel off, and so &thorn;ai fynd writen. And &thorn;ai say also &thorn;at &thorn;aire
Scripture saise &thorn;at Adam fell seke and said to his sone Seth, &thorn;at he schuld ga to Paradys and pray &thorn;e aungell &thorn;at
kepes Paradys, &thorn;at he wald send him of &thorn;e oile of &thorn;e tree of mercy for to enoynt with his membres, &thorn;at he
mygth hafe hele. And Seth went forth to Paradys; bot &thorn;e aungel wald no&yogh;t late him in, bot said til him &thorn;at he
myght no&yogh;t hafe of &thorn;e oile of mercy. Bot he tuke him foure
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">three, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>; and so also in French texts.</NOTE> graynes of &thorn;e same tree &thorn;at his fader ete &thorn;e appel
off, and bad him, als sone as his fader ware deed, &thorn;at he schuld putte &thorn;ase graynes vnder his tung and graue
him so, and of &thorn;ase foure graynes schuld spring trees &thorn;at schuld bere a fruyte thurgh whilk Adam schuld be
saued. And, when Seth come hame agayne, he fand his fader nere deed; and he did with &thorn;e graynes as &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio">aungel bad, of whilk sprang foure trees, wharof a crosse was made &thorn;at bare gude fruyte, Ihesu Criste, thurgh
wham Adam and all &thorn;at comme of him er saued and delyuerd fra deed withouten end, bot if it be &thorn;aire awen
defeute. &THORN;is haly crosse had &thorn;e Iews hidd in &thorn;e erthe vnder &thorn;e roche of mount Caluarie; and it lay &thorn;are
cc. &yogh;ere and mare vnto &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at saynt Helyne fand it, &thorn;e whilk saynt Helyne was moder of Constantyne
&thorn;e emperour of Rome. And scho was doghter of Coel, kyng of Ingeland, &thorn;at was &thorn;at tyme called &thorn;e mare
Bretayne. And &thorn;e emperour of Rome, when he was in &thorn;at cuntree and sawe hir grete bewtee, he tuke hir to
his wyfe and gatte on hir &thorn;e forsaid Constantyne. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e crosse of oure Lorde was of
lenth viii. cubits; and &thorn;at tree &thorn;at was ouerthwert had in lenth three cubits and a halfe. A party of &thorn;e coroun
of thornes wharwith oure Lorde was coround and ane of &thorn;e nayles, and &thorn;e spere heued, and many o&thorn;er relyques
er in Fraunce in &thorn;e kynges chapell. And &thorn;e coroune lyes in a vessell of cristall, wele dight and richely. A
kyng of Fraunce boght &thorn;ise relyques sum tyme of &thorn;e Januenes, to wham &thorn;e emperour had layd &thorn;am in wedd
for a grete soume of gold. And if all it be so &thorn;at men saise &thorn;at &thorn;is coroun be of thornes, &yogh;e schall vnderstand
&thorn;at it was of iunkes of the see, &thorn;at ware whyte and prikked als scharpely as thornes. For I hafe many tymes sene

<PB N="7">
bathe &thorn;at &thorn;at es at Parysch and &thorn;at &thorn;at es at Constantinople; for &thorn;ai ware bathe of ane, made of junkes of
<MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e see, bot men has departed &thorn;am in twa parties, of whilk a party es at Parysch and &thorn;e to&thorn;er party es at
Constantinople. And I hafe a prikk &thorn;eroff, &thorn;at semes a whyte thorne; and &thorn;at was giffen me for grete
frenschepe. For &thorn;are er many of &thorn;am broken and fallen doune in &thorn;e vessell whare in &thorn;e coroun es, ay as
&thorn;ai breke when men stirrez &thorn;e vessell to schewe &thorn;e coroun to grete lordes and to pilgrimes &thorn;at commes
&thorn;ider.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.7.6" CORRESP="Cot.8.27">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at oure Lorde, &thorn;at nyght &thorn;at he was taken, he was ledd in til a gardyne, and
&thorn;are he was opposed scharply; and &thorn;are &thorn;e Iews scorned him and sett a coroun on his heued and thrast it &thorn;eron
so fast &thorn;at &thorn;e blude ran doune by many placez of his visage and his neck and his schulders. And &thorn;at
coroun was made of braunches of albespyne; and &thorn;erfore has &thorn;e albespyne many vertuz. For he &thorn;at beres
a braunche &thorn;eroff apon him, &thorn;er schall na thunder ne na maner of tempest dere him; ne &thorn;e hous whare it es
in may nane ill spirit comme in, ne in na place whare it es. And in &thorn;e same gardyne sayne Petre forsuke oure
Lord thryes. Afterward was oure Lord ledd before &thorn;e bischope and &thorn;e officers of &thorn;e lawe in ano&thorn;er gardyn
of Annas; and &thorn;are he was opposed also and scorned and coround eft with a thorne &thorn;at men callez &thorn;e
barbaren, &thorn;at growed in &thorn;at gardyn. And &thorn;at also has many vertuz. And afterward he was ledd in to a
gardyn of Cayphas; and &thorn;are he was coround with ane engletere. And seyne he was ledd in to &thorn;e chaumbre
of Pylate; and &thorn;are he was opposed and coround. For the Iews sette him in a chaier and cledd him in a
<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio">mantell; and &thorn;an made &thorn;ai &thorn;e coroun of &thorn;e junkes of &thorn;e see, and &thorn;ai knelid to him and coround him &thorn;erwith
and said <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Aue, rex Iudeorum</Q>, &thorn;at es at say, "Haile, kyng of Iews." And &thorn;is coroun, of whilk &thorn;e ta halfe es at
Parisch and &thorn;e to&thorn;er at Constantinople, had Criste apon his heued when he was done on &thorn;e crosse. And
&thorn;erfore men schuld maste wirschepe it, and hald it mare worthy &thorn;an any of &thorn;e o&thorn;er. &THORN;e schaft of &thorn;e spere
with whilk Criste was stanged to &thorn;e hert hase &thorn;e emperour of Almayne; bot &thorn;e heued &thorn;erof es at Parisch.
&THORN;e emperour of Constantinople saise &thorn;at he has &thorn;e spere heued; and &thorn;at spere heued hafe I oft sene, bot it es
gretter &thorn;an &thorn;at of Parisch.</SEG></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.3" N="3" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.3">
<PB N="8">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER III</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the cytee of Costantynoble; and of the feithe of Grekes.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.8.1" CORRESP="Cot.9.24">ALSO at Constantinople lies saynt Anne, oure Lady moder, wham saynt Helyne gert be broght fra
Ierusalem. And &thorn;ar lies also &thorn;e body of Iohn Crisostom, &thorn;at was bischope of Constantinople. And &thorn;are
lies sayne Luke, &thorn;e euangelist; for his banes ware broght fra Bethany,
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">Bithynia.</NOTE> whare he was grauen. And
many o&thorn;er reliques er &thorn;are. And &thorn;are es of &thorn;e vesselles of stane, as it ware marble, whilk men callez ydrious,
&thorn;at euermare droppes water and filles &thorn;aim self ilk a &yogh;ere. And I do &yogh;ow to wit &thorn;at Constantinople es ri&yogh;t a
faire citee and a gude, and wele walled; and it es three cornerd. And &thorn;are es ane arm of &thorn;e see &thorn;at men
calles Ellespount; and sum calles it &thorn;e Bouche of Constantinople, and sum Brace Sayne George. And &thorn;is water
enclosez twa parties of &thorn;e citee. And vp toward &thorn;e see apon &thorn;e same water was wont to be &thorn;e grete citee
of Troy in a faire playne; bot &thorn;at citee was destruyd with &thorn;aim of Grece.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.8.12" CORRESP="Cot.10.9">Aboute Grece er many Iles, &thorn;at es to say Calcas,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Chalce, now Carki.</NOTE> Calistra,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Calliste, Thera.</NOTE> Oertige,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Ortygia, Delos.</NOTE> Teshiria,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Lesbos?</NOTE> Minca,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Minois, Paros.</NOTE> Flaxania,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Naxos?</NOTE> Melo,
Carpateya,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">Carpathus, Scarpanto.</NOTE> Lempnia.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">Lemnos.</NOTE> And in &thorn;is ile es &thorn;e mount Caucase
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">Athos, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at passez &thorn;e clowdes. &thorn;are er also many o&thorn;er
diuerse cuntreez and spechez &thorn;at er tributaries and obeyand to &thorn;e emperour, &thorn;at es at say Turcople, Pyncenard,
Comange, Tracy, Macedoyne, of whilk Alexander was kyng, and many o&thorn;er. In this cuntree was Aristotle
borne, in a citee &thorn;at men calles Strages, a litill fra Tracy. At Strages lyes Aristotle, and &thorn;are es ane awtere
apon his toumbe. And &thorn;are make &thorn;ai a solempne feste ilke a &yogh;ere, as he ware a saynt. And apon his awter
&thorn;ai hald &thorn;aire grete counsaile and assemblee; and &thorn;ai trowe &thorn;at thurgh inspiracion of Godd and him &thorn;ai sall hafe
&thorn;e better counsaile. In &thorn;at cuntree es ri&yogh;t grete mountaynes toward &thorn;e end of Macedoyne. And amanges
o&thorn;er &thorn;er es ane &thorn;at men calles Olympus, &thorn;at departes Macedoyne and Tracy; and it es hye abouen &thorn;e

<PB N="9">
clowdes. &THORN;are es also ano&thorn;er hill &thorn;at men calles Athos; and &thorn;at es so hie &thorn;at &thorn;e schadowe &thorn;eroff rechez vnto
Lempny, &thorn;e whilk es &thorn;erfra nere lxxvii. myle. Abouen on &thorn;ir hilles es &thorn;e aer so clere and so sutill &thorn;at men
may fele na wynd &thorn;are; and &thorn;erfore may na beste ne fewle liffe &thorn;are, so es &thorn;e aer drye. And men saise in &thorn;ase
cuntrees &thorn;at philosophirs sum tyme went vp on &thorn;ir hilles and held to &thorn;aire noses spoungez moisted with water
for to cacche aer, for &thorn;e aer &thorn;are was so drie. And also abouen on &thorn;ir hilles in &thorn;e powder &thorn;ai wrate letters
<MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio">with &thorn;aire fingers, and at &thorn;e &yogh;ere end &thorn;ai went agayne and fand &thorn;e same letters &thorn;at &thorn;ai had writen &thorn;e &yogh;ere
before als fresch as &thorn;ai ware on &thorn;e first day withouten any defaute. And &thorn;erfore it semes wele &thorn;at &thorn;ase hilles
passez &thorn;e clowdes to the pure aere.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.9.9" CORRESP="Cot.11.4">In &thorn;e citee of Constantinople es &thorn;e emperours palays ri&yogh;t faire and wele dight; and &thorn;are be syde es a fayre
place ordaynd for iustyng. And &thorn;er er stagez made all aboute it and grecez, &thorn;at men may sit on, ilk ane
abouen o&thorn;er, to see &thorn;e iustyng, so &thorn;at nane schall dere o&thorn;er ne lett o&thorn;er to see. And vnder &thorn;e stages
er stables vowted wele for &thorn;e emperour hors; and all &thorn;e pilers er of marbill. And in &thorn;e kirk of saynt
Sophy ane emperour on a tyme wald hafe layd &thorn;e body of his fader, when he was deed; and, als &thorn;ai made a
graue, &thorn;ai fand a body in &thorn;e erthe, and apon &thorn;at body lay a grete plate of gold and &thorn;erapon was writen in
Hebrew, in Grewe and in Latyne, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ihesus Christus nascetur de virgine Maria; et ego credo in eum</Q>, &thorn;at
es to say, "Ihesus Criste sall be borne of &thorn;e virgyn Mary; and in him trowe I." And &thorn;e date when &thorn;is
was writen and layd in &thorn;e erthe was ii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> &yogh;ere before &thorn;e incarnacioun of Criste. And &yogh;it es &thorn;at plate in &thorn;e
tresoury of &thorn;e kirke; and men saise &thorn;at &thorn;at body was &thorn;e body of Ermogenes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Hermogene, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. But see the French text.</NOTE> &thorn;e wyse man.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.9.19" CORRESP="Cot.11.21">And if all it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e Grekes be Cristen, &yogh;it &thorn;ai vary fra oure faith. For &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;e Haly Gaste
commes no&yogh;t oute of &thorn;e Sonne, bot anely of &thorn;e Fader; and &thorn;ai er no&yogh;t obeyand to &thorn;e kirke of Rome, ne to &thorn;e
Pope. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;aire Patriarke has als mykill power be&yogh;ond &thorn;e Grekis see as oure Pope hase on
<MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="folio">&thorn;is syde. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e Pope Iohn &thorn;e xxii. sent letters to &thorn;aim schewand &thorn;am how &thorn;at &thorn;e cristen faith
schuld be all ane, aud &thorn;at all cristen men schuld be obeyand to a pope, whilke es Cristez vicar in erthe, to
wham Godd gaffe full powere for to bynd and to louse; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai schuld be <CORR SIC="odient" RESP="GW">obedient</CORR> til him. And
&thorn;ai sent to him many answers; and amanges o&thorn;er &thorn;ai sent him ane, and said on &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Potentiam tuam
summam circa tuos subiectos firmiter credimus; superbiam tuam summam tollerare non possumus; auariciam

<PB N="10">
tuam summam saciare non intendimus. Dominus tecum sit, quia Dominus nobiscum est. Vale</Q>. &THORN;is es to say,
"We trowe wele &thorn;i powere es grete apon &thorn;i subgets; we may no&yogh;t suffer &thorn;i grete pride; we er no&yogh;t in purpose
to staunche &thorn;i grete couetise. Godd be with &thorn;e, for Godd es with vs. Fare wele." And o&thorn;er answere had he
no&yogh;t of &thorn;aim. &THORN;e Grekes also makes &thorn;e sacrement of &thorn;e autere of leuaynd breed
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">therf bred, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; for oure Lord made it of
leuaynd breed, when be made his maundee. And &thorn;ai say we erre &thorn;at makes &thorn;e sacrement of tharf breed.
And on &thorn;e schire Thursday make &thorn;ai &thorn;at breed in a takenyng of &thorn;e maundee, and dries it at &thorn;e soune, and kepez it
all &thorn;e &yogh;ere, and giffez it to seke men in steed of howsill. And &thorn;ai make bot ane vnccioun, when &thorn;ai cristen childer,
ne dippes &thorn;aim bot anes in &thorn;e fount. &THORN;ai anoynt na seke men; and &thorn;ai say &thorn;er es na purgatory, and &thorn;at
saules sall now&thorn;er hafe ioy ne payne before &thorn;e day of dome. &THORN;ai say also &thorn;t fornicacion es na dedly bot a
<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio">kyndely thing, and &thorn;at men and wymmen schuld no&yogh;t be wedded bot anes, and, wha so weddes ofter &thorn;an anes,
&thorn;aire childer er bastardes and geten in synne. &THORN;aire prestes also er wedded. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at oker es na
dedly synne. &THORN;ai sell benificez of haly kirk, and so duse men in o&thorn;er placez; and &thorn;at es grete sclaunder and
grete harme. For now es symony kyng corouned in haly kirk. Godd may amend it, when his will es. &THORN;ai
say also &thorn;at in lentyn men schuld no&yogh;t synge messe bot on &thorn;e Setirday and on &thorn;e Sonounday. And &thorn;ai fast
no&yogh;t &thorn;e Seterday na tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, bot it be &yogh;ole euen or pask euen. &THORN;ai suffer na man &thorn;at,commes fra &thorn;is
syde of &thorn;e Grekes see syng on &thorn;aire awters; and, if it fall &thorn;at &thorn;ai do, &thorn;ai wasche &thorn;e awter alsone with haly
water. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;er schuld bot a messe be sungen at ane awter on a day. Ouer &thorn;at &thorn;ai say &thorn;at oure
Lorde ete neuer bodily mete, bot he made signe of etyng and feyned as he had etyn, schewand taken
of manhede. &THORN;ai say we synne dedly in &thorn;at we schaue oure berdes, for pai say &thorn;at &thorn;e berde es taken of
manhede and &thorn;e gifft of Godd. And &thorn;a &thorn;at
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">And &thorn;a &thorn;at &hellip; wyfes, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> schafes &thorn;aire berdes, &thorn;ai do it all anely for to plese &thorn;e werld and
&thorn;aire wyfes. &THORN;ai say also &thorn;at we synne dedly in etyng of bestez &thorn;at ware forbedd in &thorn;e alde lawe, as swyne,
hares and o&thorn;er bestez &thorn;at chewes no&yogh;t cudde. Also &thorn;ai say &thorn;at we synne in etyng of flesch in &thorn;e three days
before Ask Wedensday, and also in etyng of flesch on Wedensdays, and when we ete whitmete on Frydays.
And &thorn;ai curse all &thorn;ase &thorn;at etes na flesh on &thorn;e Saterday. Also &thorn;e emperour of Constantynople makes &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="folio">patriarkes, ercebischopes and bischopes, and he giffes all &thorn;e digniteez of haly kirk in &thorn;at cuntree; and he
pryues &thorn;aim &thorn;at him think vnworthy. And so he es &thorn;are lorde bathe of temperaltee and of spiritualtee.</SEG></P>

<PB N="11">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.11.1" CORRESP="Cot.13.10">If &yogh;e wil wit of &thorn;e abce of Grew and what kyn letters &thorn;ai hafe, here &yogh;e may see &thorn;am and &thorn;er names also:&mdash;
alpha <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, beta <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, gamma <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, delta <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, e breuis <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, epissima <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>: the character <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN> used only as a numeral&mdash;6.</NOTE> zeta <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, hetha <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, tetha <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, iota <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, kappa <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, mi <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, ni <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>,
xe <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, o breuis <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, pe <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, cope <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>,
<NOTE N="2"><FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, used as a numeral&mdash;90.</NOTE>  ro <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, sima <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, tau <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, gui<FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, fi <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, xi <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, spi <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, o longa <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, encos <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>,
<NOTE N="3"><FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>for <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>.</NOTE> chile <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>.
<NOTE N="4"><FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>, the latter character for <FOREIGN LANG="greek"><GAP></FOREIGN>.</NOTE></SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.4" N="4" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.4">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER IV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of seynt John the euangelist; and of Ypocras doughter transformed from a womman to a dragoun.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.11.7" CORRESP="Cot.13.13">AND if all it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ire thynges touche no&yogh;t to teching of &thorn;e way to &thorn;e haly land, neuer &thorn;e les &thorn;ai
touche &thorn;at &thorn;at I hafe hight to schewe, &thorn;at es at say of &thorn;e customes and maners and diuersteez of
cuntreez. And for &thorn;e land of Grece es &thorn;e next cuntree &thorn;at variez and es discordand in faith
and lettres fra vs and oure faith, &thorn;erfore I hafe sette it here, &thorn;at &yogh;e may wit &thorn;e diuersetee &thorn;at es betwene oure
trowth and &thorn;aires; for many men has grete lyking and comforth to here speke of straunge thinges.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.11.12" CORRESP="Cot.13.21">Now comme I agayne for to teche &thorn;e way fra Constantinople to &thorn;e haly land. He &thorn;at will ga thurgh
Turkye, he gase to &thorn;e citee &thorn;e whilk es called Nyke,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Nic&aelig;a, in Bithynia.</NOTE> and so thurgh &thorn;e &yogh;ate of Chiuotot,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Cibotus, Civitot, now Gemlik.</NOTE> and to &thorn;e mount
of Chiuotot, &thorn;at es ri&yogh;t hie; and it es o&thorn;er halfe myle fra &thorn;e citee of Nyke. Wha so will passe fra Constantinople to &thorn;e haly land by see, he schall ga by &thorn;e Brace of Sayn George, and so, sayland in &thorn;e Grekes see, by
a place
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Myra, in Lycia.</NOTE> whare sayne Nicholas lies and by many o&thorn;er places. And first men commes til ane ile &thorn;e whilk es
called Sylo.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">Chios, Scio.</NOTE> And in &thorn;at yle growes mastik apon smale treesse; and it springes oute of &thorn;am as it ware &thorn;e
gum of plum tree or chiry tree.</SEG></P>

<PB N="12">
<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.12.1" CORRESP="Cot.14.1">Seyne men passez by &thorn;e ile of Pathmos, whare sayn Iohn &thorn;e euaungelist wrate &thorn;e <TITLE>apochalipse</TITLE>. And
&yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at, when oure Lorde died, sayn Iohn was of elde xxxii. &yogh;ere, and he liffed after &thorn;e
passioun of Criste lxii. &yogh;ere.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">lxvii. &yogh;eer and in the c. &yogh;eer of his age he dyede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Fra Pathmos men gase til Ephesum, a faire citee and nere to &thorn;e see; and &thorn;are
died sayne Iohn, and was grauen behind &thorn;e awter in a toumbe. And &thorn;are es a faire kirk; for Cristen men
ware wont for to hafe &thorn;at citee in hand. Bot now it es occupied with Turkes, and so es all Asy &thorn;e less; and
&thorn;erfore es Asy &thorn;e lesse called Turky. In &thorn;e toumbe of sayne Iohn men may fynd na thyng bot manna;
for sum men saise his body was translated in to paradyse. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at sayn Iohn gert make
his graue &thorn;are in his lyfe and laid himself &thorn;erin all qwikk; and &thorn;erfore sum saise &thorn;at he dyed no&yogh;t, bot &thorn;at he
restez &thorn;are to &thorn;e day of dome. And forsothe &thorn;are es ri&yogh;t a grete meruaile; for men may see &thorn;are &thorn;e erthe
of &thorn;e toumbe many a tyme stirre and moue, as &thorn;er ware a qwikke thing vnder.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.12.11" CORRESP="Cot.14.20">Fra Ephesum men passez by many iles in &thorn;e see vnto &thorn;e citee of Pateran,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Patera, in Lycia.</NOTE> whare sayne Nicholas was
borne, and so to the citee of Marc,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Myra.</NOTE> whare he was chosen to be bischope. &THORN;are growes ri&yogh;t gude wyne and
myghty, &thorn;e whilk men callez wyne of Marc. Fra &thorn;eine men passez to &thorn;e ile of Grece,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Crete.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e
emperour gafe sum tyme to &thorn;e Ianuynes. And fra &thorn;eine men wendes to &thorn;e ile of Cophos,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Cos, another name for Lango, the birthplace of Hippocrates.</NOTE> and so by &thorn;e
ile of Lango, of whilk iles Ypocras was sum tyme lorde.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.12.16" CORRESP="Cot.14.28">And sum saise &thorn;at in &thorn;e ile of Lango es Ypocras doghter in likness of a dragoun, &thorn;e whilk es a hundreth
fote lang, as men saise, for I hafe no&yogh;t sene it. And folk &thorn;are calles hir Lady of &thorn;at ile. Scho lies in ane alde
castell, and schewes hir thries in &thorn;e &yogh;ere; and scho duse na man harme. Scho was changed &thorn;us fra a faire
damysell til a dragoun thurgh a goddess &thorn;at men called Diane. And men saise &thorn;at scho sall dwell so vnto &thorn;e
tyme &thorn;at a knyght comme &thorn;at schall be so hardy &thorn;at he sall dare ga to hir and kisse hir mouth. And &thorn;an sall
scho turne agayne to hir awen kynde and be a womman; bot scho sall liffe bot lytill while efter. And it es no&yogh;t
lang sithen a knyght of Rodes, the whilk was a doghty man and a hardy, said &thorn;at he wald kisse hir. And he
leped on his coursere and went to &thorn;e castell and entred in to &thorn;e caue whare &thorn;e dragoun lay. And scho began to
lift vp hir heued agayne him; and &thorn;e knyght
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">So also in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. In the French it is the "chival," not "chivaler."</NOTE> sawe it so hidous, and fast he fledd away. And &thorn;e dragoun folowed
and tuke &thorn;e knyght and bare him maugree his til a cragg of &thorn;e see, and ouer &thorn;at cragg scho kest him in to &thorn;e see;

<PB N="13">
and so was &thorn;at knyght lost. Also a &yogh;ong man, &thorn;e whilk wist no&yogh;t of &thorn;at dragoun, went oute on a tyme of a
schippe for to refresch him, and walked furth in &thorn;is ile til he come to &thorn;e castell, and entred in to &thorn;e caue. And
so he fand a chaumbre, and &thorn;erin he sawe a damysell kemmand hir hare and loked in a mirrour, and scho had
mykill tresoure aboute hir. And he supposed &thorn;at scho had bene a common womman, &thorn;at had dwelled &thorn;are to
kepe men &thorn;at come thurgh &thorn;e cuntree; and he stude still &thorn;are behind hir till scho turned hir toward him and
<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio">asked him what he wald. And he said &thorn;at he wald be hir paramour. And scho asked him if he ware a knyght,
and be said nay. And scho said &thorn;at &thorn;an myght he no&yogh;t be hir lemman; bot scho bad him go agayne to his
felawes and make him knyght and com agayne on &thorn;e morue, and scho schuld com oute of &thorn;e caue. And scho
bad him &thorn;at he schuld kisse hir mouthe and hafe na drede of hir, what figure so euer he sawe hir, for scho schuld
do him no harme, if all scho ware neuer so vggly ne so hidous til his sight. For, scho said, it was done by
enchauntement, for scho was swilk as he sawe hir &thorn;at tyme. And scho said him &thorn;at, if he kissed hir, he schold
hafe all &thorn;at tresour and be lord of hir and of &thorn;ase iles. And he went fra hir and come to his felawes to &thorn;e
schippe and gert make him knyght and went agayne apon the morue to kisse &thorn;e damysell. And, when he sawe
hir comme oute of &thorn;e caue in liknes of a dragoun, he had so grete drede &thorn;at he fledd to &thorn;e schippe, and scho
folowed him. And when scho saw &thorn;at he turned no&yogh;t agayne, scho began to crie, as a thing &thorn;at had mykill
sorowe. To &thorn;e schippe scho folowed him and, when he was entred in to &thorn;e schippe, scho turned agayne with a
hidous crie; and sone after &thorn;e knyght died. And seyne hiderward myght na knyght see hir, &thorn;at ne he died sone
after. Bot, when a knyght commes &thorn;at es so hardy &thorn;at he dare kisse hir, he schall no&yogh;t die, bot he schall turne
&thorn;at damysell in to hir ri&yogh;t schappe, and he schall be lord of hir and of &thorn;e iles beforesaid.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.13.20" CORRESP="Cot.16.14">Fra &thorn;is ile men passez to &thorn;e ile of Rodes, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e Hospitelers haldez and gouernes. And &thorn;is ile &thorn;ai
wan of &thorn;e emperour of Constantinople. And it was sum tyme called Colos,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">From the Colossus.</NOTE> and so calles &thorn;e Turkes it &yogh;it.
<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="folio">And sayne Paule in his pistle wrate to &thorn;am of &thorn;at ile <TITLE LANG="lat">ad Colocenses</TITLE>. &THORN;is ile es viii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> myle fra Constantinople,</SEG>
for to wende by &thorn;e see.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.5" N="5" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.5">
<PB N="14">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER V.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">There is no division or rubric here in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, although the matter following is not covered by the rubric of chp. iv.</NOTE></HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of diversities in Cyprus; of the road from Cyprus to Jerusalem; and of the marvel of a fosse full of sand.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.14.1.3" CORRESP="Cot.16.21">FRA &thorn;is ile of Rodes men passez in to Cypre, whare er many vynes, of &thorn;e whilk es made noble wyne and
myghty; &thorn;e whilk er &thorn;e first &yogh;ere reed, and after a &yogh;ere it turnez to whyte, and, ay &thorn;e elder it es, &thorn;e
whittere it waxes and &thorn;e mare clere and mare myghty and &thorn;e better smell hase. Vnto Cypre men
passez by a place &thorn;at es called &thorn;e Gulf of Cathaly,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Satalia, or Adalia, on the mainland, N.W. of Cyprus.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk was sum tyme a grete cuntree and a faire, and a
faire citee &thorn;erin, &thorn;at hight Cathaly. And all &thorn;at cuntree was lost thurgh foly of a &yogh;ong man. For &thorn;er was a
faire damysell whilk he luffed wele, and scho dyed sudaynely and was layd in a graue of marble; and for &thorn;e
grete lufe &thorn;at he had to hir he went on a nyght til hir grafe and opned it and went in and lay by hir and &yogh;ode
his way. And at &thorn;e nynde moneth end a voice come to him on a nyght and said, "Ga to &thorn;e graue of &thorn;at
womman and open it, and behald what &thorn;ou has geten on hir. And, if &thorn;ou ga noght, &thorn;ou schall hafe grete harme
and grete disese." And he went and opned &thorn;e grafe, and &thorn;er flewe oute a heued
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">an eddere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> ri&yogh;t horrible and hidous to
see, &thorn;e whilk flewe all aboute &thorn;e citee, and alssone it sank and all &thorn;e cuntree aboute it. And &thorn;are er many
perilous passagez.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.14.15" CORRESP="Cot.17.9">Fra Rodes to Cypre es nere v<HI REND="sup">c</HI> myle; bot men may wende to Cipre and no&yogh;t com at Rodes. Cypre es a
gude ile and a grete; and &thorn;are er many gude citez, bot principally foure. &THORN;are er also three bischopes and ane
<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio">ercebischope. &THORN;e ercebischope see es at Nicosy.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Nicosia, Lefkosia.</NOTE> &THORN;e principale citee of Cypre es Famagost
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Famagosta.</NOTE>; and &thorn;are es &thorn;e
best hauen of &thorn;e see in all &thorn;e werld, for &thorn;are arryues Cristen men and hathen and men of all naciouns. And
in
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">And in &hellip; Lymettes, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Cypre es ano&thorn;er hauen at &thorn;e citee of Lymettes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Limasol.</NOTE> In Cypre also es &thorn;e hill of &thorn;e Haly Crosse; and &thorn;are es ane
abbay of mounkes, and &thorn;are es <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;e</SUPPLIED> crosse of &thorn;e gude theeffe Dismas, as I hafe said before. And sum trowes &thorn;at
&thorn;are es &thorn;e half of &thorn;e crosse of oure Lord, bot it es no&yogh;t so. In Cipre lyes sayn Genouefe, of wham men
of &thorn;at cuntree makes grete feste and grete sollempnytee. And in &thorn;e castell of Amours liez &thorn;e body
of saynt Hillarion, and men kepes it full wirschipfully. In Cipre men huntes with papiouns, &thorn;e whilk er

<PB N="15">
lyke to leoperds; and &thorn;ai take wylde bestes ri&yogh;t wele, &yogh;a better and mare swiftly &thorn;an hundes. And &thorn;ai er sum
dele mare &thorn;an lyouns.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and &thorn;ei taken more scharpelych the bestes and more delyuerly &thorn;an don houndes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In Cipre es &thorn;e maner &thorn;at all men, bathe lordes and o&thorn;er, etez &thorn;aire mete apon &thorn;e erthe.
For &thorn;ai make pittes in &thorn;e erthe all aboute &thorn;e hall, depe to &thorn;e knee, and &thorn;ai ger paue &thorn;am wele; and, when &thorn;ai
will ete, &thorn;ai ga in to &thorn;a pittes and settes &thorn;am doune. And &thorn;is es &thorn;e cause, for to be mare fresche; for &thorn;at land
es mare hate &thorn;an it es here. At grete festes, and for straunge men &thorn;at commez &thorn;ider, &thorn;ai sette burdes and
fourmes, as men duse in &thorn;is cuntree; bot &thorn;ai ware leuer sitte on &thorn;e erthe.</SEG></P>
<P>In Cipre
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">In Cipre &hellip; &thorn;at salt, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;er es a laake half a myle fra &thorn;e see, &thorn;e water of &thorn;e whilk ilk a &yogh;ere a certayne tyme congelez in
to gude salt; and &thorn;erfor schippes &thorn;at commes fra &thorn;e Haly Land commes &thorn;er away for to fraght &thorn;am with &thorn;at salt.</P>
<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.15.11" CORRESP="Cot.17.37">Fra Cipre men may wende by ysee and by land to Ierusalem; and in a day and a nyght he &thorn;at has gude wynd
may com to &thorn;e hauen of Tyre, &thorn;at now es called Surry,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">S&ucirc;r.</NOTE> and it
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and it &hellip; Surrie, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> es at &thorn;e entree of Surrie. &THORN;are was sum tyme
a faire citee of Cristen men, but Sarzenes hase destruyd it a grete party; and &thorn;ai kepe &thorn;at hauen ri&yogh;t strangly,
for drede &thorn;at &thorn;ai hase of Cristen men. Men myght passe to &thorn;at hauen righter and better and com no&yogh;t at Cipre,
bot &thorn;ai wende gladly to Cipre to rest &thorn;am &thorn;are on &thorn;e land and to refresch &thorn;am, and
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">and &hellip; before, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> also to fraght &thorn;er schippes
with salt, as I talde &yogh;ow before, and to by &thorn;am o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe nede off to &thorn;aire liffing. At Tyre euen
apon &thorn;e see syde men may fynd many rubies. And &thorn;are es also &thorn;e well of whilk haly writte
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Canticles [Song of Solomon], iv. 15.</NOTE> saise &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Fons
ortorum, puteus aquarum viuencium</Q>. In &thorn;is citee of Tyre said &thorn;e womman Samaritane til oure Lorde &thorn;ir
wordes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Luke xi. 27.</NOTE> <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Beatus venter qui te portauit et vbera que suxisti</Q>, &thorn;at es at say, "Blissed be &thorn;e wambe &thorn;e bare and
&thorn;e pappes &thorn;at &thorn;ou sowked." And &thorn;are forgafe oure Lord &thorn;e womman of Cananee hir synnes. Before &thorn;e citee of
Tyre was sum tyme &thorn;e stane whareon oure Lorde satte and preched; and on &thorn;at stane was founded &thorn;e kirk of
saynt Saueour.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.15.21" CORRESP="Cot.18.21">And viii. myle fra Tyre apon &thorn;e see syde es &thorn;e citee of Saphon,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">S&ucirc;rafend.</NOTE> or Sarepte, toward &thorn;e este. &THORN;are was &thorn;e
prophete Helyas wont for to dwelle; and &thorn;are raised oure Lorde Iesus &thorn;e wydow son
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">and &thorn;ere reysed he [<HI REND="i">sc</HI>. Elijah] Jonas the widwes sone, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> fra deed to lyue. And
v. myle &thorn;eine es &thorn;e citee of Sydon, of whilk citee Dydo, &thorn;at was Eneas wyf after &thorn;e destruccion of Troy, was
lady. And scho founded Cartage in Affryk; the whilk es now called Dydoncato.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">and now is cleped Sydon Sayete, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;e citee of Tyre regned
<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio">Achilles, Dydon fader. And xviii. myle fra Sydon es &thorn;e citee of Beruch.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="11">Beirut.</NOTE> And fra Beruch three day iourneez
es &thorn;e cytee of Sardyne. And fyue myle &thorn;eine es &thorn;e citee of Damasc.</SEG></P>

<PB N="16">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.16.1" CORRESP="Cot.18.32">Qwha so wil ga langer tyme on &thorn;e see and com nere to Ierusalem, he schall go fra Cipre by see vnto porte
Jaff, for &thorn;at es &thorn;e next hauen to Ierusalem. For fra &thorn;at hauen to Ierusalem es no&yogh;t bot a day iournee and a half.
&THORN;are es &thorn;e citee of Joppe; bot it es called Jaffe after ane of Noe sones, &thorn;at hight Japhet, whilk founded it. And
sum men saise it es &thorn;e eldest citee of &thorn;e werld, for it was made before Noe flude. And &thorn;are er banes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">irene cheynes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, and otherwise following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR> literally.</NOTE> of a geaunt,
&thorn;at hight Andromedes; and ane of his ribbes es xl. fote lang. Wha so arrvues at &thorn;e first hauen of Tyre or of
Surry, whilk I spakke off before, he may, if he will, ga by land to Ierusalem. And he sall ga to &thorn;e citee of Acon,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Acre, Akka, or Acco Ptolemais, 27 miles south of Tyre.</NOTE>
&thorn;at was sum tyme called Tholomayda, a day iournee fra Tyre. And it was a citee of Cristen men sum tyme, bot
now it es destruyd for &thorn;e maste party. And fra Venice til Acon es by see ii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> and iiij<HI REND="sup">xx</HI><SUPPLIED RESP="GW">2080</SUPPLIED> myle of Lumbardy;
and fra Calabre, or fra Cicil, til Acon es i<HI REND="sup">m</HI> and ccc. myle. And &thorn;e ile of Grece
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">i.e., Crete, as in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> es ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e mydde way. Beside
&thorn;e citee of Acon toward &thorn;e see, as it ware sex <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">score</SUPPLIED> furlangs &thorn;eine, on &thorn;e ri&yogh;t hand toward &thorn;e south es &thorn;e hill of
Carmele, whare Helyas &thorn;e prophete dwelled. And &thorn;are was &thorn;e order of frere Carmes first founded. &THORN;is hill es
no&yogh;t ri&yogh;t grete ne hie. At &thorn;e fote of &thorn;is hill was sum tyme a gude cytee of Cristen men, &thorn;at men called Cayphas,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Haifa, or Caiffa.</NOTE>
<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio">because &thorn;at Cayphas founded it; bot it es now all wasted. And at &thorn;e left syde of &thorn;e hill es a toune &thorn;at men calles
Saffre,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Sepphoris, Seff&ucirc;rieh.</NOTE> and it es sette apon ano&thorn;er hill. &THORN;are was sayn Jame and sayn John borne; and in &thorn;e place of &thorn;aire birthe
&thorn;er es a faire kirke standand. Also fra Acon til a hill &thorn;at men calles Scale de Tyre
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Scala Tyriorum, or R&acirc;s en N&acirc;k&ucirc;rah, north of Acre.</NOTE> es a c. furlangs.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.16.16" CORRESP="Cot.19.28">And be syde of Acon rynnes a litil riuer, &thorn;at men calles Belyon,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Belus, W&acirc;dy Abellin.</NOTE> and &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e fosse of Mynon, all
rounde, &thorn;e whilk es nere hand a c. cubites large; and it es all full of grauell. And if &thorn;er be neuer so mykil
taken on &thorn;e ta day, on the morue it es als full as euer it was; and &thorn;at es a grete meruaile. And &thorn;er es euermare
grete wynd in &thorn;at fosse, &thorn;at stirres all way &thorn;e grauell and makez it to buyle vp. And if a man putte &thorn;erin any
metell, it turnez alssone in to glasse. &THORN;is grauell es schynand, and men makes &thorn;eroff gude glasse and clere. &THORN;e
glasse &thorn;at es made of &thorn;is grauell, if it be putte agayne in to &thorn;e grauell, it turnes agayne in to grauell, as it was
first. And sum saise &thorn;at it es a swelgh of &thorn;e Grauelly See. Men commes fra ferre cuntreez with schippes by see
and with cartes by land to fecche of &thorn;at grauell.</SEG>

<PB N="17">
</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.17.1" CORRESP="Cot.20.5">Also fra Acon before said gase men three day iournez to &thorn;e citee of Palestyne, &thorn;at now es called Gaza, and
it es a full faire citee and full of ricches and of folk. Fra &thorn;is citee til a hill withoute bare Sampson &thorn;e forte &thorn;e
&yogh;ates of &thorn;e citee, &thorn;e whilk ware made of brasse. And in &thorn;at citee he sloghe &thorn;e kyng in his palays and many
o&thorn;er also aboute iij<HI REND="sup">m</HI>, and himselfe with &thorn;am. For &thorn;ai had taken him and putte oute bathe his eghen, and culled
<MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="folio">off his hare, and putte him in prisoun. And at &thorn;aire festes &thorn;ai broght him furth before &thorn;am and made dance
before &thorn;am and make iapes. So on a hie feste day, when he was wery for <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;at he</SUPPLIED> danced before &thorn;am, he bad
him &thorn;at ledd him &thorn;at he suld lede him to &thorn;e post &thorn;at bare vp all &thorn;e hous; and he tuke &thorn;e post in his armes and
schoke doune all &thorn;e hous apon &thorn;am, and so he sloghe himself and all &thorn;at ware &thorn;erin, as it telles in &thorn;e <TITLE>bible</TITLE> in
xvi. chapetre of <TITLE LANG="lat">Judicum</TITLE>. Fra &thorn;is citee
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> Acre. The proper order, from north to south, of the places mentioned is Acre, Castellum Peregrinorum (<HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> 'Athl&icirc;t), C&aelig;sarea, Jaffa, Ascalon, and Gaza.</NOTE> men may ga to &thorn;e citee of Gerare, and so to &thorn;e castell of Pilgrimes,
and so to Ascalon, and &thorn;an to Iaff, and so to Ierusalem.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.17.11" CORRESP="Cot.20.19">He &thorn;at will ga first to Babilone whare &thorn;e Sowdane dwelles to hafe leue for to passe mare surely thurgh &thorn;e
cuntreez and for to ga to &thorn;e mount Synay before he com to Ierusalem and &thorn;an turne agayne to Ierusalem, he
sall ga fra Gaza to &thorn;e castell of Ayre.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Daron, Darum.</NOTE> And &thorn;an a man passez oute of Surry and enters in til wildernes, whare
&thorn;e way es ri&yogh;t sandy. And &thorn;at wildernes lastes viii. day iournez. Neuer&thorn;eles men schall fynd all way by &thorn;e way
all &thorn;at &thorn;am nedes of vitailes. &THORN;is wildernes es called Acchelek. And, when a man commes oute of &thorn;is deserte,
he enters in til Egipte, whilk also es called Canopak; and in ano&thorn;er langage it es called Merfyne. And &thorn;e first
gude toune &thorn;at men fyndes es called Balbeor;
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Belbays.</NOTE> and it es at &thorn;e end of &thorn;e kyngdom of Halope. And fra &thorn;eine men
gase til Babilon and to &thorn;e citee of Caire.</SEG></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.6" N="6" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.6">
<PB N="18">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER VI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of manye names of Soudans; and of the Tour of Babiloyn.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.18.3" CORRESP="Cot.21.1">IN Babilon es a faire kirk of oure Lady, whare scho dwelled viii. &yogh;ere, when scho fledd oute of &thorn;e land of
Iudee for drede of Kyng Herode. And &thorn;are lies &thorn;e body of &thorn;e haly virgyn sayn Barbara, and &thorn;are
<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio">dwelled Ioseph, when his bre&thorn;er had salde him in til Egipte. And &thorn;are
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">A confusion between Babylon of Egypt, or Cairo, and Babylon of Chald&aelig;a.</NOTE> also gert kyng Nabugodonosor
putte &thorn;e three childer in &thorn;e fyre, for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai held &thorn;e ri&yogh;t beleue. And &thorn;ase childer hight Anany, Azary and
Mysael, as &thorn;e psalme saise of <TITLE LANG="lat">Benedicite</TITLE>. Bot Nabugodonosor called <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;am</SUPPLIED> o&thorn;er names, &thorn;at es at say Sydrak,
Mysak and Abdenago, whilk er &thorn;us mykil to say, Godd glorious, Godd victoriouse, Godd ouer all kyngdomes;
and &thorn;at by cause of &thorn;e myracle &thorn;at he sawe, when he sawe Goddes son ga with &thorn;ase childer vp and doune in &thorn;e
fire. At Babilon es comounly &thorn;e dwellyng of &thorn;e sowdan in a faire castell and a strang, sette apon a hie roche.
In &thorn;at castell er all way dwelland, for to kepe &thorn;e castell and to serue &thorn;e sowdan, ma &thorn;an viii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">vi<HI REND="sup">m</HI> persones, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>; circa sex milia personarum, Boldensele.</NOTE> &thorn;at takes all
&thorn;aire necessaries of &thorn;e courte of &thorn;e sowdan. &THORN;e maner of his courte schold I wele ynogh ken; for I dwelled a
lang tyme with &thorn;e sowdan and was sowdiour with him in his weres agayne &thorn;e Bedoynes. And he wald hafe
maried me richely with a grete prince doghter and giffen me many grete lordschepes, so &thorn;at I wald hafe
forsaken my byleue and turned to &thorn;aires; bot I wald no&yogh;t.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.18.16" CORRESP="Cot.21.24">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e sowdan es lord of fyue kyngdomes, whilk he has geten by conquest and
approperd vntil him. And &thorn;ir er &thorn;ai:&mdash; Egipte; and &thorn;e kyngdom of Ierusalem, of whilk Dauid and Salomon
ware kynges sum tyme; Surry, of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e citee of Damasc was cheeff; &thorn;e kyngdom of Halope in &thorn;e land of
Dameth; and &thorn;e kyngdom of Araby, of whilk ane of &thorn;e three kynges &thorn;at made offerand til oure Lord, when he
was borne, was kyng. And many o&thorn;er landes he haldes in his hand. And &yogh;it ouer &thorn;is he es called Caliphes, &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="folio">es a name of grete dignitee and of grete worschepe,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">he holdethe Calyffes, &thorn;at is a fulle gret thing in here langage, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and it es als mykill at say as kyng; for &thorn;e sowdan es of als
grete auctoritee amanges &thorn;aim as &thorn;e kyng es here amanges vs. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;are was sum tyme
fyue sowdanes, after &thorn;e noumer of &thorn;e fyue kyngdomes &thorn;at langes to &thorn;e sowdan &thorn;at es now. Bot now &thorn;er es bot
a sowdan, &thorn;e whilk es called &thorn;e sowdan of Babilon.</SEG></P>

<PB N="19">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.19.1" CORRESP="Cot.22.6">&THORN;e first sowdan of Egipte was called Yaracon, and he was Saladyne fader; &thorn;e whilk was sowdan after
Yaracon, &thorn;e same tyme &thorn;at kyng Richard was in &thorn;ase cuntrez with his oste of Cristen men. After Saladyn
regned his son Boradyn, and after him regned his neuew. Qwhen he was deed, &thorn;e comoun pople of Egipte tho&yogh;t
&thorn;am ouer mykill thralled and bun in awe, and sawe &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware strang by cause of &thorn;e multitude of &thorn;am, and went
and chose &thorn;am ane of &thorn;aim self for to be &thorn;aire sowdan; and he was called Melechsala. And in his tyme Lowice
&thorn;e kyng of Fraunce went in to &thorn;e Haly Land and faght with &thorn;e sowdan; and &thorn;are &thorn;e king was taken and putte
in prisoun. &THORN;is same sowdan afterward was slayne with his awen seruands and ano&thorn;er was chosen in his steed, &thorn;e
whilk was called Tympieman. And he raunsouned Kyng Lowice and deliuerd him oute of prisoun. Afterward
ane of &thorn;e comouns, &thorn;at hight Cothas, slew Tympieman and was made sowdan for him; and he gert call him
Melechomethos. Wham sone after ano&thorn;er of &thorn;e comouns, Bendochdaer by name, slewe and regned in his
steed; and he was called Melechdaer. In his tyme &thorn;e gude kyng Edward went in to Surry and didd grete
harme to &thorn;e Sarzenes. &THORN;is same sowdan was puysond at Damasc and died &thorn;are. And after him his son wald
<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio">hafe regned as next ayr, and gert call him Melechsayt. Bot sone &thorn;er come ano&thorn;er, &thorn;at hight Elphy, with mykill
folk and drafe Melechsayt oute of &thorn;e land and made him self sowdan. He tuke &thorn;e citee of Triple and slewe
many Cristen men &thorn;erin in &thorn;e &yogh;ere of oure Lord m<HI REND="sup">l</HI>cclxxix.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">mill cc. iiii. score and ix., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Afterwardes he, &thorn;is Elphy, was puysound thurgh
ano&thorn;er &thorn;at coueited to be sowdan; and he also was slayne sone afterward. And &thorn;an &thorn;ai chose til &thorn;aire sowdan
&thorn;e son of Elphi and called him Melechesserak. He tuke &thorn;e citee of Acoun and schotte oute of it all &thorn;e Cristen
men &thorn;at ware &thorn;erin. Afterward he died of puysoun, and his bro&thorn;er regned for him and was called Melechinasser.
Sone after ane &thorn;at hight Guytoga tuke &thorn;is sowdan and empresound him in &thorn;e castell of Mount Reall and regned
in his steed as sowdan; and he was called Melechadell. He &thorn;is, by cause he was ane aliene, &thorn;at es at say a
Tartarene, was putte oute of &thorn;e land; and ano&thorn;er, &thorn;at hight Bathyn, was made sowdan, and was called
Melechynanser. &THORN;e whilk on a day, as he playd with ano&thorn;er at &thorn;e chesse and his swerde standand drawen
besyde him, fell at debate with &thorn;e to&thorn;er, and the to&thorn;er hent his awen swerde and slew him &thorn;erwith. And
afterward &thorn;er was grete discorde amanges &thorn;am for the chesing of ano&thorn;er sowdan. At &thorn;e last &thorn;ai ascented all &thorn;at
&thorn;e forsaid Melechinasser, wham Guytoga had empresound before in &thorn;e castell of Mount Reall, schuld be &thorn;aire
sowdan. &THORN;is ilk Melechinasser regned a lang tyme and gouerned him wonder wysely, so &thorn;at, after &thorn;e decesse

<PB N="20">
of him, his eldest son was chosen sowdan, and he was called Melechinader. Qwham his bro&thorn;er gert sla priuely
<MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="folio">and regned in his steed, and gert call him Melechimandabron. And he &thorn;at was sowdan when I parted oute
of &thorn;at land.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.20.4" CORRESP="Cot.23.22">&THORN;e sowdan may lede oute of Egipte ma &thorn;an xx<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men of armes; and oute of &thorn;e rewme of Surry and of Turky,
and oute of o&thorn;er rewmes &thorn;at er vnder his subieccion he may bring ma &thorn;an l. thousand men of armes. And all
&thorn;ai take &thorn;aire wagez and all &thorn;at &thorn;aim nedes of &thorn;e sowdan, &thorn;at es to say ilk ane of &thorn;am takes &yogh;erely vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> florenes;
bot ilk ane of &thorn;am buse hald three horses and a camell. And &thorn;are er ordaynd amanges &thorn;am in diuerse citeez
and tounes certayne persouns, &thorn;e whilk er called admyralles; and ilk ane admyrall sall hafe at his ledyng
foure or fyue or sex men of armes, and sum ma. And ilke ane admyrall sall take als mykill by him self as all &thorn;a
&thorn;at er vnder him. And for &thorn;i, when &thorn;e sowdan lykes to avaunce any man of gude &thorn;at es with him, he makes
him ane admyrall. And if any derth com in &thorn;e cuntree, &thorn;an pure knyghtes and sodyours selles &thorn;aire hernays
for mischeeffe.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.20.13" CORRESP="Cot.24.2">&THORN;e sowdan has three wyfes, of &thorn;e whilke ane sall be a Cristen womman and &thorn;e o&thorn;er twa Sarezenes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">iiii. wyfes, on Cristene and iii. Sarazines, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And ane
of &thorn;ir wyfes sall dwell in Ierusalem, ano&thorn;er at Damasc, and &thorn;e thridd at Ascalon. And, ay when him list, he
gase to visit &thorn;am, and vmqwhyle ledes &thorn;am aboute with him. Noght for&thorn;i he has lemmanes, als many as him list
haue; for, when he comes till any citee or toune, he gers bring before him all &thorn;e nobilest and &thorn;e fairest
maydens of &thorn;e cuntree nere aboute, and he gers &thorn;am be keped honestly and wirschipfully. And, when he will
<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio">hafe any of &thorn;am, he gers &thorn;aim all be broght before him, and wha so es maste lykand till him, he sendes till hir
or takes &thorn;e ryng off his fynger and castez till hir. And &thorn;an sall scho be tane and waschen and bawmed and
wirschipfully cledd and after souper be broght till his chaumbre. And &thorn;us he duse ay when he will. Before
&thorn;e sowdan sall na straunger com &thorn;at he ne sall be cledd in clathe of gold or tars or in chamelet, a maner of
clething whilk &thorn;e Sarzenes vsez. And als sone as he has sight of &thorn;e sowdan, be it at wyndow or elleswhare, him
behoues knele doune and kisse &thorn;e erthe; for swilk es &thorn;e maner &thorn;are to do reuerence to &thorn;e sowdan, when any
man will speke with him. And, when any straungers commes till him in message oute of ferre landes, his men
sall stand aboute him with drawen swerdes in handes, and &thorn;er handes vp on loft, to stryke &thorn;am doune, if &thorn;ai
speke any thing &thorn;at displesez &thorn;e sowdan. &THORN;are sall na straunger com before him for to ask him any thing &thorn;at ne
his asked sall be graunted him, if it be resounable and no&yogh;t agayne &thorn;aire lawe. And ri&yogh;t so duse all o&thorn;er princez

<PB N="21">
and lordes in &thorn;at cuntree; for &thorn;ai say &thorn;at na man suld com before a prince &thorn;at he ne schuld passe gladder away
&thorn;an he come &thorn;iderward.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.21.3" CORRESP="Cot.24.37">And wit &yogh;e wele &thorn;at &thorn;is Babiloyne of whilk I speke now, whare &thorn;e sowdan es dwelland, es no&yogh;t &thorn;e grete
Babilon, whare &thorn;e confusioun of tunges was made, when &thorn;e toure of Babilon was in makyng; &thorn;e walles of &thorn;e
whilk ware lxiiii. furlanges hye, and it es in &thorn;e desertes of Araby, as men gase toward &thorn;e kyngdom of Caldee.
Bot it es lang sen any durst com nere &thorn;at wricched place; for it es waste and so full of dragouns and nedders
and o&thorn;er venymous bestes, &thorn;at &thorn;are dare na man com nere it. &THORN;e sercle of &thorn;e toure with &thorn;e compas of &thorn;e citee
<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at was &thorn;are sum tyme contenes xxv. myle aboute, as &thorn;ai say &thorn;are in &thorn;at cuntree. And if all it be called a
toure, &thorn;are ware sum tyme within it many faire edificaciouns, &thorn;e whilk er now destruyd and no&yogh;t bot wilderness.
And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at it was made foure square, and <CORR SIC="ilk ilka" RESP="GW">ilka</CORR>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and &thorn;at tour conteyned gret contree in circuyt, for the tour allone conteyned x. myle sqware, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> square contened sex myle and mare. &THORN;is ilke
toure made Nemprot, &thorn;at was kyng of &thorn;at land; and men saise &thorn;at he was &thorn;e first erthely kyng &thorn;at euer was.
He gert also make ane ymage in mynde of his fader, and comaundid all his subgetes to wirschippe &thorn;at ymage.
On &thorn;e same wyse did o&thorn;er grete lordes aboute; and on &thorn;is maner began ydolatry first. &THORN;at ilke citee of grete
Babilon was sette in a faire playne, &thorn;e whilk was called Sennaar felde, apon &thorn;e ryuer of Eufrates, &thorn;at ran thurgh
&thorn;e citee &thorn;at tyme. And &thorn;e walles of &thorn;e citee ware cc. cubites hie and l. cubites thikk. Bot efterward Syrus, &thorn;e
kyng of Perse, withdrew &thorn;e water and destruyd &thorn;e citee and all &thorn;e cuntree &thorn;are aboute. He departed &thorn;e grete
riuer of Eufrates, and gert it rynne in ccc. and xl. diuerse ways. For he had made his grete athe and sworne
so greuously &thorn;at he schuld bring it to swilke a state &thorn;at wymmen schuld mow wade ouer and no&yogh;t wete &thorn;aire
kneesse
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">myghte wel passe &thorn;ere withouten castynge of of hire clothes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and so he did. And &thorn;e cause was for in &thorn;at ryuer &thorn;er ware oft tymes many of his worthiest men
drouned.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.21.21" CORRESP="Cot.25.36">Fra &thorn;at Babilon &thorn;er &thorn;e Sowdan dwelles for to passe north este to &thorn;e grete Babilon er xl. day iourneez
thurgh deserte. And &thorn;at Babilon es no&yogh;t in &thorn;e subieccioun of &thorn;e Sowdan, bot within &thorn;e lordschippe of &thorn;e kyng
of Perse. And it es halden of &thorn;e grete Caan, &thorn;e whilk es a grete emperour, &yogh;a &thorn;e grettest of &thorn;e werld, for he es
<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio">lord of &thorn;e grete Ile of Cathay and of many o&thorn;er cuntreez, and of a grete party of Inde. His land marchez with
Prestre Iohn land; and he has so grete lordschippes &thorn;at he knawes nane end of &thorn;am. He es gretter and

<PB N="22">
myghtier &thorn;an &thorn;e Sowdan withouten comparisoun. Of his grete state and magestee I think to speke afterwardes,
when I com &thorn;erto.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.22.3" CORRESP="Cot.26.14">In &thorn;e grete desertes of Araby es &thorn;e citee of Meek,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Mecca.</NOTE> and &thorn;are ligges &thorn;e body of Machomete full wirschipfully
in a temple &thorn;at &thorn;e Sarezenes calles Musket.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Mosque.</NOTE> And &thorn;is citee es fra Babilon whare the Sowdan dwelles xxxii. day
iournees. And &yogh;e sall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e rewme of Araby es ri&yogh;t large; bot it hase &thorn;erin many desertes, &thorn;e whilk
may no&yogh;t wele be inhabit for defaute of water. For &thorn;a desertes er so drie and sandy &thorn;at &thorn;ar may na thing grow
in &thorn;am. Bot &thorn;are whare &thorn;e land es inhabit &thorn;er er ri&yogh;t mykill folk. Araby strechez fra &thorn;e end of Caldee to &thorn;e
last end of Affric, and it ioynes apon Ydumee toward Botron.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">El Buseirah, Bozra.</NOTE> &THORN;e cheeffe citee of Caldee es Baldak
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Baghdad.</NOTE>; and of
Affric &thorn;e cheeffe citee es Cartage, &thorn;e whilk Dydo founded, &thorn;at was &thorn;e wyf of Eneas, first kyng of Troy and seyne
of Italy. Mesopotamy also marchez apon &thorn;e desertes of Araby; and it es a grete cuntree, in &thorn;e whilk es &thorn;e
citee of Aran, whare Abraham &thorn;e patriarch dwelled sum tyme. Of &thorn;is citee was &thorn;e grete clerk Effrem and
Teophill, whilk oure Lady delyuerd oute of &thorn;e thraldom of &thorn;e fende, as men may fynd writen in &thorn;e buke of &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="folio">Miracles of oure Lady. Mesopotamy lastez fra &thorn;e ryuer of Eufrates to &thorn;e riuer of Tygre, for betwix &thorn;a twa
riuers ligges &thorn;at rewme. And be&yogh;ond Tygre es &thorn;e kyngdom of Caldee, &thorn;e whilk es a grete cuntree and a large.
In &thorn;at cuntree, as I said before, es &thorn;e citee of Baldak, in &thorn;e whilk Caliphes wont to dwell, &thorn;at was pope and
emperour of &thorn;at folk, &thorn;at es at say lord of temperaltee and of spiritualtee. And he was successour of Macomete
and of his kynredyn. &THORN;is citee of Baldak was sum tyme called Susis,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Susa. Its identification with Baghdad is, of course, an error.</NOTE> and Nabugodonosor founded it. &THORN;are
dwelled Danyel &thorn;e prophete, and sawe oft tymes many visiouns of Godd; and &thorn;are he interpretid &thorn;e kynges
dremes. Fra
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">A passage in the French text is omitted here; it is given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, beginning, "And in old tyme &thorn;ere were wont to be iii. Calyffeez, he of Arabye and he of Caldeez; and &thorn;ei dwelleden in the cytee of Baldak aboveseyd," and otherwise closely following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR>.</NOTE> Saladyn &thorn;e Sowdan hiderward hase &thorn;e Caliphes bene called Sowdanes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.22.20" CORRESP="Cot.27.25">Babilon &thorn;e lesse, whare &thorn;e Sowdan dwelles, and &thorn;e citee of Caire, &thorn;at es negh &thorn;erby, er bathe grete citeez
and faire. And &thorn;e tane of &thorn;am es sett apon &thorn;e tyuer Gyon, &thorn;at es also called Nilus, and it commes oute of
Paradys terrestre. &THORN;is ryuer ilka &yogh;ere, when &thorn;e sonne entres into &thorn;e signe of Cancre, begynnes for to flow, and so

<PB N="23">
it flowes continuelly als lang as &thorn;e sonne es in &thorn;at signe and in &thorn;e signe of Lyoun. It flowes so &thorn;at sum tyme it es
xx. cubites depe, and &thorn;an it ouerflowez all &thorn;e land and oft tyme duse mykill harme to placez pat ligges nere &thorn;e
ryuer. For &thorn;er may na man &thorn;at tyme labour aboute tillynge of land, and swa &thorn;er falles oft sithes grete derth of
corne in &thorn;at cuntree by cause of ouer mykill wete. And on &thorn;e same &thorn;er fallez grete derth, when &thorn;at ryuer rysez
no&yogh;t bot lytill, by cause of ouer mykil drught. And, when &thorn;e sonne entres &thorn;e signe of Virgyn, &thorn;an begynnes
<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio">Nilus to decreesse vntil &thorn;e sonne entre in to &thorn;e signe of Libre, and &thorn;an it haldez it within &thorn;e bankes. &THORN;is ryuer,
as I said before, commes oute of Paradys and rynnes thurgh &thorn;e desertes of Inde, and &thorn;an it synkkes doune into
&thorn;e erthe and rynnes so vnder &thorn;e erthe a grete cuntree and commes vp agayne vnder a mountayne &thorn;at hat Alloche,
&thorn;e whilk es betwix Inde and Ethiope, as it ware fyue moneth iournees fra &thorn;e entree of Ethiope. And &thorn;an it
rynnes all aboute Ethiope and Mauritane and so all &thorn;e lenth of Egipte to &thorn;e citee of Alexander; and &thorn;are it
entres in to &thorn;e see at &thorn;e end of Egipte. Aboute &thorn;is ryuer er grete plentee of fewles &thorn;at er called in Latyne
Ciconie or Ibices.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.7" N="7" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.7">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER VII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the contree of Egipt; of the brid Fenix of Arabye; of the cytee of Cayre; of the connynge to knowen bawne and to prouen it; and of the gerneres of Joseph.
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">This rubric, though found in <ABBR>C</ABBR>., is imitted in the edition of 1725 and in subsequent reprints, Ch. v. covering Ch. vi.-viii. as here printed</NOTE>]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.23.16" CORRESP="Cot.28.19">THE land of Egipte es lang, bot it es narowe; for men may no&yogh;t inhabit it on brede for desertes, whare
grete defaute es of water and &thorn;erfore it es inhabit on length endlang &thorn;e forsaid riuer. For &thorn;ai hafe na
moisture bot &thorn;at &thorn;e forsaid ryuer ministers; for it raynes no&yogh;t &thorn;are, bot &thorn;e land es ower flowed &thorn;erwith
certayne tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, as I said before. And for &thorn;are es na trubling of &thorn;e aer thurgh raynes, bot &thorn;e aer es
&thorn;are all way faire and clere withouten cloudes, &thorn;erfore &thorn;er was wont to be &thorn;e best astronomyers of &thorn;e werld. &THORN;e
forsaid citee of Cayre, in &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e Sowdan dwelles, es besyde &thorn;e citee of Babilon, as I talde before, no&yogh;t bot a
lytill fra &thorn;e forsaid riuer of Nilus toward &thorn;e desertes of Surry. Egipte es diuysed in twa parties; &thorn;e ta party es

<PB N="24">
betwix Nilus and Ethiope, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er betwix Nilus and Arabie. In Egipte es &thorn;e cuntree of Ramesses and
<MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e cuntree of Gesen, whare Iacob &thorn;e patriarc and his offspring dwelt. Egipte es ri&yogh;t a strang cuntree; and
many perlious
<NOTE RESP="GW">shrewede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> hauens er &thorn;erin, for &thorn;er lies in ilke a hauen many grete cragges of stane in &thorn;e entree of &thorn;am.
Egipte hase on &thorn;e este syde &thorn;e Reed See, &thorn;at rynnes vnto &thorn;e citee of Couston. And on &thorn;e west syde es &thorn;e land of
Liby, &thorn;e whilk by cause of ower mykill hete es barayne and beres na maner of fruyte. On &thorn;e south syde es
Ethiopie, and on &thorn;e north es &thorn;e grete desertes, &thorn;at lastez vnto Surry. And &thorn;us is Egipte strang on ilke a syde.
&THORN;e land of Egipte hase on lenth xv. day iournee&yogh; and on brede bot three, withouten desertes. Betwix Egipte and
&thorn;e land &thorn;at es called Numid er xii. day iourneez in desertes. &THORN;e folk &thorn;at wones in &thorn;at cuntree er called Numidianes,
and &thorn;ai are cristned. Bot &thorn;ai er blakk of colour;</SEG> and &thorn;at
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and &thorn;at &hellip; black withall; an interpolation, neither in the French texts nor in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;ai hald a grete bewtee, and ay &thorn;e blakker &thorn;ai er &thorn;e
fairer &thorn;am think &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at, and &thorn;ai schuld paynt ane aungell and a fende, &thorn;ai wald paynt &thorn;e aungell
black and &thorn;e fende qwhite. And, if &thorn;aim think &thorn;am no&yogh;t black ynough when &thorn;ai er borne, &thorn;ai vse certayne
medecynes for to make &thorn;am black withall. &THORN;at cuntree es wonder hate, and &thorn;at makes &thorn;e folk &thorn;eroff so black.</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.24.13" CORRESP="Cot.29.22">In Egipte er v. cuntreez, ane &thorn;at es called Sahit, ano&thorn;er Demeser, &thorn;e thridd Resich, and it es ane ile in &thorn;e
riuer of Nilus, &thorn;e ferthe es Alisaunder, &thorn;e fift es Damiete. &THORN;e citee of Damyete was sum tyme ri&yogh;t strang; bot
it was taken twys thurgh Cristen men, and &thorn;erfore afterwardes &thorn;e Sarezenes kest doune &thorn;e walles &thorn;eroff and of all
<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e castelles in &thorn;at cuntree. And &thorn;ai made ano&thorn;er citee apon &thorn;e see syde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">more fer from the see, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and called it New Damyete. At &thorn;is
cite of Damyete es ane of &thorn;e hauens of Egipte and ano&thorn;er at Alisaunder, &thorn;e whilk es a strang citee and a wele
walled. Bot &thorn;ai hafe na water bot &thorn;at commes in cundites fra &thorn;e riuer of Nilus. And &thorn;erfore, and men withdrew
water fra &thorn;am, &thorn;ai myght na while endure. In Egipte er bot fewe castelles for &thorn;e cuntree es strang ynogh
of &thorn;e self.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.24.21" CORRESP="Cot.30.1">In &thorn;e deserte of &thorn;e land of Egipte a haly hermite mette on a tyme a beste forschapen; for it had &thorn;e schappe
of a man fra &thorn;e nauel dunward
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">The words "dunward" and "vpward" should be transposed.</NOTE> and fra &thorn;eine vpward &thorn;e schappe of a gayte, with twa hornes standand on &thorn;e
heued. &THORN;e hermite asked him in Goddes name, what he was; and &thorn;e beste answerd and said, "I am a creature
dedly,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">So also in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>; meaning "mortal."</NOTE> as Godd hase made me, and in &thorn;is deserte I dwell and gase to gete my sustinaunce. Wharfore I pray
&thorn;ee, hermite, &thorn;at &thorn;ou will pray to Godd for me, &thorn;at he &thorn;at come fra hauen till erthe for &thorn;e saluacioun of mannes
saule, and was borne of a mayden, and sufferd hard passioun, thurgh wham we all liffe, stirres, and hase beyng,
&thorn;at he hafe mercy on me." &YOGH;it es &thorn;e heued of &thorn;at beste with &thorn;e hornes halden and keped at Alisaunder
for a miracle.</SEG></P>

<PB N="25">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.25.1" CORRESP="Cot.30.18">In Egipte also es a citee &thorn;at es called Eliople, &thorn;at es als mykill at say as &thorn;e citee of &thorn;e sonne. In &thorn;is citee
es a temple round in &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e temple of Ierusalem. &THORN;e preste of &thorn;e temple has writen in a buke &thorn;e date
of a fewle &thorn;at men calles Fenix; and &thorn;er es bot ane in all &thorn;e werld. And &thorn;is fewle liffes fyue hundreth &yogh;ere;
<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio">and at &thorn;e fyue hundreth &yogh;ere end he commes to &thorn;e forsaid temple and apon &thorn;e awter he brynnes him self all to
powder. And &thorn;e preste of &thorn;e temple, &thorn;at knawes by his buke &thorn;e tyme of his commyng, makes &thorn;e awter redy
and lays &thorn;erapon diuerse spiceries and sulphure viue, and stikkes of &thorn;e iunipre tree, and o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;at will sone
brynne. And &thorn;an the fewle commes, and lightes apon &thorn;e awter, and fannez with his wenges ay till &thorn;e forsaid
thinges be sett on fire; and &thorn;are he brynnes him self all till asches. On &thorn;e morue &thorn;ai fynd in &thorn;e asches as it ware
a worme; on &thorn;e secund day &thorn;at worme es turned till a fewle perfitely fourmed; and on &thorn;e thridd day it flies fra
&thorn;at place to &thorn;e place whare it was wont to dwell. And so &thorn;er es neuermare bot ane. &THORN;is ilke fewle betakens
oure Lord Ihesu Criste, in als mykill as &thorn;er es bot a Godd, &thorn;at rase on &thorn;e thridd day fra deed to lyfe. &THORN;is forsaid
fewle es oft tymes sene ayrand aboute, when
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">when &hellip; fewle of heuen, not in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e weder es faire and clere; and &thorn;ai say &thorn;are &thorn;at, when &thorn;ai see &thorn;at
fewle sore in &thorn;e aer, &thorn;ai sall afterward hafe gude &yogh;eres and miry, for &thorn;ai say it es a fewle of heuen. And &thorn;is
fewle es na mare &thorn;an ane egle of body. He has on his heued a creste as a pacok, bot it es mykill mare &thorn;an &thorn;e
creste of a pacok. His nekke es &yogh;alow, and his back es ynde colour; his wenges er reed, and his taile es barred
ouerthwert with grene and &yogh;alowe and reed. And in &thorn;e sonne he semes wonder faire, for &thorn;ir er &thorn;e colours &thorn;at er
fairest schewand.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.25.18" CORRESP="Cot.31.9">In Egipte er placez whare &thorn;e erthe beres fruyt viii. tymes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">vii. tymes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e &yogh;ere. And &thorn;are &thorn;ai fynd in &thorn;e erthe &thorn;e
fairest smaragdes &thorn;at er ower whare; and &thorn;at es &thorn;e cause &thorn;at &thorn;ai er so gude chepe &thorn;are, forby in o&thorn;er places.
<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio">Also, if it fall &thorn;at it rayne anes in &thorn;e sumer, &thorn;an all &thorn;e land of Egipte es full of mysz. At &thorn;e citee of Caire
&thorn;ai bring to &thorn;e markett men and wymmen &thorn;at er of o&thorn;er cuntrees borne and sellez &thorn;am comounly, as men duse
bestes in o&thorn;er cuntrees. Also &thorn;er es in &thorn;e citee of Caire a comoun hous ordaynd and made full of holes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">of smale furneys, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> as it
ware hen nestes; and &thorn;ider &thorn;e wymmen of &thorn;e cuntree bringes egges of hennes and geese and dukes, and layes
&thorn;am in &thorn;e nestes. And certayne persones er ordaynd to kepe &thorn;at ilke hous and to couer &thorn;aim with warme hors
dung; and thurgh &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e hors dung &thorn;e egges bringges furth briddes withouten sittyng of hen or any o&thorn;er
fewle. And at &thorn;e end of iii. or iiii. wekes &thorn;e wemmen commes &thorn;at bro&yogh;t &thorn;ider the egges, and beres away &thorn;e
briddes and bringes &thorn;am vp as &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e cuntree askes. And &thorn;us es all &thorn;e cuntree replenyscht with swilk
maner of fewles. And &thorn;us &thorn;ai do als wele in winter as in somer.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.25.29" CORRESP="Cot.31.25">In &thorn;at cuntree men selles in a certayn tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere lang appels, &thorn;e whilk men of &thorn;at cuntree callez
appelles of paradyse; and &thorn;ai er swete and deliciouse in &thorn;e mouthe. And, when men scheres &thorn;am in diuerse
partys, euermare in &thorn;e middes of &thorn;am es funden &thorn;e figure of &thorn;e crosse. Bot &thorn;ai will be roten within viii. dayes;
and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai may no&yogh;t be caried into ferre cuntrees. The treessez that beres &thorn;am hafez lefes of a fute brede

<PB N="26">
and a halfe; and comounly men may fynd a c. of &thorn;ase appells on a clustre.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">fynden the mountance of a hundred in a bascat to selle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;are er also o&thorn;er appels &thorn;at er
called Adam appels; and ilke ane of &thorn;am hase in &thorn;e ta syde a merk of teeth, ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ai ware biten with mannes
teethe. &THORN;er er also fige treezse &thorn;at beres neuer lefes; bot &thorn;ai bere fruyte on &thorn;e bare braunches. And &thorn;ai er
<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio">called Pharao fyges. A lytill fra &thorn;e citee of Caire es a felde whare in bawme growes apon smale brusches, as it
ware of a fote height
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">to a mannes breek girdill, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;ai er lyke vnto wylde wynes. In &thorn;is felde also er vii. welles, whare
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;at oure Lord Ihesu Crist made with on of his feet, whan he wente to pleyen, <HI REND="i">etc</HI>., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Criste in his
&yogh;outhede was wont for to play him with o&thorn;er childer; and &thorn;are he schewed diuerse meruailes. &THORN;is felde es no&yogh;t
so wele closed &thorn;at ne men may go in &thorn;at will, oute taken &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e bawme growes; and &thorn;an &thorn;at felde es
keped ri&yogh;t straytely. For it growes newer whare bot &thorn;are, now&thorn;er in &thorn;at cuntree ne elleswhare. For, if all men
take plantes or slyfynges &thorn;eroff and sett &thorn;am in o&thorn;er placez, &thorn;ai may wele growe, bot &thorn;ai sall neuer bere fruyte.
The lefes of &thorn;e bawme smellis no&yogh;t so wele as &thorn;e bawme self duse.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and the leves of bawme ne fallen noughte, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;ai cutte away &thorn;e deed braunches with
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">with a scharp flyntston [caillou aigu] or with a scharp bon, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
ane instrument made &thorn;erfore, bot no&yogh;t of yrne; and &thorn;at instrument es called gaylounagon. If &thorn;at instrument ware
of yrne, it wald corrumppe &thorn;e vertu and &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e treezse, as it has oft bene proued by experience. Men
of &thorn;at cuntree, what tyme &thorn;at felde sall be tilled, getes &thorn;am Cristen men for to tille it and to geder it; and elles
&thorn;a treesz schold bere na fruyte, as &thorn;e Sarzenes saise &thorn;aim self and oft tymes has bene assayd. &THORN;e Sarzenes calles
&thorn;e treessz &thorn;at beres &thorn;e bawme Enochbalse; and &thorn;e fruyt, &thorn;at es lyke vntill hostez, &thorn;ai call Abebissam. Bot &thorn;e
liquour &thorn;at distilles oute of &thorn;e braunches calle &thorn;ai Oxbalse, &thorn;at es at say opobalsamum. Sum men saise &thorn;at &thorn;er
growes bawme in Inde &thorn;e mare, in &thorn;e deserte &thorn;er &thorn;e treessz of &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e mone spak till grete Alexaunder.
<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="folio">Bot &thorn;at place hafe I no&yogh;t sene by cause of &thorn;e perlious wayse &thorn;ertill, and &thorn;erfore I can tell na so&thorn;e &thorn;eroff. And
&yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at men may lightly be begyled in &thorn;e bying of bawme, bot if &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;e better connyng &thorn;erin.
For sum selles a maner of gumme, &thorn;at es called Turpentyne, and puttes &thorn;erto a lytill bawme for to make it smell
wele. Sum also puttes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">putten wax [cuire, cire] in oyle of the wode of the fruyt, <HI REND="i">etc</HI>., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;erto oile of &thorn;e tree or of &thorn;e beries of bawme and saise it es gude bawme. Sum distilles
gariofles, spikenarde and o&thorn;er spiceries &thorn;at er wele smelland, and &thorn;e licour &thorn;at es distilled of &thorn;am &thorn;ai sell in steed
of bawme; and on &thorn;is wyse er many men dessayued, bathe lordes and o&thorn;er smaler men. For &thorn;e Sarezenes makes
swilke sophisticaciouns for to dessayfe Cristen men withall, as I hafe oft tymes witen by experience. Marchandes
also and apothecaries puttes &thorn;erto o&thorn;er sophisticaciouns afterward, and &thorn;an es it of lesse valu. Bot, if &yogh;ow list, I
sall schew &yogh;ow how &yogh;e may proue and assay whilk es trewe bawme, and no&yogh;t be dessaued. &YOGH;e schall vnderstand
&thorn;at balme &thorn;at es kyndely and gude es ri&yogh;t clere and &yogh;alow and hase a strang reflaire and a gude. And, if it be
thikk, reed or blak, &thorn;an es it sophisticate. Also take a litill bawme and lay it on &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;i hand and hald it

<PB N="27">
in &thorn;e sonne; and, if &thorn;ou may no&yogh;t endure it na while for hete, it es gude bawme. Take also a litill bawme on &thorn;e
poynt of &thorn;i knyffe and touche &thorn;e fire &thorn;erwith; and, if it brynne, it es a gude taken. &YOGH;it take a drope of bawme
and putte it in a dische or a coppe, and putte &thorn;erto gayte mylke; and, if &thorn;e balme be gude, alsone &thorn;e mylke sall
<MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="folio">leper.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">anon it wole take and beclippe the mylk, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Putte also a drope &thorn;eroff in clere water in a pece or in a clene bacyn and stirre &thorn;e water and &thorn;e bawme
togyder; and, <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">if</SUPPLIED> &thorn;e water be clere after &thorn;e stirring, &thorn;e bawme es gude, and, if it be thikk and drubly, it es
sophisticate. &THORN;e gude
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">This sentence translated literally in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> bawme also es mykill stranger &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;at es sophisticate.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.27.7" CORRESP="Cot.33.34">Now hafe I schortly talde &yogh;ow sum what of bawme; and now will I tell &yogh;ow of Joseph bernes, &thorn;at er &yogh;it in
Egipte be&yogh;ond &thorn;e water of Nilus toward &thorn;e deserte &thorn;at es betwene Egipte and Affric. &THORN;ir er &thorn;e bernes of
Joseph &thorn;at ware made for to kepe corne in for &thorn;e seuen barayne &yogh;eres &thorn;at ware betakned by &thorn;e seuen deed qwhete
eres, whilk kyng Pharao sawe in swefnyng, as &thorn;e first buke of <TITLE>Bible</TITLE> telles. And &thorn;ai er made wonder craftily of
clene hewen stane. Twa of &thorn;am er wonder hie and wyde also, and &thorn;e remanand er no&yogh;t so hie. Ilk ane of &thorn;am
hase a porche at &thorn;e entree. &THORN;ir ilke bernes er now full of nedders; and men may &yogh;it see writen on pam
withouten many scripturs of diuerse langagez. Sum men saise &thorn;at &thorn;ai er graues of sum grete men in alde tyme;
bot &thorn;e comoun voice es &thorn;are &thorn;at &thorn;ai er &thorn;e bernes of Joseph, and &thorn;at find &thorn;ai in &thorn;aire cronicles. And sothely it es
no&yogh;t likly &thorn;at &thorn;ai schold be graues, in als mykill as &thorn;ai er voyd within and hase porches before &thorn;am and &yogh;ates.
And also graues schold no&yogh;t by resoun be so hie.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.27.17" CORRESP="Cot.34.21">In Egipte er diuerse langagez and diuerse letters and of o&thorn;er schappe &thorn;an er in oper placez; and &thorn;erfore will
I here sette bathe &thorn;e letters and &thorn;aire soune and &thorn;aire names, &thorn;at &yogh;e may knawe &thorn;e difference betwix &thorn;a letters
<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio">and letters of o&thorn;er langagez:</SEG>&mdash;a, Athomanus; b, Binchi; e, Chinok; d, Dynam; e, Em; f, Fiu; g, Gomor;
h, Heket; i, Janiu; k, Karacta; l, Liuzamiu; in, Miche; n, Narme; o, Oldach; p, Pilon; q, Qyny; r, Rou;
s, Sicheu; t, Thela; v, Vr; x, Xyron; y, Ypha; z, Zarum; thi, Thou.</P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.8" N="8" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.8 Cot.Ch.9">
<PB N="28">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER VIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the yle of Cecyle; of the weye fro Babyloyne to the Mownt Synay; of the chirche of Seynte Kateryne; and of alle the meruaylles there.
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">This rubric in <ABBR>C</ABBR>. is omitted in the printed editions.</NOTE>]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.28.3" CORRESP="Cot.34.26">AR I passe any for&thorn;er, I will turne agayne and tell o&thorn;er ways &thorn;at men may wende til Babilon whare &thorn;e
sowdan dwelles, &thorn;e whilk es at &thorn;e entree of Egipte. For many pilgrymes wendes first &thorn;ider and seyne
to &thorn;e mount Synai, and so turnes to Ierusalem agayn, as I said before. For first &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire
ferrest pilgrimage and &thorn;an commes agayneward by haly placez &thorn;at er nerre, if all &thorn;ai be not
<NOTE RESP="GW">"not" an insertion, the sentence originally running "if all &thorn;ai be of mare dignitee."</NOTE> of dignitee as
Ierusalem es, to &thorn;e whilk na pilgrimage may be lyke. Bot, for to make all &thorn;aire iournees maste suerly and with
leste labour, sum men gas first to &thorn;e ferrer placez and seyne to &thorn;e placez &thorn;at er on &thorn;is syde. Now he &thorn;at will go
first to Babilon by ano&thorn;er way mare compendious &thorn;an I hafe tald off before fra &thorn;is cuntree or fra o&thorn;er &thorn;at er
nere, he may go thurgh Fraunce and thurgh Burgoyne. And it nedes no&yogh;t to tell all &thorn;e names of &thorn;e citeez and
tounes by &thorn;e whilk men most go, for &thorn;e way es comoun and wele ynogh knawen with all men &thorn;at vsez trauaile.
Bot &thorn;er er many hauens for to schippe at; for sum schippes at &thorn;e cite of Geen, sum at Venice and sailez thurgh
&thorn;e see Adrias, &thorn;at es cald &thorn;e Gulff of Venice and partes Italy and Grece on &thorn;at syde, and sum wendez to Naples,
<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio">sum to Rome and swa til Brunduse
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Brundusium, Brindisi.</NOTE> and schippes &thorn;are, or elles in sum o&thorn;er placez whare &thorn;ai fynd hauens and
redy schipping. Also sum wendez thurgh Tuscayne and Campayne and Calabre and Apuyle and &thorn;e Iles of Ytaly
by Choos,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Corsica.</NOTE> Sardine and Cicile, &thorn;e whilk es a faire ile and a grete. In &thorn;at ile es a gardyne with diuerse maners
of fruytes; and &thorn;at gardyne es all way grene and full of floures, bathe wynter and sumer. &THORN;is ile es cccl. leeges
aboute; and betwix Cicile and Italy es bot a litill arme of &thorn;e see, &thorn;e whilk es called Fare.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">The Faro; the Farde of Mescyne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is ile of Cicile es
betwene &thorn;e see Adriac and &thorn;e see of Lumbardie. Oute of Cicile into Calabre er viii. myles of Lumbardy. In
Cicile es a maner of nedder, with whilk men of &thorn;at land vsez to proue &thorn;aire childer, wheder &thorn;ai be geten in leel
spousage or noght. For, if &thorn;ai be geten in leel spousage, &thorn;e nedder will go aboute &thorn;am and do &thorn;am na harme

<PB N="29">
and, if &thorn;ai be geten in advoutry, &thorn;e nedders will stang pam and venym &thorn;am. And on &thorn;is wise men of &thorn;at cuntree
&thorn;at hase euill suspecioun to &thorn;aire wyfes prouez &thorn;aire childer, wheder &thorn;ai be &thorn;airs or no&yogh;t. In &thorn;is ile also es &thorn;e
mount of Ethna, &thorn;e whilk by ano&thorn;er name es called Gebel. &THORN;are er swelghes in &thorn;e erthe allway brynnand, and
namely in seuen places, oute of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;er commes flawme of fire of diuerse colours. And by &thorn;e chaungeyng of
the coloures men of &thorn;at cuntree knawes and coniectures wheder it schal be derthe of corne or gude chepe,
<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="folio">wheder &thorn;e weder sall he calde or hate, rayne or faire weder; and many o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;ai pronostic and diuines by
&thorn;e colour of &thorn;a flawmes. Fra Italy to &thorn;a swelghes er no&yogh;t bot xxv. myle; and &thorn;ai say &thorn;are &thorn;at &thorn;ai er
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">ben weyes of helle (<HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> "chemins" for "cheminees"), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e entreez
and &thorn;e &yogh;ates of hell.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.29.9" CORRESP="Cot.36.13">He &thorn;at wendes by &thorn;e citee of Pisane, as sum men duse, whare &thorn;er es ane arme of &thorn;e see and twa hauens, and
enters &thorn;e see &thorn;are, he schall wende by &thorn;e ile of Greff, &thorn;e whilk pertenes to &thorn;e Ianuenes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Greef, &thorn;at is at Gene, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. Corfu seems to be meant.</NOTE> And seyne he aryfes in
Grece at citee of Mirrok, or at &thorn;e citee of Valon, or at Duraz, &thorn;at es &thorn;e Dukes of Duraz, or at sum o&thorn;er hauens &thorn;at
er on &thorn;a costes of &thorn;e see, and swa to Constantinople, and &thorn;an by see to &thorn;e iles of Grece, and to &thorn;e iles of Rodes and
of Cipre. And so, for til hald &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way by see, fra Venice to Constantinople er i<HI REND="sup">m</HI>viii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> and iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> miles of Lumbardy.
Fra &thorn;e rewme of Cypre men may passe by see to &thorn;e porte Iaffe and so, lefyng all &thorn;at cuntree on &thorn;e left hand, till
&thorn;e burgh of Alisaunder, &thorn;at standes apon &thorn;e see syde. In &thorn;at citee was Sayne Kateryne heued striken off; and
in &thorn;at citee was Sayne Marc martird and grauen. Bot afterward &thorn;e emperour Leo gert his banes be broght and
caried till Venice, and &thorn;are ligg &thorn;ai &yogh;it. And &yogh;it es &thorn;are at Alisaunder a faire kirk all ouer whyte blaunched; and
swa er all &thorn;e kirkes of Cristen men &thorn;are, for &thorn;e paynymes and &thorn;e Sarzenes gert blaunche &thorn;am on &thorn;at wyse to
fordo &thorn;e paynture and &thorn;e ymages &thorn;at ware purtraid on &thorn;e walles. &THORN;is citee of Alisaunder has in lenth
<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio">30 furlanges and x. on brede; and it es ri&yogh;t a faire citee and a noble. At &thorn;is citee the ryuer of Nilus enters in
to &thorn;e see, as I talde before. And in &thorn;at ryuer er oft tymes funden many precious stanes, and of &thorn;e tree &thorn;at men
callez Aloes, &thorn;e whilk commes oute of Paradys. A medicinal thing it es for many euils, and it es salde wonder
dere. Fra Alisaunder men wendez til Babilon whare &thorn;e sowdan dwelles; and it standes apon &thorn;e ryuer of Nile.
&THORN;is es &thorn;e lightest way &thorn;at men may wende to Babilon and &thorn;e schortest.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.29.25" CORRESP="Cot.37.13">Now
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Preceded in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (f.26) by a rubric, as follows: "Of the weye that goth from Babiloyne vnto the mownt Synay and of the merueyles &thorn;ere." The matter, however, is covered by the rubric of chp. viii.</NOTE> will I tell what way men schall hald fra Babilon to &thorn;e mount Synai, whare &thorn;e body of Sayn Kateryne
lyes. Men behoues passe thurgh &thorn;e desertes of Araby, whare Moyses and Aaron ledd &thorn;e folk of Israel. And
in &thorn;at way &thorn;er es a well, to &thorn;e whilk Moyses ledd &thorn;am and gafe &thorn;am a drynk off, when &thorn;ai made murmuracion

<PB N="30">
agaynes him by cause of thrist. For&thorn;ermare on &thorn;e way es ano&thorn;er well, &thorn;at es called Marrac, whare &thorn;ai fand
bitter water, when &thorn;ai schold hafe drunken; and Moyses putt &thorn;erin a maner of tree, and alssone &thorn;e bitternes
was away. Fra &thorn;eine men schall passe thurgh &thorn;is deserte to &thorn;e vale of Elym, whare er xii. welles and lxii.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">lxxii., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
palme treesse berand dates, whare Moyses made &thorn;e childer for to loge. Fra &thorn;is vale vnto &thorn;e mount Synai es
bot a day iournee.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.30.6" CORRESP="Cot.37.27">Qwha so will go ano&thorn;er way fra Babilon to &thorn;e mount Synai, him behoues passe by &thorn;e Reed See, whilk es
ane arme of &thorn;e west see,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">the see occean, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whare thurgh &thorn;e childer of Israel went drye fote, when kyng Pharao persued &thorn;am,
<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="folio">and <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">in</SUPPLIED> &thorn;e whilk he and all his oste ware drouned. And it es &thorn;er anentes vi. myle brade. &THORN;e water of &thorn;at see
es na redder &thorn;an o&thorn;er water es of &thorn;e see ellesqwhare; bot, for &thorn;er es mykill reed grauell be &thorn;e coste of &thorn;e see,
&thorn;erfore men callez it &thorn;e Reed See. And it rynnes in to the marchez of Araby and Palestyne. By &thorn;is see may men
passe mare &thorn;an foure day iourneez, and &thorn;an &thorn;ai schall com to &thorn;e forsaid desertes and to &thorn;e forsaid vale of Elym
and so to &thorn;e mount Synai. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at thurgh &thorn;a desertes may na man passe with horsez, for
&thorn;er er no stablez ne esement for horsez of mete ne of drynk. And &thorn;erfor men makes &thorn;at pilgrimage with
camellez; for &thorn;ai may aywhare fynd bowghes of treessez in &thorn;e way &thorn;at &thorn;ai may ete, for &thorn;at fude lufe &thorn;ai wele,
and &thorn;ai may forbere drink twa dayes or three, and so may noght horsez do. Fra Babilon vnto &thorn;e mount Synai
er xii. day iournez. Neuer&thorn;eles sum hastez &thorn;am so fast in &thorn;aire iournee &thorn;at &thorn;ai wende it in less tyme.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">And sum men maken hem more, and sum men hasten hem and peynen hem and &thorn;erefore &thorn;ei maken hem lesse, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And
in &thorn;is iournee &thorn;am behoues hafe with &thorn;am sum men &thorn;at can speke Latyne
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">latymeres (<HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> interpreters), to go with hem in the contrees and ferthere be&yogh;onde, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> ay till &thorn;ai cun &thorn;e langage of &thorn;e
cuntree; and so behoues &thorn;am hafe in o&thorn;er cuntreez toward &thorn;ase partys. &THORN;am behoues also trusse &thorn;aire vitailes
with &thorn;am thurgh &thorn;e forsaid desertes, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may liffe with.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.30.20" CORRESP="Cot.38.22">&THORN;e mount Synai es called &thorn;e deserte of Syn, &thorn;at es als mykill at say as Brynnand Busk; for &thorn;are sawe Moyses
oure Lord Godd spekand till him in a busk brynnand. At &thorn;e fote of &thorn;e mount Synai es founded ane abbay of
mounkes, wele enclosed with hie walles and yrne &yogh;ates for drede of crowell wilde bestes and fell &thorn;at wonnes in
&thorn;a desertes. &THORN;e mounkes &thorn;at wonnes &thorn;erin er Arabites and Grekez, and &thorn;ai er cledd lyke hermytes; and &thorn;er es
<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio">a grete couent of &thorn;am. &THORN;ai liffe with dates and rutes and herbes; &thorn;ai drink na wyne comounly, bot on hegh feste
days. &THORN;ai er deuote men and ledez pure lyf, and liffez in grete abstinence and in grete penaunce. &THORN;are es &thorn;e
kirk of Sayne Kateryne with many lawmpes brynnand. Oile of oliue vse &thorn;ai als wele for metes as for lawmpes

<PB N="31">
brynnyng. &THORN;at oile commes to &thorn;am as by miracle. For &thorn;er commes rukes and crakes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">the ravenes and the crowes and the choughes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and o&thorn;er fewles flyand
ilk &yogh;ere aboute &thorn;at place in grete multitude togyder, als &thorn;ai suld make pilgrimage in &thorn;aire maner; and ilk ane of
&thorn;am bringes in &thorn;aire nebbe in steed of offerand a braunche of olyue
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">a braunche of the bayes or of olyue, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and lefez &thorn;am &thorn;are, and on &thorn;at wise &thorn;er es
grete plentee of olyuez left to &thorn;e sustynance of &thorn;e hous. Now, sen it es so &thorn;at fewles, &thorn;at na resoun can, duse
swilk reuerence to &thorn;at glorious virgine, wele aght vs Cristen men to visit &thorn;at haly place with grete deuocioun.
Behind &thorn;e hie awter of &thorn;at kirke es &thorn;e place whare Moyses sawe oure Lord in &thorn;e brynnand busk. And, when &thorn;e
mounkes commez to &thorn;at place, &thorn;ai putte off &thorn;aire hose and &thorn;aire schone by cause Godd said to Moyses, "Do off &thorn;i
schone of &thorn;i fete, for &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;ou standes es haly erthe." &THORN;at place es called &thorn;e schadow of Godd. And
by syde &thorn;e hie awter er iiii. greez to gang vp at to &thorn;e toumbe of alabastre whare in &thorn;e body of &thorn;e haly virgyne
Sayne Kateryne lyes. &THORN;e prelate of &thorn;e mounkes schewes &thorn;e relyques of &thorn;is virgyn vnto pilgrymmes; and with
ane instrument of siluer he stirrez &thorn;e banes of &thorn;e virgyne apon ane auter. And &thorn;an commez oute a litill oile, as
<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="folio">it ware swete; bot it es lyke now&thorn;er oile ne bawme, for it es mare blakk. Of &thorn;is liquour &thorn;ai giffe a lytill
quantitee til pilgrimes; for it es bot lytill &thorn;at commes oute. After &thorn;at &thorn;ai schew &thorn;e heued of Sayne Kateryne,
and &thorn;e clathe &thorn;at it was wonden in, when &thorn;e aungelles broght &thorn;e body vp to &thorn;e mount of Synai. And &thorn;are &thorn;ai
groue it with &thorn;at ilke clathe; and &yogh;it es it bludy, and euermare sall be. And &thorn;ai schew also &thorn;e busk &thorn;at Moyses
sawe brynnand, when oure Lord spakk vntil him. &THORN;ai schew also many o&thorn;er relyques. Ilk a mounke of &thorn;e hous
has euermare a lawmpe brynnand; and, as it was talde me, when ane abbot dyes, his laumpe gase oute. And in
chesyng of ano&thorn;er abbot his laumpe lightes by it self whilk by &thorn;e grace of Godd es maste worthy to be next
Abbot. Ilk ane of &thorn;am hase his laumpe, as I said before; and &thorn;ai wate by &thorn;e laumpe when any of &thorn;am sall sone
dye, for agayne &thorn;at tyme will &thorn;e laumpe of him &thorn;at sall dye giffe litill light. It was talde me also &thorn;at, when a
prelate es deed and schall be grauen, he &thorn;at singes &thorn;e hie messe schall fynd in a scrowe before him on &thorn;e awter
&thorn;e name of him &thorn;at sall be chosen to be &thorn;aire prelate; and I asked &thorn;e mounkes if it ware so. Bot &thorn;ai wald
no&yogh;t tell me, bot said sum tyme it fell swa; and &yogh;it &thorn;ai wald no&yogh;t say so mykill, before I said &thorn;am &thorn;at it fell
no&yogh;t to &thorn;am to hald counsaile ne to layne Goddes myracle and his grace, bot for to publisch it and schew it in
apperte to excit men til deuocioun. And I said &thorn;am ower &thorn;at &thorn;ai did grete synne for to layne it, as me tho&yogh;t, for
&thorn;e miracles &thorn;at Godd schewes er witness of his grete myght, as David saise in &thorn;e <TITLE>sawter</TITLE>. When I had said
<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;am swilk wordes, &thorn;an at &thorn;e first talde &thorn;ai me &thorn;e wordes whilk I talde &yogh;ow before; and mare wald &thorn;ai no&yogh;t
graunt me of questiouns &thorn;at I asked &thorn;am. In &thorn;at abbay commes neuer fleess, ne flyes, ne nan o&thorn;er swilk vermyn
of corrupcioun, thurgh myracle of Godd and of his moder Saynt Mary and of &thorn;e haly virgyn Sayne Kateryne.

<PB N="32">
For sum tyme &thorn;er was so grete multitude of swilke vnclene vermyn &thorn;at &thorn;e mounkes of &thorn;at abbay ware so
tourmentid with &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;ai left &thorn;e place and went away fleand &thorn;eine by cause of &thorn;am vp in to &thorn;e mountes.
And ri&yogh;t so come &thorn;e blissed Virgyn and mett &thorn;am and badd &thorn;am turne agayne to &thorn;aire abbay, and &thorn;ai schuld
neuer hafe swilke greuaunce ne disese of &thorn;am mare. And &thorn;ai did as scho bad &thorn;am and turned agayne, and neuer
after &thorn;at day sawe &thorn;ai in &thorn;at abbay flee ne flye, ne na maner of swilk corrupcioun to greue &thorn;am. Before &thorn;e &yogh;ate
of &thorn;at abbay es &thorn;e well whare Moyses strake on &thorn;e stane with his &yogh;erde, and it ran of water and sall do
euermare.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.32.8" CORRESP="Cot.40.32">Fra &thorn;is abbay men gas vp on many grecez to &thorn;e mount of Moyses; and &thorn;er es a kirk of oure Lady, whare
scho mett &thorn;e mounkes, as I talde before.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">A passage in the French text, "Et pluis haut &hellip; staphis," is omitted here. It is translated literally in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And vppermare in to &thorn;e mount es Moyses chapell, and &thorn;e roche &thorn;at
he fledd in to when he sawe oure Lord. In &thorn;e whilk roche es &thorn;e prynte and &thorn;e fourme of his body; for so fast
he thrast his body &thorn;erto fleand &thorn;at &thorn;orow &thorn;e myracle of Godd &thorn;e fourme of his body <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">was</SUPPLIED> left &thorn;erin.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at all his body was dolven withinne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And
&thorn;are fast by es &thorn;e place whare oure Lord gafe Moyses &thorn;e ten comaundementz of &thorn;e lawe writen in twa tables of
stane with Goddez awen handes. And vnder a roche &thorn;are es a caue, whare Moyses dwelled when he fasted xl.
<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio">days and xl. nyghtes. Bot he dyed in &thorn;e haly land, and na man wate whare he was grauen. Fra &thorn;is mount
men gase ower a grete valay till ano&thorn;er grete mount, whare &thorn;e aungels groue &thorn;e body of Sayne Kateryne. In
&thorn;at valay es a kirk of xl. martirs, whare &thorn;e mounkes of &thorn;e forsaid abbay synges oft tyme; and &thorn;at valay es ri&yogh;t
calde. And &thorn;an men gase vp on &thorn;e mount of Sayn Kateryne; and it es mykill hyer &thorn;an &thorn;e mount Moyses. And
&thorn;are whare Sayne Kateryne was grauen es na kirk, ne na chapell, ne o&thorn;er dwellyng place; bot &thorn;er es a hepe of
stanes gaderd sammen on &thorn;e place &thorn;er scho was grauen. &THORN;are was sum tyme a chapell, bot now it es all doune,
and &yogh;it lies &thorn;e stanes &thorn;are. And, if all it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e colett of Sayne Kateryne say &thorn;at it es all a
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc</HI>. one.</NOTE> place whare
oure Lorde gaffe &thorn;e lawe vnto Moyses and &thorn;ar Sayn Kateryne was grauen, &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at it es all in a
cuntree, or elles in twa steedes &thorn;at beres bathe a name. For &thorn;ai er bathe called Mount Synai, bot it es a grete
way betwene &thorn;am, and a grete valay and a depe.</SEG></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.9" N="9" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.10">
<PB N="33">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER IX</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the desert betwene the chirche of Seynte Kateryne and Jerusalem; of the drie tre; and how roses cam first in the world.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.33.4" CORRESP="Cot.42.1">QWHEN men has visit &thorn;is haly place of Sayn Katerynes and will turne to Ierusalem, first &thorn;ai take lefe at
&thorn;e mounkes and recomaundes &thorn;am specially to &thorn;er praiers. And &thorn;ase mounkes giffez with gude will
vitailles to pilgrimes to passe with thurgh &thorn;e desertes toward Surry. And &thorn;at lastez nere xiii. day
iournez or xiiii. In &thorn;a desertes dwellez mykill pople &thorn;at men callez Arabienes, Bedoynes and Ascopardes. &THORN;ai
er folk of full euill condiciouns, and full of all maner of wickedness and malice. Housez hafe &thorn;ai nane bot
<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio">tentes, whilk &thorn;ai make of skynnes of camelles and o&thorn;er wylde bestes &thorn;at &thorn;ai ete, and drinkez water when &thorn;ai may
any get. And &thorn;ai dwell in placez whare &thorn;ai may hafe water, as on &thorn;e Reed See and o&thorn;er placez whare &thorn;ai find
any water. And oft tymes it falles &thorn;at, whare men fyndez water a tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, ano&thorn;er tyme &thorn;er es nane
funden; and &thorn;erfore make &thorn;ai na house in a certayne place, bot now here now &thorn;are, as &thorn;ai may fynd water. &THORN;is
folk, &thorn;at I speke off, trauailez no&yogh;t aboute tillyng of land, for &thorn;ai ete na breed comounly, bot if it be any &thorn;at
dwellez nere sum gude towne, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may ga to for to gete &thorn;am breed. &THORN;ai roste all &thorn;aire flesch, and &thorn;e fisch
&thorn;at &thorn;ai ete, apon stane thurgh &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e sonne. And no&yogh;t forthy &thorn;ai er strang men and wele feightand; and
grete multitude &thorn;er es of &thorn;am. &THORN;ai do no&yogh;t elles bot chacez wilde bestes, to take &thorn;am for &thorn;aire sustynaunce.
And &thorn;ai sett no&yogh;t by &thorn;aire lyfes; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai drede no&yogh;t &thorn;e sowdan ne nan o&thorn;er prince of all &thorn;e werld, &thorn;at ne
&thorn;ai will feight with &thorn;am, and &thorn;ai do &thorn;am any greuaunce. &THORN;ai hafe oft tymes foghten with &thorn;e sowdan, and namely
&thorn;at same tyme &thorn;at I dwelled with him. Armour hafe &thorn;ai nane to defend &thorn;am with, bot anely a schelde and a
spere. &THORN;ai wynd &thorn;aire heuedes and &thorn;aire nekkes in a whyte lynnen clathe. &THORN;ai er ri&yogh;t foule folk and crowell
and of euill kynde.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.33.22" CORRESP="Cot.43.2">After &thorn;at men be passed &thorn;is deserte command toward Ierusalem, &thorn;ai com til a citee whilk es called
Bersabee, &thorn;at was sum tyme a faire citee and a gude and inhabited with Cristen men, and &yogh;it es &thorn;er sum of &thorn;aire
<MILESTONE N="28" UNIT="folio">kirkes standand. In &thorn;at citee dwelled sum tyme Abraham &thorn;e patriarke. &THORN;is citee founded Bersabee &thorn;e wyf of

<PB N="34">
Vry, and called it after hir self Bersabee. In &thorn;at citee
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">on the whiche [<HI REND="i">sc</HI>. Bathsheba], <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, omitting "on hir" below.</NOTE> Dauid &thorn;e kyng gat on hir Salomon &thorn;e wyse, &thorn;at was
kyng of Ierusalem xl. &yogh;ere. And fra &thorn;eine gase men to &thorn;e vale of Ebron, whilk es fra &thorn;eine xii. myle
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">ii. gode myle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and sum
callez it &thorn;e Vale of Mambre, &thorn;at es at say &thorn;e Vale of Gretyng,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Vale of Teres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for als mykill as Adam oure forme fader made
his lamentacioun in &thorn;at place a hundreth &yogh;ere for &thorn;e deed of his son Abel, &thorn;at Cayn slew. In Ebron was sum
tyme &thorn;e cheffe citee of &thorn;e Philistienes; and &thorn;are dwelled geauntz. It was also afterwardes &thorn;e citee of prestez
&thorn;at ware of &thorn;e kynredyn of Iudas, Iacob son &thorn;e patriarc. And it had swilk a priuilege &thorn;at, what man so fledd
&thorn;ider for manslaghter or any o&thorn;er forfeture, he myght seurly dwell in &thorn;at citee withouten empeching of any man
or any harme takyng. In Ebron Iosue and Caleph and &thorn;aire felyschepe come first to aspye how &thorn;ai myght
wynne &thorn;e land of promission. In Ebron kyng Dauid regned first vii. &yogh;ere and a halfe; and in Ierusalem he
regned xxxiii. &yogh;ere and a halfe. In &thorn;e citee of Ebron er &thorn;e grauez of &thorn;e patriarches Adam, Abraham, Ysaach
and Iacob, and of &thorn;aire wyfes Eue, Sara and Rebecca, and &thorn;ai er in &thorn;e hingand of &thorn;e hill. And ower
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">And ower &hellip; castell, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;aim es a
ri&yogh;t faire kirke wele bretist aboute, as it ware a castell, &thorn;e whilk Sarzenes kepez ri&yogh;t wele. And &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;at
place in grete wirschippe for &thorn;e haly patriarkes &thorn;at lies &thorn;are. And &thorn;ai suffer na Cristen men ne Iews com in
<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;are, bot if &thorn;ai hafe special lefe of &thorn;e sowdan; for &thorn;ai hald Cristen men and Iews bot as hundes, &thorn;at schuld
comme in na haly place. &THORN;at place es called Spelunca Duplex, or double caue, or double graue, for ane lyes on
ano&thorn;er. And &thorn;e Sarzenes callez it in &thorn;aire langage Cariatharbe, &thorn;at es to say &thorn;e place of patriarches. And &thorn;e
Iews calles it Arboth. In &thorn;at same place was Abraham hous &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he sawe, sitand in his dore, &thorn;e three
men and wirscheped ane, as haly writte witnessez, sayand <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Tres vidit et vnum adorauit</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">The reference is to Gen. xviii. 1, 2; but see [commentary].</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "He sawe
three, and he wirschepid ane." And &thorn;are tuke Abraham aungelles in to his hous, in steed of gestez. And &thorn;are
a lytill beside es a caue in a roche, whare Adam and Eue ware dwelland when &thorn;ai ware dryfen oute of Paradys;
and &thorn;are gat &thorn;ai &thorn;aire childer. And, as sum saise, in &thorn;at same place was Adam made; for men called &thorn;at place
sum tyme &thorn;e felde of Damasc, for it was in &thorn;e lordschippe of Damasc. And fra &thorn;eine he was translated in to
Paradys, as &thorn;ai sai; and afterward he was dryfen oute of Paradys and putt &thorn;are agayne. For &thorn;e same day &thorn;at
he was putte in to Paradys &thorn;e same day he was dryfen oute; for als sone as he had synned, he was putt oute of
&thorn;at ioyfull place. &THORN;are begynnes &thorn;e vale of Ebron, and it lastez nere to Ierusalem. And &thorn;are &thorn;e aungell bad
Adam &thorn;at he schuld dwell with his wyf; and &thorn;are &thorn;ai engendred Seth, of whas lynage oure Lord Ihesu Criste was
borne. In &thorn;at valay es a felde, whare men drawez oute of &thorn;e erthe a thing &thorn;at men callez Cambille; and &thorn;ai ete

<PB N="35">
&thorn;at thing in steed of spice, and oft tymes &thorn;ai bere it to sell in &thorn;e cuntree aboute. Men may no&yogh;t make &thorn;e pitte
<MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="folio">&thorn;er &thorn;ai graue it vpp so depe ne so wyde &thorn;at it nes at &thorn;e &yogh;ere end full agayne vp to &thorn;e brerdes thurgh &thorn;e
grace of Godd.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.35.4" CORRESP="Cot.44.27">Twa myle fra Ebron es &thorn;e grafe of Loth &thorn;e neuow of Abraham; and a lytill fra Ebron es &thorn;e mount
Mambree, of whilk &thorn;at valay tuke his name. And &thorn;er es a tree of ake, &thorn;at &thorn;e Sarzenes callez Dyrpe, and it es of
Abraham tyme. &THORN;is es &thorn;e tree &thorn;at men callez &thorn;e drie tree; and &thorn;ai say &thorn;are &thorn;at it has bene fra &thorn;e begynnyng of
&thorn;e werld, and &thorn;at it was allway grene and bare lefes vnto &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at oure Lord died on &thorn;e crosse, and &thorn;an it
dried. And so did, as sum men saise, all &thorn;e treesse in &thorn;e werld, or elles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">or elles &hellip; diuerse placez, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;ai failed in &thorn;aire hertes and become
holle within, of whilk &thorn;er er many &yogh;it standand in diuerse placez. Sum prophecies saise &thorn;at a grete lord of the
west syde of &thorn;e werld sall conquer &thorn;e haly land with help of Cristen men, and he sall ger syng a messe vnder &thorn;at
drie tree, and &thorn;an sall it wax grene agayne and bere leefes and fruyt, and thurgh vertu of &thorn;at miracle many
Sarzenes and Iews sall be turned to Cristen faith. And for&thorn;i &thorn;at tree es halden &thorn;are in grete prys, and grete
reuerence dose &thorn;e folk of &thorn;e cuntree &thorn;erto and kepez it ri&yogh;t bisily. And, if all it be called and es a drie tree,
neuer &thorn;e les &thorn;er es grete vertu &thorn;erin; for, wha so beres any porcion &thorn;eroff apon him, he sall neuer be trauelled
with &thorn;e falland euill, ne his hors sall neuer be afounded, whils he hase it apon him. And many o&thorn;er vertuz has
&thorn;at drie tree, and &thorn;erfore it es halden ri&yogh;t precious.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.35.17" CORRESP="Cot.45.14">Fra Ebron men gase to Bethleem in halfe a day, for it es bot fyue myle; and it es a faire way and a lykand,
thurgh a playne and a wode. Bethleem es bot a lytill citee and a narow, bot it es wele lang, and it es wele
<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio">walled all aboute and dyked. And it was called in alde tyme Effrata, as haly writte saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ecce, audiuimus
eum in Effrata</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Ps. cxxxi. 6, but with "eam."</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Loo, we herd him in Effrata." Toward &thorn;e este end of &thorn;at citee es a faire kirke
with many kirnelles and toures and wele bretist all aboute; and within &thorn;at kirk er xliiii. pilers of marble, grete
and faire. And betwene &thorn;is kirk and &thorn;e citee es &thorn;e Felde Floridus; and it es called Felde Florischt for als mykill
as a faire &yogh;ung maiden was blamed with wrang, &thorn;at scho schuld hafe done fornicacioun, for whilk cause scho was
demed to be brint in &thorn;at place. To &thorn;e whilk place scho was ledd and bun by a stake and fagotes of thornes
and o&thorn;er wode laid aboute hir; and, when scho sawe &thorn;e wodde begynne to brynne, scho made hir praier til oure
Lord &thorn;at, as scho was no&yogh;t gilty of &thorn;at thing, he wald helpe hir and saue hir, &thorn;at it myght be knawen till all
men. And, when scho had &thorn;us prayd, scho went in to the fire; and als sone it was oute, and &thorn;ase braunchez &thorn;at
ware brynnand become reed roseres, and &thorn;ase braunchez &thorn;at ware no&yogh;t kindled become whyte roseres, full of

<PB N="36">
roses. And &thorn;ase ware &thorn;e first rosez and roseres &thorn;at any man sawe. And &thorn;us was &thorn;e mayden saued thurgh &thorn;e
grace of Godd. Also by syde &thorn;e qwere of &thorn;at kirk, at &thorn;e ri&yogh;t syde as men commez dounward xvii.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">xvi., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> greez, es &thorn;e
place whare oure Lord was borne, &thorn;at is now full wele dight and richely depaynted with gold and siluer and
azure and o&thorn;er diuerse coloures. And a lytil &thorn;eine, as it ware three paassez, es &thorn;e cribbe of &thorn;e ox and &thorn;e asse.
And besyde &thorn;at es a pitte whare in &thorn;e sterne fell &thorn;at ledd &thorn;e three kynges till oure Lord; and &thorn;aire names ware
Iasper, Melchior and Balthazar. Bot
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> here follows <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR> literally.</NOTE> men of Grece callez &thorn;am &thorn;us, Galgalath, Malgalath, and Seraphy. &THORN;ise
<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="folio">three kynges offredd till oure Lord incense, gold and mirre. And &thorn;ai come &thorn;ider thurgh myracle of Godd, for
&thorn;ai mette sammen in a citee of Inde, &thorn;at men callez Chasak,
<NOTE N="3" RESP="GW">Cassak, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whilk es liii. day iourneez fra Bethleem, and &thorn;ai
<NOTE N="4" RESP="GW">And &thorn;ai &hellip; &thorn;e sterne, translated more literally in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
ware at Bethleem &thorn;e ferthe day after &thorn;at &thorn;ai had sene &thorn;e sterne. Also vnder &thorn;e cloister of &thorn;is kirke, xviii. greez
at &thorn;e right syde, es &thorn;e Charnell of &thorn;e Innocentz, whare &thorn;aire banes lies. And before &thorn;at place whare Criste was
borne es &thorn;e toumbe of sayne Ierome, &thorn;at was preste and cardinale, &thorn;e whilk <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">did</SUPPLIED> translate &thorn;e <TITLE>Bible</TITLE> into Latyne
oute of Hebrew. And withouten &thorn;e kirk es his chaier, whare in he satt when he translated &thorn;e <TITLE>Bible</TITLE>. A lytill
fra &thorn;is kirk es ano&thorn;er kirk of sayn Nicholas, whare oure Lady restid hir when scho was delyuer of hir childe.
And, for scho had to mykill mylke in hir pappes, whilk greued hir sare, scho mylked it oute apon &thorn;e reed stanes
of marble &thorn;at ware &thorn;are; and &yogh;it &thorn;e spottes of &thorn;e qwhit mylk er sene apon &thorn;e stanes. And &yogh;e sall vnderstand
&thorn;at nere hand all &thorn;at dwellez in Bethleem er Cristen men. And &thorn;er er faire vynes aboute &thorn;e citee and grete
plentee of wyne thurgh &thorn;e ordynaunce and labouryng of Cristen; for &thorn;e Sarzenes laboures no&yogh;t aboute vynes, ne
&thorn;ai drink na wyne. For &thorn;aire buke of lawe &thorn;at Machomete betuke &thorn;am, whilk &thorn;ai call <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>, and sum callez
it <TITLE>Massap</TITLE>, and sum callez it <TITLE>Harme</TITLE>, forbides &thorn;am to drink wyne. For in &thorn;at buke Machomete cursez all &thorn;ase
&thorn;at drinkez wyne and all &thorn;at sellez it. For sum men saise &thorn;at he sloghe anes a gude hermyte, whilk he lufd
mykill, in his drunkenness, and &thorn;erfore he cursed &thorn;e wyne and &thorn;aim &thorn;at drinkez wyne. Bot his malisoun be
<MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="folio">turned to him self, as haly writte saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Et in verticem ipsius iniquitas eius descendet</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Ps. vii. 17.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "And
intill his awen heued his wikkidness schall descend." &THORN;e Sarzenes also bringes furth na grysez, ne &thorn;ai ete na
swyne flessch; for &thorn;ai say it es bro&thorn;er to man and <CORR SIC="at" RESP="GW">&thorn;at</CORR> it was forbedd in &thorn;e alde lawe. Also in &thorn;e land of

<PB N="37">
Palestyne, ne in &thorn;e land of Egipte, &thorn;ai ete bot lytill veel or beeff, bot if it be so alde &thorn;at it may ne mare trauaile
ne wirk, no&yogh;t for it es forbedd, bot &thorn;ai kepe &thorn;am for tillyng of land. In &thorn;is citee of Bethleem was Dauid kyng
borne; and he had syx
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">syx, over erasure, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>; lx., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> wyfes, of whilk &thorn;e first was called Michol, &thorn;e doghter of kyng Saul. He had also
many
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">ccc., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> lemmannes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.37.5" CORRESP="Cot.47.28">Fra Bethleem to Ierusalem er bot twa myle. And in &thorn;e way to Ierusalem, halfe a myle fra Bethleem, es
a kirk, whare &thorn;e aungell said to &thorn;e schephirdes of &thorn;e birth of Criste. And in &thorn;at way es &thorn;e toumbe of Rachel,
Ioseph moder, &thorn;e patriarc; and scho died als sone as scho had borne Beniamyn. And &thorn;are was scho grauen; and
Iacob hir housband sette xii. grete stanes on hir, in takennyng of &thorn;e twelfe patriarkes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">in tokene &thorn;at sche had born xii. children, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Halfe a myle fra
Ierusalem apperde &thorn;e sterne agayne to &thorn;e three kynges. And in &thorn;is way to Ierusalem er many kirkes, by whilk
pilgrimes gase to Ierusalem.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.10" N="10" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.11">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER X</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the pilgrimages in Jerusalem; and of the Holy Places there abowte.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.37.13" CORRESP="Cot.48.6">FOR to speke of Ierusalem, &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at it standes faire amang hilles; and &thorn;er es now&thorn;er
ryuer ne well, bot &thorn;er commes water &thorn;erto by cundytes fra Ebron. And I do &yogh;ow to wit &thorn;at &thorn;is
citee was first called Iebus vnto &thorn;e tyme of Melchisedech, and seyne was it called Salem vnto &thorn;e
tyme of kyng Dauid. And he sett &thorn;ise twa names sammen and called it Iebusalem; and &thorn;an come Salomon
<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="folio">and called it Ierusalem, and so es it &yogh;it called. And aboute Ierusalem es &thorn;e kyngdom of Surry; and &thorn;are by es
&thorn;e land of Palestyne, and Ascalon. Bot Ierusalem es in &thorn;e land of Iudee; and it es called Iudee for Iudas
Machabeus
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Machabeus, erased, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>.</NOTE> was prince of &thorn;at land. And it marchez estward on &thorn;e kyngdom of Araby, and on &thorn;e southe syde
on &thorn;e land of Egipte, on &thorn;e west syde apon &thorn;e grete see, and on &thorn;e north syde apon &thorn;e kyngdom of Surry and
&thorn;e see of Cypre. In Ierusalem was wont to be a patriark, and ercebischopes and bischopes aboute in &thorn;e cuntree.
Aboute Ierusalem er &thorn;ir citeez, Ebron at vii. myle, Iericho at vi. myle, Bersabee at viii. myle, Ascalon at

<PB N="38">
xviii.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">xvii., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> myle, Iaff at xxvii.,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">xvi., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Rames
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Ramatha, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> at iii. myle, and Bethleem at ii. myle. And twa myle fra Bethleem, toward &thorn;e
south, es a kirke of Sayne Markaritot, &thorn;at was sum tyme abbot &thorn;are, for wham &thorn;e mounkes made mykill sorowe
at his dying. And &yogh;it es &thorn;are paynting, whare in &thorn;e grete dole &thorn;at &thorn;ai made es representid and purtraid,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and &yogh;it &thorn;ei ben in moornynge in the wise &thorn;at &thorn;ei maden here lamentacion for him the firste tyme, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and it
es a piteous thing to behald.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.38.5" CORRESP="Cot.49.4">&THORN;is land of Ierusalem has bene in many diuerse naciouns handes, as Iews, Cananez, Assirienes, men of
Perse, Medoynes, Massidoynes, Grekes, Romaynes, Cristen men, Sarzenes, Barbarenes, Turkes, and many o&thorn;er
naciouns. For Criste will no&yogh;t &thorn;at it be lang in &thorn;e handes of traytours ne synners, be &thorn;ai Cristen er o&thorn;er. And
now has mescreauncez halden &thorn;at land in &thorn;aire handes vii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> &yogh;ere
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">xl. &yogh;ere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and mare; bot thurgh &thorn;e grace of Godd &thorn;ai
schall no&yogh;t hald it lang.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.38.10" CORRESP="Cot.49.16">And &yogh;e sall vnderstand &thorn;at, when men commez to Ierusalem, &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire first pilgrimage to &thorn;e kirk
<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio">whare es &thorn;e sepulcre of oure Lorde, whilk was sum tyme withouten &thorn;e citee on &thorn;e north syde; bot it es now
closed within &thorn;e wall of &thorn;e toune. And &thorn;er es a full faire kirk all rounde, thekid
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">covered, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> wele with leed; and on &thorn;e
west syde of &thorn;e kirke es a faire toure and a strang, fore belles. And in &thorn;e myddes of &thorn;at kirke es a tabernacle, as
as it ware a lytill hous made in maner of half a cumpas, dight ri&yogh;t wele and richely with gold and siluer and
azour and o&thorn;er diuerse colours; and on &thorn;e ryght syde &thorn;eroff es &thorn;e sepulcre of oure Lord. &THORN;is tabernacle es viii.
fote lang, and fyue fote wyde, and xi. fote hegh. And it es no&yogh;t lang sen &thorn;e sepulcre was all open, &thorn;at men my&yogh;t
kisse it and touche it. Bot for men &thorn;at come &thorn;ider paynd &thorn;am to breke &thorn;e stane in pecez or pouder to bere
with &thorn;am, &thorn;arfore &thorn;e sowdan has gert make a wall aboute &thorn;e graue, &thorn;at na man may touche it, bot on &thorn;e left
syde.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">But in the left syde of the walle of the tabernacle is, wel the heighte of a man, a gret ston, to the quantytee of a mannes hed, &thorn;at was of the Holy Sepulcre, and &thorn;at ston kissen the pilgrymes &thorn;at comen &thorn;ider, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;at tabernacle has na wyndowes, bot &thorn;er es &thorn;erin many lawmpes light. Bot ymanges o&thorn;er &thorn;er es ane
before &thorn;e sepulcre allway brynnand; and ilk a gude Fridday it gase oute by it self, and on &thorn;e Pasch day it
lightez agayne by it self &thorn;at same hour &thorn;at oure Lord raise fra deed to lyf. Also within &thorn;at kirk on &thorn;e ri&yogh;t syde es
&thorn;e mounte of Caluary, whare oure Lord was done on &thorn;e crosse. And &thorn;e crosse was sette in a mortays in the
roche, &thorn;at es whyt of colour and a lytill reed melled &thorn;erwith. Apon &thorn;e roche dropped blode of &thorn;e woundes of
oure Lorde, when he was pyned on &thorn;e crosse. And &thorn;at es now called Golgatha; and men gase vp &thorn;erto apon

<PB N="39">
<MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="folio">grecez. And in &thorn;at mortays was Adam heued founden aftre Noe flode, in takne &thorn;at &thorn;e synnes of Adam schuld
be boght in &thorn;at same place. And abouen on &thorn;at roche made Abraham sacrifice til oure Lord. And &thorn;are es ane
awter; and before &thorn;at awter lyes Godfray de Boloon and Bawdewyne his bro&thorn;er, and o&thorn;er &thorn;at ware Cristen and
kynges of Ierusalem. And &thorn;are, whare oure Lord was done on &thorn;e crosse, es writen in Grew lettres, sayand
&thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="greek">Otheos basileon ysmon presemas ergaste sothias oys</Q>, and sum bukez saise &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="greek">Otheos basileon ymon
proseonas ergasa sothias emesotis gis</Q>, &thorn;at es to say on Latyn &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Hic deus, rex noster, ante saecula operatus est
salutem in medio terre</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Here Godd, oure kyng, before werldes has wro&yogh;t hele in myddes of &thorn;e
erthe." And also apon &thorn;e roche whare &thorn;e crosse was fitthed es writen &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="greek">Gros guist rasis thou pestes thoy
thesmoysi</Q>, or &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="greek">Oyos iustiys basis thou pesteos thoy themosi</Q>, &thorn;at es to say in Latyn, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quod vides, est
fundamentum totius fidei mundi huius</Q>, &thorn;is es to say, "&THORN;at &thorn;ou seez es &thorn;e ground of all &thorn;e fayth of &thorn;is werld."
And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at oure Lord when he died was xxxiii. &yogh;ere alde and three monethes. Bot &thorn;e
prophecy of Dauid saise &thorn;at he schuld hafe xl. &yogh;ere are he died, &thorn;are he saise on &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quadraginta annis
proximus fui generacioni huic</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Ps. xciv.10, but with "offensus" for "proximus."</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Fourty &yogh;ere was I neghbour to &thorn;is kynde." And hereby schuld
it seme &thorn;at haly writte ware no&yogh;t trewe; bot sikerly it es trew ynogh, for in alde tyme men made &yogh;eres of ten
<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio">monethes, of whilk &thorn;e moneth of Marce was &thorn;e first and December &thorn;e last. Bot Iulius Cesar, &thorn;at was emperour
of Rome, gert sette to &thorn;ise twa monethes, Ianuere and Feuerere, and ordayned &thorn;e &yogh;ere to be of xii. monethes, &thorn;at
es to say of ccclxv. dayes, withouten lepe &yogh;ere, after &thorn;e propre course of &thorn;e sonne. And &thorn;erfore, after
accountyng of ten monethes to &thorn;e &yogh;ere, he dyed in &thorn;e fourty &yogh;ere, and after oure &yogh;eres of twelfe monethes he had
xxxiii. &yogh;ere and three monethes are he dyed. Fast by &thorn;e mount of Caluary, at &thorn;e ri&yogh;t syde, es ane awter, whare
&thorn;e piler lyes to &thorn;e whilk oure Lord was bounden, when he was scourged. And foure fote &thorn;eine er foure stanes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">pileres of ston, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
whilk all way droppez water; and sum men saise &thorn;at &thorn;ase stanes grette for oure Lordes deed. And nere to &thorn;is
forsaid awter, in a place vnder &thorn;e erthe xlii. grecez depe, fand saynt Helene &thorn;e crosse of oure Lord Ihesu Criste,
vnder a roche whare &thorn;e Iews had hidd it. And &thorn;are were founden also o&thorn;er twa crossez, &thorn;at &thorn;e twa thefez
ware done apon, whilk hang on ayther syde Criste. And saynt Helen wist no&yogh;t witerly whilk was &thorn;e crosse &thorn;at
Criste was done apon; and &thorn;an scho tuke ilk ane efter o&thorn;er and layd &thorn;am apon a deed man, and, als sone as &thorn;e
verray crosse &thorn;at Criste was done apon was laid apon &thorn;e deed body, &thorn;e cors rase fra deed to lyfe. And &thorn;are by
in &thorn;e wall es &thorn;e place whare &thorn;e foure nayles &thorn;at Criste was nayled with thurgh fote and hand ware hidd; for he
had twa nayles in his hend and twa in his fete. And of ane of &thorn;ase nayles gert &thorn;e emperour Constantyne make him
ane yrne till his brydill,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">made a brydill to his hors, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk he vsed ay when he went to bataile; for thurgh vertu &thorn;eroff he ouercome his
<MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="folio">enmys and conquerd many diuerse rewmes, &thorn;at es to say Asy &thorn;e less, Turkie, Ermony &thorn;e less and &thorn;e mare,

<PB N="40">
Surry, Ierusalem, Araby, Perse, Mesopotamy, &thorn;e rewme of Halope, and of Egipte, bathe &thorn;e ouermare and &thorn;e
ne&thorn;er mare, and many o&thorn;er landes vnto wele lawe in Ethiope and vnto Inde &thorn;e less, &thorn;at &thorn;an was Cristen for &thorn;e
mare party. And &thorn;are ware in &thorn;at tyme many gode haly men and haly hermytes in &thorn;ase cuntreez, of wham &thorn;e
buke of <TITLE LANG="lat">Vitas patrum</TITLE> spekez. And now fore &thorn;e maste party &thorn;ase landes er in payenes and Sarzenes handes.
Bot , when Godd will, ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ise landes er lost thurgh synne of Cristen men, so schall &thorn;ai be wonnen agayne by
Cristen men, thurgh helpe of Godd. In &thorn;e middes of &thorn;e qwere of &thorn;e forsaid kirk es a sercle, in &thorn;e whilk Ioseph
of Aramathy layd &thorn;e body of oure Lord, when he had tane him off &thorn;e crosse; and men saise &thorn;at &thorn;at cumpas es
in &thorn;e middes of &thorn;e werld. And in &thorn;at place wascht Ioseph &thorn;e woundes of oure Lord. Also in &thorn;e kirk of &thorn;e
sepulcre, on &thorn;e north syde, es a place whare oure Lord was done in prisoun, for he was emprisouned in many
placez. And &thorn;are es &yogh;it a porcioun of &thorn;e chayne wharwith he was bunden. And &thorn;are he appered first to Mary
Mawdelayne, when he rase fra deed to lyfe, and scho wend &thorn;at he had bene a gardenere. In &thorn;e kirke of &thorn;e
Sepulcre ware wont to be chanouns of &thorn;e ordre of saynt Austyne, and &thorn;ai had a priour; bot &thorn;e patriarc was
&thorn;aire souerayne. And withouten &thorn;e dore of &thorn;e kirke, at &thorn;e ri&yogh;t syde, as men gase vpp xviii. greez, sayd oure
Lord till his moder, when he hang on &thorn;e crosse, apon &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Mulier, ecce, filius tuus</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">John xix. 26.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say,
<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio">"Womman, loo, &thorn;are &thorn;i son," and he ment of sayne Iohn &thorn;at stode &thorn;are by syde. And till him he said, "Loo,
&thorn;are &thorn;i moder." Vppe at &thorn;is grece went Criste with &thorn;e crosse on his bakk to &thorn;e place whare he was crucified.
And vnder &thorn;is grece es a chapell, whare prestez synges, bot no&yogh;t aftre oure lawe, bot aftre &thorn;aire awen lawe.
And all way &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire sacrement of &thorn;e awter of breed, sayand &thorn;e <TITLE LANG="lat">Pater noster</TITLE> and &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e
sacrement and lytill mare; for &thorn;ai knawe no&yogh;t &thorn;e addiciouns of papez, whilk oure prestez vsez for to say at
messez. Neuer &thorn;e les &thorn;ai syng &thorn;aire messez with grete deuocioun. And &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e place whare oure Lord
rested him, when he was wery of bering of &thorn;e crosse. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at ynentes &thorn;e kirk of &thorn;e
Sepulcre es &thorn;e citee maste wayke, for &thorn;e grete playne &thorn;at es betwene &thorn;e citee and &thorn;e kirke on &thorn;e este syde.
And withouten &thorn;e walles toward &thorn;e est es &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat, &thorn;e whilk commes euen to &thorn;e walles. Abouen &thorn;at
vale withouten &thorn;at citee es &thorn;e kirke of saynt Steuen, whare he was staned to deed. And &thorn;are by syde es &thorn;e &yogh;ate
whilke men callez Porta aurea, &thorn;e whilk may no&yogh;t be opned. In at &thorn;at yhate come oure Lord Ihesu rydand on
Palme Sunday apon ane asse; and &thorn;at &yogh;ate opned agayne him, when he come to &thorn;e temple. And &yogh;it er &thorn;e
steppes of &thorn;e asse sene in thre placez of &thorn;e grece of stane. Before &thorn;e kirke of &thorn;e Sepulcre cc. passez es a grete
hospitale of saynt Iohn, of whilk &thorn;e hospitalleres hase &thorn;aire first fundacion. And to ga toward &thorn;e est fra &thorn;e

<PB N="41">
<MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="folio">hospitale es a ri&yogh;t fair kirke, &thorn;at men callez Nostre Dame le graunt. And a lytill &thorn;eine es ano&thorn;er kirke, &thorn;at es
called Nostre Dame de Latynes. And &thorn;are stude Mary Mawdelayne and Mary Cleophe, makand sorow for
oure Lord, when he was done to deed, and drawand off &thorn;aire hare. In
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">This sentence in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> is higher up, as in the French texts, and follows <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR> more exactly.</NOTE> &thorn;e forsaid hospitale of sayne Iohn es a
grete hous ordaynd for seke folk, and &thorn;er er in &thorn;at hous vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI>iiii. pilers of stane &thorn;at beres vp &thorn;e hous.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.11" N="11" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.12">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the temple of oure Lord; of the crueltee of kyng Heroud; of the mount Syon; of Probatica Piscina; and of Natatorium Siloe.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.41.8" CORRESP="Cot.53.22">FRA &thorn;e kirke of &thorn;e sepulcre, toward &thorn;e est, ane aght score passez es &thorn;e temple Domini, whilke es ri&yogh;t a
faire hous. And it es all rounde and ri&yogh;t hye and wele thekid with leed, and it es wele paued with
whyte marble. Bot &thorn;e Sarzenes will suffer na Cristen men ne Iews comme &thorn;erin; for &thorn;ai say &thorn;at so
foule men schuld no&yogh;t comme in to so haly place. Neuer&thorn;eles I come in &thorn;are, and in o&thorn;er placez whare I wald;
for I had lettres of &thorn;e sowdan with his grete seele, in &thorn;e whilk he commaunded straitely til all his subiectes, &thorn;at
&thorn;ai schuld late me see all &thorn;e placez whare I come, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld schew me &thorn;e relykes and &thorn;e placez at my
will and &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld lede me fra citee to citee, if miste ware,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&yogh;if it were nede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and benignely ressayue me and all my felaws,
and be obeischaunt to myne askynges in all thing &thorn;at was resounable, bot if it ware agaynes &thorn;e reall dignitee of &thorn;e
sowdan, or elles agayne &thorn;aire lawe. Till o&thorn;er &thorn;at askes leue of &thorn;e sowdan and grace to passe by &thorn;e placez
before said he giffez comounly bot his signet; &thorn;e whilke pilgrimes beres before &thorn;am thurgh &thorn;e cuntree
hingand apon a spere or apon a rodd, to &thorn;e whilke &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at land dose grete reuerence. Bot to me, by
<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio">cause I was lang in his courte and in his seruice, he didd speciale grace. Till his forsaid signet swilk reuerence
&thorn;ai do, &thorn;at, when &thorn;ai see it passe before &thorn;am, &thorn;ai knele doune &thorn;erto, as we do when &thorn;e preste passez by vs with
&thorn;e pyxe.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;e pyxe, over an erasure, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>; and knelen &thorn;ereto as lowly as wee don to <HI REND="i">Corpus Domini</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And till his lettres also &thorn;ai do grete reuerence; for, when &thorn;ai comme till any lorde or til any o&thorn;er
man, als sone as he seez &thorn;am, he inclynes &thorn;erto reuerently and ressayfez &thorn;am and lays &thorn;am apon his heued, and
seyne he kissez &thorn;am and redez &thorn;am kneland and &thorn;an proferes him to do all thing &thorn;at &thorn;e bringer will efter &thorn;e
tenenour of &thorn;am. In &thorn;is forsaid temple Domini ware wont to be chanouns reguleres; and &thorn;ai had ane abbot to

<PB N="42">
wham &thorn;ai ware obedient. And in &thorn;is temple was Charlemayne, when &thorn;e aungell broght him &thorn;e prepuce of oure
Lord, when he was circumcised; and afterward kyng Charles gert bere it to Parysch.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">to Parys into his chapelle; and after &thorn;at he leet brynge it to Peyteres [Poitiers] and after &thorn;at to Chartres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &yogh;e schall vnderstand
&thorn;at &thorn;is es no&yogh;t &thorn;e temple &thorn;at Salomon made; for &thorn;at temple lasted bot a thousand cii. &yogh;ere. For Tytus,
Vaspasiane son, &thorn;at was emperour of Rome, layd ensege vnto Ierusalem for to destruy &thorn;e Iews, for &thorn;ai did
Criste to deed withouten leue and ascent of &thorn;e emperour. And, when he had taken &thorn;e citee, he gert brynne &thorn;e
temple and cast it doune and destruyd it and tuke all &thorn;e Iews and slew of &thorn;am elleuen hundreth thowsand; and
&thorn;e remenaunt he putte in presoun and salde of &thorn;am xxx. for a peny, for he had herd tell &thorn;at &thorn;ai salde Criste for
<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio">xxx. penys.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and he made of hem bettre cheep, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Lang after &thorn;is &thorn;e emperour Iulyan Apostata, whilk renayd and forsuke Cristen fayth, gafe &thorn;e Iewes
leue to make agayne &thorn;e temple in Ierusalem, for &thorn;e hatredyn &thorn;at he had till Cristen men, if all he ware a Cristen
man before. And when &thorn;ai had made &thorn;e temple, &thorn;er come ane ertheqwakyng, as Godd wald, &thorn;at kest all doune
&thorn;at &thorn;ai had made. And seyne &thorn;e emperour Adrian, &thorn;at was of &thorn;aim of Troy, reparailed &thorn;e citee of Ierusalem
and restored &thorn;e temple and made it new agayne in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at Salomon made it, reall and noble. Bot he
wald suffer na Iew com &thorn;erin, bot al Cristen men; for, if all it ware so &thorn;at he ware no&yogh;t Cristen, he lufed
Cristen men mare &thorn;an any o&thorn;er men, saue men of his awen fayth. And &thorn;is emperour gert enclose &thorn;e kirk of &thorn;e
sepulcre with a wall and made it to be within &thorn;e citee, &thorn;at before was withouten. And he chaunged &thorn;e name
of &thorn;e citee and called it Helyam,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&AElig;lia Capitolina.</NOTE> bot &thorn;at name lasted no&yogh;t lang. To &thorn;e temple Domini duse &thorn;e Sarezens grete
reuerence, and saise &thorn;at &thorn;at place es ri&yogh;t haly. And, when &thorn;ai gang in to it, &thorn;ai do off &thorn;aire schone and knelez
oft sythez with grete reuerence. And, when my felawes and I sawe &thorn;am do so, we didd off oure schoos and
tho&yogh;t it ware mare skill &thorn;at we Cristen men didd swilke wirschepe &thorn;are to at &thorn;e reuerence of Godd &thorn;an
mistrowand. &THORN;is temple hase lxiiii. cubites of wydeness, and als many of lenth, and of heyght vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> and fyfe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> cubites, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>;
and it es within all aboute of pilers of marble. And ymiddez of &thorn;e temple es a stage of xxiiii. grecez hie, and
gode pilers all aboute. &THORN;is place callez &thorn;e Iews Sancta Sanctorum. And in &thorn;at place come nane bot all anely
<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e bischope of &thorn;aire lawe, when he made &thorn;aire sacrificez. And &thorn;e folke stude all aboute in diuerse stagez after
&thorn;at &thorn;ai ware of dignytee and wirschepe. And &thorn;are er in to &thorn;is temple foure entreez; and &thorn;e dures er of cipresse,
craftily made and wele. And within &thorn;e est dore oure Lord said, "Here es Ierusalem." And on &thorn;e north
syde, within &thorn;e dore, es a well, bot &thorn;are rynnes na water oute of it, of whilk Haly Writte
<NOTE N="5" RESP="DR">Cp. Ezekiel 47.1; see also Warner's commentary.</NOTE> spekes &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Vidi

<PB N="43">
aquam egredientem de templo, &amp;c</Q>. And on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde es a roche, &thorn;at men called sum tyme Moriac, bot
seyne was it called Bethel, whare &thorn;e ark of Godd stude and o&thorn;er reliques of &thorn;e Iews. &THORN;is ark gert Titus lede with
&thorn;e reliques vnto grete Rome, when he had discumfit &thorn;e Iews. In &thorn;at arc ware Moyses tables, wharin &thorn;e ten
comaundementz ware writen, and Aaron wand, and &thorn;e &yogh;erde of Moyses, with &thorn;e whilk he departid &thorn;e Reed
See, when &thorn;e childer of Israel passed thurgh it drie fote and kyng Pharao folowed &thorn;am. And with &thorn;at ilke
&yogh;erde Moyses smate on &thorn;e drie roche, and &thorn;an water come oute rynnand at grete fuysoun. And with &thorn;at same
wand he didd many wonders. In &thorn;e forsaid ark also was a vessell of gold full of manna, &thorn;at men callez
aungelles fode, with many o&thorn;er ournementz and clething of Aaron and of &thorn;e tabernacle. And &thorn;are was a table
of gold, euen sqware, with xii. precious stanes, and a boist of grene iasper with foure figures and viii. names of
oure Lord &thorn;erin, and vii. candelstiks of gold, and xii. fiolles of gold, and foure encensours of gold, and ane awter
of gold, and foure lyouns of gold, apon whilk &thorn;ai had cherubyn of gold xii. span lang, a cercle with &thorn;e xii. signez
<MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="folio">of &thorn;e firmament,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and the cercle of swannes of heuene, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. A confusion between "signes" and "cignes."</NOTE> and a tabernacle of gold, and xii.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">ii., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> trumppes of siluer, and a table of siluer, vii. haly lafes, and
many o&thorn;er reliques and precious thinges &thorn;at pertende to Goddes seruice before &thorn;e incarnacioun of Criste. And
also apon &thorn;is roche sleped Iacob, when he sawe aungelles steigh vpp and doune by a stye, and said on &thorn;is wyse,
<Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Vere locus iste sanctus est, et ego nesciebam</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Vere Dominus est in loco isto, et ego nesciebam, Gen. xxviii. 16.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Forsothe, &thorn;is place es haly, and I wist noght."
And &thorn;are held Iacob &thorn;e aungell still,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">an aungel helde Iacob stille, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at chaunged his name and called him Israel. And in &thorn;at place sawe
Dauid &thorn;e aungell smytand &thorn;e folk with a swerde and seyne puttand it all bludy in &thorn;e schethe. And
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">The omitted sentences [i.e., found in the French text but not here] given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on
&thorn;is roche oure Lord sette him, when &thorn;e Iews wald hafe staned him to deed, and &thorn;e roche clafe in twa, and in
&thorn;at rift he hidd him; and a sterne come doune and gafe him light. And on &thorn;is roche satt oure Lady and lerned
hir sawter. And &thorn;are oure Lord forgafe synnes to &thorn;e womman &thorn;at was taken in avoutry. And &thorn;are was Criste
circumcised. And &thorn;are schewed &thorn;e aungell &thorn;e natiuitee of sayn Iohn Baptist. And &thorn;are offerd Melchisedech
breed and wyne till oure Lord in takennyng of &thorn;e sacrement &thorn;at was to come. And &thorn;are kneled Dauid,
prayand til oure Lord &thorn;at he wald hafe mercy of him and of his folke; and oure Lord herd his praier. And
&thorn;are he wald hafe made &thorn;e temple; bot oure Lord forbedd him by ane aungell, for he had done treyson, when he
slogh Vry, a gude knyght, by cause of his wyf. And &thorn;erfore all &thorn;at he had ordaynd to &thorn;e makyng of &thorn;e temple
he tuke it to Salomon his son; and he made it. And he prayd oure Lorde, &thorn;at all &thorn;ase &thorn;at prayd in &thorn;at place

<PB N="44">
<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio">deuotely and with gude hert, &thorn;at he wald here &thorn;aire praier and graunt &thorn;at &thorn;ai asked ri&yogh;twisely; and oure Lord
graunted it. And &thorn;erfore Salomon called it &thorn;e temple of counsaile and helpe of Godd and of &thorn;e grace of Godd.
Withouten &thorn;e dore of &thorn;e temple es ane awter, whare &thorn;e Iewes ware wount to offer dowfes and turtils.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">The sentence [in the French text] omitted here, also omitted in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And in
&thorn;at temple was &thorn;e prophete Zachary slayne. And off a pynnacle of &thorn;is temple kest &thorn;e Iews sayne Iame doune,
&thorn;e whilk was &thorn;e first bischope of Ierusalem. And at &thorn;e entree of &thorn;is temple es &thorn;e &yogh;ate &thorn;at es called Speciosa,
whare
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">whare &hellip; for to go, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sayne Petre heled &thorn;e cruked man and made him for to ga. A lytill fra &thorn;is temple, on &thorn;e right syde, es a
kirk theked with leed, &thorn;at es called &thorn;e Scole of Salomon. And toward &thorn;e south es &thorn;e temple Salomon, &thorn;e whilk
es a full faire place; and it standez in a faire playne and a large.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">temple of Salomon, &thorn;at is right fair and well pollisscht, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And in &thorn;at place dwelled knyghtes, &thorn;at ware
called Templeres; and &thorn;at was &thorn;e fundacioun of &thorn;e Templeres and of &thorn;aire ordre. And, ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ar was &thorn;are
dwelland knyghtes, so was &thorn;er chanounes dwelland in &thorn;e temple Domini. Fra &thorn;is temple toward &thorn;e este at
vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> pascez in a nuke of &thorn;e citee es &thorn;e bathe of oure Lord; and in to &thorn;is bathe was water wount for to comme
oute of Paradys. A lytill &thorn;erfra es oure Lady bedd; and nere &thorn;are es &thorn;e toumbe of saynt Symeon. And
withouten &thorn;e temple, toward &thorn;e north, es a faire kirke of saynt Anne, oure Lady moder; &thorn;are was oure Lady
consayued. And before &thorn;at kirke es a tree &thorn;at began to growe &thorn;at same nyght. And, as men gase doune fra &thorn;at
kirke xxii. grecez, lyes Ioachim, oure Lady fader, in a toumbe of stane. And &thorn;are besyde him lay sum tyme
<MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="folio">saynt Anne; bot saynt Helyne gert translate hir to Constantynople. In &thorn;is kirke es a well in maner of a cisterne,
&thorn;e whilk es called Probatica Piscina; and it had sum tyme v. entreez. In &thorn;at cisterne ware aungels wont to
bathe &thorn;am and stirre &thorn;e water, and, what man so first bathed him &thorn;erin after stirring of &thorn;e water, he was made
hale, what sekenes so he had. And &thorn;are was &thorn;e man made hale &thorn;at was seke xxxviii. &yogh;ere. And &thorn;are oure
Lorde said vntil him, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Tolle grabatum tuum et ambula</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">John v. 8.</NOTE> &thorn;at es at say, "Take &thorn;i bedd and ga." And a lytil
&thorn;eine was &thorn;e hous of Pilate, and also &thorn;e hous of Herode, &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at gert slae &thorn;e Innocentz. &THORN;is ilke Herode
was a ful wikked man and a fell. For first he gert sla his wyf, whilk he luffed passand all o&thorn;er creatures; and
for &thorn;e grete lufe &thorn;at he had till hir, when he sawe hir deed, he went oute of his witte and so was he lang.
Afterward, when he was commen agayne to his witte by processe of tyme, he gert sla his childer &thorn;at he had
geten of hir. And &thorn;an he gert sla his o&thorn;er wyf, and a son &thorn;at he had of hir, and his awen moder. And so he
wald hafe done his bro&thorn;er, bot he dyed are he myght com til his purpose. And, when he sawe &thorn;at he suld dye,

<PB N="45">
he sent after his sister and all &thorn;e grete lordes of his land, and when &thorn;ai ware commen, he gert putte all &thorn;e lordes
in a toure and said vnto his sister he wist wele &thorn;at men of his land schuld make na sorow for him, when he
ware deed, and &thorn;erfore he gert hir swere &thorn;at scho suld gere do to deed all &thorn;ise lordes, als sone as he ware deed,
<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio">and &thorn;an schuld all &thorn;e cuntree make sorowe at my deed. And &thorn;us he made his testament and dyed sone after.
Bot his sister fulfilled no&yogh;t his will; for, als sone als he was deed, scho delyuerd &thorn;e lordes oute of &thorn;e toure and
talde &thorn;am hir bro&thorn;er will and lete ilk ane ga whare he wald. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;are ware three
Herodes, &thorn;e whilk ware wikked men and cruell. He, &thorn;is of wham I speke off, was called Herode Ascalonyte;
and he &thorn;at gert smyte off sayne Iohn Baptist heued was called Herode Antipater
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Antypa, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and Herode Agrippa gert
sla sayne Iame, sayne Iohn bro&thorn;er &thorn;e euangelist, and putte sayne Petre in prisoun.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.45.10" CORRESP="Cot.59.30">For&thorn;ermare in &thorn;e citee of Ierusalem es a kirk of saynt Saueour, and &thorn;are es &thorn;e left arme of sayne Iohn
Crisostom, and &thorn;are es &thorn;e mare party of sayn Steuen heued. And a lytill &thorn;eine toward &thorn;e south, as men gas to
mount Syon, es a faire kirke of sayne Iame, whare his heued was smyten off. And &thorn;an es &thorn;e mount Syon; and
&thorn;are es a faire kirke of Godd and oure Lady, whare scho was dwelland and dyed. And &thorn;are was sum tyme ane
abbot, with chanounes regulers. And fra &thorn;at place was oure Lady borne with &thorn;e apostils to &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat.
&THORN;are es also a stane bro&yogh;t till oure Lady by aungelles fra &thorn;e mount of Synai; and it es lyke in all thinges to &thorn;e
roche of &thorn;e mount sayne Kateryne. And &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e &yogh;ate &thorn;at oure Lady went furth att to Bethleem. Also in
&thorn;e entree of mount Syon es a chapell; and in &thorn;at chapell es &thorn;e stane, grete and large, with whilk &thorn;e sepulcre of
Criste was couerd, when he was layd &thorn;erin; whilk stane &thorn;e three Mariez saw turned vpward and tumbled off &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio">graffe, when &thorn;ai come to &thorn;e sepulcre. And &thorn;are es a lytill pece of &thorn;e piler to &thorn;e whilk oure Lord was bunden,
when he was scourged. And &thorn;are was Annas hous, &thorn;at was bischope of &thorn;e Iews in &thorn;at tyme. And &thorn;are es a
party of &thorn;e burde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">table, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on &thorn;e whilk Criste made his maundee with his disciples and gafe &thorn;am his body in fourme of
breed and wyne. And &thorn;are denyed Petre oure Lord thryess are &thorn;e cokk crewe. Vnder &thorn;is chapell, for to ga
doune xxxii. grecez, es &thorn;e place whare oure Loud wascht his disciples fete; and &yogh;it es &thorn;are &thorn;e vessell &thorn;at &thorn;e water
was in. And &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e place whare sayne Steuen was grauen. And &thorn;are es ane awter, whare oure Lady
herd aungelles syng mess. &THORN;are apperde Criste first to his disciples after his resurreccioun, and &thorn;e dures sperde,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">the &yogh;ates enclosed, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
and said vnto &thorn;am, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Pax vobis</Q>. And on &thorn;e mount Syon apperde Criste to sayne Thomas and bad him fele his

<PB N="46">
woundez; and &thorn;an trowed he first and said, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Dominus meus et Deus meus</Q>. In &thorn;e forsaid chapell behind &thorn;e hye
awter ware all &thorn;e apostils togyder on Whitsonondy, when &thorn;e Haly Gaste descended on &thorn;am in likness of fyre.
And &thorn;are made Criste pasch with his disciples; and &thorn;are sleped sayn Iohn &thorn;e euaungelist in oure Lordes knee
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">breeste, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
and sawe slepand many priuee thinges of heuen.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.46.5" CORRESP="Cot.61.5">&THORN;e mount Syon es within &thorn;e citee, and it es sumwhat hyer &thorn;an o&thorn;er placez of &thorn;e citee. And &thorn;e citee es
stranger on &thorn;at syde &thorn;an on ano&thorn;er syde; for at &thorn;e fote of mount Syon es a faire castell and a strang, &thorn;e whilk
&thorn;e sowdan gert make. On mount Syon was kyng Dauid and Salomon and o&thorn;er many grauen. And &thorn;are es &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio">place whare sayne Petre grette full tenderly, when he had forsaken Criste. And a lytil &thorn;eine, as it ware a
fynger stane cast, es ano&thorn;er chapell, whare oure Lord was demed to deed; and &thorn;are was Cayphas hous. Fra
&thorn;is chapell, toward &thorn;e est, a vii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> passez es a depe caue vnder a roche, whilk es called Galilea Domini
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">the Galylee of oure Lord, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;are
hidd sayne Petre him after &thorn;at he had denyed Criste thrys. Betwene temple Salomon and &thorn;e mount Syon es
&thorn;e place whare oure Lorde raised &thorn;e mayden fra deed to lyfe. Vnder &thorn;e mount Syon, toward &thorn;e vale of
Iosaphat, es a well, &thorn;at men callez Natatorium Syloe. &THORN;are was oure Lord waschen after &thorn;at he was baptized;
and &thorn;are he made &thorn;e blynd to see. &THORN;are also was &thorn;e prophete Ysai grauen. A lytill &thorn;eine, euen ouerynentes &thorn;e
forsaid well, es ane ymage of stane of alde werk, whilk Absalon gert make; and it es called Absalon hand. And
a lytill &thorn;eine es &thorn;e tree on whilk Iudas hanged him self, when he had salde Criste. And &thorn;an es &thorn;e synagog
whare &thorn;e bischope of &thorn;e Iewes and &thorn;e Pharisenes come sammen to hald &thorn;aire counsailes agaynes Ihesus. And
&thorn;are Iudas kest &thorn;e xxx. penys before &thorn;am and said, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Peccaui, tradens sanguinem iustum</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Matt. xxvii. 4.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "I hafe
synned, betrayand ri&yogh;twyse blude." And on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde of mount Syon, toward &thorn;e south, a stane cast es &thorn;e
felde &thorn;at was boght with &thorn;ase xxx. penys; and it es called &thorn;are Acheldemak, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;e Felde of Blude. In
&thorn;is felde er many grafez of Cristen pilgrimes; for &thorn;are ware pilgrimes wont to be grauen. &THORN;are er also many
kirkes and chapelles and hermytages, whare hermytes ware wount for to dwell. And a c. pascez &thorn;eine, toward
<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e este, es &thorn;e charnell of &thorn;e hospitale of sayne Iohn.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.46.24" CORRESP="Cot.62.11">A myle fra Ierusalem, toward &thorn;e west, es a fayre kirke, whare &thorn;e tree growed of whilk &thorn;e Haly Crosse was
made. And twa myle &thorn;eine es a faire kirke, whare oure Lady mette with Elizabeth, when &thorn;ai ware bathe with

<PB N="47">
childe, and sayne Iohn stirred in his moder wambe and did wyrschepe till oure Lorde his maker. And &thorn;are
vnder &thorn;e awter es &thorn;e place whare sayne Iohn Baptist was borne. And bot a myle &thorn;eine es &thorn;e castell of Emaus,
to &thorn;e whilk twa of Cristez disciples went after &thorn;e resurreccioun; and &thorn;are &thorn;ai knew oure Lord in breking of
breed. And
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">The passage found in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR>, "Item dautre &hellip; voluntee divine," omitted here, is given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> twa myle fra Ierusalem es &thorn;e Mount Ioy, whilk es a faire place and a lykand; and &thorn;are lyes
Samuel &thorn;e prophete in a faire toumbe. And it es called Mount Ioy, for &thorn;are may pilgrimes first see to Ierusalem,
of whilk sight &thorn;ai hafe grete ioy and comforth after &thorn;aire grete trauaile. Betwene Ierusalem and &thorn;e mount of
Oliuete es &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat vnder &thorn;e walles of &thorn;e citee, as I said before; and ymiddes of &thorn;e vale es a lytill
bekk, &thorn;at es called Torrens Cedron. And ouer &thorn;is bekk lay &thorn;e tree &thorn;at &thorn;e haly Crosse was made off, for a
plaunchoure to men at gang on ower &thorn;at bekk. And no&yogh;t bot a lytill &thorn;eine es a pitte in &thorn;e erthe; and &thorn;are in es &thorn;e base
of &thorn;e piler to whilk Criste was bunden &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he was scourged. And in &thorn;e myddez of &thorn;e vale es a kirke of
oure Lady; and &thorn;are es oure Lady graue. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at oure Lady was, when scho dyed, lxxii. &yogh;ere
alde. And &thorn;are nere hir grafe es &thorn;e place whare oure Lorde forgafe sayne Petre all his synnes. And bot a lytill
&thorn;eine, toward &thorn;e west, vnder ane awter es a well &thorn;at commes fra ane of &thorn;e ryuers of Paradys. And it es for to wit
<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at, &thorn;of &thorn;is kirke seme now lawer &thorn;an &thorn;e erthe aboute it, at &thorn;e first fundacioun &thorn;eroff it was no&yogh;t swa; bot of breking
of &thorn;e walles of &thorn;e citee &thorn;at hase fallen doune &thorn;e erthe aboute &thorn;e kirk es risen, and so it es now hegher &thorn;an &thorn;e kirk
&thorn;at at &thorn;e first tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e kirk was made was euen &thorn;erwith. Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;e comoun opinioun es &thorn;at &thorn;e erthe es waxen
heghe swa of &thorn;e self, sen &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at oure Lady was grauen &thorn;are, and &yogh;it waxez day by day. In &thorn;is kirk ware
wont to be blakk mounkes, &thorn;e whilk had ane abbote. Besyde &thorn;is kirk es a chapell, nere &thorn;e roche &thorn;at es called
Gethsemany, whare Iudas kissed oure Lorde, when he was taken of &thorn;e Iews. And &thorn;are left Criste his disciples
before his passioun, when he went to pray and sayd, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Pater, si fieri potest, transeat a me calix iste</Q>, that es to say,
"Fader, if it may be done, lat &thorn;is passioun ga fra me." And &yogh;it may men see in &thorn;e roche &thorn;e prynte of oure Lorde
hend, &thorn;are he thrast &thorn;am to &thorn;e roche, when &thorn;e Iews tuke him. And a stane cast &thorn;eine, toward &thorn;e south, es ano&thorn;er
chapell, whare oure Lord swette blude. And &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e toumbe of king Iosaphat; of wham &thorn;at vale tuke
his name, for he was king of &thorn;at cuntree.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and was conuerted by an heremyte &thorn;at was a worthi man and dide moche gode, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And a bow schote fra &thorn;eine, toward &thorn;e south, es a kirk, whare sayne

<PB N="48">
Iame was grauen and Zachary &thorn;e prophete. On &thorn;e ta syde of &thorn;e vale of <MILESTONE UNIT="f.40">Iosaphat es &thorn;e mount of Olyuete; and
it es called so by cause &thorn;are growes many olyues. And it es hegher &thorn;an &thorn;e citee of Ierusalem, and &thorn;erfore fra
&thorn;eine <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">may men see</SUPPLIED> in to all
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">manye of, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e stretez of Ierusalem. Betwene &thorn;at hill and &thorn;e citee es no&yogh;t bot &thorn;e vale of
Iosaphat, &thorn;e whilk es no&yogh;t full large. Apon &thorn;at hill stode oure Lord when he steigh in till heuen; and &yogh;it may men
see &thorn;e steppe of his left fote in a stane &thorn;at he stode on. And &thorn;are was sum tyme ane abbay of black chanouns, bot
now es &thorn;er no&yogh;t bot a kirk. And a lytill &thorn;eine, xxviii. paassez, es a chapell, and &thorn;are es &thorn;e stane on whilk oure
Lord satte and prechid to &thorn;e folk, sayand &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Beati pauperes spiritu, quoniam ipsorum est regnum
celorum, &amp;c.</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Matt. v. 3.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Blissed be &thorn;ai &thorn;at er pouer in spirit, for &thorn;aires es &thorn;e kingdom of heuen." And
&thorn;are he taght his disciples &thorn;e <TITLE LANG="lat">Pater noster</TITLE>, wrytand &thorn;are in &thorn;e stane; &thorn;e whilk wryting
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;e whilk wryting &hellip; &thorn;is day, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> schewez &yogh;it to &thorn;is day.
And &thorn;are nere es a kirk, whare Mary Egipciane lyes in a toumbe. And a lytill &thorn;eine, toward &thorn;e est, es Bethphage,
whare oure Lorde sent twa of his disciplez to fecche him ane asse on Palme Sonounday. A lytil fra &thorn;e mount
of Olyuete, toward &thorn;e est, es a castell &thorn;at men callez Bethany. &THORN;are dwelt Symon &thorn;e leprous, &thorn;at herberd oure
Lord and his disciples. He, &thorn;is Symon, afterwardes was baptized of &thorn;e Apostils, and called Iulyan, and seyne
made a bischope. &THORN;is Iulyan es he &thorn;at men callez on for gude herbery. In &thorn;at same place forgafe oure Lord
Mari Mawdelayne hir synnes; and &thorn;are scho wescht his fete with teres of hir eghen and dried &thorn;am with hir
hare. And &thorn;are was Lazare raised fra deed to lyfe, whilk had lyggen foure daies stinkand in graue. Ana &thorn;are
was &thorn;e hous of Lazare and of Martha his sister. &THORN;are also dwelt Mary Cleophe. &THORN;is castell es bot a myle fra
Ierusalem. And a lytill &thorn;eine es &thorn;e place whare oure Lord was, when he wepid for &thorn;e citee of Ierusalem. And
<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;are nere es &thorn;e place whare oure Lady gafe sayn Thomas hir gyrdle after hir Assumpcioun. And a lytill &thorn;eine es
a stane wharon oure Lord satt and preched; and in &thorn;e same place he sall appere on &thorn;e day of dome. A lytill
fra &thorn;e mount of Olyuete es &thorn;e mount of Galile, whare &thorn;e apostels ware all togyder when Mary Mawdelayne talde
&thorn;am of Cristes rysing fra deed to lyfe. And in mydd way betwene mount Olyuete and mount Galile es a kirk,
whare &thorn;e aungell talde oure Lady before of hir dying.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.48.24" CORRESP="Cot.65.10">Fra Bethany to Iericho er fyue myle. Iericho was sum tyme a faire citee; bot it es destruyd, and so &thorn;er es
now bot a lytill village. &THORN;is citee tuke Iosue thurgh &thorn;e miracle of Godd, and kest it doune, and made it euen
playne with &thorn;e erthe, and commaunded &thorn;at it schuld neuer be bigged agayne; and also he weried all &thorn;a &thorn;at
bigged it agayne. Of &thorn;is citee was Zacheus, &thorn;at &thorn;e <TITLE>Gospell</TITLE> spekez off, &thorn;at clambe vp in til a sycomour tree for to
see oure Lord because he was a lytill man. Of &thorn;is citee also was Raab &thorn;e comoun womman, &thorn;at ressayued &thorn;e

<PB N="49">
messangers of Israel, whilk come for to aspye &thorn;e cuntree, and feled &thorn;am in hir hous amang towe of lyne and said
&thorn;ai ware went oute of &thorn;e citee are &thorn;e &yogh;ates ware spered, and afterwards by nyght scho lete &thorn;am ouer &thorn;e wall of
&thorn;e citee by a rape and saued &thorn;am fra &thorn;e deed. Wharfore afterward, when &thorn;e citee was wonne, scho was wele
rewarded, as scho was wele worthy. For Haly Writte saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Qui recipit prophetam in nomine prophete, mercedem
prophete accipiet</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Matt. x. 41.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "He &thorn;at ressayuez a prophete in name of me, he schall take hyre of a prophete."
<MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="folio">And &thorn;erfore scho had a speciale gift of Godd; for scho prophecied to &thorn;e forsaid messangers &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld wynne
all &thorn;at land,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Josh. ii. 9.</NOTE> and so it befell. And afterward wedded hir Salmon, &thorn;at was prince of &thorn;e kynredyn of Iuda; and
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and fro &thorn;at tyme was sche a worthi womman and serued God wel, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
of &thorn;aire kynredyn by processe of tyme come oure Lady saynt Mary, &thorn;e moder of oure Lord Ihesu Criste.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.49.9" CORRESP="Cot.65.30">Fra Bethany men gase to &thorn;e flum Iordan thurgh deserte; and it es nere a day iournee. Fra Bethany also
til a hill whare oure Lord fasted xl. days and xl. nyghtes er sex myle; and men callez &thorn;at hill Quarentane. And
&thorn;are &thorn;e fende come to tempte oure Lord and said vntill him &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Dic, ut lapides isti panes fiant</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Matt. iv. 3.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say,
"Bidd &thorn;at &thorn;ir stanes be breed." Apon &thorn;at hill in &thorn;at same place was sum tyme a faire kirke; bot now &thorn;er es na
thing left bot ane hermytage, whare a maner of Cristen men dwellez &thorn;at er called Georgienes, for sayn George
conuerted &thorn;am. And apon &thorn;at hill dwelled Abraham a grete whyle. Betwene &thorn;is hill and &thorn;e flum Iordan
rynnes a lytill bekk, of whilk &thorn;e water was sum tyme wonder bitter; bot, fra &thorn;e prophete Helizeus had blist it, it
was swete ynogh and hable for to drink. At &thorn;e fote of &thorn;is hill toward &thorn;e playne es a grete well, whilk rynnes in
to Iordan. Fra &thorn;is hill vnto Iericho es bot a myle, as men gas dounward to &thorn;e flum Iordan. And in &thorn;e way
as men gase to Iericho satt &thorn;e blynd man, cryand, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ihesu fili Dauid, miserere mei</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Mark x. 47.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Ihesu, Dauid
son, hafe mercy on me."</SEG>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">The passage in the French text omitted here is given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR> literally.</NOTE></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.12" N="12" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.13">
<PB N="50">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the Dede See, and of the flom Jordan; of the hed of seynt John the Baptist; and of the vsages of the Samaritanes.]</HEAD>

<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.50.4" CORRESP="Cot.66.19">THREE myle fra Iericho es &thorn;e Deed See. Betwene Iericho and &thorn;at see es &thorn;e cuntree of Engaddy.
And &thorn;are growed bawme sum tyme; bot it was translated fra &thorn;eine in till Egipte, whare &yogh;it &thorn;e treessez
&thorn;at &thorn;e bawme growez on er called &thorn;e vynes of Engaddy. On &thorn;e ta syde of &thorn;is see, as men commes
doune fra Araby, es a hill of Moabites, whilk es called Arnon.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">mounte of &thorn;e Moabytes, where there is a cave &thorn;at men clepen Karua, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Apon &thorn;is hill ledd Balach, Beor son, &thorn;e prophete
Balahaam for to wery &thorn;e childer of Israel. &THORN;is ilke Deed See departez &thorn;e land of Iudee and of Arabie; and it
lastez fra Zorea
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Soara, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. The same as Segor.</NOTE> vntill Araby. &THORN;e water of &thorn;is see es full bitter and salt &thorn;arwith; and, if &thorn;e erthe be sprenged
&thorn;erwith, it sall wax barayne and neuer bere fruyt. &THORN;is water chaungez &thorn;e coloure oft sythez. &THORN;is see castez a
thing oute of it whilke men callez asfaltum. And men may find ilk a day on ilke syde of &thorn;is see grete lumppes
&thorn;aroff, &yogh;a als grete as a hors, casten vp on &thorn;e land; and it es lyke pikk. And &thorn;erfor sum men callez it &thorn;e Lac
Asfaltit, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;e Lac of Pikke. It es also called a see, for &thorn;e greteness &thorn;eroff; for it es vii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> and foure
score furlanges on lenth and cl. on brede. And it es called &thorn;e Deed See for it rynnes no&yogh;t, ne now&thorn;er ebbez ne
flowez, bot standez ay still, and also for it bringes furth ne nurischez na qwikk thing. For it will ressayfe na
maner of qwikk thing in to it, now&thorn;er man ne beste, fisch ne fewle. And &thorn;at hase bene proued; for men hase
oft tymes casten &thorn;erin misdoers, &thorn;at hase bene foringged for &thorn;aire trespass,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">that han disserved to ben dede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and it kest &thorn;aim oute agayne alssone.</SEG>
Schippes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">schippes &hellip; to &thorn;e ground, not in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> or French texts.</NOTE> may nane ga &thorn;eron, bot if &thorn;ai be wele enoynted with pikk; for &thorn;er may na thing &thorn;at es deed comme
<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="folio">&thorn;eron &thorn;at ne it sinkes to &thorn;e ground als sone as it commes &thorn;eron, bot if it be enoynted with pikk. If men caste
in to it a lanterne light, it fletez abouen; and, if it be casten &thorn;erin vnlight, alssone it synkez to &thorn;e ground. <SEG ID="Eg.50.20" CORRESP="Cot.67.16">Also, if
men cast yrne &thorn;erin, it commes vp agayne and fletez abouen; and, if men cast a fether &thorn;erin, it synkez to &thorn;e
grund. And &thorn;at es agaynes kynde. And ri&yogh;t so for synne agaynes kynde ware fyue citeez, whilk stode &thorn;are

<PB N="51">
sum tyme, sunken and fordone, &thorn;at es to say Sodom and Gomorre, Aldama, Sobeym and Segor. Bot Segor at &thorn;e
praier of Loth was saued for &thorn;e mare party, for it stude on a hill; and &yogh;it in clere weder men may see of &thorn;e
walles &thorn;eroff abouen &thorn;e water. Nere &thorn;is see dare na man dwell, ne drink of &thorn;e water &thorn;eroff. Sum men, as I said
before, callez it &thorn;e Lac Asfaltit, and sum &thorn;e Fendez Lac,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">the Flom of Develes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sum &thorn;e Stynkand Flum, for &thorn;e water &thorn;eroff es stynkand.
By &thorn;is see syde growez tressez &thorn;at berez appels faire of coloure and delitable to behald; bot, when a man brekez
&thorn;am or scherez &thorn;am, he fyndes no&yogh;t in &thorn;am bot aschez and poudre and coles, in taken of &thorn;e vengeaunce &thorn;at Godd
tuke on &thorn;a fyue citeez and &thorn;e cuntree aboute &thorn;am, brynnand &thorn;aim with &thorn;e fire of hell.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.51.7" CORRESP="Cot.68.13">At
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">The passage about Lot and his daughters [in the French text], omitted here, is given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, which in other respects also closely follows <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Harley 4383">H</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e ri&yogh;t side of &thorn;is see
was Loth wyf turned intil a salt catte,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">dwelleth &yogh;it the wif of Loth in lyknesse of a salt ston, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. The reading "salt catte" is probably unique!</NOTE> because scho luked behind hir agaynes &thorn;e bidding of &thorn;e aungell &thorn;at tyme
&thorn;at Godd fordidd &thorn;e forsaid citeez. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at Loth was Aram son, &thorn;e whilk Aram was
Abraham bro&thorn;er; and Sara, Abraham wyf, and Melcha, Nachor wyf, ware Loth systers. Sara what tyme &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio">scho bare Ysaach was fourscore &yogh;ere alde and ten. Abraham also had ano&thorn;er son, &thorn;at hight Ismael; and he
was circumcized when he was xiiii. &yogh;ere alde. Bot Ysaach was circumcized when he was viii. days alde; and
&thorn;ai ware bathe circumcized on a day.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Wherefore the Jewes &thorn;at comen of Ysaacces lyne ben circumcyded the viii. day and the Sarrazines &thorn;at comen of Ysmaeles lyne ben circumcyded whan &thorn;ei ben xiiii. &yogh;eer of age, add <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.51.14" CORRESP="Cot.68.28">&THORN;e flum Iordan rynnes into &thorn;e Deed See; and &thorn;are it endez, for ferrer rynnes it no&yogh;t. And it es bot a myle
fra a kirk of sayne Iohn Baptiste toward &thorn;e west, whare sayne Iohn baptized oure Lord; and &thorn;are vsez Cristen
men to bathe &thorn;am comounly. And a myle fra Iordan es ano&thorn;er water, &thorn;at men callez Iaboth, whilk Iacob
passed ouer, when he come oute of Mesopotamy. &THORN;e flum Iordan es na grete water, bot it es ri&yogh;t plentifous of
fisch; and it commez fra &thorn;e mount Liban of twa welles &thorn;at springes vp &thorn;are, of whilk &thorn;e tane hat Ior and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er Dan; and of &thorn;ir twa welles takez it &thorn;e name. And it rynnez thurgh a cuntree &thorn;at es called Maran,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">a lake, &thorn;at is clept Maron (Merom), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and
seyne thurgh &thorn;e see of Tiberias and vnder &thorn;e hilles of Gelboe; and &thorn;are es a faire playne on ayther syde &thorn;e
ryuer. &THORN;e mount of Lyban lastes on lenth to &thorn;e deserte of Pharan; and &thorn;ai departe &thorn;e kyngdom of Surry and
&thorn;e cuntree of Fenice.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Ph&oelig;nicia.</NOTE> Apon &thorn;ir hilles growez cedres wonder hye, and &thorn;ai bere lang appels, whilk er als grete as
a mannes heued. &THORN;e flum Iordan departez Galilee and &thorn;e land of Ydumee and &thorn;e land of Betron; and in sum

<PB N="52">
place it rynnez vnder &thorn;e erthe vntil a faire playne &thorn;at men callez Meldan,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Meldan in Sarmoyz, &thorn;at is  to seye feyre or markett in here langage, be cause &thorn;at &thorn;ere is often feyres in &thorn;at playn, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;are es Iordan ri&yogh;t brade. In &thorn;at
playne es &thorn;e sepulcre of Iob. In &thorn;is flum was Criste baptized of sayne Iohn; and &thorn;are was herd &thorn;e voice of &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="folio">Fader sayand, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Hic est filius meus dilectus, in quo michi bene complacui</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Here es my son &thorn;at I
luffe, of wham I am wele payd. Heres him." And &thorn;are &thorn;e Haly Gaste descended on him in likness of a
douffe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">a colver, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and so was &thorn;are at his baptizing all &thorn;e Trinytee. Thurgh &thorn;at flum Iordan passed &thorn;e childer of Israel
drye fote; and &thorn;ai sett grete stanes in myddes of &thorn;e water in taken of &thorn;e miracle. Also in &thorn;at flum Naaman of
Siry bathed him seuen sythes, and he was clensed of lepre and made fisch hale.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">toke his hele, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Aboute &thorn;e flum Iordan er
many kirkes, and cristen men dwelland at &thorn;am. And a lytill &thorn;erfra es a citee &thorn;at es called Hayla,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Ai. "Hayla" (Haylla, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>) seems to represent "<HI REND="i">Hay la</HI> quelle" of the French text.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk
Iosue enseged and tuke. Be&yogh;ond Iordan es &thorn;e vale of Mambree, and it es ri&yogh;t a faire vale. Also twa myle fra
&thorn;e hill &thorn;at I spakk off before, whare oure Lord fasted xl. days and xl. nyghtes, toward Galile es a hie hill and
vp on &thorn;at hill ledd &thorn;e fende oure Lord, and schewed him all &thorn;e kyngdommes of &thorn;e werld and said vntill him,
"All &thorn;ir," quod he, "salle I giffe &thorn;e, with &thorn;i &thorn;ou will falle doun and adoure me."</SEG>
</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.52.13" CORRESP="Cot.70.4">And &yogh;e sall vnderstand &thorn;at for to ga fra &thorn;e Deed See estward oute of &thorn;e marchez of &thorn;e land of promission es
a strang castell and a faire, standand on a hill &thorn;at men callez Carras, &thorn;at es to say Mount Real.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Carak en Sarmoyz, &thorn;at is to seyne Ryally, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is castell gert
Bawdewyne make, &thorn;at was king of Ierusalem
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">France, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and conquerde all &thorn;at land, and inhabited it with Cristen men.
And vnder &thorn;at castell es a faire toune, &thorn;at men calles Soboach, wharin many Cristen men dwellez suerly ynogh
<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio">vnder tribute. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to Nazareth, wharoff oure Lord had his o toname. And fra &thorn;eine to Ierusalem
es iii. day iourneez. And men gase thurgh &thorn;e cuntree of Galile thurgh Ramathaim Sophim and by &thorn;e hilles of
Effraym, whare Helchana dwelt and Anna, Samuel &thorn;e prophete fader and moder. &THORN;are was Samuel borne; bot
he was grauen on &thorn;e Mount Ioy, as I said before. And &thorn;an commes men to Sylo, whare &thorn;e arke of Godd
was keped vnder Hely &thorn;e preste of &thorn;e lawe. And &thorn;are made &thorn;e folk of Ebron sacrifice till oure Lord. And
&thorn;are spak oure Lord first vnto Samuel. And &thorn;are nere, at &thorn;e left syde, es Gabaon and Rama Beniamyn, of whilk
Haly Writte spekez. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to Sychem, &thorn;at by ano&thorn;er name es called Sychar; and it es in &thorn;e
cuntree of Samary, and it es x. myle fra Ierusalem. Sum men callez it Neopolis, &thorn;at es to say &thorn;e new citee.

<PB N="53">
&THORN;are fast by es Iacob well, whare oure Lord spak to &thorn;e womman Samaritane. And &thorn;are was sum tyme a kirk;
bot it es now destruyd. &THORN;are be syde &thorn;at well gert Ieroboam kyng of Israel make twa calfez of golde, and sent
&thorn;e tane of &thorn;am to Dan and &thorn;e to&thorn;er to Bethel, and comaunded &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld wirschepe &thorn;am in steed of
goddes. A myle fra Sychar es a citee &thorn;at men callez Luza,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">cytee of Deluze (<HI REND="i">sc.</HI> cite de Luze), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whare Abraham dwelled sum tyme. And a lytill
&thorn;eine es &thorn;e sepulcre of Ioseph Iacob son, &thorn;at gouerned Egipte; and fra Egipte ware his banes broght and
grauen &thorn;are. In &thorn;e citee of Sychem was Dyna Iacob doghter rauyst; for wham hir bre&thorn;er sloghe mykill of &thorn;e folk
of &thorn;at citee. A lytill fra &thorn;at citee es &thorn;e mount Garisym, whare &thorn;e Samaritanes makes &thorn;aire sacrificez. In &thorn;at hill
<MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="folio">schuld Abraham hafe offerd his son Ysaach til oure Lorde. And &thorn;are nere es &thorn;e vale of Dothaym. And in &thorn;at
vale es &thorn;e cisterne, wharin Ioseph was casten of hys bre&thorn;er before &thorn;ai salde him to &thorn;e Ismaelites; and it es twa
myle fra Sychar. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to a citee of Samary &thorn;at es called Sebaste
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">gon men to Samarye, &thorn;at men clepen now Sebast, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and it es &thorn;e chieff citee of &thorn;at
cuntree, and it standez amanges hilles,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">betwene &thorn;e hille of Aygnes (entre montaignes!), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> as Ierusalem duse. Bot &thorn;at citee es no&yogh;t now so grete as it was sum tyme.
&THORN;are was sayne Iohn Baptist grauen betwene twa prophetez, &thorn;at es to say Helizeus and Abdias. Bot he was heueded
in &thorn;e castell of Macheron beside &thorn;e Deed See; and his disciples bare him to Sebaste. And &thorn;are gert Iulyan
Apostata take his banes and brynne &thorn;am, for he was emperour &thorn;at tyme; and &thorn;e askes of him ware casten in &thorn;e
wynd. Bot &thorn;e finger with whilk sayne Iohn schewed oure Lord, sayand, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ecce Agnus Dei, &amp;c.</Q>, myght no&yogh;t be
brynt. &THORN;is fynger sayne Tecle &thorn;e virgyn gert bere in to mountes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">in to the hille of Sebast, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;are es done grete wirschepe &thorn;erto. In
&thorn;at place was sum tyme a faire kirke; bot now it es destruyd, and many o&thorn;er kirkes also &thorn;at ware &thorn;are. &THORN;are
was &thorn;e heued of sayne Iohn closed in a wall. Bot &thorn;e emperour Theodosius gert take it oute; and he fand it
lapped in a clathe all blody. And so gert he bere it to Constantinople; and &thorn;are es &yogh;it &thorn;e ta half &thorn;eroff, and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er half es at Rome in &thorn;e kirke of sayne Siluestre.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5"><ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> adds, "where be nonnes of an hundred orders (the translator mistaking "cordelers" for "c. ordres"), and it is &yogh;it all broylly as &thorn;ough it were half brent. For the emperour Iulianus aboueseyd, of his cursedness and malice, let brennen &thorn;at partie with the o&thorn;er bones, and &yogh;it it scheweth."</NOTE></SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.53.20" CORRESP="Cot.72.8">And &thorn;e vessell whare in his heued was layd, when it was
smyten off, es at Geen, and men dos grete wirschepe &thorn;arto. Sum men saise &thorn;at sayne Iohn heued es at
<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio">Amyas in Pykardy; and sum saise &thorn;at it es &thorn;e heued of sayn Iohn &thorn;e bischope. I wate no&yogh;t; Godd wate.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.53.23" CORRESP="Cot.72.16">Fra Sebaste to Ierusalem er xii. myle. And betwene &thorn;e hilles of &thorn;is cuntree es a well &thorn;at chaungez his

<PB N="54">
coloure foure tymes in &thorn;e &yogh;ere. For sum tyme it es grene and sum tyme reed, sum tyme trublee and sum tyme
clere; and men callez &thorn;at well Iol. &THORN;e folk of &thorn;at cuntree er called Samaritanes, and &thorn;ai ware conuerted and
baptized thurgh &thorn;e apostels. Bot &thorn;ai hald no&yogh;t &thorn;e apostels techinges, and so &thorn;ai er fallen in errours and
haldez a secte by &thorn;am self and a lawe diuerse fra &thorn;e lawe of Cristen and of Iewes, Sarzenes and Payenes.
Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai trowe in a Godd, and saise &thorn;er es nane bot he, &thorn;at made all and all schall deme. &THORN;ai kepe &thorn;e
fyue bukes of &thorn;e <TITLE>Bible</TITLE> efter &thorn;e letter, and vsez &thorn;e <TITLE>sawter</TITLE> as &thorn;e Iews duse. &THORN;ai say &thorn;ai er verray Goddes childer
and better luffed with Godd &thorn;an any o&thorn;er men. &THORN;aire clething also es diuerse fra o&thorn;er men, and &thorn;aire heuedes
&thorn;ai wende in a reed lynnen clathe to be knawen fra o&thorn;er. For &thorn;e Sarzenes lappez &thorn;aire heuedes in whyte, and
Cristen men &thorn;at dwelles &thorn;are in blewe, and Iews in &yogh;alow clathe. For &thorn;are dwellez many Iews, payand tribute
as Cristen men duse. And if &yogh;e will witt what kyn lettres &thorn;e Iews vsez, here &yogh;e schall fynd &thorn;am sette all redy
and &thorn;e names of &thorn;e lettres also, as &thorn;ai call &thorn;am:&mdash;Aleph, Beth, Gymel, Deleth, He, Vau, Zai, Heth, Theth, Ioth,
Caph, Lameth, Mem, Nun, Sameth, Ain, Fe, Sade, Coph, Res, Sen, Tau.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Over these letters are placed those of the English alphabet in regular order from <HI REND="i">a</HI> to <HI REND="i">y</HI>, excluding <HI REND="i">j</HI> and <HI REND="i">w</HI>. The forms of the Hebrew characters are too corrupt to be worth reproducing.</NOTE> Now will I sette &thorn;e figures of &thorn;e lettres
&thorn;at &thorn;ai vse &hellip;</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.13" N="13" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.14">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the prouince of Galilee, and where Antecrist schall be born; of Nazareth; of the age of oure Lady; of the day of doom; and of the customes of Jacobites, Surryenes; and of the vsages of Georgyenes.]</HEAD>

<MILESTONE N="45" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.54.17" CORRESP="Cot.73.7">FRA &thorn;is cuntree &thorn;at I hafe spoken off men gase to &thorn;e playne of Galilee and lefes &thorn;e hilles on &thorn;e ta syde.
Galile es a cuntree of &thorn;e land of promissioun; and in &thorn;at cuntree es &thorn;e citee of Naym and &thorn;e citee of
Capharnaum and of Corozaim and of Betsayda, whare sayne Petre and saynt Andrew was borne.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">The sentence [from the French text] omitted here is translated in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG>
<SEG ID="Eg.54.20" CORRESP="Cot.73.17">And at Corsaym sall Antecriste be borne. Bot sum men sayse he schall be borne in Babiloyne, and &thorn;erfore
saise &thorn;e prophecie &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">De Babilonia exiet Coluber, qui totum <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">mundum</SUPPLIED> deuorabit</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Of

<PB N="55">
Babiloyne sall a nedder
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">a worm, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> comme, &thorn;at sall deuoure all &thorn;e werld." And he &thorn;is antecriste sall be nurischt in
Bethsaida, and he sall regne in Corozaym; and &thorn;erfore saise Haly Writte of &thorn;aim &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ve tibi, Corozaym! Ve
tibi, Bethsaida! Ve tibi, Capharnaum!</Q> &thorn;at es to say, "Wa be to &thorn;e Corozaym ! Wa be to &thorn;e, Bethsaida! Wa be
to &thorn;e, Capharnaum." Also &thorn;e Cane of Galilee es &thorn;are, iiii. myle fra Nazareth; and &thorn;are was sayn Symon borne.
&THORN;are also did oure Lord &thorn;e first miracle at &thorn;e wedding of Architriclyne,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> architriclinus, the governor of the feast, John ii. 8.</NOTE> when he turned water in to wyne. In
&thorn;e marchez of Galilee betwene &thorn;e mountaynes was &thorn;e arch of Godd taken. And on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde es &thorn;e hill of
Endor in Hermon.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">mownt Hendor or Hermon. And &thorn;ere about goth the broke of <HI REND="i">Torrens Cison</HI>, &thorn;at somtyme was clept the broke Radumu, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And a lytill &thorn;eine Barach, Abymalech son, and &thorn;e prophetisse Debbora ouercome &thorn;e oste
of Ydumee, when Cisara &thorn;e kyng was slayne thurgh Iabel, Aber wyf, as tellez &thorn;e <TITLE>Byble</TITLE>. And in &thorn;at same place
<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio">Gedeon and ccc. men with him discoumfit three kynges, &thorn;at es to say Zeb, Zebee, and Salmana, and pursued
ouer &thorn;e flum Iordan and slew &thorn;am and &thorn;aire folk for &thorn;e maste party. Fyue myle fra Naym es &thorn;e citee of
Iesrael, &thorn;e whilk also es called Zaraym. Of &thorn;at citee was Iesabel, &thorn;e wikked qwene, &thorn;at gert sla vnri&yogh;twisely
Naboth for his vyne&yogh;arde. A lytill fra &thorn;is citee es &thorn;e felde of Mageddo, whare &thorn;e kyng of Samary slewe Iosias
&thorn;e kyng of Iuda, &thorn;e whilk efterward was broght to &thorn;e mount Syon and grauen &thorn;are. Also a myle fra Iesrael er &thorn;e
mountes of Gelboe, whare kyng Saul and Ionathas his son and a grete noumer of &thorn;e childer of Israel ware slayne
in bataile. Wharfore kyng David weried &thorn;e forsaid mountes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">cursed hem, as holy writt seyth, <HI REND="i">Montes Gelboe nec ros nec pluuia</HI>, &amp;c. (ii. Sam. i. 21), &thorn;at is to  seye, "&yogh;ee hilles of Gelboe mou&thorn;er dew ne reyn com vpon &yogh;ou," <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And a myle &thorn;eine, toward &thorn;e este, es a citee &thorn;at
men callez Citople or Bethsaym. Apon &thorn;e walles of &thorn;at citee hinged &thorn;e Philistenes &thorn;e heued of kyng Saul.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.55.17" CORRESP="Cot.74.32">Fra &thorn;eine men gase thurgh &thorn;e playne of Galile to Nazareth, whilk was sum tyme a grete citee; bot now
&thorn;er es no&yogh;t bot a lytill village, and it es no&yogh;t walled aboute. In Nazareth was oure Lady borne, bot scho was
consayued at Ierusalem. Of Nazareth tuke oure Lord his to name. And &thorn;are wedded Ioseph oure Lady,
when scho was xiiii. &yogh;ere alde. And &thorn;are &thorn;e aungell Gabriel grette oure Lady, sayand &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Aue, gratia plena!
Dominus tecum</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Hayle, Mary, full of grace! Godd es with &thorn;e." And in &thorn;at same place es a
chapell, bigged by syde a piler of a kirk &thorn;at was &thorn;are in alde tyme; and &thorn;are es grete offering of Cristen
<MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="folio">pilgrimes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">And this salutacioun was don in a place of a gret awteer of a faire chirche &thorn;at was wont to be som tyme, but is now all downe; and men han made a lityll resceyt besyde a pylere of &thorn;at chirche for to resceyue the offrynges of pilgrimes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is chapell gers &thorn;e Sarzenes kepe ri&yogh;t straytely by cause of auauntage of &thorn;e offerandes. And &thorn;are er
wonder euill Sarzenes, and mare cruell &thorn;an er in any o&thorn;er place; for &thorn;ai hafe destruyd all &thorn;e kirkez &thorn;at ware

<PB N="56">
wount to be &thorn;are. And &thorn;are es &thorn;e well of Gabriell, whare oure Lord was wont to bathe him, when he was
&yogh;ung; and at &thorn;at well was he wount to fecche his moder water; and &thorn;are was scho wount to wasch his clathez.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">clowtes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
Fra Ierusalem to Nazareth er iii. day iourneez. And &thorn;are was oure Lord nurischt. Nazareth es als mykill at say
as Floure of Gardyne; and it may wele be called so, for &thorn;are was nurischt &thorn;e Floure of Lyf, &thorn;at es to say oure
Lord Ihesu Criste. And twa myle fra Nazareth, in &thorn;e way as men gase to &thorn;e citee of Acon, es &thorn;e citee of Sephor.
And halfe a myle fra Nazareth es &thorn;e leep &thorn;at oure Lord leped fra &thorn;e Iews, when &thorn;ai ledd him apon a hie roche
to hafe casten him downe and slayne him; bot he passed thurgh &thorn;am and leped till ano&thorn;er roche, whare his
steppes er &yogh;it sene. And &thorn;erfore saise sum men, when &thorn;ai hafe drede of thefez, &thorn;is verse &thorn;at es writen here,
<Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ihesus autem transiens per medium illorum ibat</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Luke, iv. 30.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say "Ihesus furth passand &yogh;ode thurgh &thorn;e middes of
&thorn;am." And &thorn;ai say also &thorn;ir versez of &thorn;e <TITLE>sawter</TITLE> buke, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Irruat super eos formido et pauor in magnitudine brachii
tui, Domine. Fiant immobiles, quasi lapis, donec pertransiat populus tuus, Domine, donec pertransiat
populus tuus iste, quem possedisti</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Exod. xv. 16.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Fall on &thorn;aim drede in &thorn;e greteness of &thorn;ine arm, Lord.
<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio">Be &thorn;ai vnmouand as a stane vnto &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;i folk passe, Lord, vnto &thorn;i folk passe, whilk &thorn;ou boght." And
when &thorn;is es said, a man may ga seurly withouten lettyng. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at oure lady saynt Mary,
when scho bare Criste, was of xv. &yogh;ere elde, and with him scho was in erthe xxxiii. &yogh;ere and iii. monethes. And
after his passioun scho liffed xxiiii. &yogh;ere, and so scho liffed in &thorn;is erthe lxxii. &yogh;ere and three monethes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.56.17" CORRESP="Cot.76.10">Fra Nazareth to &thorn;e mount Thabor es iii. myle, and it es a faire hill and a hie. And &thorn;are was sum tyme a
toune and many kirkes, bot now &thorn;ai er all destruyd. Bot &yogh;it &thorn;er es a place &thorn;at &thorn;ai call &thorn;e Scole of oure Lord,
whare he teched his disciples &thorn;e priuetez of heuen. And at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;at mount Melchisedech, &thorn;at was kyng of
Ierusalem and Goddes preste, mette Abraham in &thorn;e commyng doune fra &thorn;at mount, when he come fra &thorn;e
descomfiture of his enmys. And on &thorn;at hill oure Lord transfigured him self before Petre, Iames and Iohn, whare
&thorn;ai sawe him spekand with
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">sawghe gostly, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR></NOTE> Moyses and Helyas. And &thorn;erfore said Petre, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Bonum est nos hic esse. Faciamus
hic tria tabernacula</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Matt. xvii. 4.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say "It es gude to be here. Late vs make three tabernacles." And Criste bad
&thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld tell na man &thorn;at visioun vnto &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he ware risen fra deed to lyfe. And apon &thorn;at same hill
and in &thorn;at same place apon &thorn;e day of dome sall foure aungels blawe &thorn;aire bemes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">trompes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and raise all &thorn;at er deed vnto
<MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e lyf. And &thorn;ai schall com in body and saule before Godd &thorn;e souerayne Iugge in &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat, to take
&thorn;aire dome apon Pasch day, in &thorn;e tyme of Cristes resurreccioun. For, as doctoures saise, &thorn;e same tyme &thorn;at he

<PB N="57">
went till hell and heried it, &thorn;e same tyme sall he spoile &thorn;e werld and take his frendes and lede &thorn;am to ioy
withouten end, and dampne &thorn;e wikked til ay lastand payne.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and &thorn;anne schall euery man haue after his dissert, ou&thorn;er gode or euyll, but &yogh;it the mercy of God passe his rightwisnesse, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG>
</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.57.3" CORRESP="Cot.77.7">Also a myle fra &thorn;e mount Thabor es &thorn;e mount Hermon; and &thorn;are was &thorn;e citee of Naym before &thorn;e &yogh;ates of
whilk oure Lorde raised &thorn;e widow son fra deed to lyfe. Also three myle fra Nazareth es &thorn;e castell of Saffra,
whare Zebedeus and Alpheus childer ware borne. And seuen myle fra Nazareth es &thorn;e mount Cain; and
vnderneth it es a well, whare Lamech slew Cayn with ane arowe,</SEG> supposing he had bene a wylde beste.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">For this Kaym wente &thorn;orgh breres and busshes as a wylde best. And he had lyued fro the tyme of Adam his fadir vnto the tyme of Noe; and so he lyuede nygh to m<HI REND="sup">l</HI>m<HI REND="sup">l</HI> &yogh;eer. And this Lamech was all blynd for elde, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE><SEG ID="Eg.57.6" CORRESP="Cot.77.19">Fra
Saffra gase men to a citee &thorn;at es called Tyberias, &thorn;e whilk standez apon &thorn;e see of Galile. And, if all it be
called a see, neuer&thorn;eles it es na see ne arme of &thorn;e see, bot a staunke of fresch water; and it es nere a hundreth
furlanges lang and fourty on brede, and &thorn;er er many gude fischez &thorn;erin, and it commes oute of Iordan and rynnez
thurgh &thorn;e myddes of &thorn;e citee.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and hathe with in him gret plentee of gode fissche, and renneth in to flom Iordan. The cytee is not full gret, but it hath gode bathes with in him, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And it es ri&yogh;t profitable for &thorn;e cuntree. And &thorn;are &thorn;are it and Iordan partes es a
grete brigg, by &thorn;e whilk men wendez oute of &thorn;e land of beheste in to &thorn;e land of Basan and in to &thorn;e land of
Gerassen, &thorn;e whilk marchez apon Iordan.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.57.13" CORRESP="Cot.77.30">And fra &thorn;eine may men wende to Damasc on three days, thurgh &thorn;e cuntree of Traconye,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Trachonitis.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk lastez
fra Hermon to &thorn;e see of Galilee, &thorn;e whilk also es called &thorn;e see of Tyberias or &thorn;e Staunkes of Genasareth. And
<MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;is diuersetee of names it hase of &thorn;e citez &thorn;at standes &thorn;er apon. Apon &thorn;is see &yogh;ode oure Lord drie fote, when he
said to Petre, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Modice fidei, quare dubitasti?</Q>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Matt. xiv. 31.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;ou man of litil faith, whi had &thorn;ou doute?" And
&thorn;at was when he went to Criste on &thorn;e water, and was in poynt to drowne, and Criste tuke him by &thorn;e hand and
said &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at I said before. And also Criste apperde til his disciples after his resurreccioun fischand in &thorn;is
see and filled &thorn;aire nettes full of fisch, and &thorn;ai bro&yogh;t him parte of a roste fisch and a hony cambe. In &thorn;is see also
fisched Petre and Andrew, Iames and Iohn, when Criste called &thorn;am and bad &thorn;am folow him, and &thorn;ai alssone
left schippe and nettes and folowed him. In &thorn;is cite of Tiberias es &thorn;e tabil on whilk oure Lord ete with his
disciples after his resurreccioun, of whilk etyng Haly Writte saise &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Cognouerunt Dominum in fractione
panis</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">Luke xxiv. 35.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;ai knew oure Lord in breking of breed." Besyde &thorn;is citee es a hill whare oure Lord fedd
v<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men with fyue laues and twa fisches. In &thorn;is citee also a wikked man on a tyme kest a brynnand fyrebrand

<PB N="58">
at oure Lord for to stirre him til ire and hitt him on &thorn;e heued, &thorn;e whilk brand efterwardes hitt on &thorn;e erthe
and stakk still &thorn;erin and growed, and by process of tyme it wex a grete tree, and &yogh;itt it growes &thorn;are.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and the bark &thorn;ere of is all lyk coles, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Also at
&thorn;e heued of &thorn;is see of Galile, toward &thorn;e north, es a castell <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;at</SUPPLIED> es called Sephor nere Capharnaum, and in all &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="48" UNIT="folio">haly land es &thorn;er noght a stranger castell &thorn;an it es. In &thorn;at castell es a gude litil toune, whilk hase &thorn;e same name
&thorn;at &thorn;e castell hase.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and &thorn;ere is a gode toun benethe, &thorn;at is clept also Saphor, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And in &thorn;at castell was saynt Anne oure Lady moder borne; and &thorn;are was &thorn;e hous of
Centurio. &THORN;at cuntree es called Galilea Gentium, and it fell in &thorn;e lote
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Galille of folk &thorn;at weren taken to  tribute, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of Zabulon and of Neptalim. And as
men commez fra &thorn;is castell at xxx. myle es &thorn;e citee of Dan, &thorn;e whilk also es called Cesarea Philippi; and it
standez at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;e mount Liban, whare &thorn;e flum Iordan begynnez. And &thorn;are also begynnez &thorn;e land of
beheste and lastez vnto Bersabee in lenth for to ga fra &thorn;e north toward &thorn;e south, and it es nere ix<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> myle.
And on brede it lastes fra Iericho to Iaffe, and &thorn;at es fourty myle of &thorn;e mylez of Lumbardy, or of oure cuntree,
for &thorn;ai er bath ane. Bot I speke no&yogh;t of leeges of Fraunce, Gascoyne, Prouince, or Almayne,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">myles of Gascoyne, ne of the prouynce of Almayne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whare &thorn;ai hafe
grete myles.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.58.13" CORRESP="Cot.78.36">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e Haly Land es in Surry. For Surry lastez fra &thorn;e desertes of Araby vnto
Cicil, &thorn;at es to say Ermony &thorn;e mare, for to ga fra &thorn;e south to &thorn;e north; and fra &thorn;e este syde to &thorn;e west syde it
lastez fra &thorn;e grete desertes of Araby vnto &thorn;e west see. Bot in &thorn;is rewme of Surry er many rewmes contende,
&thorn;at es to say Iudee, Palestine, Galile, Sem Cecil and many o&thorn;er cuntreez. And in &thorn;at cuntree and many o&thorn;er
aboute it &thorn;er es swilk a custom &thorn;at, when twa rewmes er at were and ow&thorn;er party ensegez citee, toune or castell,
<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;an, in steed of messangers to ga betwene &thorn;e partys, &thorn;ai ordayne dowfes for to bere lettres, and bindez &thorn;am aboute
&thorn;e nekkes of &thorn;e dowfes, and &thorn;an &thorn;ai late &thorn;am flie furth; and &thorn;ai, thurgh comoun custom and vsage &thorn;at &thorn;ai er wont
vnto, fliez to &thorn;e to&thorn;er party, and when &thorn;e letters er tane fra &thorn;aire neckes &thorn;ai flie agayne whare &thorn;ai ware
nurischt.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.58.22" CORRESP="Cot.79.18">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at amanges &thorn;e Sarezenes in diuerse placez &thorn;er dwellez many Cristen men vnder
tribute, &thorn;e whilk vsez diuerse lawez and custommes after &thorn;e constitucioun and &thorn;e ordinaunce of &thorn;e rewmes
whare &thorn;ai dwell. Neuer&thorn;eles all er &thorn;ai baptized and trowez in Godd, Fader and Sonne and Haly Gaste. Bot &yogh;it
&thorn;ai faile in sum articles of oure beleue. &THORN;are er sum Cristen men &thorn;at er called Iacobynes, &thorn;e whilk sayn Iame &thorn;e

<PB N="59">
apostel conuerted, and sayn Iohn &thorn;e evaungelist baptized &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai say and affermez &thorn;at confessioun suld be
made all anely to Godd and no&yogh;t to man. For &thorn;ai say Godd bad neuer &thorn;at a man schuld schryfe him till ano&thorn;er
man, and &thorn;erfore Dauid saise in &thorn;e <TITLE>sawter</TITLE>, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Confitebor tibi, Domine, in toto corde meo</Q>,
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">Ps. ix. 2.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Lord, I
sall schryfe me to &thorn;e in all my hert." And in ano&thorn;er place he saise &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Delictum meum tibi cognitum feci</Q>,
<NOTE N="2" RESP="GW">Ps. xxxi. 5.</NOTE>
&thorn;at es to say "Lord, to &thorn;e I sall make aknawen my trespas." And also he saise &thorn;us, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Deus meus es tu, et
confitebor tibi</Q>,
<NOTE N="3" RESP="GW">Ps. cxvii. 28.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;ou ert my Godd, and to &thorn;e I sall be schrifen." And &yogh;it he saise in ano&thorn;er place,
<Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quoniam cogitacio hominis confitebitur tibi</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Ps. lxxv. 11.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "For thoght of man sall schryfe to &thorn;e." For &thorn;ai say
<MILESTONE N="49" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at a man schuld all anely ask him forgifnes wham he trespast to. Bot Godd ordayned neuer, ne na prophete,
as &thorn;ai say, &thorn;at a man suld schew his synnes til any bot all anely to Godd. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai alegge &thorn;e auctoritez of
&thorn;e <TITLE>sawter</TITLE> &thorn;at I talde &yogh;ow before. &THORN;ai say also &thorn;at saynt Austyne and sayne Gregore and o&thorn;er doctours affermez
&thorn;e same. For saynt Austyne saise on &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Qui scelera sua cogitat et conuersus fuerit, veniam sibi credat</Q>,
&thorn;at es to say, "Wha so knawez his synnez and es turned, he may trowe to hafe forgifnes." And sayn Gregore
sayse on &thorn;is maner, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Dominus potius mentem quam verba considerat</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Oure Lord takes mare hede
to tho&yogh;t &thorn;an to word." Saynt Hilari also saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Longorum temporum crimina in ictu oculi perient, si corde nata
fuerit contempcio</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5"><HI REND="i">compunccio</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Synnez &thorn;at er done of lang tyme sall perisch in twynkelyng of ane egh, if
despysing of &thorn;am be borne in a mannes hert." Swilk auctoritez &thorn;ai alegge in &thorn;aire awen langage and no&yogh;t in
Latyne; and for &thorn;ir auctoritez &thorn;ai say &thorn;at men schall schryfe &thorn;am all anely to Godd and no&yogh;t to man. And
&thorn;erfore, when &thorn;ai will schryfe &thorn;am, &thorn;ai make a fyre besyde &thorn;am and castez &thorn;erin encense, and, when &thorn;e reke gase
vp, &thorn;ai say, "I schryfe me to Godd and askez forgifnes of my synne." And, no&yogh;t for&thorn;i in alde tyme &thorn;is was &thorn;e
maner of schryfing, bot sayn Petre, and o&thorn;er apostels &thorn;at come seyne, thurgh gude skille has ordaynd &thorn;at men
sall schryue &thorn;am to prestez, &thorn;at er men as &thorn;ai er. For &thorn;ai considred &thorn;at men may giffe na gude medecyne to a
<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="folio">man &thorn;at es seke bot if &thorn;ai knawe &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e sekeness; and ri&yogh;t so a man may gyffe no couenable penaunce
bot if he knawe &thorn;e qualitee and &thorn;e quantitee of &thorn;e synne. For a maner of synne es mare greuous &thorn;an ano&thorn;er,
and in sum place mare &thorn;an in sum o&thorn;er, and in sum tyme mare &thorn;an in sum o&thorn;er; and &thorn;erfore it es nedefull &thorn;at a
man knawe &thorn;e synne with &thorn;e circumstauncez &thorn;at sall enioyne couenable penaunce.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.59.26" CORRESP="Cot.80.25">O&thorn;er Cristen men &thorn;er er &thorn;at er called Surrianez. &THORN;ai hald a lawe in meen betwene vs and &thorn;e Grekez. And
&thorn;ai late &thorn;aire berdes grow as &thorn;e Grekez dus, and makes &thorn;e sacrement of &thorn;e awter of soure bred as &thorn;e Grekez
duse, and vsez &thorn;e lettres of Grewe,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">And in here langage &thorn;ei vsen lettres of Sarazines; but after the misterie of holy chirche thei vsen lettres of Grece, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and schryfez &thorn;am as &thorn;e Iacobynes duse. Also &thorn;er er o&thorn;er &thorn;at er called

<PB N="60">
Georgienes, whilk sayn George conuerted; and him &thorn;ai honoure and wirschepes before all o&thorn;er halowes. And
all &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;aire crownes schauen, &thorn;e clerkes rownde and &thorn;e lawed men foure cornerd. And &thorn;ai hald &thorn;e lawe of
Grekez. &YOGH;it es &thorn;are ano&thorn;er of folk, &thorn;e whilk er called Cristen men of gyrdils, for &thorn;ai er gyrdid as frere menoures
er. Sum also er called Nestorianes, sum Arrianes, sum Nubienes, sum Gregorienes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">summe of Grees, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sum Indynes, whilk er of
Prestre Iohn land. All er &thorn;ai called Cristned men; and many of &thorn;e articles of oure beleue &thorn;ai hald and vsez,
bot neuer&thorn;eles in many poyntes &thorn;ai vary fra vs and fra oure faith. All &thorn;aire variaunce ware to mykil to tell.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.14" N="14" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.15">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XIV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the cytee of Damasce; of iii. weyes to Jerusalem, on be londe and be see, another more be londe than be see, and the thridde weye to Jerusalem all be londe.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.60.10" CORRESP="Cot.81.10">SEN I hafe talde &yogh;ow of many maners of men &thorn;at dwellez in cuntrez beforesaid, now will I turne agayne
<MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="folio">to my way and tell how men sall comme fra &thorn;ase cuntreez vnto &thorn;ise cuntreez agayne. Qwha so will
comme fra &thorn;e land of Galile &thorn;at I spakk off before, he schall ga by Damasc, whilk es a faire citee and
full of gude marchandyse. And it es three iournez fra &thorn;e see, and fra Ierusalem fyue iournes. Bot &thorn;ai cary
marchandyse apon camels, mules, dromedaries and hors, and o&thorn;er maner of bestez; and &thorn;ase marchandisez er
broght by see fra Inde, fra Persy, fra Caldee, fra Ermony, and fra many o&thorn;er regiounes. &THORN;is citee founded
Eleazar of Damasc, &thorn;at was &thorn;e son of &thorn;e steward
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at was &yogh;oman and despenser, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of Abraham &thorn;e patriark, and &thorn;erfore was &thorn;e citee called
Damasc after his surename; for he wend to hafe bene lord of &thorn;at cuntree after Abraham, for Abraham &thorn;at tyme
had no&yogh;t geten his son Ysaac. In &thorn;at place slew Cayn his bro&thorn;er Abel. Besyde Damasc es &thorn;e mount Seyr. In
Damasch er many welles, bathe within &thorn;e citee and withouten; and &thorn;er er also many faire gardyns ri&yogh;t plentifous
of fruyte. &THORN;er es nower whare swilke ano&thorn;er citee of gardynes and of fruyte. In &thorn;at citee also es wonder
mykill folk, and it es wele walled aboute with a dowble wall. In &thorn;at citee also dwellez many phisicienes; and
&thorn;are vsed sayn Paule sum tyme &thorn;e craft of phisic, before &thorn;at he was conuerted, and sayne Luc was his disciple to

<PB N="61">
lere phisic, and many o&thorn;er ma. For in &thorn;at citee held he scole in &thorn;at science, bot efterwardes he was a phisiciene
of saules. In Damasc was he conuerted and dwelled &thorn;erin three days and three nyghtes, and now&thorn;er ete ne
<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio">drank ne sawe na sight with his bodily eghen, bot in spirit he was rauischt intill heuen, whare he sawe heuenly
priuetez. A litill fra Damasc es a castell &thorn;at es called Arkes; and it es a gude castell and a strang. Fra
Damasc men commes by a place &thorn;at es called Nostre Dame de Sardenake,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Oure Lady of Sardenak, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> fyue myle on &thorn;is syde Damasc; and
it es apon a roche. And it es a faire place and a delitable, and &thorn;er semez, as it ware, a castell, and so &thorn;are was
sum tyme. And &thorn;are es a faire kirk, whare Cristen mounkes and nonnes dwellez. Vnder &thorn;e kirk also es a
vowte, whare Cristen men dwellez. And &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;are right gude wyne. And in &thorn;e kirke behind &thorn;e hie awter
in &thorn;e wall es a table of tree,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">a table of blak wode, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on &thorn;e whilk ane ymage of oure Lady was depaynted sum tyme, &thorn;e whilk oft tymes
turned into flesch; bot &thorn;at ymage nowe es bot lytill sene. Neuer&thorn;eles
<NOTE N="3" RESP="GW">Three leaves beginning at this point are lost in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (after f. 53), the lacuna ending at the words "&thorn;ei ete," p. 64 below. The text in the edition of 1725 is taken from Royal MS. 17 B. xliii. f.46b. The readings of this MS. are very inferior, and are seldom worth quoting.</NOTE> &thorn;at table euermare</SEG> droppez oel, as it
ware of oliue; and &thorn;are es a vessell of marble vnder &thorn;e table to ressayue &thorn;e oel. &THORN;aroff &thorn;ai giffe to pilgrimes,
for it heles of many sekeness; and men saise &thorn;at, if it be keped wele seuen &yogh;ere,
<NOTE N="4" RESP="GW">a &yogh;ere, <ABBR>B</ABBR>. A confusion of "vn" and "vii."</NOTE> efterwardes it turnes into
flesch and blud.</P>
<P>Fra
<NOTE N="5" RESP="GW">This paragraph not in <ABBR>B</ABBR>.</NOTE> Sardenak men commez thurgh &thorn;e vale of Bochar, &thorn;e whilk es a faire vale and a plentifous of all
maner of fruyte; and it es amanges hilles. And &thorn;er er &thorn;arin faire ryuers and grete medews and noble pasture
for bestez. And men gas by &thorn;e mountes of Libane, whilk lastez fra Ermony &thorn;e mare towardes &thorn;e north vnto
<MILESTONE N="51" UNIT="folio">Dan, &thorn;e whilk es &thorn;e end of &thorn;e land of repromissioun toward &thorn;e north, as I said before. &THORN;ir hilles er ri&yogh;t
fruytfull, and &thorn;are er many faire welles and cedres and cipressez, and many o&thorn;er treesse of diuerse kyndes. &THORN;are
er also many gude tounes toward &thorn;e heued of &thorn;ir hilles, full of folk.</P>
<P>Betwene &thorn;e citee of Arkez and &thorn;e citee of Raphane es a riuer, &thorn;at es called Sabatory; for on &thorn;e Seterday it
rynnez fast, and all &thorn;e weke elles it standes still and rynnez no&yogh;t, or elles bot fairely. Betwene &thorn;e forsaid hilles
also es ano&thorn;er water &thorn;at on nyghtes fresez hard and on days es na frost sene &thorn;eron. And, as men commez
agayne fra &thorn;ase hilles, es a hill hier &thorn;an any of &thorn;e o&thorn;er, and &thorn;ai call it &thorn;are &thorn;e Hegh Hill. &THORN;are es a grete citee
and a faire, &thorn;e whilk es called Tryple,
<NOTE N="6" RESP="GW">Tripoli.</NOTE> in &thorn;e whilk er many gude Cristen men, &yogh;emaund &thorn;e same rytes and
custommes &thorn;at we vsen. Fra &thorn;eine men commez by a citee &thorn;at es called Beruch,
<NOTE N="7" RESP="GW">Beyrout.</NOTE> whare sayne George slew &thorn;e
dragoun; and it es a gude toune, and a faire castell &thorn;erin, and it es iii. iournez fra &thorn;e forsaid citee of Sardenak.

<PB N="62">
At &thorn;e ta syde of Beruch xvi. myle, to comme hiderward, es &thorn;e citee of Sydon. At Beruch entres pilgrimes in to
&thorn;e see &thorn;at will comme to Cipre, and &thorn;ai aryfe at &thorn;e porte of Surry or of Tyer, and so &thorn;ai comme to Cipre in a
lytill space. Or men may comme fra &thorn;e porte of Tyre and comme no&yogh;t at Cipre and aryfe at sum hauen of Grece,
and so comme to &thorn;ise partyse, as I said before.</P>
<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio">
<P>I hafe talde &yogh;ow now of &thorn;e waye by whilk men gase ferrest and langest to Ierusalem, as by Babilon and
mount Synay and many o&thorn;er placez whilk &yogh;e herd me tell off, and also by whilk ways men schall turne agayne to
&thorn;e Land of Repromission. Now will I tell &yogh;ow &thorn;e rightest way and &thorn;e schortest to Ierusalem. For sum men will
no&yogh;t ga &thorn;e to&thorn;er; sum for &thorn;ai hafe no&yogh;t spending ynogh, sum for &thorn;ai hafe na gude cumpany, and sum for &thorn;ai may
no&yogh;t endure &thorn;e lang trauail, sum for &thorn;ai drede &thorn;am of many perils of desertes, sum for &thorn;ai will haste &thorn;am
hameward, desirand to see &thorn;are wifes and &thorn;are childer, or for sum o&thorn;er resonable cause &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe to turne sone
hame. And &thorn;erfore I will schew how men may passe tittest, and in schortest tyme make &thorn;aire pilgrimage to
Ierusalem. A man &thorn;at commes fra &thorn;e landes of &thorn;e west, he gas thurgh Fraunce, Burgoyne, and Lumbardy, and
so to Venice or Geen, or sum o&thorn;er hauen, and schippes &thorn;are and wendez by see to &thorn;e ile of Greff, &thorn;e whilk
pertenez to &thorn;e Ianuenes. And seyne he aryuez in Grece at Porte Mirrok, or at Valoun, or at Duras, or at sum
o&thorn;er hauen of &thorn;at cuntree, and ristez him &thorn;are and byez him vitailes and schippez agayne and sailez to Cipre
and aryuez &thorn;are at Famagost and commez no&yogh;t at &thorn;e ile of Rodes. Famagost es &thorn;e chieff hauen of Cipre; and
&thorn;are he refreschez him and puruays him of vitailes, and &thorn;an he gase to schippe and commez na mare on land, if he
<MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="folio">will, before he comme at Porte Iaffe, &thorn;at es &thorn;e next hauen to Ierusalem, for it es bot a day iournee and a half
fra Ierusalem, &thorn;at es to say xxxvi. myle. Fra &thorn;e porte Iaffe men gase to &thorn;e citee of Rames, &thorn;e whilk es bot a
lytill &thorn;eine; and it es a faire citee and a gude and mykill folk &thorn;erin. And withouten &thorn;at citee toward &thorn;e south
es a kirk of oure Lady, whare oure Lord schewed him till her in three cloudes, &thorn;e whilk betakned &thorn;e Trinitee.
And a lytill &thorn;eine es ane o&thorn;er citee, &thorn;at men calles Dispolis, bot it hight sum tyme Lidda, a faire citee and a
wele inhabited; &thorn;are es a kirk of sayne George, whare he was heuedid. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to &thorn;e castell of
Emaus, and so to &thorn;e Mount Ioy; &thorn;are may pilgrimes first see to Ierusalem. At Mount Ioy liggez Samuel &thorn;e
prophete. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to Ierusalem. Beside &thorn;ir ways es &thorn;e citee of Ramatha and &thorn;e mount Modyn;

<PB N="63">
and &thorn;eroff was Matathias, Iudas Machabeus fader, and &thorn;are er &thorn;e graues of &thorn;e Machabeez. Be&yogh;ond Ramatha es
&thorn;e towne of Techue, wharoff Amos &thorn;e prophete was; and &thorn;are es his grafe.</P>
<P>I hafe talde &yogh;ow before of &thorn;e haly placez &thorn;at er at Ierusalem and aboute it, and &thorn;erfore I will speke na
mare of &thorn;am at &thorn;is tyme. Bot I will turne agayne and schewe &yogh;ow o&thorn;er ways a man may passe mare by land,
and namely for &thorn;aim &thorn;at may no&yogh;t suffer &thorn;e sauour of &thorn;e see, bot es leuer to ga by land, if all it be &thorn;e mare payne.
Fra a man be entred in to &thorn;e see he schall passe till ane of &thorn;e hauenes of Lumbardy, for &thorn;are es &thorn;e best making
<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio">of purueaunce of vitailes; or he may passe to Ieen or Venice or sum o&thorn;er. And he sall passe by see in to
Grece to &thorn;e porte Mirrok, or to Valoun, or to Duras, or sum o&thorn;er hauen of &thorn;at cuntree. And fra &thorn;eine he sall
ga by land to Constantinople, and he sall passe &thorn;e water &thorn;at es called Brace Sayne George, &thorn;e whilk es ane arme
of &thorn;e see. And fra &thorn;eine he sall by land ga to Ruffynell, whare a gude castell es and a strang; and fra &thorn;eine he
sall ga to Pulueral, and seyne to &thorn;e castell of Synople, and fra &thorn;eine to Capadoce, &thorn;at es a grete cuntree, whare
er many grete hilles. And he sall ga thurgh Turky to &thorn;e porte of Chiutok and to &thorn;e citee of Nyke, whilk es
bot vii. myle &thorn;eine. &THORN;at citee wanne &thorn;e Turkes fra &thorn;e emperour of Constantinople; and it es a faire citee and
wele walled on &thorn;e ta syde, and on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde es a grete lake and a grete riuer, &thorn;e whilk es called Lay.
Fra &thorn;eine men gase by &thorn;e hilles of Nairmount and by &thorn;e vales of Mailbrins and straite felles and by &thorn;e toune of
Ormanx or by &thorn;e tounes &thorn;at er on Riclay and Stancon, &thorn;e whilk er grete waters and noble, and so to Antioche
&thorn;e lesse, whilk es sett on &thorn;e ryuer of Riclay. And &thorn;are aboutes er many gude hilles and faire, and many faire
wodes and grete plentee of wylde bestes for to hunt at.</P>
<P>And he &thorn;at will ga ano&thorn;er way, he schall ga by &thorn;e playnes of Romany costayand &thorn;e Romayn See. On &thorn;at
coste es a faire castell &thorn;at men callez Florach, and it es right a strang place. And vppermare amanges &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="53" UNIT="folio">mountaynes es a faire citee, &thorn;at es called Toursout, and &thorn;e citee of Longemaath, and &thorn;e citee of Assere, and &thorn;e
cite of Marmistre. And, when a man es passed &thorn;ase mountaynes and &thorn;ase felles, he gase by &thorn;e citee of
Marioch and by Artoise, whare es a grete brigg apon &thorn;e riuer of Ferne, &thorn;at es called Farfar, and it es a grete
riuer berand schippes and it rynnes ri&yogh;t fast oute of &thorn;e mountaines to &thorn;e cite of Damasc. And besyde &thorn;e citee
of Damasc es ano&thorn;er grete riuer &thorn;at commes fra &thorn;e hilles of Liban, whilk men callez Abbana. At &thorn;e passing of
&thorn;is riuer saynt Eustace, &thorn;at sum tyme was called Placidas, lost his wyf and his twa childer. &THORN;is riuer rynnes

<PB N="64">
thurgh &thorn;e playne of Archades, and so to &thorn;e Reed See. Fra &thorn;eine men gase to &thorn;e cite of Phenice, whare er hate
welles and hate bathez. And &thorn;an men gase to &thorn;e cite of Ferne; and betwene Phenice and Ferne er x. myle.
And &thorn;are er many faire woddes. And &thorn;an men commez til Anthioche, whilk es x. myle &thorn;eine. And it es a
faire citee and wele walled aboute with many faire toures; and it es a grete cite, bot it was sum tyme gretter
&thorn;an it es nowe. For it was sum tyme twa myle on lenth and on brede o&thorn;er half myle. And thurgh &thorn;e myddes
of &thorn;at citee ranne &thorn;e water of Farphar and a grete brigg ower it; and &thorn;are ware sum tyme in &thorn;e walles aboute
&thorn;is citee ccc. and fyfty toures, and at ilk a piler of &thorn;e brigg was a toure. &THORN;is es &thorn;e cheeffe cite of &thorn;e kyngdom of
Surry. And ten myle fra &thorn;is cite es &thorn;e porte of Saynt Symeon; and &thorn;are gase &thorn;e water off Farphar in to &thorn;e see.
Fra Antioche men gase to a cite &thorn;at es called Lacuth, and &thorn;an to Gebel, and &thorn;an to Tortouse. And &thorn;are nere
<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio">es &thorn;e land of Channel; and &thorn;are es a strang castell &thorn;at es called Maubek. Fra Tortouse passez men to Tryple
by see, or elles by land thurgh &thorn;e straytes of mountaynes and felles. And &thorn;are es a citee &thorn;at es called Gibilet. Fra
Triple gase men til Acres; and fra &thorn;eine er twa ways to Ierusalem, &thorn;e tane on &thorn;e left half and &thorn;e to&thorn;er on &thorn;e
ri&yogh;t half. By &thorn;e left way men gase by Damasc and by &thorn;e flum Iordan. By &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way men gase by Maryn and
by &thorn;e land of Flagramy and nere &thorn;e mountaynes vnto &thorn;e cite of Cayphas, &thorn;at sum men callez &thorn;e Castell of
Pilgrimes. And fra &thorn;eine to Ierusalem er iii. day iournez, in &thorn;e whilk men schall ga thurgh Cesaria Philippi,
and so to Iaffe and Rames and &thorn;e castell of Emaus, and so to Ierusalem.</P>
<P>Now hafe I talde &yogh;ow sum ways by land and by water &thorn;at men may ga by to &thorn;e Haly Land after &thorn;e cuntreez
&thorn;at &thorn;ai comme fra. Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai comme all til ane ende. &YOGH;it es &thorn;are ano&thorn;er way to Ierusalem all by land, and
passe no&yogh;t &thorn;e see, fra Fraunce or Flaundres; bot &thorn;at way es full lang and perlious and of grete trauaile, and
&thorn;erfore few gase &thorn;at way. He &thorn;at schall ga &thorn;at way, he schall ga thurgh Almayne and Pruyss and so to Tartary.
&THORN;is Tartary es halden of &thorn;e Grete Caan of Cathay, of wham I think to speke efterward. &THORN;is es a full ill land
and sandy and lytill fruyt berand. For &thorn;are growes na corne, ne wyne, ne beenes, ne peese, ne nan o&thorn;er fruyt
couable to man for to liffe with. Bot &thorn;are er bestez in grete plentee; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai ete bot flesch withouten
<MILESTONE N="54" UNIT="folio">breed and soupez &thorn;e broo, and &thorn;ai drink mylke of all maner of bestez. <SEG ID="Eg.64.24" CORRESP="Cot.82.26">&THORN;ai ete
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">The lacuna in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> ends here.</NOTE> cattes and hundes, ratouns and
myesse, and all o&thorn;er maner of bestez; and, for &thorn;ai hafe lytill wode, &thorn;ai dight
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">warmen and sethen, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;aire mete with dung of bestez
dried at &thorn;e sonne. &THORN;ai ete bot anes on &thorn;e day, now&thorn;er prince nor o&thorn;er; and &yogh;it &thorn;at anes &thorn;ai ete bot ri&yogh;t lytill.
&THORN;ai er ri&yogh;t foule folk and fell and full of malice. &THORN;at cuntree es selden withouten grete tempestez. And in

<PB N="65">
somer es &thorn;er grete thundres and leightens, &thorn;at slaez mykill folk and many bestez. And ri&yogh;t sodaynely es &thorn;are
chaungeyng of &thorn;e aer, nowe grete calde and now grete hete; and so &thorn;are es euill dwelling. &THORN;e prince &thorn;at
gouernes &thorn;at land es called Baco, and he dwellez in a citee &thorn;at men callez Orda. Sothely &thorn;are will
na gude manne dwell in &thorn;at land; for it es gude to sawe in humbloks and nettles and swilk o&thorn;er wedes,
and o&thorn;er gude nane,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">For the lond and the contree is not worthi houndes to duell inne. It were a gode contree to sowen inne thristell and breres and broom and thornes and breres, and for non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing is it not good, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> as I hafe herd say, for I hafe no&yogh;t bene &thorn;are. Bot I hafe bene in o&thorn;er landes &thorn;at
marchez &thorn;eron, as &thorn;e land of Russy and Nyfland and &thorn;e kingdom of Crakow and Lettow and in &thorn;e kingdom of
Graften and many o&thorn;er placez. Bot I went neuer by &thorn;at way to Ierusalem, and &thorn;erfore I may no&yogh;t wele tell it.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">But, &yogh;if this matiere plese to ony worthi man &thorn;at hath gon be &thorn;at weye, he may telle it, &yogh;if him lyke, to &thorn;at entent &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;at wolen go by &thorn;at weye and maken here viage be &thorn;o costes mowen knowen what weye is &thorn;ere, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG>
<SEG ID="Eg.65.8" CORRESP="Cot.83.24">For, as I hafe vnderstanden, men may no&yogh;t wele ga &thorn;at way bot in wynter for waters and maracez &thorn;at er &thorn;are,
whilk a man may no&yogh;t passe, bot if he hafe ri&yogh;t hard frost and &thorn;at it be wele snawen abouen. For warne &thorn;e
snawe ware, &thorn;are schuld na man passe ower &thorn;e ysz. Of swilk way schall a man ga iii. day iournez fra Pruyss are
<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio">he comme to &thorn;e land of Sarezens habitable, whare Sarzenes dwellez. And, if all it be so &thorn;at Cristen men ilk a
&yogh;ere passe &thorn;are, &thorn;ai cary &thorn;aire vitailes with &thorn;am apon &thorn;e ysz with sleddes and carres withouten wheles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">carres &thorn;at haue no wheles, &thorn;at &thorn;ei clepen scleyes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; for &thorn;are
schall &thorn;ai fynd nane bot &thorn;at &thorn;ai bring with &thorn;am. And, als lang as &thorn;aire witailes lastes may &thorn;ai habyde &thorn;are and
langer no&yogh;t. And, when spyes of &thorn;e cuntree seez Cristen men com to werray apon &thorn;am, &thorn;ai rynne to &thorn;e tounes
and criez ri&yogh;t lowd "Kera, Kera, Kera"; and alssone &thorn;ai aray &thorn;am for to kepe &thorn;am. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand
&thorn;at &thorn;e frost and &thorn;e ysz es mykill harder &thorn;are &thorn;an here; and &thorn;erfore ilk a man &thorn;are hase a stewe in his hous, &thorn;are
he etez and drinkes. For &thorn;are es owtrage calde, by cause it es at &thorn;e north syde of &thorn;e werld, whare comounly
es mare intense calde &thorn;an in o&thorn;er placez, for &thorn;e sonne schynez bot lytill &thorn;are. And on &thorn;e south syde of &thorn;e werld
es it in sum place so hate &thorn;at na man may dwell &thorn;are for &thorn;e owtrage hete.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.15" N="15" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.16">
<PB N="66">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the customes of Sarasines and of hire lawe; and how the Soudan arresond me, auctour of this book; and of the begynnynge of Machomete.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.66.4" CORRESP="Cot.84.17">FOR als mykill as I hafe spoken of Sarzenes and of &thorn;aire landes, I will now tell &yogh;ow a party of &thorn;aire lawe
and &thorn;aire belefe, after &thorn;at it es contende in &thorn;e buke of &thorn;aire lawe, &thorn;at es called <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>. And sum
callez it <TITLE>Messaph</TITLE>, and sum <TITLE>Harme</TITLE>, after langagez of diuerse cuntreez. &THORN;e whilk buke Machomete
gafe to &thorn;am. In &thorn;at buke amanges o&thorn;er thinges es contende, as I hafe oft tymes redd &thorn;erin and sene, &thorn;at
gude men, when &thorn;ai er deed, sall ga vnto Paradys and &thorn;ai &thorn;at er wikked sall ga to &thorn;e payne of hell. And &thorn;is
trowez stedfastly all Sarzenes. And, if a man ask &thorn;am of whilk paradys &thorn;ai mene, &thorn;ai say it es a place of delytez,
<MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="folio">whare a man schall fynd all maner of fruytez all tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, and riuers rynnand with wyne, mylke and
hony, and fresch water; and &thorn;ai schall hafe faire palaycez and grete and faire housez and gude, after &thorn;ai hafe
disserued, and &thorn;ase palacez and housez er made of precious stanes, gold and siluer; and ilk a man sall hafe
iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> wyfes of faire damiselles, and he schall hafe at do with &thorn;am ay when him list, and he sall euermare fynd
&thorn;am maydens. &THORN;is trowe &thorn;ai all &thorn;at &thorn;ai sall hafe in paradys; and &thorn;is es agayne oure lawe. Also &thorn;e Sarzenes
trowez &thorn;e incarnacioun, and gladly will &thorn;ai speke of &thorn;e Virgin Mary and saise &thorn;at scho was lerned by
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">taughte of, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e aungell
and &thorn;at &thorn;e aungell Gabriell said to hir &thorn;at scho was chosen of Godd before &thorn;e begynnyng of &thorn;e werld for to
consayfe Ihesu Criste and for to bere him, wham scho bare and scho mayden efter as scho was before; and &thorn;is
witnessez wele &thorn;e buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at Criste spak alssone as he was borne, and &thorn;at he was and
es a haly prophete and a verray in worde and in dede, and meke and ri&yogh;twise to all and withouten vice. &THORN;ai
afferme also &thorn;at, when &thorn;e aungell grette oure Lady and talde hir of &thorn;e incarnacioun, by cause scho was &yogh;ung,
scho was gretely aschamed and astonayd of his wordes, and principally, as &thorn;ai say, by cause of a mysdoer &thorn;at
was &thorn;at tyme in &thorn;at cuntree, &thorn;e whilk hight Takyna, &thorn;at delt with sorcery and thurgh his enchauntementz feyned
him ane aungell and begyled &yogh;ung damyselles oft sythes and lay by &thorn;am. And &thorn;erfore was Marie fered and
coniured &thorn;e aungell &thorn;at he suld say hir whe&thorn;er he ware Takyna or no&yogh;t. And &thorn;e aungell answerd hir and bad
<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio">hir hafe na drede, for he was verray messanger of Godd. Also &thorn;aire buke of <TITLE>Alkaroun</TITLE> saise &thorn;at, when Mary

<PB N="67">
was delyuer of hir childe vnder a palme tree, scho was gretely aschamed and weped and said scho wald scho
ware deed. And alssone &thorn;e childe spakk and comforthed hir and said, "Be no&yogh;t affered, for in &thorn;e Godd hase
his sacrement
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">hath hidd in &thorn;e his preuytees, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for &thorn;e saluacioun of &thorn;is werld." And in many o&thorn;er placez witnessez &thorn;aire buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE> &thorn;at
Ihesu Christ spakk alssone as he was borne. And &thorn;at buke saise &thorn;at Criste was sent fra Godd all myghty in til
erthe for to be ensaumple and mirroure til all men. &THORN;at buke also spekez of &thorn;e day of dome, how &thorn;at Godd
schall comme and deme all men; &thorn;e gude he sall drawe on his party and gorifie &thorn;am in ioy withouten end, and
&thorn;e wikked he sall dampne till ay lastand paynes of hell. Amanges all prophetes &thorn;ai say &thorn;at Criste es &thorn;e best,
&thorn;e worthiest and next to Godd, and &thorn;at he made &thorn;e <TITLE>Ewangels</TITLE>, in &thorn;e whilk es helefull teching and sothefastnes
and preching til &thorn;aim &thorn;at trowes in Godd, and &thorn;at he was mare &thorn;an prophete, liffand withouten syn, &thorn;at gafe sight
to &thorn;e blynd and heled meselles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">lepres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and raised men fra deed to lyf and went all qwikk in to heuen. And, when &thorn;ai
may get &thorn;e <TITLE>Gospels</TITLE> writen, &thorn;ai do grete wirschepe to &thorn;am and namely &thorn;e gospell of <TITLE LANG="lat">Missus est</TITLE>, whilk gospell &thorn;ai
&thorn;at er letterd amanges &thorn;am kissez with grete deuocioun, and saise it oft tymes amanges &thorn;aire praiers. &THORN;ai fast ilk
a &yogh;ere a hale moneth, and etez na mete bot at euen, and abstenez &thorn;am fra &thorn;aire wyfez all &thorn;at moneth. Bot &thorn;ai
&thorn;at er seke er no&yogh;t constreyned to &thorn;at fast.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.67.14" CORRESP="Cot.86.15">Also &thorn;e buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE> spekez of &thorn;e Iewes, and saise &thorn;at &thorn;ai er
<MILESTONE N="56" UNIT="folio">wikked and cursen, for &thorn;ai will no&yogh;t trowe &thorn;at Ihesus was sent fra Godd; and &thorn;at &thorn;ai lye falsly on Mary and hir
son Ihesu Criste, when &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ai didd him on &thorn;e crosse. For &thorn;ai crucified no&yogh;t Ihesus, as &thorn;ai say, for Godd
tuke him vp til him
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> le fist Dieu monter, <HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text; God made him to stye vp to him, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> withouten deed and transfigured &thorn;e fourme and &thorn;e likness of his body in to Iudas Yscarioth,
and him didd &thorn;e Iews on &thorn;e crosse and wend it had bene Ihesus. Bot Ihesus was taken all qwikk, &thorn;ai say, in til
heuen, and so
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and so &hellip; werld, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sall he comme to deme all &thorn;e werld. And &thorn;is wate no&yogh;t Cristen men; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai er
no&yogh;t right belefand, when &thorn;ai trowe &thorn;at Ihesu Criste was done on &thorn;e crosse. All &thorn;ir poyntes er contende in &thorn;e
buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>. &THORN;e Sarzenes saise also &thorn;at, if Ihesu Criste had bene crucified, Godd &thorn;an had done agayne his
ri&yogh;twisness for to suffer swilk ane innocent die withouten gylt; and in &thorn;at &thorn;ai say we erre. Neuer&thorn;eles in &thorn;at erre
&thorn;ai. &THORN;ai graunt wele &thorn;at all &thorn;e werkes of Criste and all his wordes and his techings and his <TITLE>ewaungelles</TITLE> er gude
and trewe, and his myracles verray and clere; and &thorn;at &thorn;e Virgyne Mary was a gude mayden and a haly before
&thorn;e birth of Criste and efter also and vnwemmed; and &thorn;at &thorn;ase &thorn;at trowes perfitely in Godd sall be sauf. And,

<PB N="68">
for als mykill as &thorn;ai ga &thorn;us nere oure faith in &thorn;ir pointes and many o&thorn;er, me think &thorn;at mykill &thorn;e titter and &thorn;e
lightlier &thorn;ai schuld be conuerted till oure lawe thurgh preching and teching of Cristen men. &THORN;ai say &thorn;ai wate
wele and findez by &thorn;aire prophecies &thorn;at Machometes lawe sall faile, as &thorn;e Iewez lawe es failed, and &thorn;at &thorn;e
Cristen lawe schall last to &thorn;e werldes end. And, if a man ask &thorn;am of &thorn;aire beleue and how &thorn;ai trowe, &thorn;ai
<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio">answere and saise, "We trowe in Godd, &thorn;at made heuen and o&thorn;er thinges of noght, and withouten him es
na thing made. And we trowe &thorn;e day of dome schall comme, whare ilk man schall hafe his mede after his
disserte. We trowe also verraily &thorn;at all es sothe &thorn;at Godd has spoken thurgh &thorn;e mouthes of his haly prophetez,
whils &thorn;ai welk in erthe." Also &thorn;ai say &thorn;at Machomete bad and commaundid in &thorn;e buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>, &thorn;at ilk
a man schuld hafe three or foure wyfes. Bot now take &thorn;ai ma, for sum of &thorn;am hase nyne; bot of
concubines ilke man takes als many as he may sustene of his gudes. And, if any of &thorn;aire wyfes do amisse
agaynes hir husband and lat ano&thorn;er man lye by hir, &thorn;an is it leuefull till hir husband to putte hir away fra him
and take ano&thorn;er in hir steed; bot him behufez gyffe hir a porcioun of his gudes. Also, when men spekes to &thorn;am
of &thorn;e Trinytee, &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai er three Persones, bot no&yogh;t a Godd. For &thorn;aire buke of <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE> spekes no&yogh;t of
Trinitee. Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai graunt and sais &thorn;at Godd has worde, and elles ware he dumbe; and &thorn;at he hase a
spirit, and &thorn;at elles behufed him be withouten lyf. And, when men spekes to &thorn;am of Cristez incarnacioun, how
by &thorn;e worde of &thorn;e aungell Godd sent wisdom in til erthe and lightid in Virgin Mary, and thurgh &thorn;e worde of
Godd &thorn;ai &thorn;at er deed schall be raised apon &thorn;e day of dome, &thorn;ai say &thorn;at all &thorn;is es sothe, and all &thorn;is &thorn;ai trowe, and
&thorn;at Goddes worde has grete vertu, and he &thorn;at knawez no&yogh;t Goddes worde he knawez no&yogh;t Godd. &THORN;ai say also
&thorn;at Criste was Goddes worde; and so saise &thorn;aire <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>, &thorn;are it saise &thorn;at &thorn;e aungell spakk to Mary and said,
<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="folio">"Mary, Godd sall send to &thorn;e worde of his mouthe, and his name sall be called Ihesu Criste." Also &thorn;ai say &thorn;at
Abraham was Goddes frende, and Moyses Goddez forspeker, and Ihesu Criste was &thorn;e worde and &thorn;e gaste of
Godd, and &thorn;at Macomete was &thorn;e verray messanger of Godd; and of all &thorn;ir foure Ihesus was &thorn;e worthiest and
maste excellent. And &thorn;us it semez &thorn;at &thorn;e Sarzenes has many articles of oure trouth, &thorn;of it be no&yogh;t perfytely;
and &thorn;arfore it ware &thorn;e lighter to conuerte &thorn;am and to bring &thorn;am till oure trouth, and namely &thorn;ase &thorn;at er letterd
and has knawyng of Scriptures. For &thorn;ai hafe amanges &thorn;am &thorn;e <TITLE>Euaungelles</TITLE> and &thorn;e <TITLE>Prophetes</TITLE> and all &thorn;e <TITLE>Bible</TITLE>
writen in Sarzene langage. Bot &thorn;ai vnderstand no&yogh;t haly writte spiritually, bot after &thorn;e letter, as &thorn;e Iews does;
and &thorn;erfore saise sayne Paule, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Litera occidit, spiritus autem viuificat</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">II. Cor. iii.6.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;e lettre slaez, and &thorn;e

<PB N="69">
spirit qwikkens." And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e Sarzenes saise &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes er wikked men and cursed, for &thorn;ai hafe broken &thorn;e
lawe &thorn;at Godd gafe &thorn;am thurgh Moyses; and Cristen men &thorn;ai say er wikked and ill, for &thorn;ai kepe no&yogh;t &thorn;e
commaundement of &thorn;e <TITLE>Gospell</TITLE>, whilk Ihesus Criste bad &thorn;am.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.69.4" CORRESP="Cot.88.23">Now will I tell &yogh;ow what &thorn;e Sowdan did tell me apon a day in his chaumbre. He gert all men void his
chaumbre, bathe lordez and o&thorn;er &thorn;at ware &thorn;erin; for he wald speke with me in priuetee betwene vs twa. And,
when all ware gane furth, he asked me how Cristen men gouerned &thorn;am in oure cuntreez. And I said, "Lord,
wele; thanked be Godd." And he answerd and said, "Sikerly, nay. It es noght so. For &yogh;our prestez," quod
<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio">he, "seruez no&yogh;t Godd duely in gude liffyng, as &thorn;ai schuld do. For &thorn;ai schuld giffe to lewed men ensaumple of
gude liffyng, and &thorn;ai do euen &thorn;e contrary; for &thorn;ai giffe &thorn;am ensaumple of all wikkidness. And &thorn;erfore on haly
days, when &thorn;e folk schuld go to &thorn;e kirke to serue Godd, &thorn;ai go to &thorn;e tauerne and occupiez all &thorn;e day and
perchaunce all &thorn;e nyght after in drinkyng and in glotry, as &thorn;ai ware bestez oute of resoun, &thorn;at knawez noght when
&thorn;ai hafe ynoghe. And afterwardes thurgh drunkenness &thorn;ai fall at grete wordes and feyghtes and flytez till ilk ane
of &thorn;am sla o&thorn;er. &THORN;e Cristen men also vsez ilkane to begyle o&thorn;er and falsely to swere grete athes. And
&thorn;erwith &thorn;ai er so bolned in pride and vayne glory, &thorn;at &thorn;ai wate neuer how &thorn;ai may clethe &thorn;am, bot now &thorn;ai vse
schort clathes, now syde, now strayte, now wyde."
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">now long, now schort. now streyt, now large, now swerded, now daggered, and in alle manere gyses, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> "&YOGH;e schuld," he said, "be symple, meke and sothfast, and
almous gerne,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">fulle of almes dede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> as Criste was, in wham &yogh;e say &yogh;e trowe. Bot it es all o&thorn;erwise. For Cristen men er so prowde,
so enuyous, so grete glotouns, and so licherous, and &thorn;erto so full of couetise, &thorn;at for a lytill siluer &thorn;ai will sell
&thorn;aire doghters, &thorn;aire sisters, &yogh;a and &thorn;aire awen wyfes, to lat men lye by &thorn;am. And ilk ane takes o&thorn;er wyf, and
nane haldez his fayth till o&thorn;er; and so &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at Criste gaffe &yogh;ow wikkidly and ill &yogh;e despise and brekez it.
And certaynely for &yogh;our synne &yogh;e hafe lost all &thorn;is land, &thorn;e whilk we hafe and haldez. For by cause of &yogh;our ill
liffing and &yogh;our synne and no&yogh;t of oure strenth Godd has giffen it intill oure handes. And we wate wele &thorn;at,
when &yogh;e serue &yogh;our Godd duely and wele and plesez him with gude werkes, na man schall mow agaynestand
&yogh;ow. We knawe wele also by oure prophecyes &thorn;at Cristen men schall recouer &thorn;is land agayne in tyme
<MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="folio">commyng, when &yogh;e serue &yogh;our Godd wele and deuotely. Bot als lang as &yogh;e liffe, as &yogh;e do, in wikkednes and in
synne, we hafe na drede of &yogh;ow; for &yogh;our Godd will no&yogh;t helpe &yogh;ow." When I had herd &thorn;e sowdan speke &thorn;ir
wordes and many ma whilk I will no&yogh;t tell at &thorn;is tyme, I asked him with grete reuerence, how he come to &thorn;us
mykill knawyng of &thorn;e state of Cristiantee. And &thorn;an he gert call in agayne all &thorn;e grete lordes and &thorn;e wor&thorn;i &thorn;at
he sent furth of &thorn;e chaumbre before; and he assigned foure of &thorn;am, &thorn;at ware grete lordes, for to speke with me.

<PB N="70">
&THORN;e whilk rekned me all &thorn;e maner of my cuntree and descryued me &thorn;e maners of o&thorn;er cuntrees of Cristendon als
graythely and als verraily as &thorn;ai had bene euer &yogh;it dwelland in &thorn;am. And bathe &thorn;e sowdan and &thorn;ai spakk
Fransch wonder wele, and &thorn;erof I meruailed me gretely. And at &thorn;e last I vnderstude &thorn;at &thorn;e sowdan sent of
his lordes in to diuerse rewmes and diuerse landes in gyse of marchandes, sum with preciouse stanes, sum with
clathez of gold, and sum with o&thorn;er iowelles, &thorn;e whilk in swilk maner visitez all rewmes for to aspie &thorn;e maners of
vs Cristen men and to knawe oure febilnes. And &thorn;an me tho&yogh;t grete schame &thorn;at Sarzenes, whilk hase now&thorn;er
ri&yogh;t beleue ne perfite lawe, schuld &thorn;us reproue vs of oure inperfiteness and kepez &thorn;aire vayne lawe better &thorn;an we
do &thorn;e lawe of Ihesu Criste; and &thorn;ai &thorn;at schuld be turned thurgh oure gude ensaumple to &thorn;e faith and &thorn;e lawe of
Ihesu Criste, &thorn;ai er drawen away thurgh oure wikked liffing. And &thorn;erfore it es na wonder if &thorn;ai call vs synfull and
<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio">wikked, for it es sothe. Bot &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t deuote in &thorn;aire lawe and ri&yogh;t trewe, and wele kepez &thorn;e commaundementz
of &thorn;aire <TITLE>Alkaron</TITLE>, whilk Godd sent to &thorn;am by his messanger Machomete, to wham, as &thorn;ai say, &thorn;e aungell Gabriell
spakk oft tymes and talde him &thorn;e will of Godd.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.70.13" CORRESP="Cot.90.13">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at Machomete was borne in Araby, and first he was a pouer knafe, &thorn;at keped
hors and camelles and went with marchaunds intil Egipte, &thorn;e whilk was &thorn;at tyme inhabited with Cristen men.
And in &thorn;e desertes of Araby by &thorn;e hie way toward Egipte was a chapell and ane hermyte dwelland &thorn;erat. And
in to &thorn;is ilke chapell went Machomete for to speke with <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;e</SUPPLIED> hermyte. And, when he entred &thorn;e chapell, &thorn;e
dure, whilk was ri&yogh;t lawe, sudaynely it wex als hie as it had bene &thorn;e &yogh;ate of a grete palace; and &thorn;is, as &thorn;ai say,
was &thorn;e first myracle &thorn;at he didd, when he was &yogh;ung. After &thorn;at began Machomete to be wyse and riche, and he
was a grete astronomyer. And &thorn;e prince of &thorn;e land of Corodan made him keper and gouernour of his land;
and he gouerned it wisely and graciousely, so &thorn;at, when &thorn;e prince was deed, he wedded &thorn;e princesse, whilk was
called Cadrige<SUPPLIED RESP="GW">Khadija.</SUPPLIED> And &thorn;is ilke Machomete had &thorn;e falland euill, and oft tymes he fell by violence of &thorn;at
sekeness; and &thorn;e lady had mykill sorow &thorn;at scho had wedded him. Bot he made hir at vnderstand &thorn;at ilke a
tyme &thorn;at he fell so &thorn;e aungell Gabriell apperid till and spak with him, and for &thorn;e grete bri&yogh;tness of &thorn;e aungell he
fell doune. And &thorn;erfore saise &thorn;e Sarzenes &thorn;at &thorn;e aungell Gabriell spakk oft tymes with him. &THORN;is Machomete
<MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="folio">regned in Araby &thorn;e &yogh;ere of oure lord vi<HI REND="sup">c</HI> and twenty; and he was of &thorn;e kynde of Ismael, &thorn;at was Abraham
sonne, whilk he gatte apon Agar his chaumberere. And &thorn;erfore sum Sarzenes er called Ismaelitez, sum
Agarrenes of Agarre, and sum Ammonytes after twa sonnes of Loth, whilk he gat on his twa doghters. And
sum er properly called Sarzenes, after &thorn;e citee of Sarras.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Sarrazines of Sarra, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Also Machomete lufed wele sum tyme a gude
hermyte &thorn;at dwelled in &thorn;e wildernes a myle fra &thorn;e mount Synai in &thorn;e way as men gase fra Araby to Caldee and

<PB N="71">
till Inde, a day iournee fra &thorn;e see, whare marchaunds of Venice commez oft tymes for to by marchandyse. And
Machomete went so oft to &thorn;is hermyte to here him preche &thorn;at his seruands wex heuy &thorn;erwith and euill apaid.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">alle his men weren wrothe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
For he went so oft &thorn;ider and so gladly herd &thorn;is hermyte preche &thorn;at many tymez he gert his men wake all &thorn;e
nyght ouer; and his men tho&yogh;t &thorn;ai wald fayne &thorn;is ilke hermyte had bene deed. So it befell apon a nyght &thorn;at
Machomete was drunken of wyne and fell on slepe; and, whils he sleped, his men drew oute his awen swerde
of &thorn;e schethe and with &thorn;at swerde &thorn;ai slew &thorn;e hermyte, and, when &thorn;ai had done, &thorn;ai putte vp &thorn;e swerde agayne
in to &thorn;e schethe all bludy. And at morue, when Machomete wakned and fand &thorn;e hermyte deed, he was wonder
wrathe and wald hafe slayne his men, for he said &thorn;ai had murtherd him amang &thorn;am. Bot &thorn;ai all with ane
accorde and ane ascent said &thorn;at him self had slayne him in his slepe, when he was drunken, and &thorn;ai schewed
him his swerde all bludy, and &thorn;an trowed he &thorn;at &thorn;ai said sothe. And &thorn;an he cursed wyne and all &thorn;ase &thorn;at it
<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio">drinkez; and &thorn;erfore Sarzenes &thorn;at er deuoute in &thorn;aire lawe will drynke na wyne. Bot &thorn;ai hafe ane o&thorn;er maner
of drinke gude and delicious and ri&yogh;t nurischand, &thorn;e whilk es made of diuerse spiceries and namely of calamel,
wharoff gude sugur es made.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at men maken sugre of, &thorn;at is of right gode sauour and it is gode for the breest, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Neuer&thorn;eles sum Sarzenes will drinke wyne gladly in priuetee, bot no&yogh;t in apperte;
for, if &thorn;ai drink wyne openly, &thorn;ai schall be blamed &thorn;erfore. Also it fallez sum tyme &thorn;at sum Cristen men
becommez Sarzenes, ow&thorn;er for pouert or sympless or for wikkedness of &thorn;am self; and he &thorn;at es &thorn;e cheeff maister
and keper of &thorn;aire lawe,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">the archiflamyn or the flamyn, as oure echebisshopp or bisshopp, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> when he ressayuez &thorn;am to &thorn;aire lawe, saise on &thorn;is wyse, <Q>La elles ella sila Machomet
rores alla hec</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;are es na Godd bot ane, and Machomete his messangere."</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.71.18" CORRESP="Cot.92.4">Sen I hafe talde &yogh;ow sum what of &thorn;e Sarzenes lawe, and of &thorn;aire maners and custommes, now will I tell &yogh;ow
of &thorn;aire letters whilk &thorn;ai vse,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">The characters in both MSS. [Egerton and Cotton] are too corrupt to be worth reproducing.</NOTE> with &thorn;e names and &thorn;e maner of &thorn;aire figures:</SEG>&mdash;Almoy, Betach, Cathi, Delphoi,
Ephoti, Fothi, Garophi, Hethim, Iocchi, Kacchi, Lothyn, Malach, Nahalet, Orthi, Porizeth, Qutholath, Routhi,
Salathi, Tothintus, Vzazot, Yrtim, Theth. &THORN;ir er &thorn;e names of &thorn;aire letteres, and now will I sett &thorn;e figures of
&thorn;am &hellip; Here will I sett &thorn;aire letters on ano&thorn;er maner, as I hafe sene &thorn;am made in sum o&thorn;er bukes; and
&thorn;is maner payes me better &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;er:&mdash;Almoy, Bethath, Cathi, Delphoi, Ephothi, Fothi, Garophi, Hechim,
<MILESTONE N="60" UNIT="folio">Iocchi, Kaythi, Lothim, Malach, Nahalot, Orthi, Corizi, &YOGH;och, Rutolath, Routhi, Salathi, Thatimus, Yrthom,
Azazoth, Arotthi, &YOGH;otipin, Ichetus. <SEG ID="Eg.71.25" CORRESP="Cot.92.8">And &thorn;ir er &thorn;e letters &hellip; &THORN;ir foure letters hafe &thorn;ai mare &thorn;an we
hafe for diuersitee of &thorn;aire langage, by cause &thorn;ai speke so in &thorn;aire throtes; as we hafe in oure speche in Ingland
twa o&thorn;er letters &thorn;an &thorn;ai hafe in &thorn;aire abce, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn; and &yogh;, whilk er called &thorn;orn and &yogh;ok.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.16" N="16" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.17">
<PB N="72">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XVI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the londes of Albanye and of Libye; of the wisshinges for wacchinge of the Sperhauk; and of Noes schippe.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.72.4" CORRESP="Cot.95.1">HERE hafe I talde &yogh;ow and declared of &thorn;e Haly Land and of cuntreez &thorn;er aboute, and of many ways &thorn;ider
and to &thorn;e mount Synai, to Babiloine and o&thorn;er placez, of whilk I hafe spoken off before. And now
will I passe for&thorn;ermare, and speke of diuerse landes and iles &thorn;at er be&yogh;ond &thorn;e Haly Land. For &thorn;er er
many diuerse kingdommes and cuntreez and iles toward &thorn;e este party of &thorn;e werld, wharin er many diuerse folk
and diuerse kyndez of bestes, and many o&thorn;er meruailous thinges. And &thorn;ase cuntreez er departed with &thorn;e foure
fludes &thorn;at commez oute of Paradys terrestre. For Mesopothamy and &thorn;e kyngdomme of Caldee and Araby er
betwene &thorn;ir twae fludes, &thorn;at es at say Tygre and Eufrates; and &thorn;e kingdom of Medie and of Perse er betwene
Tygre and Nilus; and &thorn;e kingdom of Surry, of Palestine and of Phenice er   betwene Eufrates and &thorn;e see
Mediterrany, &thorn;e whilk see lastez on lenth fra &thorn;e citee of Marrok, &thorn;e whilk standes apon &thorn;e Spaynisch see, vnto
&thorn;e grete see. So &thorn;at it lastez be&yogh;ond Constantinopil iii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> and fourty myle of Lumbardy. And toward &thorn;e see &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio">es called Occiane es &thorn;e kingdom of Scithy, whilk es all enclosed with hilles. Vnder Scithi, fra &thorn;e see of Caspy
vnto &thorn;e flude of Thanay, es &thorn;e land of Amazoun, and &thorn;at es &thorn;e land of wymmen,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Femynye, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whare wymmen dwellez by &thorn;am
self and na men amanges &thorn;am. And &thorn;an es &thorn;e rewme of Albany, a grete land; and it es called swa for &thorn;e folk
of &thorn;at land er whitter &thorn;an &thorn;e folk of o&thorn;er landes aboute it. And in &thorn;at land er wonder grete dogges and wight,
&thorn;e whilk feight with any lyouns and sla &thorn;am. And &thorn;an es &thorn;e land of Hircany, of Bactrice
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Bactrye, Hiberye and <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and many o&thorn;er.
And betwene &thorn;e Reed See and &thorn;e grete see Occiane, toward &thorn;e south, es Ethiopi and Libi &thorn;e vppermare. For
Liby &thorn;e ne&thorn;ermare begynnez at &thorn;e Spaynisch see, whare &thorn;e pilers er of Hercules, and lastez til Egypte and
Ethiopy. In Liby &thorn;e see semez mykill hegher &thorn;an &thorn;e land, and it es like as it schuld ouerflowe all &thorn;e land, and
&yogh;it it passez no&yogh;t &thorn;e bankes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">his markes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;at land es a grete hill, &thorn;e whilk men may see on ferrum, bot &thorn;ai may no&yogh;t
comme nere it. In Libi, when a man turnez him to &thorn;e est, his schadow es on his ri&yogh;t syde, as it es here in &thorn;is
cuntree on oure left syde. In &thorn;e Liby see er na fischez fun; for &thorn;are may nane liffe &thorn;erin by cause of &thorn;e owtrage

<PB N="73">
hete of &thorn;e sonne. For &thorn;e water &thorn;are by cause of grete hete es euermare as it ware buylland. And &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;er er many ma cuntreez and iles in &thorn;ase parties of &thorn;e werld, whilk ware to mykill to tell all;
bot of sum sall I tell mare playnely afterwardes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.73.4" CORRESP="Cot.96.15">Now he &thorn;at will passe in to Tartari, or Perse, or to Caldee, or Inde, he schall entre &thorn;e see at Geen, or at
<MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="folio">Venice, or at sum o&thorn;er hauen before nefned, and so passe &thorn;e see and arryue at &thorn;e hauen of Trapazonde, whilk
es a gude citee and was sum tyme called <NAME LANG="lat">Le Porte de Pounce</NAME>.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and it was wont to ben the hauene of Pountz. &THORN;ere is the hauene of Persanes and of Medaynes and of the marches &thorn;ere be&yogh;onde, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;is citee lyes saynt Athanase, &thorn;at was
bischope of Alisaundre, and he made &thorn;e psalme <TITLE LANG="lat">Quicunque wlt</TITLE>. &THORN;is Athanase was a grete doctour of diuinitee,
and for he preched mare profoundely of Haly Writte &thorn;an o&thorn;er didd, &thorn;erfore he was accused to &thorn;e pape of heresy;
and &thorn;e pape sent for him and gert putte him in presoun. And, whils he was in presoun, he made &thorn;e psalme
beforsaid and sent it to &thorn;e pape and said, "If I be ane heretyc," quod he, "&thorn;an es all heresy &thorn;at here es writen,
for &thorn;is es my trouthe." And, when &thorn;e pape sawe &thorn;at, he said it was all hally oure beleue and gert deliuer him
oute of presoun and comaunded &thorn;at psalme to be said ilk a day at prime; and he held Athanase for a gude man
and a haly. Bot Athanase wald neuer after ga to his bischoperyke agayne, for &thorn;at wikked men had thurgh
hatredyn accused him to &thorn;e pape. Trapazedy was sum tyme halden of &thorn;e emperour of Constantinople; bot a
myghty man and a riche, wham &thorn;e emperour sent to kepe it agayne &thorn;e Turkes, held it still vntill him self and
gert call him emperour of Trapazedy.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.73.17" CORRESP="Cot.97.6">Fra &thorn;e citee of Trapazedy men gase to Lytill Hermony. In &thorn;at cuntree es ane alde castell sett apon a
roche, whilk es called in Fransch <NAME LANG="lat">Le Chastel Despuere</NAME>, &thorn;at es to say on Inglish, "&thorn;e Castell of &thorn;e Sperhawke."
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">the whiche is cleped the Castelle of the Sparrehawk, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And it es betwene &thorn;e citee of Larrais
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Layays, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;e citee of Percipre,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Pharsipee, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk es &thorn;e lordes of Croke
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Cruk, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and he es a riche
<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio">man and a gode Cristen man. In &thorn;at castell men fyndes a sperhawke sittand apon a perke, and a faire lady of
Fairye sittand &thorn;erby and kepand it. And wha so will com and kepe &thorn;at sperhawke, wakand it continuelly vii.
days and vii. ny&yogh;tes, or, as sum men saise, iii. days and iii. nyghtes, withouten company and withouten sleping,
&thorn;is faire lady sall com to him at &thorn;e seuend day, or &thorn;e thridd day, end, and scho sall graunt him what sum euer
he askez of erthely thing; and &thorn;at hase bene many a tyme assayd. For &thorn;are come sum tyme a kyng of Ermony,
a myghty lorde and a wor&thorn;i, and woke &thorn;is hawke to &thorn;e end of &thorn;e days; and &thorn;an &thorn;e lady come to him and bad
him ask what erthely thing as he wald, as he &thorn;at wele had done his deuer. &THORN;e kyng answerd and said, "I am,"
quod he, "a lord riche ynogh; for&thorn;i I will nan o&thorn;er thing ask bot &thorn;i body to hafe it at my will." And scho

<PB N="74">
answerd and said, "Vnhappily," quod scho, "and vnwisely has &thorn;ou asked. For my body may &thorn;ou no&yogh;t hafe, by
cause I am no&yogh;t erthely, bot spirituall." "Certes," quod &thorn;e kyng, "I will ask no thing elles." "Now fra &thorn;i
foly," quod &thorn;e lady, "may I no&yogh;t drawe &thorn;e. Bot I schall giffe &thorn;e vnasked &thorn;at es ri&yogh;twyse; for &thorn;ou and all &thorn;at
of &thorn;ee sall com sall hafe were <CORR SIC="with" RESP="GW">withouten</CORR>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">withouten pees, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> ferme pees all way vnto &thorn;e nynde degree and all ways be in &thorn;e
subieccioun of &yogh;oure enmys and hafe defaute of all maner of gude." And ri&yogh;t so it es befallen; for &thorn;e king of
Ermony had neuer pes, bot ay were, sen &thorn;at tyme, and he and all his er ay pure and nedy and liffez vnder &thorn;e
tribute of &thorn;aire enmys.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">of the Sarrazines, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Ano&thorn;er tyme &thorn;er come a symple mannes son and woke &thorn;e sperhawke. And he asked
<MILESTONE N="62" UNIT="folio">of &thorn;e lady &thorn;at he my&yogh;t be riche and happy in marchandyse for to gete werldly gudes; and scho graunted him.
And he become &thorn;e ricchest marchand of all &thorn;at land, so &thorn;at he knew no&yogh;t &thorn;e thowsand parte of his gude; and so
he was wyser &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng before. After &thorn;is &thorn;er come a knyght of &thorn;e Templers and woke &thorn;is sperhawke wele
and asked &thorn;at he myght hafe euermare his purs full of gold; and &thorn;e lady graunted him his asking. Bot scho
said &thorn;at he asked &thorn;e destruccioun and &thorn;e vndoyng of his order, for &thorn;e grete pride of his ricches and &thorn;e grete trist
of &thorn;at purs; and so it befell afterward. For&thorn;i it es gude to him &thorn;at schall wake &thorn;is hawke &thorn;at he be wele warre
&thorn;at he slepe no&yogh;t; for, if he slepe, he bese lost for euer, and neuermare comme whare men er. &THORN;is ilke castell
es no&yogh;t in &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way to &thorn;e cuntrez before neuend; bot he &thorn;at will see swilk meruailes, him behoues sum tyme
&thorn;us wende oute of &thorn;e way.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.74.17" CORRESP="Cot.98.19">&THORN;e ri&yogh;t way fra Trapazedy til Ermony &thorn;e mare es to a citee &thorn;at men calles Artiron, &thorn;e whilk was wont to
be a gude citee and a riche and a faire, bot &thorn;e Turkes hase destruyd it. Aboute it growez bot lytill <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW" SOURCE="Cot">wyn</SUPPLIED> or
lytill o&thorn;er fruyt, for &thorn;e land es hegh and calde; bot &thorn;er er many riuers and gude welles &thorn;at commes vnder &thorn;e
erthe fra Eufrates, &thorn;e whilk es fra &thorn;at citee a day iournee. And &thorn;is riuer of Eufrates commes vnder &thorn;e erthe
toward Inde, and afterward it commez vp in &thorn;e land of Allazar. Thurgh &thorn;is Ermony &thorn;e mare men passez and
commez to &thorn;e see of Perse. Fra &thorn;e forsaid citee of Artiron men gase to a hill &thorn;at es called Sabissebella or
<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio">Sabissacolle. And &thorn;are nere es ano&thorn;er hill &thorn;at men callez Ararath, bot &thorn;e Iews callez it Thano, whare Noe
schippe restid after &thorn;e flude. And &yogh;it es it &thorn;are, and may be sene on ferrom in clere weder. &THORN;at hill es seuen
myle hegh. Sum saise &thorn;ai hafe bene &thorn;are att and putte &thorn;aire fyngers in &thorn;e hole whare &thorn;e fende &yogh;ode out, when
Noe said Benedicite; bot &thorn;ai say no&yogh;t sothe. For &thorn;er may na man ga vp on &thorn;at hill for snawe, &thorn;at es all way

<PB N="75">
&thorn;er apon, bathe wynter and somer. Ne &thorn;er come neuer man &thorn;erat sen Noe was, bot a mounk, &thorn;at thurgh grace
of Godd &yogh;ode &thorn;ider and bro&yogh;t &thorn;eine with him a burde of &thorn;e schippe, &thorn;e whilk es &yogh;it in ane abbay at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;e
hill.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.75.3" CORRESP="Cot.99.10">&THORN;is ilke mounke desired gretely to ga vp on &thorn;at hill; and so apon a day he afforced him &thorn;erto and went
vpward on &thorn;e hill. And by he had gane &thorn;e thridd parte of &thorn;e hill, he was so wery &thorn;at he my&yogh;t na ferther, and
he rested him &thorn;are and fell on slepe. And, when he wakned, he fand him doune agayne at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;e hill.
And &thorn;an he besoght Godd &thorn;at he wald suffer him ga vp; and ane aungell come to him and bad him ga vp. And
he did so, and broght &thorn;eine &thorn;e forsaid plaunke. And seyne come neuer man &thorn;are; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai say wrang
&thorn;at saise &thorn;ai hafe bene &thorn;are.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.75.9" CORRESP="Cot.99.8">A lytill
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">A lytill &hellip; kirkes, in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> higher up, as in the French text.</NOTE> &thorn;eine es &thorn;e citee of Dayne, &thorn;e whilk Noe founded; and also a lytill &thorn;eine es &thorn;e cite of Anye, in &thorn;e
whilk ware wont to be i<HI REND="sup">m</HI> kirkes.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.75.10" CORRESP="Cot.99.20">Fra &thorn;e forsaid hill men gase to a cite &thorn;at es called Taurizo, and it es a faire
<MILESTONE N="63" UNIT="folio">cite and a gude. Besyde &thorn;at citee es a hill of salt, and &thorn;eroff may ilke man take what he will. And &thorn;are
dwellez many Cristen men, payand tribute to &thorn;e Sarzenes. &THORN;e citee of Taurizo was sum tyme called Faxis; and
it es ane of the gude citez of marchandisez in &thorn;e werld, and &thorn;ider commez marchandez oute of many landes.
For &thorn;are may &thorn;ai fynd for to sell all maner of marchandise &thorn;at &thorn;ai will spirre efter. &THORN;is cite es in &thorn;e emperour
land of Persy, and men saise &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour takez mare of &thorn;at citee to customez of marchandise &thorn;an &thorn;e ricchest
Cristen king of &thorn;e werld may dispend.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.75.17" CORRESP="Cot.99.32">Fra &thorn;is cite men gase by many tounes and castelles and many iournez toward Inde and commez to a cite
&thorn;at men <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">calles</SUPPLIED> Sodonie, &thorn;e whilk es x. day iournez fra Taurizo; and it es a faire cite and a noble. And &thorn;are
dwellez &thorn;e emperour of Perse all &thorn;e somer, by cause &thorn;e cuntree es calde. And &thorn;are er many grete riuers, &thorn;at
will bere grete schippez. Seyne men gase toward Inde many day iournez thurgh many cuntreez, and commez
to a cite &thorn;at es called Cassach, &thorn;e whilk es a gude citee and a riche and plentifous of corne and o&thorn;er maner of
vitailes. At &thorn;at citee, as men saise, mette &thorn;e three kynges &thorn;at went to make offerand to Criste in Bethleem;
and it es fra Bethleem three and fyfty day iourneez. Fra &thorn;is citee men gase til ano&thorn;er cite, &thorn;at es called Beth;
and it es a day iournee fra &thorn;e Grauelly See. &THORN;is es &thorn;e nobillest within &thorn;e empire of Perse; and sum callez it
Cardabago, and sum Vapa.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">And &thorn;ei clepen flessch &thorn;ere Dabago and the wyn Vapa, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e Sarzenez &thorn;are saise &thorn;at &thorn;er may na Cristen men <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">dwell</SUPPLIED> in &thorn;at citee na while &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio">ne &thorn;ai schall dye; &thorn;e cause why, wate na man. Fra &thorn;eine men gase many iourneez by many citez, &thorn;e whilk ware
ouerlang to rekken, to &thorn;ai comme til a citee &thorn;at es called Carnaa, &thorn;at was wont to be so grete &thorn;at &thorn;e walle

<PB N="76">
aboute was xxv. myle; and &thorn;are endez &thorn;e land of &thorn;e emperour of Perse And,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">And &yogh;if &yogh;ee wole knowe the lettres of Persaynes and what names &thorn;ei han, &thorn;ei ben suche as I last deuysed &thorn;ou, but not in sownynge of here wordes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. Over the letters in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR> are those of the English alphabet in regular order.</NOTE> if &yogh;e will wit whatkyn letters
&thorn;ai vse, here &yogh;e may here &thorn;am:&mdash;Alma, Bem, Cem, Dem, Ethin, Folthin, Gith, Hith, Iothin, Kinyn, Lathin,
Moin, Nichoin, Ozeph, Phisan, Quinth, Yr, Seth, Toith, Vith, Xith, Ya, Zofin.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.17" N="17" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.18">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XVII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the lond of Job, and of his age; of the aray of men of Caldee; of the lond where wommen duellen withouten companye of men; of the knouleche and vertues of the verray dyamaunt.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.76.7" CORRESP="Cot.100.26">FRA men passe fra Carnaa &thorn;ai entre in to &thorn;e land of Iob; and it es a faire cuntree and a gude, and grete
plentee &thorn;erin of fruytz and o&thorn;er ricches. And &thorn;at land es called Sweze. In &thorn;at land es &thorn;e citee of
Theman. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">Iob</SUPPLIED> was Are son of Gosra, and he was prince and lord of
&thorn;at cuntree. And he was so riche &thorn;at he knew no&yogh;t &thorn;e end of his gudez by a hundreth partes. And if all he
ware a paynymme, neuer &thorn;e latter he serued Godd full deuoutely after &thorn;e custom of his lawe, whas seruyse was
acceptable to Godd. Afterward it befell thurgh &thorn;e sufferaunce of Godd &thorn;at sudaynely he fell to grete mischeffe
and grete pouert, when he was of elde iii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> &yogh;ere and ten.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">corrected to "xviii."</NOTE> Bot Godd, hafand reward til his grete pacience and
his mekeness, sent him agayne mare ricches &thorn;an euer he had before and mare wirschepe. &THORN;e whilk efterward,
when &thorn;e kyng of Ydumee was deed, was made kyng of Ydumee, and, as sum saise, his name was chaunged and
<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio">called Iobab. And &thorn;are he liffed clxx. &yogh;ere; and, when he dyed, he was of age cc. &yogh;ere and xlviii. In &thorn;e land of
Iob es na defaute of thing &thorn;at es nedefull to &thorn;e liffyng of man. &THORN;are er hilles whare men findez manna mare
plentifously and better &thorn;an in any o&thorn;er place. Manna es called breed of aungels, and it es a thing ri&yogh;t whyte and
swete, &yogh;a swetter &thorn;an sugur or hony. And it commez of &thorn;e dew of heuen, &thorn;at fallez on &thorn;e herbes, and &thorn;are it
coagules and waxez white. And men duse it in medecines for grete men and riche for costyfnes and for
clensing of corrupte blude.</SEG></P>

<PB N="77">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.77.1" CORRESP="Cot.101.24">&THORN;is land of Iob marchez on &thorn;e land of Caldee, &thorn;e whilk es a grete land; and &thorn;aire langage es gretter and
mare generall &thorn;an of any land on &thorn;at syde &thorn;e see. And men gase &thorn;ider by &thorn;e toure of Babilon, as I said before,
whare &thorn;e first chaungeyng of tunges was made; and it es fra Caldee foure day iournez. In &thorn;e rewme of Caldee
er ri&yogh;t faire men and wele apparailed in clathes of gold and precious stanes. Bot &thorn;e wymmen er ri&yogh;t layth and
ill araid,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">righte foule and euylle arrayed, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;ai ga barfote. And &thorn;ai hafe on ane vnthrifty garement, wyde and schort by &thorn;e knee, and it has
lang slefez and wyde, as it ware of blak mounkes, hingand to &thorn;aire fete. &THORN;aire hare of &thorn;aire heueds es blak and
grete, and hingez doune aboute &thorn;aire scholdres. And &thorn;ir wymmen er ri&yogh;t blak and vggly to behold and of euill
nurture. In &thorn;e rewme of Caldee es a citee &thorn;e whilk es called Vr, wherin Thare, Abraham fader, dwelled sum
<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio">tyme; and &thorn;at was in &thorn;e tyme of Ninus, &thorn;at was king of Babiloyne, of Araby and of Egipte. He, &thorn;is Ninus,
made &thorn;e cite of Niniue, bot Noe began it first; and by cause &thorn;at Ninus endid it, &thorn;erfore is it called Niniue
after his name. In Niniue was Thoby grauen, of wham Haly Writte spekez. Oute of &thorn;e citee of Vr went
Abraham at &thorn;e bidding of Godd, after &thorn;at his fader was deed, and tuke with him Sara his wyf and his bro&thorn;er son
Loth, for &thorn;at tyme he had na childer him self, and come in to &thorn;e land of Canaan and dwelled &thorn;are in a place &thorn;at
es called Sychem. &THORN;is Loth was he &thorn;at was saued at &thorn;e subuersioun of Sodom and Gomorre. &THORN;e folk of Caldee
has a propre langage and propre lettres and figures; and &thorn;ir er &thorn;e figures of &thorn;aire lettres &hellip;
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Twenty-two characters here follow, but they are too corrupt to be recognisable.</NOTE></SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.77.16" CORRESP="Cot.102.22">Besyde Caldee es &thorn;e land of Amazoun, whilk
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;at is the lond of Femynye, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> we call &thorn;e mayden land or &thorn;e land of wymmen; for &thorn;are
dwellez na men &thorn;erin, bot all anely wymmen. No&yogh;t, as sum men saise, for &thorn;at na men may liffe in &thorn;at land, bot
for&thorn;i &thorn;at wymmen will no&yogh;t suffer men for to hafe gouernaunce of &thorn;e rewme. For &thorn;are was sum tyme a kyng in
&thorn;at land, &thorn;e whilk hight Colopheus, and men dwelland &thorn;erin as duse in o&thorn;er cuntrez. And it befell &thorn;at &thorn;is kyng
had were with &thorn;e kyng of Sithy, and so befell &thorn;at he went ane tyme to bataile agaynes &thorn;e grete kyng his
<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio">aduersary, and was slayne in &thorn;e stoure and all &thorn;e grete men of his rewme with him. And, when &thorn;e qwene and
o&thorn;er ladys of &thorn;at land herd tell &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng and &thorn;e lordes ware &thorn;us slayne, &thorn;ai gadred &thorn;am togyder with ane
asscent and armed &thorn;am wele and tuke with &thorn;am grete company of wymmen and slewgh doune clenly all &thorn;e men
&thorn;at ware left amanges &thorn;am. And sen &thorn;at tyme hiderward wald &thorn;ai neuer late men dwell with &thorn;am ower seuen
days, ne neuer suffer knafe childe be nurisched amanges &thorn;am. Bot, when &thorn;ai will hafe felischepe of men, &thorn;ai

<PB N="78">
drawe &thorn;am to &thorn;e syde of &thorn;e land, whare &thorn;aire lemmans dwellez, and &thorn;are &thorn;ai dwell with &thorn;am viii. or ix. days and
&thorn;an wendez hame agayne. And, if any of &thorn;am be with childe and hafe a son, &thorn;ai kepe it till it can speke and ga
and ete by it self and &thorn;an sendez it to &thorn;e fader, or elles slaez it. And, if it be a mayden childe, &thorn;ai schere away
hir a pappe,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;ei don awey with on pappe with an hote hiren, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of a womman of grete astate hir left pappe, and brynnez it, for scho sall &thorn;e better bere hir schelde;
and, if &thorn;ai be of lawe degree, &thorn;ai schere away &thorn;e ri&yogh;t pappe, for
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">for to scheten with bowe turkeys, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> it sall no&yogh;t lette &thorn;am to schote, for &thorn;ai can ri&yogh;t
wele &thorn;e craft of schotyng. &THORN;are es euermare in &thorn;at rewme a qwene &thorn;at has &thorn;e gouernaunce of &thorn;e land, and til
hir &thorn;ai er all obeyand. And &thorn;is qwene es euermare chosen by eleccioun, for &thorn;ai chese hir &thorn;at es &thorn;e doghtyest in
armes. &THORN;ir wymmen er noble werrayours and wys; and &thorn;erfore kynges of o&thorn;er rewmes neghe &thorn;am wagez &thorn;am
for to helpe &thorn;am in &thorn;aire weres. &THORN;is land of Amazoun is bot ane ile, closed all aboute with water, oute taken twa
<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio">placez, whare er twa entreez; and be&yogh;ond &thorn;ir waters dwellez &thorn;aire forsaid lemmannes, to &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai may ga,
when &thorn;am list, for to hafe bodily lyking of &thorn;am. Be syde &thorn;e land of Amazoun es a cuntree &thorn;at es called Termegutte,
a faire cuntree and a lykand; and for &thorn;e grete bewtee and bountee of &thorn;is cuntree kyng Alexander wald hafe sett
&thorn;are &thorn;e first citee of Alysaunder. For in &thorn;at land he made xii. Alysaunders, of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;is es &thorn;e first; bot now
it es called Celsite.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.78.15" CORRESP="Cot.103.33">On &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde of Caldee, toward &thorn;e southe, es &thorn;e land of Ethiopy, &thorn;e whilk es a grete land and lastez
vntil Egipte. Ethiopy es diuised in twa principale parties, &thorn;at es to say in &thorn;e south party and &thorn;e <DEL TYPE="cancellation" RESP="GW">northe</DEL><ADD PLACE="superlinear" RESP="GW">est</ADD>.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">written over "northe."</NOTE> &THORN;e south
party es called Mauritayne, and &thorn;e folk of &thorn;is party es blacker &thorn;an of &thorn;e este party.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and &thorn;ei ben clept Mowres, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;is party also es a well
&thorn;at on &thorn;e day es so calde &thorn;at na man may drink &thorn;aroff, and on &thorn;e nyght so hate &thorn;at na man may suffer his hand
&thorn;erin. Be&yogh;ond Mauritayne, for to wende by see toward &thorn;e southe, es a grete cuntree, bot it es inhabitable by
cause of &thorn;e owtrage hete
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">the feruent brennynge, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e sonne. In Ethiopy all &thorn;e waters er so trublee and so salt for ouermykill hete of
&thorn;e sonne, &thorn;at na man dare wele dele with &thorn;am. And &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at land will lightly be drunken; and &thorn;ai hafe
lytill appetite to &thorn;aire mete; and &thorn;ai hafe comounly &thorn;e flux; and &thorn;ai liffe bot schort tyme. And in &thorn;at land er
folk of diuerse schappes. For &thorn;are er sum &thorn;at hase bot a fote; and &thorn;ai will rynne so fast apon &thorn;at a fote &thorn;at it
<MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="folio">es wonder to see. And &thorn;at ilke fote es so mykill &thorn;at it will couer and oumbre all his body for &thorn;e sonne. In
Ethiopy
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">In Ethiope, whan the children ben &yogh;onge and lytill, &thorn;ei ben all &yogh;alowe; and whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei wexen of age, &thorn;at &yogh;alowness turneth to ben all blak, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> er &yogh;ung childer white hared, and, when &thorn;ai er of elde, &thorn;aire hare waxez blakk. In &thorn;is land of Ethiopy
es &thorn;e citee of Saba, of whilk ane of &thorn;e three kynges &thorn;at offerd till oure Lord was kyng.</SEG></P>

<PB N="79">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.79.1" CORRESP="Cot.104.24">Fra Ethiopy men gase intill Inde thurgh many diuerse cuntrez.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and men clepen the high Ynde Emlak, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at Inde es
diuised in three partys, &thorn;at es to say in Inde &thorn;e mare, &thorn;e whilk es a hegh cuntree and a hate; and in Inde &thorn;e
lesse, &thorn;e whilk es a temperee land, and it es toward &thorn;e south; &thorn;e thridd parte es toward &thorn;e northe, and it es so
calde a cuntree &thorn;at for &thorn;e grete calde and continuele frost &thorn;e water congelez in to cristall. And apon &thorn;e roche
of cristall growez gude dyamaundes, &thorn;at er of &thorn;e colour of cristall, bot &thorn;ai er mare dymme coloured &thorn;an &thorn;e
cristall and broune as oile. And &thorn;ai er so hard &thorn;at &thorn;are may na metell pulisch &thorn;am ne breke &thorn;am. O&thorn;er
dyamaundes fyndez men in Araby, &thorn;at er no&yogh;t so gude, whilk er mare tendre. And sum er fun in Cypre, &thorn;at er
mare tendre &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;er; and &thorn;erfor may &thorn;ai &thorn;e lyghtlyer be pulischt. Also men fyndez sum in Macedoyne;
bot &thorn;ase of Inde er &thorn;e best. And sum er fun oft tymes in a masse &thorn;at commez oute of &thorn;e myne, whare men
fyndez gold, and &thorn;ase er als hard as &thorn;ase of Inde. And, if all it be so &thorn;at men fyndez gude dyamaundes in Inde
apon &thorn;e roche of cristall, also men fyndez dyamaundes gude and hard apon &thorn;e roche of &thorn;e adamaund in &thorn;e see
<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio">and apon hilles also, of &thorn;e mykilnes of hesill nuttes. And &thorn;ai er foure cornerd of &thorn;aire awen growyng and foure
squarre. And &thorn;ai growe sammen, male and female; and &thorn;ai er nurischt with dew of heuen. And &thorn;ai engender
and consayuez, as it ware, in &thorn;aire kynde and bringes furth smale childer, and so &thorn;ai multiply and growez all
way. I haue many tymes assaied and sene, &thorn;at, if a man take &thorn;am with a lytill of &thorn;e roche &thorn;at &thorn;ai growe on, so
&thorn;at &thorn;ai be taken vp by &thorn;e rutes and oft sythes wette with &thorn;e dew of May, &thorn;ai growe ilke a &yogh;ere visibilly, so &thorn;at &thorn;e
smale waxez grete.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">For right as the fyn perl congeleth and wexeth gret of the dew of heuene, right so doth the verray dyamand. And right as the perl of his owne kynde taketh roundness, right so the dyamand be vertu of God taketh squareness, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> A man sall bere &thorn;e dyamaund at his left syde; and &thorn;an es it of mare vertu &thorn;an on &thorn;e ri&yogh;t
syde, for &thorn;e strenth of his growyng es toward &thorn;e north, whilk es &thorn;e left syde of &thorn;e werld and &thorn;e left syde of a
man, when he turnez his visage toward &thorn;e este.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.79.20" CORRESP="Cot.105.34">And, if &yogh;e will knawe &thorn;e vertuz of &thorn;e dyamaund, I sall tell &yogh;ow as
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">as men may fynden in the lapidarye, &thorn;at many men knowen noght, I schall telle &yogh;ou as &thorn;ei be&yogh;onde the see seyn and affermen, of whom all science and all philosophie cometh from, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Ysidre libro 16 <TITLE LANG="lat">Ethicorum</TITLE>, capitulo de
cristallo, and Bertilmew <TITLE LANG="lat">De Proprietatibus Rerum</TITLE>, libro 16, capitulo de adamante, saise. &THORN;e dyamaund giffez to
him &thorn;at berez it on him hardyness, if it be freely giffen him, and it kepez &thorn;e lymmes of a man hale. It giffez
him grace to ouercomme his enmys, if his cause be ri&yogh;twys, bathe in were and in motyng. It kepez him in his
ri&yogh;t witte. It kepez him fra stryfez, debates, ryotes, and fra ill dremes and fantasies, and fra wikked spirits.

<PB N="80">
And if any man &thorn;at deles with sorcery or enchauntementz wald grefe him &thorn;at beres &thorn;e dyamaund, he schall no&yogh;t
dere him. Also &thorn;er sall na wylde beste assayle him &thorn;at berez it, ne &yogh;it na venymmous beste. And &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e dyamaund schuld be giffen freely, no&yogh;t couaited ne boght, and &thorn;an it es of mare vertu and makes
<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio">a man mare stalworth agayne his enmys. It helez him &thorn;at es lunatyc; and, if venym or puyson be bro&yogh;t in place
whare &thorn;e dyamaund es, alsone it waxez moyst and begynnez to swete, and men may wele polisch it. Bot sum
werkmen for malice will no&yogh;t polisch it, for &thorn;at men schuld trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ai my&yogh;t no&yogh;t be pulischt. In Inde also may
men fynd dyamaundz of violet colour and sum what browne, &thorn;e whilk er ri&yogh;t gude and full precious. Bot sum
men luffez &thorn;am no&yogh;t so wele as &thorn;ir o&thorn;er &thorn;at I hafe spoken off before. Neuer&thorn;eles me think &thorn;am als gude and
as precious as &thorn;e o&thorn;er; for sikerly I hafe oft sythez sene &thorn;am assaid. &THORN;ai hafe o&thorn;er also, &thorn;e whilk er white as
cristall, bot &thorn;ai er mare dymme and trublee; neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t gude and of grete vertu. And &thorn;ai er nere hand
all foure sqware and poynted, bot sum of &thorn;am er of &thorn;aire awen kynde three cornerd and sum sex.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.80.12" CORRESP="Cot.106.32">&YOGH;it will I tell &yogh;ow mare of &thorn;is stane, and
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at knowen hem not be not disceyued be gabberes, &thorn;at gon be the contree &thorn;at sellen hem, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> namely for &thorn;aim &thorn;at berez &thorn;is stane to diuerse cuntreez for to sell.
He &thorn;at will by &thorn;is stane, it es nedefull till him &thorn;at he cunn perfitely knawe &thorn;at stane for &thorn;e dessait of &thorn;am &thorn;at
sellez &thorn;am. For oft tymes &thorn;ai sell to &thorn;aim &thorn;at hase na grete knawyng of stanes in steed dyamaundez cristalles
pale and o&thorn;er maner of stanes, &thorn;e whilk er no&yogh;t so hard as dyamaundes, and comounly &thorn;aire poyntes er broken
off and &thorn;ai will lightly be polischt. Neuer&thorn;eles sum werkmen will no&yogh;t polisch &thorn;am fully, for to gere men wene
<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at &thorn;ai may no&yogh;t be polischt forhand. Neuer&thorn;eles men may assay &thorn;e dyamaund in &thorn;is manere. First for to take
&thorn;e dyamaund and rubbe it on &thorn;e safir or on cristall or sum o&thorn;er precious stanez or on clene burnyscht stele.
And seyne take
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">men taken the ademand &thorn;at is the schipmannes ston, &thorn;at draweth the nedle to him, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e adamand, &thorn;at drawez &thorn;e nedill til him, by &thorn;e whilk schippe men er gouerned in &thorn;e see, and
lay &thorn;e dyamaund apon &thorn;e adamaund and lay a nedill before &thorn;e adamaund. And, if &thorn;e dyamaund be gude and
vertuous, &thorn;e adamand drawes no&yogh;t &thorn;e nedill to him, whils &thorn;e dyamand es &thorn;are. And &thorn;is es &thorn;e assay whilk &thorn;ai
make be&yogh;ond &thorn;e see. Bot it fallez oft tymez &thorn;at &thorn;e gude dyamaund losez his vertu by defaute and incontinence of
him &thorn;at beres it. And &thorn;erfore it es nedefull to make it to hafe his vertu agayne or elles it es of lytill prys.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.18" N="18" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.19">
<PB N="81">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XVIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the customs of yles abouten Ynde; of the difference betwix ydoles and simulacres; of iii. maner growynges of peper vpon o tree; of the welle that chaungethe his odour euery hour of the day, and that is meruaylle.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.81.5" CORRESP="Cot.107.21">IN Inde er many diuerse cuntreez; and it es called Inde by cause of a water &thorn;at rynnez thurgh &thorn;at
land, &thorn;e whilk men callez Inde. In &thorn;at water men fyndez elez of xxx. fote lang. And folk &thorn;at
dwellez nere &thorn;at water er ill coloured, &yogh;alow and grene. In Inde er ma &thorn;an v<HI REND="sup">m</HI> iles &thorn;at men dwellez
in, gude and grete, withouten o&thorn;er &thorn;at men dwellez no&yogh;t in. And in ilke ane of &thorn;ase iles er many citez and
tounes and mykill folk. For men of Inde er of &thorn;at condicioun &thorn;at &thorn;ai passe no&yogh;t comounly oute of &thorn;aire awen
land, for &thorn;ai dwell vnder a planett &thorn;at es called Saturnus. And &thorn;at planet makes his turne by &thorn;e twelfe signes
in xxx. &yogh;ere; and &thorn;e mone, &thorn;e whilk es oure planet, passez by &thorn;e xii. signes in a moneth. And for Saturnus es
<MILESTONE N="68" UNIT="folio">of so late mouyng, &thorn;erfore men &thorn;at dwellez vnder him and in &thorn;at climate hase na gude will to be mykill stirrand
aboute, bot for to dwell still in &thorn;aire awen land and to couaite nan o&thorn;er. Bot in oure cuntree es euen &thorn;e
contrary. For we er in a clymate &thorn;e whilke es vnder &thorn;e gouernaunce of &thorn;e moone, &thorn;at es a planet of light
mouyng; and it es &thorn;e planet of way. And &thorn;erfore it giffez vs will to be mykill stirrand aboute and to ga in to
diuerse cuntrez of &thorn;e werld; for it passez aboute &thorn;e world mare lightly &thorn;an ano&thorn;er planet.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.81.17" CORRESP="Cot.108.20">Also men gase thurgh Inde by many cuntreez vnto &thorn;e grete see Occean; and &thorn;an &thorn;ai fynd &thorn;e ile of Chermes,
whider marchandes of Venice, of Geen and of many o&thorn;er cuntreez commez to bye marchandysez. Bot it es so
hate &thorn;are in &thorn;at ile &thorn;at men ballokes hyngez doune to &thorn;aire schankes for &thorn;e grete violence of hete, &thorn;at dissoluez
&thorn;aire bodys. And men of &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;at kennez &thorn;e manere byndez &thorn;am vp and vsez certayne oynementz calde
and restrictiue to hald &thorn;am vpp, or elles my&yogh;t &thorn;ai no&yogh;t liffe. In &thorn;is land and in Ethiopy and many o&thorn;er cuntrez
men and wymmen gase comounly to waters and lays &thorn;am in &thorn;am all naked fra vndrun of &thorn;e day to it be passed

<PB N="82">
none, for &thorn;e grete hete of &thorn;e sonne; and &thorn;ai ligg all vnder &thorn;e water bot &thorn;e heued. And wymmen &thorn;are schamez
no&yogh;t &thorn;of men see &thorn;am naked. And &thorn;are may a man see mykill dishonestee.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">many foule figure assembled, and namely nygh the gode townes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;is ile er schippes made
withouten nayles or bandes of yrne; and &thorn;at es by cause of roches of adamaundez &thorn;at er in &thorn;e see, whilk wald
<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio">drawe schippes to &thorn;am. And &thorn;are es so grete plentee of &thorn;ase rochez in &thorn;ase parties &thorn;at, if any schippes passed
&thorn;er away in &thorn;e whilk ware any maner of yrne, &thorn;ai schuld <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">be drawen</SUPPLIED> to &thorn;e rochez by &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e adamaund,
so &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld eschape on na wyse.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.82.7" CORRESP="Cot.109.9">Fra &thorn;is ile men wendez by see to &thorn;e ile of Cana, whare es grete plentee of wyne and of corne. It was sum
tyme a grete ile, and a gude hauen &thorn;erin; bot it es destruyd by &thorn;e see for &thorn;e mare party. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at ile
was sum tyme so grete and so myghty &thorn;at he faght with grete Alexander. Folk of &thorn;at ile hase diuerse lawes;
for sum wirschepez &thorn;e sonne in steed of Godd, sum &thorn;e fire, sum nedders, sum treessez, sum &thorn;e first thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai
mete at morne, sum wirschepez simulacres, sum ydoles. Betwene simulacres and ydoles es a grete difference.
For simulacres er ymages made to &thorn;e liknes of sum thing &thorn;at es kyndely; and ydoles er ymagez made to &thorn;e
liknes of what thing a man will &thorn;at es no&yogh;t kyndely. For amanges all maner of bestes &yogh;e schall fynd nane &thorn;at
hase three heueds, ane of a man, ano&thorn;er of a hors, ano&thorn;er of ane ox or of sum o&thorn;er beste, as &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire
ydoles. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at wirschepes simulacres wirschepes &thorn;am for sum worthy men, &thorn;at
ware sum tyme doghty men in armes, as Hercules, Achilles and swilk o&thorn;er, whilk didd many meruailes in &thorn;aire
<MILESTONE N="69" UNIT="folio">tymes. For &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai wate wele &thorn;ai er no&yogh;t Godd of kynde, &thorn;at made all thing, bot &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t wele with Godd
for meruailes &thorn;at &thorn;ai didd. And so say &thorn;ai of &thorn;e sonne; for it chaungez oft &thorn;e tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere and giffez hete
to nurisch all thinges of &thorn;e erthe. And, for it es of so grete profit, &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai wate wele &thorn;at it es wele with
Godd and &thorn;at Godd lufes it mare &thorn;an any o&thorn;er thing; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai wirschepe it. And &thorn;e same &thorn;ai say of o&thorn;er
planets and of &thorn;e fyre, by cause of &thorn;e grete profit &thorn;at commes of &thorn;am. And of ydoles &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;e ox es &thorn;e
halyest beste &thorn;at es in erthe and maste profitable, for he duse mykill gude and nane ill. And &thorn;ai wate wele, &thorn;ai
say, &thorn;at may no&yogh;t be withouten speciale grace of Godd; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire godd half man and half ox,
for man es &thorn;e fairest and &thorn;e best creature &thorn;at Godd made and &thorn;e ox &thorn;e halyest. &THORN;ai do wirschepe also to
nedders and o&thorn;er bestez whilk &thorn;ai mete first at morne, and namely to &thorn;ase bestez &thorn;at er gude and happy to mete,

<PB N="83">
after whaym &thorn;ai spede wele all &thorn;e day efter, whilk &thorn;ai hafe proued of lang tyme. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai say &thorn;is gude
metyng commez of Godd; and &thorn;erfore hafe &thorn;ai gert make ymagez lyke to &thorn;ase in &thorn;aire houses, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may
wirschepe &thorn;am before &thorn;ai mete with any o&thorn;er thinges.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">The passage following in the French text, down to "esperance en nostre Seignur," omitted here, is translated in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (see [commentary]).</NOTE></SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.83.3" CORRESP="Cot.111.18">In &thorn;is ile of Cana er many wylde bestez, as lyouns,
leoperds, beres and swilk o&thorn;er.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">lyouns and many o&thorn;er wylde bestes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;are er ratouns als grete as hundes er here; and &thorn;ai take &thorn;am with grete
mastyfes, for cattes er to smale to take &thorn;am. In &thorn;is cuntree and in many o&thorn;er, when men er deed, &thorn;ai graue
&thorn;am no&yogh;t; for &thorn;er es so grete hete &thorn;at alssone &thorn;e flessh es consumed euen to &thorn;e bane.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.83.7" CORRESP="Cot.111.23">Fra &thorn;eine men commez to a citee &thorn;at es called Sarchie, and it es a faire citee and a gude. And &thorn;are
dwellez many gude Cristen men of gude beleue; and &thorn;are er many men of religioun, and namely of freres.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">mendyuantes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Fra
&thorn;eine men gase to &thorn;e land of Lombe by see. In &thorn;at land growez peper in a forest, whilk es called Combar; and
it growez in na place of &thorn;e werld bot anely in &thorn;at forest. &THORN;at forest es xxiiii. iournez on lenth. And &thorn;are er twa
gude citez, of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e tane hat Flabryne and &thorn;e to&thorn;er &YOGH;inglauns; and in bathe &thorn;ir citez dwellez Cristen men
and Iews in grete noumer, for &thorn;e cuntree es right plentifous and gude. Bot it es ri&yogh;t hate, and &thorn;erfore &thorn;er es
grete haboundance of diuerse nedders and wormes. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at pepre growez in maner of
wilde wynes be syde &thorn;e treesse of &thorn;e forest, for to be suppoweld by &thorn;am. &THORN;e fruyt &thorn;eroff hinges in grete
clustres in maner of bobbes of grapes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">in manere as reysynges, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;ai hing so thikk &thorn;at, bot if &thorn;ai ware suppoweld by o&thorn;er treesse, &thorn;ai
myght no&yogh;t bere &thorn;aire fruyt. Qwhen &thorn;e fruyt es rype, it es all grene lyke &thorn;e berys of wodbind
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">as it were iuy beryes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;an &thorn;ai
gader &thorn;e fruyt and driez it at &thorn;e sonne and seyne layez it apon a flure
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">owven, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> til it becom blakk and runklid. And so
&thorn;ai hafe &thorn;are three maners of peper growand on a tree, &thorn;at es to say lang peper rype of &thorn;e awen kynde, whyte
peper no&yogh;t brynt ne birstlid with fyre ne with hete of &thorn;e sonne, and blak peper dried with hete of &thorn;e fyre or of
&thorn;e sonne. Lang peper call &thorn;ai Spotyn,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">sorbotyn, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> blakk Fulphul,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">fulfull, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and whyte Bonoile.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">bano, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> First commez oute &thorn;e lang peper,
when &thorn;e lefez begynnez to spring; and it es lyke vnto &thorn;e floure of &thorn;e hesill,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">chattes of hasell, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="f.70"> &thorn;at springes oute before &thorn;e lefes.

<PB N="84">
&THORN;an commez oute white peper with &thorn;e lefes in grete clustres, as
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">at, MS</NOTE> it ware grene grapes; &thorn;e whilk, when it es
gaderd, es whyte, and it es sum what lesse &thorn;an blakk peper. Seyne springes oute blak peper in grete
haboundaunce. Of &thorn;e white peper sell &thorn;ai bot lytill til o&thorn;er cuntrez or elles no&yogh;t, bot kepez it till &thorn;aire awen
vse; for it es better and mare profitable and of mare attemperee wirkyng &thorn;an &thorn;e o&thorn;er, and langer will <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">be</SUPPLIED> kepid
in his vertu.</SEG> And &yogh;e
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">And &yogh;e &hellip; fresch and new, not in French text or in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sall vnderstand &thorn;at, ay &thorn;e heuer peper es, &thorn;e better it es and &thorn;e newere. Neuer&thorn;eles it
fallez oft tyme &thorn;at marchands sophisticatez peper, when it es alde, as Ysidoris tellez. For &thorn;ai take alde peper
and stepez it and strewez apon it spume of siluer or of leed and driez it agayne, and so by cause of &thorn;e weight it
semes fresch and new. And &thorn;ai hafe of nane of &thorn;ir three maners of peper <SEG ID="Eg.84.8" CORRESP="Cot.112.19">so grete haboundaunce as of &thorn;e blakk.
In &thorn;at cuntree, as I said before, er many diuerse maners of nedders and of o&thorn;er wormes by cause of &thorn;e grete
hete of &thorn;e cuntree and also of &thorn;e peper. And sum men saise &thorn;at a certayne tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, when &thorn;ai ga for to
gader &thorn;is peper, &thorn;ai make fyres here and &thorn;are, for to brynne &thorn;e nedders or elles make &thorn;am to flee &thorn;eine. Bot,
saue &thorn;aire grace, it es no&yogh;t so. For, if &thorn;ai &thorn;us made fires aboute &thorn;e peper, &thorn;ai schuld brynne &thorn;e peper and &thorn;e
treess &thorn;at it growez on, or elles drie &thorn;am so &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld na mare bere fruyt; and &thorn;at es no&yogh;t trew. Bot &thorn;ai
<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio">enoynt &thorn;aire hend and &thorn;aire fete and o&thorn;er placez of &thorn;aire bodys with ane oynement made of &thorn;e iuys of a fruyte &thorn;at
&thorn;ai call lymons
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;ei enoynten here hondes and here feet [with a juice] mad of snayles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. A confusion between "limons" and "lima&ccedil;ons."</NOTE> menged with o&thorn;er certayne thinges, and &thorn;an &thorn;ai ga baldely for to gader &thorn;e peper. And &thorn;e
nedders and venymmous wormes, when &thorn;ai fele &thorn;e reflaire of &thorn;e oynement, fleez away; and on &thorn;is wyse in sothefastnes get &thorn;ai &thorn;e peper.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.84.18" CORRESP="Cot.112.35">At &thorn;e heued of &thorn;is ilk forest es &thorn;e citee of Polombe; and besyde &thorn;at citee es a mountayne, wharoff &thorn;e citee
takez &thorn;e name, for men callez &thorn;e mountayne Polombe. And at &thorn;e fote of &thorn;is mountayne es a well, noble and
faire; and &thorn;e water &thorn;eroff has a swete sauour and reflaire, as it ware of diuerse maner of spicery. And ilke
houre of &thorn;e day &thorn;e water chaungez diuersely his sauour and his smell. And, wha so drinkes fastand thryes of &thorn;at
well, he sall be hale of what maner of malady &thorn;at he hase. And for&thorn;i &thorn;e &thorn;at wonnez nere &thorn;at well drynkez &thorn;eroff
&thorn;e ofter, and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai hafe neuermare sekeness, bot euermare &thorn;ai seme &yogh;ung. I, Iohn Maundeuill, sawe &thorn;is
well and drank &thorn;eroff thrys and all my felawes, and euermare sen &thorn;at tyme I fele me &thorn;e better and &thorn;e haler and
supposez for to do till &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at Godd of his grace will make me to passe oute of &thorn;is dedly lyf.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">I haue dronken &thorn;ere of iii. or iiii. sithes, and &yogh;it me thinketh I fare the better, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Sum men
callez &thorn;at well <NAME LANG="lat">Fons iuuentutis</NAME>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">welle of &yogh;outhe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at es for to say, &thorn;e well of &yogh;owthehede; for &thorn;ai &thorn;at drinkez &thorn;eroff semez all
way &yogh;ung. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;is well commez fra Paradys terrestre, for it es so vertuous. Thurgh oute all &thorn;is
cuntree &thorn;er growes &thorn;e best gynger &thorn;at es ower whare; and marchaunds commez &thorn;ider fra ferre cuntreez
for to bye it.</SEG></P>

<PB N="85">
<MILESTONE N="71" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.85.1" CORRESP="Cot.113.16">And in &thorn;is
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">An &thorn;is, MS.</NOTE> cuntree &thorn;e folk &thorn;eroff wirschepez &thorn;e ox, in steed of Godd, for &thorn;e sympilnes and &thorn;e gudeness &thorn;at
commez of him. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;are &thorn;at &thorn;e ox es &thorn;e halyest best of &thorn;e werld and many vertuz has in him; for
sex &yogh;ere or seuen &thorn;e ox will drawe in &thorn;e plugh and helpe to labour for mannes sustynaunce, and efter &thorn;at men
may ete him. &THORN;e king of &thorn;at land hase euermare ane ox with him, whare so euer he be, and honoures it as his
godd. And he &thorn;at kepez &thorn;is ox gaders &thorn;e dung of him in a vessell of gold and &thorn;e vryne in ano&thorn;er; and all &thorn;at
euer he gaders on &thorn;e nyght on &thorn;e morue he beres to &thorn;aire prelate, whilk es called Archiprothopapaton, and he
berez it to &thorn;e kyng and makes &thorn;ar ower many blissings. And &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng puttez his handes in &thorn;e vryne of &thorn;e
ox, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai call gaul, and &thorn;erwith he rubbez his frunt and his breste. And &thorn;an with grete reuerence he takez
of &thorn;e dung and rubbez it on his visage and his breste, as he did with &thorn;e vryn, in &thorn;at entent &thorn;at he be fulfilled
with &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e haly ox and &thorn;at he be blissed with &thorn;at haly thing. And after &thorn;e kyng o&thorn;er lordes and princez
dose on &thorn;e same maner; and efter &thorn;aim seruandes and o&thorn;er men, ilk ane in &thorn;aire degree, als lang as oght
lastez &thorn;eroff. In &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;aire ydoles, &thorn;at es &thorn;aire fals goddes, hase half schappe of man and half of ane ox;
and in &thorn;ase ydoles &thorn;e fende spekez to &thorn;am and giffes answere of what so &thorn;ai ask. Before &thorn;ise fals goddes &thorn;ai
sla &thorn;aire childer many tymes in steed of sacrifice, and takes &thorn;aire blude aud sprenklez it apon &thorn;aire mawmets,
<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio">and &thorn;us &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire sacrifice to &thorn;am. And, when any man dies in &thorn;at land, &thorn;ai brynne his body, for &thorn;at he
suld suffer na payne, when he es in his graue, thurgh etyng of wormes. And, if he hafe na childer, &thorn;ai brynne
his wyf with him. For &thorn;ai say &thorn;at it es resoun &thorn;at scho bere him cumpany in &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld as scho did here in
&thorn;is werld. And, if scho hafe childer, &thorn;ai late hir liffe for to bring &thorn;am vp, if scho will. And, if it be swa &thorn;at
scho chese rather to liffe with hir childer &thorn;an to be brynned with hir housband, &thorn;an sall scho be arettid vntrew
and vnkynde,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">men holden hire for fals and cursed, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and scho sall neuer be praised, ne na man sall efter &thorn;at tyme trist on hir. And, if &thorn;e wyf dye
before hir husband, he schall no&yogh;t be brynt with hir agayne his will; bot, if him list, he may take him ano&thorn;er
wyf. In &thorn;at cuntree also growez gude wynes; and &thorn;are sall &thorn;e wymmen drinke wyne, and no&yogh;t &thorn;e men. And
wymmen schafez &thorn;er beerdes, and no&yogh;t men.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.19" N="19" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.20">
<PB N="86">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XIX</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the domes made be seynt Thomas hond; of deuocioun and sacrifice made to ydoles there in the cytee of Calamye; and of the processioun in goynge aboute the cytee.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.86.4" CORRESP="Cot.114.20">FRA &thorn;is land men gase by many diuerse placez to a cuntree &thorn;at es called Mabaron; and it es fra &thorn;e
forsaid land x. day iourneez. And it es a grete rewme and a large, and many gude citeez and tounes
&thorn;erin. In &thorn;at land of Mabaron liez sayne Thomas &thorn;e apostle, and his body all hale, in a faire toumbe
in &thorn;e citee of Calamy; for &thorn;are was he martird and grauen. Bot afterwardes &thorn;e Assirienes tuke his body and
<MILESTONE N="72" UNIT="folio">bare it to a citee in Mesopotamy &thorn;at es called Edisse. Bot eft sones it was translated agayne to &thorn;e forsaid citee
and layd in &thorn;e forsaid toumbe; and his arme with his hand &thorn;at he putt in oure Lordes syde after his resurreccioun,
when he said, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Noli esse incredulus, sed fidelis</Q>, lyez withouten in a vessell. And by that hand men of &thorn;at
cuntree giffez &thorn;aire iugementz, to wit wha has ri&yogh;t. For, if any stryf be betwene twa parties and ayther party
affermez &thorn;at he has ri&yogh;t in his cause, &thorn;an &thorn;ai ger write in a scrowe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">in ii. billes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e ri&yogh;t of ayther party and puttez &thorn;ase billes
in &thorn;e hand of sayne Thomas; and als fast &thorn;e hand castez oute &thorn;e bille &thorn;at contenez &thorn;e fals cause, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er it
haldez still. And &thorn;erfore men commez oft tymes oute of ferre cuntreez &thorn;ider, for to declare a ri&yogh;twys cause
betwene party and party, &thorn;e whilk es in doute. &THORN;e kirke whare sayne Thomas lyes es mykill and faire and
full of ymagery of &thorn;aire mawmets;
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">fulle of grete sumulacres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;ase ymagez er ilk ane of &thorn;e stature of twa men at &thorn;e leste.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.86.17" CORRESP="Cot.115.17">Bot &thorn;are es ane &thorn;at passez all o&thorn;er of stature; and &thorn;at es richely and really enourned with gold and precious
stanes all aboute
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and &thorn;at ydole is the god of false Cristene &thorn;at han reneyed hire feythe, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and sittez in a chaier nobelly arraied. And he has aboute his nekk as it ware brade gyrdils
of silke,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">of silke, om <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> wele hernayst with gold and preciouse stanes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">And this chirche is full richely wrought and all ouer gylt withinne, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> To &thorn;at ymage men commez fra ferre in pilgrimage with
grete deuocioun, als comounly als Cristen men commez to sayne Iames. And sum of &thorn;am, for &thorn;e grete deuocioun

<PB N="87">
&thorn;ai hafe to &thorn;at mawmet, ay as &thorn;ai ga, er lukand douneward to &thorn;e erthe and will no&yogh;t luke aboute &thorn;am, for &thorn;ai
<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio">schuld see na thing &thorn;at schuld lette &thorn;aire deuocioun. &THORN;are commez sum also &thorn;ider in pilgrimage &thorn;at beres
scharpe knyfes in &thorn;aire handes, with whilk, ay as &thorn;ai ga by &thorn;e way, &thorn;ai wound &thorn;am self in &thorn;e legges and &thorn;e armes
and in o&thorn;er placez of &thorn;aire body, &thorn;at &thorn;e blude rynnez doune fra &thorn;er woundes in grete fuysoun. And &thorn;is &thorn;ai do for
lufe of &thorn;at ydole, and saise &thorn;at he es full blissed &thorn;at will dye for &thorn;e lufe of his mawmet. And sum of &thorn;am
bringez with &thorn;am &thorn;aire childer and slaez &thorn;aim and makes sacrifice of &thorn;am to &thorn;aire mawmet; and &thorn;ai take &thorn;e blude
of &thorn;aire childer and sprenklez it apon &thorn;e ymage. Sum also, fra &thorn;ai passe oute of &thorn;er housez til &thorn;ai comme before
&thorn;aire mawmet, at ilke a thridd passe knelis doune apon &thorn;e erthe with grete deuocioun. And &thorn;ai bring with &thorn;am
incense and o&thorn;er thinges swete smelland for to turify
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">sensen, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at ymage, as we do here to Goddes body. And &thorn;are es
before &thorn;at ymage, as it ware, a poonde or a vyuer, full of water; and in to &thorn;at pilgrimes castez gold and siluer
and precious stanes withouten noumer in steed of offerand. And for&thorn;i &thorn;e mynisters &thorn;at kepez &thorn;at ilk mawmet,
when &thorn;ai hafe mister of any monee for reparailyng
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">neden to maken ony reparacion, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of &thorn;aire kirk or for any o&thorn;er thing &thorn;at fallez to &thorn;at ilke
mawmet, &thorn;ai ga to &thorn;at ilke poonde and takez oute &thorn;eroff als mykill as &thorn;am nedez. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at,
when grete festez commez of &thorn;at mawmet, as &thorn;e dedicacioun of &thorn;e kirk or &thorn;e tronyng of &thorn;at mawmet, all &thorn;e
cuntree assemblez &thorn;ider; and &thorn;ai sett &thorn;is mawmet with grete wirschepe in a chariot, wele arraid with clathez of
<MILESTONE N="73" UNIT="folio">gold and of silke,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">of tartarye, of camacaa and o&thorn;er precyous clothes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and ledez him with grete sollempnitee aboute &thorn;e citee. And before &thorn;e chariot gase first in
processioun all &thorn;e maydens of &thorn;e cuntree, twa and twa togyder; and &thorn;an all &thorn;e pilgrymmes &thorn;at commez &thorn;ider fra
ferre cuntreez, of whilke sum for &thorn;e grete deuocioun &thorn;ai hafe to &thorn;at mawmet fallez doune before &thorn;e chariot and
latez it gang ouer &thorn;am. And so er sum of &thorn;am slayne, sum &thorn;aire armes and sum &thorn;aire schankes broken; and &thorn;ai
trowe &thorn;at, &thorn;e mare payne &thorn;ai suffer here for lufe of &thorn;aire mawmet, &thorn;e mare ioy in &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld sall &thorn;ai hafe and
&thorn;e nerre &thorn;aire godd sall &thorn;ai be. And sikerly &thorn;ai suffer so mykill payne and martirdom apon &thorn;aire bodys for &thorn;e
lufe of &thorn;at ilke mawmet &thorn;at vnnethes will any Cristen man suffer half so mykill, ne &thorn;e tende parte, for &thorn;e lufe of
oure Lorde Iesu Criste.</SEG> For sum tyme &thorn;are slaez &thorn;am self for luffe of &thorn;at mawmet cc. or three apon a day,
<SEG ID="Eg.87.24" CORRESP="Cot.117.14">whas bodys er bro&yogh;t before &thorn;at mawmet and accounted in nowmer of sayntes. For, ri&yogh;t as a man amanges vs
wald think it a grete wirschepe, if &thorn;er ware in his kyn canonized a haly martir or a confessour and his vertuz

<PB N="88">
and his myracles writen in bukes, ri&yogh;t so think &thorn;aim it a grete wirschepe, when any of &thorn;er cusyns or of &thorn;er
frendes slaez &thorn;am self for lufe of &thorn;er mawmet, and writez &thorn;aire dedes and &thorn;er names in bukes and in &thorn;aire letanys.
And, ay &thorn;e ma of &thorn;er kyn &thorn;at slaez &thorn;am self on &thorn;is wise, &thorn;e mare glad &thorn;ai er, and saise ilk ane of &thorn;am till o&thorn;er,
<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio">"We hafe ma sayntes in oure kynne &thorn;an &yogh;e haue." And, when any of &thorn;am purposez him to sla him self for his
mawmet lufe, he callez all his frendez togyder and gers many mynstralles ga before &thorn;am with grete sollempnytee;
and so &thorn;ai comme before &thorn;e mawmet. And he &thorn;at sal sla him self standes before &thorn;e mawmet with a scharpe drawen
knyf in his hand, and with &thorn;at knyf he cuttez oute a pece of his flesch and castez it in &thorn;e visage of &thorn;e mawmet and
saise deuote praiers
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">in the face of his ydole, seyenge his orysounes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and commendez him till his godd, and seyne he smytez him self with &thorn;e knyf in diuerse
placez ay till he fall doune deed. And &thorn;an his frendez offers his body to &thorn;e mawmet, syngand and sayand,
"Loo how &thorn;i lele seruand has done for &thorn;e! He hase forsaken wyf and childer and all &thorn;e ricches and solacez of
&thorn;e werld and his awen lyf for &thorn;i lufe and made sacrifice vnto &thorn;e of his flesch and his blude. Wharfore, we pray
&thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sett him by syde &thorn;e amanges &thorn;i dere frendez in &thorn;e ioy of paradys, for he hase wele disserued it."
And, when &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;us done, &thorn;ai brynne his body and ilke ane of &thorn;am takez a porcioun of &thorn;e aschez and kepez
&thorn;am in steed of relyques. And &thorn;ai say it es a haly thing and &thorn;at thurgh &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;ase aschez &thorn;ai schall be
saued and keped fra all maner of perils.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.88.15" CORRESP="Cot.117.5">And,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">This passage higher up in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, as in the French texts.</NOTE> when &thorn;ai lede &thorn;aire mawmet aboute &thorn;e citee, as I talde
before, with processioun, next before &thorn;e chariot gase all &thorn;e mynistralles of &thorn;e cuntree with all maner of
<MILESTONE N="74" UNIT="folio">instruments of music, and &thorn;ai make a grete melody. And, when &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;usgates ledd him all aboute &thorn;e citee
with grete sollempnytee, &thorn;ai lede him agayne vnto &thorn;e temple and settez agayne in his place &thorn;are he was wont to
be. And &thorn;an for wirschepe of &thorn;at mawmet and of &thorn;e feste diuerse persones slaez &thorn;am self with scharpe knyfes
in grete nowmer, as I said before.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.20" N="20" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.21">
<PB N="89">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XX</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the euyll customs vsed in the yle of Lamary; and how the erthe and the see ben of rownd forme and schappe, be pref of the sterre that is clept Antartyk, that is fix in the south.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.89.4" CORRESP="Cot.118.14">FRA &thorn;is cuntree men gase by &thorn;e grete see Occean thurgh many iles and diuerse cuntrez, whilke ware
lang to tell. At &thorn;e last after lii. day iournez men commez till a land, a large and a mykill, &thorn;e whilke
es called Lamory. In &thorn;at land es wonder grete hete; and &thorn;e custom es &thorn;are &thorn;at men and wymmen
gase all naked and schamez no&yogh;t for to schew &thorn;am as Godd made &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai scorne o&thorn;er &thorn;at er cledd; for
&thorn;ai say &thorn;at Godd made Adam and Eue naked, and &thorn;at men schuld hafe na schame of &thorn;at &thorn;at Godd made, for
na thing &thorn;at es kyndely es foule. &THORN;ai say also &thorn;at men &thorn;at vsez clathez er of ano&thorn;er werld, or elles &thorn;ai trowe
no&yogh;t in Godd, &thorn;at made all &thorn;e werld. In &thorn;at cuntree es na mariage betwene man and womman; bot all &thorn;e
wymmen of &thorn;at land er comoun till ilke man. And &thorn;ai say, if &thorn;ai did o&thorn;er wyse, &thorn;ai did grete synne, by cause
Godd said till Adam and Eue, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Crescite et multiplicamini, et replete terram</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Waxez and beese
multiplied and fillez &thorn;e erthe." And for&thorn;i na man &thorn;are saise, "&THORN;is es my wyfe"; ne na womman, "&THORN;is es my
<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio">housband." And when wymmen er delyuer of childer, &thorn;ai giffe &thorn;am to wham &thorn;ai will of men &thorn;at hase lyen by
&thorn;am. And on &thorn;e same wyse &thorn;e land es comoun till ilke man. For &thorn;at &thorn;at a man hase a &yogh;ere ano&thorn;er hase
ano&thorn;er &yogh;ere; and ilke man takez what him list, now here now &thorn;are. For all thinges er comoun, as I said before,
bathe cornes and all o&thorn;er gudes; for &thorn;are es na thing vnder lokk, and als riche es a man as ano&thorn;er. Bot &thorn;ai haue
ane euill custom amanges &thorn;am; for &thorn;ai will gladlier ete mannes flesch &thorn;an any o&thorn;er. Neuer &thorn;e latter &thorn;e land
es plentifous ynogh of flesch and fisch and of corne, and also of gold and siluer and many o&thorn;er gudes. And
&thorn;ider bringes marchandes childer for to sell; and &thorn;e men of &thorn;at cuntre byes &thorn;am. And &thorn;ase &thorn;at er fatte &thorn;ai ete;
and &thorn;ase &thorn;at er no&yogh;t fatte &thorn;ai fede to &thorn;ai be fatte, and &thorn;an slaez &thorn;am and etez &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai say it es &thorn;e best
and &thorn;e swettest flesch of &thorn;e werld.</SEG></P>

<PB N="90">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.90.1" CORRESP="Cot.119.22">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at in &thorn;is land, and in many o&thorn;er &thorn;are aboute, men may no&yogh;t see &thorn;e sterne &thorn;at es
called <NAME LANG="lat">Polus Articus</NAME>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;e Sterre of &thorn;e See, &thorn;at is vnmevable and &thorn;at is toward the north, &thorn;at wee clepen &thorn;e Lode Sterre, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whilk standes euen north and stirrez neuer, by whilk schippe men er ledd, for it es
no&yogh;t sene in &thorn;e south. Bot &thorn;er es ano&thorn;er sterne, whilke es called Antartic, and &thorn;at es euen agayne &thorn;e to&thorn;er
sterne; and by &thorn;at sterne er schippe men ledd &thorn;are, as schippe men er ledd here by <NAME LANG="lat">Polus Articus</NAME>. And, ri&yogh;t
as &thorn;at sterne may no&yogh;t be sene here, on &thorn;e same wyse &thorn;is sterne may no&yogh;t be sene &thorn;are. And &thorn;are by may men
<MILESTONE N="" UNIT="folio">see wele &thorn;at &thorn;e werld es all rounde; for parties of &thorn;e firmament whilk may be sene in sum cuntree may no&yogh;t
be sene in ano&thorn;er. And &thorn;at may men proue &thorn;us. For, if a man myght fynd redy schipping and gude company
and &thorn;erto had his hele and wald ga to see &thorn;e werld, he myght ga all aboute &thorn;e werld, bathe abouen and benethe.
And &thorn;at prufe I &thorn;us, after &thorn;at I hafe sene. For I hafe bene in Braban and sene by &thorn;e astrolaby &thorn;at &thorn;e pole
artyc es &thorn;are liii. degreez hegh, and in Almayne towardes Boem
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> Bohemia; more for&thorn;ere in Almayne and Bewme, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> it has lviii. degrez, and for&thorn;ermare toward &thorn;e
north it has lxii. degrez of height and sum mynutes. All &thorn;is I persayued by &thorn;e astrolaby. And &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at in &thorn;e south, euen ynentes &thorn;is sterne, es &thorn;e sterne &thorn;at es called Pole Antartic. &THORN;ise twa sternes
stirrez neuer mare; and aboute &thorn;aim mouez &thorn;e firmament, as a qwhele duse aboute ane axeltree. And so &thorn;e
lyne &thorn;at es betwene &thorn;ise twa sternez departez all &thorn;e firmament in twa partes, ayther ylike mykill. Afterwardes
I went toward &thorn;e south, and I fand &thorn;at in Liby seez men first &thorn;e sterne Antartyke; and, as I went ferrer, I fand
&thorn;at in hie Liby it hase in height xviii. degreez and sum mynutes, of whilke mynutes lx. makez a degre. And so,
passand by land and by see toward &thorn;e cuntree &thorn;at I spakk off are, and oper landes and iles &thorn;at er be&yogh;ond, I fand
&thorn;at &thorn;is sterne Antartik had in height xxxiii. degreez.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and mo mynutes, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, if I had had cumpany and schipping &thorn;at wald hafe
<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio">gane ferrer, I trow forsothe &thorn;at we schuld hafe sene all &thorn;e roundeness of &thorn;e firmament, &thorn;at es to say bathe &thorn;e
emisperies, &thorn;e vppermare and &thorn;e nedermare. For, as I sayd &yogh;ow before, halfe &thorn;e firmament es betwene &thorn;ise twa
sternes; &thorn;e whilk I hafe sene. And of &thorn;e to&thorn;er I sawe a party toward &thorn;e north, &thorn;at es to say lxii. degreez and
x. mynutes, vnder &thorn;e pole Artyk
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">under the Transmontane, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and ano&thorn;er party I sawe toward &thorn;e south, &thorn;at es to say xxxiii. degreez and
xvi. mynutes, vnder &thorn;e pole Antartyke. And halfe &thorn;e firmament contenez bot nyne score degreez, of whilk I
hafe sene lxii. degreez of Artyk and ten mynutes, and of Antartyk toward &thorn;e south I hafe sene xxxiii. degreez
and xvi. mynutes. &THORN;ise er iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> and xv. degreez and nere half a degree. And so &thorn;er lakkez bot iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> and foure

<PB N="91">
degreez and mare &thorn;an halfe a degree, &thorn;at I ne hafe sene all &thorn;e firmament. For &thorn;e ferthe parte contenes iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> and
x. degreez. And so &thorn;e three partes hafe I sene and v. degreez mare and nere a half. And &thorn;erfore I say sikerly
&thorn;at a man myght go all &thorn;e werld aboute, bathe abouen and bynethe, and comme agayne to his awen cuntree, so
&thorn;at he had his hele, gude schipping, and gude company, as I said before. And all way he schuld fynd men,
landes and iles and citeez and townes, as er in &thorn;ir cuntrees. For &yogh;e wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;ase men &thorn;at dwellez euen
vnder &thorn;e pole Antartyk er fote agayne fote to &thorn;ase &thorn;at dwellez euen vnder &thorn;e &thorn;ole Artyke, als wele as we and
<MILESTONE N="76" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ase men &thorn;at dwellez agaynes vs er fote agayne fote; and ri&yogh;t so it es of o&thorn;er parties of &thorn;e werld. For ilke a
party of &thorn;e erthe and of &thorn;e see hase his contrary of thinges, whilk er euen agaynes him. And &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at, as I coniecture, &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn, emperour of Inde, es euen vnder vs. For, if a man
schall ga fra Scotland or Ingland vnto Ierusalem, he sall ga all way vpward. For oure land es &thorn;e lawest party
of &thorn;e west, and &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn es in &thorn;e lawest party of &thorn;e este. And &thorn;ai hafe day when we hafe nyght,
and nyght when we hafe day. And, als mykill as a man ascendes vpward oute of oure cuntreez to Ierusalem,
als mykill schall he go dounward to &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn; and &thorn;e cause es for &thorn;e erthe and &thorn;e see er rounde.
For it es &thorn;e comoun worde &thorn;at Ierusalem es in myddes of &thorn;e erthe; and &thorn;at may wele be proued &thorn;us. For, and
a man &thorn;are take a spere and sett it euen in &thorn;e erthe at midday, when &thorn;e day and &thorn;e nyght er bathe ylyke lang, it
makez na schadowe till na party. And Dauid also beres witnes &thorn;eroff, &thorn;are he saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Deus autem rex noster
ante secula operatus est salutem in medio terre</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Ps. lxxiii. 12.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Godd oure kyng before &thorn;e begynnyng of &thorn;e
werld wroght hele in myddes of &thorn;e erthe." And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai &thorn;at gase oute of oure cuntreez of &thorn;e west toward
Ierusalem, als many iournez as &thorn;ai make to ga &thorn;ider vpward, als many iournez sall &thorn;ai make to ga in to &thorn;e land of
Prestre Iohn dounward fra Ierusalem. And so he may ga in to &thorn;ase iles enuirounand all &thorn;e roundness of &thorn;e erthe
<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio">and of &thorn;e see till he com euen vnder vs. And &thorn;erfore I hafe oft tymes thoght on a tale &thorn;at I herd, when I was
&yogh;ung, how a worthy man of oure cuntree went on a tyme for to see &thorn;e werld; and he passed Inde and many iles
by&yogh;onde Inde, whare er ma &thorn;an v<HI REND="sup">m</HI> iles, and he went so lang by land and by see, envirounand &thorn;e werld, &thorn;at he
fand ane ile, whare he herd men speke his awen langage. For he herd ane dryfe bestez sayand to &thorn;am swilke
wordes as he herd men say til oxen in his awen cuntree gangand at &thorn;e plugh; of whilk he had grete meruaile,
for he wist no&yogh;t how it myght be. Bot I suppose he had so lang went on land and on see, envirounand &thorn;e

<PB N="92">
werld, &thorn;at he was commen in to his awen marchez; and, if he had passed for&thorn;ermare, he schuld hafe commen
euen to his awen cuntree. Bot for he herd &thorn;at meruaile and myght get schipping na ferrere, he turned agayne as
he come; and so he had a grete trauaile.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and so he loste moche peynefull labour, as him self seyde a gret while after &thorn;at he was comen hom, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And it befell efterward &thorn;at he went in to Norway; and a tempest of
wynd in &thorn;e see drafe him, so &thorn;at he arryued in ane ile. And, when he was &thorn;are, he wist wele it was &thorn;e ile in
whilk he had bene before and herd his awen speche, as men drafe bestez. And &thorn;at myght right wele be; &thorn;of
all it be &thorn;at symple men of cunnyng trowe no&yogh;t &thorn;at men may ga vnder &thorn;e erthe bot if &thorn;ai fall vnto &thorn;e firmament.
For as vs think &thorn;at &thorn;ase men er vnder vs, so think &thorn;aim &thorn;at we er vnder &thorn;aim. For, if a man myghte fall fra &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio">erthe to &thorn;e firmament, by mare skill &thorn;e erthe and &thorn;e see, &thorn;at er so heuy, schuld fall vnto &thorn;e firmament. Bot &thorn;at
may no&yogh;t be, as Godd witnessez him self &thorn;are he saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Non timeas me, qui suspendi terram ex nichilo</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Apparently a misquotation of Job xxvi. 7.</NOTE></SEG> &thorn;at es to
say, "Hafe na drede of me, &thorn;at hynged &thorn;e erthe of no&yogh;t."</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.92.11" CORRESP="Cot.123.11">And, if all it be possible &thorn;at a man may ga all aboute &thorn;e erthe, neuer&thorn;eless of a thowsand perauenture ane
schuld no&yogh;t do it in all his lyf, for to take &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way all aboute &thorn;e erthe til he come till his awen cuntree
agayne &thorn;at he come fra. For &thorn;er er so many wayes and cuntreez &thorn;at a man schuld lightly faile, bot if it ware by
special grace of Godd. For &thorn;e erthe is ri&yogh;t grete and large, and it contenes in roundeness aboute, abouen and
bynethe xx<HI REND="sup">m</HI>iiii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> and xxv. myle, after &thorn;e opinioun of alde wyse men &thorn;at saise it, whilke I will no&yogh;t reproue. Bot
after my feble witte me thinke, saue &thorn;aire grace, &thorn;at it es mykill mare aboute. And for to make &yogh;ow to
vnderstand how, I ymagyne a figure of a grete compas; and aboute &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;at compas, whilke es called
&thorn;e centre, be ano&thorn;er lytill compas departed by lynes in many parties and &thorn;at all &thorn;ase lynes mete sammen on &thorn;e
centre, so &thorn;at als many parties or lynes as &thorn;e grete compas hase be on &thorn;e lytill compas, if all &thorn;e space be less.
Now be &thorn;e grete compas sette for &thorn;e firmament, &thorn;e whilk by astronomyeres es diuided in twelfe signez, and ilke
a signe es diuided in xxx. degreez; &thorn;is es ccc. and lx. degreez &thorn;at it es aboute. Now be &thorn;e less compas sett for
<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e erthe and departid in als many parties as &thorn;e firmament, and ilkane of &thorn;ase parties answere to a degree of
&thorn;e firmament; &thorn;ise er in all dcc. and xx.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and wyteth it wel &thorn;at after the auctoures of astronomye dc. furlonges of erthe answeren to a degree of the firmament and &thorn;o ben iiii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI>vii. miles and iiii. furlonges, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Now be &thorn;ise all multiplied ccc. tymes and lx. and it schall amount

<PB N="93">
in all til xxxi<HI REND="sup">m</HI> myle and fyue, ilke a myle of viii. furlangs, as myles er in oure cuntree. And so mykill hase &thorn;e
erthe in roundeness all aboute after myne opinioun and myne vnderstanding. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand after &thorn;e
opinioun of alde wise philosopheres and astronomyeres &thorn;at Ingland, Scotland, Wales ne Ireland er no&yogh;t rekned
in &thorn;e height of &thorn;e erthe, as it semez wele by all &thorn;e bokes of astronomy. For &thorn;e height of &thorn;e erthe es departed in
vii. parties, &thorn;e whilk er called vii. climates after &thorn;e vii. planetes, &thorn;at er called climates; and til ilk ane of &thorn;a
planets es approperd ane of &thorn;e climatez. And &thorn;ise cuntreez &thorn;at I spakk of er no&yogh;t in &thorn;ase climatez, for &thorn;ai er
dounward toward &thorn;e west. And also iles of Inde, whilke er euen agaynes vs, er no&yogh;t rekned in &thorn;e climates, for
&thorn;ai er toward &thorn;e est. &THORN;ise climatez envirouns all &thorn;e werld.</SEG> Neuer&thorn;eles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">From here to the end of the chapter not in the French text, nor in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> sum astronomieres appropers &thorn;ise
forsaid countreez to &thorn;e mone, whilk es &thorn;e lawest planet, and swiftliest makez his course. Now will I turne
agayne to my mater &thorn;are I left, and tell &yogh;ow of ma cuntreez and iles, whilke er in Inde and be&yogh;ond.</P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.21" N="21" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.22">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the palays of the kyng of the yle of Jaua; of the trees that beren mele, hony, wyn and venym; and of othere meruaylles and customs vsed in the yles marchinge there abouten.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.93.14" CORRESP="Cot.124.24">NERE &thorn;is ile of Lamory whilke I spakk off es ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;at men callez Somober. &THORN;is es a grete ile and
<MILESTONE N="78" UNIT="folio">a gude, and a noble kyng &thorn;erin and a myghty. &THORN;e folk of &thorn;is cuntree gers merk &thorn;am in &thorn;e visage
with a hate yrne for grete noblay, to be knawen fra o&thorn;er folk; for &thorn;ai hald &thorn;am selfe &thorn;e maste wor&thorn;i
folke of &thorn;e werld. And &thorn;ai hafe were euermare agaynes &thorn;e naked men whilk I spakk off before. And nere
&thorn;is ile es ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;e whilk es called Boteniga, a gude ile and full replenischt of many maners of ricches.
And aboute &thorn;is ile er many o&thorn;er iles and diuerse cuntreez, and diuerse maners of men, of whilk it ware to mykill
to speke of all.</SEG></P>

<PB N="94">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.94.1" CORRESP="Cot.125.7">Bot to passe a lytill &thorn;eine by see men schal fynd a grete ile, &thorn;at es called Iaua. And &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;is ile es a
grete lorde and a myghty, and hase vii. o&thorn;er kinges vnder him of vii. iles, whilke er aboute &thorn;at ile. In &thorn;e ile of
Jaua es wonder mykill folk; and &thorn;are growez diuerse maners of spicery in mare plentee &thorn;an in o&thorn;er placez, &thorn;at
es to say gynger clowes, canell,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">clowegylofres, canelle, zedewall, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> nutemuges, macez, and many o&thorn;er. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e macez
er &thorn;e huskes of &thorn;e nutemug.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">For right as the note of &thorn;e hasell hath an husk withouten, &thorn;at the note is closed in til it be ripe, and after falleth out, right so it is of the notemuge and of the maces, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;is ile es grete plentee of all thing. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;is land hase a faire palays
and a riche. For all &thorn;e grecez in to his hall and his chaumbres er ane of gold, ano&thorn;er of siluer. &THORN;e flurez also
of &thorn;e hall and &thorn;e chaumbres er of gold and siluer. And all &thorn;e walles within er couerd with plates of gold and
siluer; and in &thorn;ase platez er storys of kynges and knyghtes and batales, with corounes and cercles on &thorn;aire
<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio">heuedes of precious stanes. &THORN;are will na man trowe &thorn;e noblay and &thorn;e richess of &thorn;is palaise, bot if he hafe sene
it. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;is ile es so grete and so myghty &thorn;at he hase oft tymes discomfit &thorn;e Grete Caan of Cathay in
bataile, whilk es &thorn;e myghtiest emperour of all &thorn;e werld. For &thorn;ai hafe oft bene at were by cause &thorn;e Grete
Caan wald hafe made &thorn;e forsaid kyng to hald his land of him; bot &thorn;e kyng hase all way agaynestanden him
and putt him off mannely.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.94.14" CORRESP="Cot.126.4">And for to ga forthe by see, men findez ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;at es called Thalamass, and sum callez it Pathen. And
it es a grete kingdom, with many faire citeez and tounes. In &thorn;is land growes treesse &thorn;at beres mele, of whilke
men makes breed, faire and whyte and of gude sauour; and it semez <CORR SIC="at" RESP="GW">as</CORR> it ware of wheet, bot it es no&yogh;t
allinges of &thorn;e same sauour. &THORN;are er also oper treessez &thorn;at berez venym, agayne whilke es na medecyne bot ane;
and &thorn;at es to take &thorn;e lefes of &thorn;e same treessez and stampe &thorn;am and tempre &thorn;am with water and drink it, or elles
a man schuld dye onane, for tiriacle may no&yogh;t helpe ne nan o&thorn;er medecyne. With &thorn;is venym had &thorn;e Iews
casten on a tyme for to hafe poysond all Cristendom, as ane of &thorn;am confessed vnto me; bot, blist be allmy&yogh;ty
Godd, &thorn;ai failed of &thorn;aire purpose. And, if &yogh;e will wit how &thorn;e treessez berez mele, I say &thorn;at men hewez with a
hacchet aboute &thorn;e fote of &thorn;e tree nere &thorn;e erthe in many placez, so &thorn;at &thorn;e barke be perched; and &thorn;an commez

<PB N="95">
<MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="folio">oute a licour thikk, whilk &thorn;ai kepe in vessell and settez it to &thorn;e sonne at drye. And, when it es drie, &thorn;ai do it
on &thorn;e mylne to grind; and &thorn;an it es faire mele and whyte. And wyne, hony, and venym er drawen on &thorn;e same
maner oute of treessez and done in vessell to kepe. In &thorn;at ile also es a deed see; and it es in maner of a lowgh,
and it has na ground. In &thorn;e whilk what thing so is casten, it sall neuer be funden agayne. Beside &thorn;at logh
growez redez of a wonderfull lenth; and &thorn;ai call &thorn;aim &thorn;are Thaby.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;at ben xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> fadme long, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And of &thorn;ir redez &thorn;ai make &thorn;are houses and
maneres and schippez and &thorn;aire o&thorn;er necessaries, as we do here of akez and o&thorn;er treesse. Na man say &thorn;at &thorn;is es
feyned thing or fable, for sikerly I sawe with myne eghen liggand apon &thorn;is see syde many of &thorn;ir redez, of &thorn;e
whilk xx. men of my felyschepe myght no&yogh;t bere ane ne wele raise it fra &thorn;e erthe. &THORN;are er also o&thorn;er redez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at ben not so longe, &thorn;at growen nere the lond and han so longe rotes &thorn;at duren wel a iiii. quarteres of a furlong or more, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of
less quantitee; and vnder &thorn;aire rotes men findes precious stanes of grete vertu. For he &thorn;at beres ane of &thorn;ase
stanes apon him, &thorn;er may na maner of yrne dere him ne drawe blude of him. And &thorn;erfore men of &thorn;at cuntree
feightes ri&yogh;t baldely bathe on water and on land by cause of &thorn;ir precious stanes. Bot &thorn;aire enmys, &thorn;at knawez
&thorn;e manere and &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;er stanes, gerres make arowes and quarelles withouten yrne, and with &thorn;ase &thorn;ai
wounde &thorn;am and slaez &thorn;am.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.95.14" CORRESP="Cot.127.16">Fra &thorn;is ile men wendez till ano&thorn;er ile by see, &thorn;e whilk men callez Calanok; and it es a grete land and
<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio">plentyuouse of gudes. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at land hase als many wyfes as he will. For he gers seke all &thorn;e faire
wymmen of &thorn;e land and bring &thorn;am before him and takez ane of &thorn;am a nyght, ano&thorn;er ano&thorn;er nyght; and swa sum
of &thorn;a kynges will hafe by diuerse tymes a thousand or ma. And scho &thorn;at es with him a nyght commez na mare
at him, bot if he send for hir.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">bot &yogh;if &thorn;at on happene to ben more lusty to his plesance &thorn;an another, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;erefore hase he a grete nowmer a sonnes and doghters; for sum kynges
hase a c. childer, sum cc., sum ma. &THORN;e kyng also has xiiii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> of tame olyfauntes, whilk he gers kepe at ilk a toune
in his rewme. And, when he hase were with any lord aboute him, he gers make castelles and brace &thorn;am on
&thorn;e olyfauntes; in &thorn;e whilk castelles he puttes men of armes for to feight agaynes &thorn;aire enmys. And on &thorn;e same
wyse duse &thorn;aire enmys; for &thorn;at es &thorn;e maner of feighting amanges lordes in batailes in &thorn;ase landes. And &thorn;ase
olyfauntes &thorn;ai call Warkes in &thorn;aire langage.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.95.24" CORRESP="Cot.128.2">In &thorn;at land also es a meruaile &thorn;at es no&yogh;t in o&thorn;er landes. For all maner of fischez of &thorn;e see commez at a
certayne tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, ilke a maner of fisch after o&thorn;er, and lays &thorn;am nere to &thorn;e land, and sum apon &thorn;e land.
And &thorn;are &thorn;ai lye three dayes; and men of &thorn;e cuntree commez &thorn;ider and takes of &thorn;am what &thorn;ai will. And &thorn;an

<PB N="96">
wendez &thorn;at maner of fischez away, and ano&thorn;er maner of fische commez and lyes nere &thorn;e land o&thorn;er three dayes;
and men takez of &thorn;am. And &thorn;us duse all maner of fischez til all hafe bene &thorn;are, and men hafe taken of &thorn;am
<MILESTONE N="80" UNIT="folio">what &thorn;ai will. And na man knawez &thorn;e cause. Bot men of &thorn;at land saise &thorn;at Godd schewez &thorn;am &thorn;at grace at &thorn;e
reuerence of &thorn;aire kyng, as &thorn;e maste worthy lord of &thorn;e werld, for he hase so many wyfes and getes so many
childer on &thorn;am and multiplies &thorn;e werld, as Godd commaundid till Adam and Eue, when he said, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Crescite et
multiplicamini et replete terram</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Waxez and multipliez and fillez &thorn;e erthe, and beese lordes of
&thorn;e fischez in &thorn;e see." And &thorn;is think me ane of &thorn;e grettest meruailes &thorn;at I hafe sene in any land, &thorn;at fischez &thorn;at
hase all &thorn;e see at will to swymme in schall with &thorn;aire awen gude will com &thorn;ider and profre &thorn;am self to &thorn;e
deed withouten constreynyng of any creature. And sikerly I wate wele it es no&yogh;t done withouten a grete
significacion and a grete cause.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.96.11" CORRESP="Cot.128.36">Also &thorn;er er in &thorn;at land so grete snyles &thorn;at in &thorn;aire schelles three men or foure may be herberd,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">many persones may loggen hem, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> as it ware
in a lytill hous or a luge. &THORN;are er o&thorn;er also of less quantitee, as
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">And of &thorn;eise snayles and of gret white wormes &thorn;at han blake hedes, &thorn;at ben als grete as a mannes thighe and some lesse, as grete worms &thorn;at men fynded &thorn;ere in wodes, men maken vyaunde rialle, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> it ware of &thorn;e mykill of a mannes thee; and
bathe &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e tother er all whyte, safe &thorn;e heued, and &thorn;at es blakk. And &yogh;it es &thorn;are &thorn;e thridd maner of
snyles; and &thorn;ai er mykill lesse &thorn;an ow&thorn;er of &thorn;e o&thorn;er. And of &thorn;am &thorn;ai make a meet for &thorn;e kyng and o&thorn;er grete
lordes. In &thorn;at land es a custom &thorn;at, when a man dyes, his wyf es grauen with him all qwikk; for &thorn;ai say it es
gude skille &thorn;at scho bere him company in &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld, as scho did in &thorn;is.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.96.17" CORRESP="Cot.129.10">Fra &thorn;is land men passez thurgh &thorn;e grete see Occiane til ane o&thorn;er ile &thorn;at es called Caffilos. And &thorn;are &thorn;ai
hafe a custom &thorn;at, when &thorn;aire frendes er grefe seke, &thorn;ai hing &thorn;am apon treesse, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may be wiried and eten
with fewles; for &thorn;ai say &thorn;at it es better &thorn;ai be eten with fewles, whilk er aungelles of Godd, &thorn;an foully to be
eten in &thorn;e erthe with wormes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.96.21" CORRESP="Cot.129.15">Fra &thorn;eine men wendez to ano&thorn;er ile, whare folk er of ane euill condicion; for &thorn;ai nurisch grete hundes
for to wiry men.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">to strangle here frendes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, when &thorn;aire frendez drawez to &thorn;e deed ward and &thorn;at &thorn;ai trowe &thorn;ai may liffe na langer,
&thorn;ai gerre &thorn;ase hundes wiry &thorn;am; for &thorn;ai will no&yogh;t lat &thorn;am dye kyndely in &thorn;aire beddes by cause &thorn;ai schuld no&yogh;t
suffer to grete penaunce in &thorn;aire dying. And, when &thorn;ai er deed, &thorn;ai ete &thorn;aire flesch in steed of venysoun.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.96.25" CORRESP="Cot.129.22">And fra &thorn;is ile men wendez by many iles in &thorn;e see til ane ile &thorn;at es called Melk; and &thorn;are er also wikked

<PB N="97">
folk and cruell. For &thorn;ai hafe nere hand na lyking, bot in slaughter of men for to drink &thorn;aire blude; and he
&thorn;at may slae mast noumer of men es of grettest name amanges &thorn;aim and maste wirschipfull. &THORN;are es na drink
&thorn;at &thorn;ai lufe so wele as mannes blude, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai say es Godd.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;ei clepen Dieu, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, if any debate be amanges &thorn;am, &thorn;er may
na full sawghtling
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">accord, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> be made till ilkane hafe drunken o&thorn;er blude; and on &thorn;e same wyse es it of affinitee makyng
amanges &thorn;am. For accorde or affinitee amanges <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;am</SUPPLIED> es noght, bot if it be made on &thorn;at wyse.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.97.6" CORRESP="Cot.129.34">Fra &thorn;is ile men passez to ano&thorn;er ile by see, &thorn;e whilk es called Tracota, whare &thorn;e folke er as bestez withouten
resoun. And &thorn;ai dwell in cafes, for &thorn;ai hafe na witte to make &thorn;am housez; and, when &thorn;ai see any straunge men
passe thurgh &thorn;e cuntree, &thorn;ai rynne to &thorn;aire cafes and hydes &thorn;am. &THORN;ai ete nedders, and &thorn;ai speke no&yogh;t, bot hisszes
ane till ano&thorn;er, as nedders duse. And &thorn;ai make na force of, na recches, now&thorn;er of gold, ne of siluer, ne of
o&thorn;er werldly gude, bot all anely of a precious stane, &thorn;e whilk hase lx. colours; and it es called traconit, after
&thorn;e ile. &THORN;is ilke stane lufe &thorn;ai wonder mykill, &thorn;of all &thorn;ai knawe no&yogh;t &thorn;e vertu &thorn;eroff, bot &thorn;ai coueit it for &thorn;e
fairness &thorn;eroff.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.97.13" CORRESP="Cot.130.11">Fra &thorn;at ile men gase by see to ano&thorn;er ile, whilk men callez Natumeran; and it es a grete ile and a faire;
and &thorn;e vmgang
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">it is in kompas aboute, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. Odoric makes it "duo milia miliarium."</NOTE> &thorn;eroff es nere a thowsand myle. Men and wymmen of &thorn;at ile hase heuedes lyke hundes; and
&thorn;ai er called Cynocephales. &THORN;is folk, &thorn;of all &thorn;ai be of swilk schappe, &yogh;it &thorn;ai er full resonable and sutill of witte.
And &thorn;ai wirschepe ane ox for &thorn;aire godd; and ilkane of &thorn;am beres ane ox made of gold or of siluer in his
front, in taken &thorn;at &thorn;ai lufe &thorn;aire godd wele. And &thorn;ai gang all naked bot a lytill clathe before &thorn;aire priuee
membres. &THORN;ai er large of stature and gude werrayours; and &thorn;ai bere a grete target, with whilk &thorn;ai couer all
&thorn;aire body, and a lang spere in &thorn;aire hand, and on &thorn;is maner arayd &thorn;ai ga baldely agayne &thorn;aire enmys. And, if
<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ai take any man in bataile, &thorn;ai ete him. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at land es a grete lorde and a myghty and a riche and full
deuote after his lawe; and he hase aboute his nekke a corde of silke, on whilke er ccc. precious stanes, grete and
orient,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">abouten his nekke ccc. perles oryent, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in maner of bedes of laumbre. And ri&yogh;t as we say oure <TITLE LANG="lat">Pater Noster</TITLE> and oure <TITLE LANG="lat">Auez</TITLE> apon oure bedes,
ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e kyng sayse ilk day apon his bedes ccc. praieres to his godd before he ete. And he beres also aboute
his nekk a ruby, fyne and gude and orient, &thorn;e whilke es nere a fote lang and v. fyngers on brede. &THORN;is ruby giffe
&thorn;ai him, when &thorn;ai make him kyng, to bere it in his hand, and so he rydez aboute &thorn;e citee and &thorn;ai er all obeyand
vntil him. And fra &thorn;eine forward he beres it aboute his nekk all way; for, if he bare it no&yogh;t, he schuld na
langer be halden kyng. &THORN;e grete Caan of Cathay hase mykill coueitid &thorn;at ruby, bot he my&yogh;t neuer get it by
were, ne by bying, ne by nano&thorn;er maner. &THORN;is kyng es full ri&yogh;twys man and a trewe in his lawe; for he

<PB N="98">
punyschez all &thorn;ase &thorn;at duse any wrang till any man within his rewme. And &thorn;erfore men may ga sauely and
sikerly thurgh his land and na man be so hardy to disturbe &thorn;am, ne robbe &thorn;am, ne take fra &thorn;am any
maner of gude.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.98.4" CORRESP="Cot.131.8">Fra &thorn;is ile menne gas to ano&thorn;er ile &thorn;at es called Silha; and &thorn;e vmgang &thorn;eroff es viii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> myle. A grete party of
&thorn;is cuntree es waste and wilderness and no&yogh;t inhabitid; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;er es grete plentee of dragouns and
<MILESTONE N="82" UNIT="folio">cocodriles and o&thorn;er maner of nedders, so &thorn;at &thorn;are may na man dwell &thorn;are. &THORN;e cocodrille es a maner of nedder,
browne abouen on &thorn;e backe, with foure fete and schort legges and twa grete eghen.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">schorte thyes and grete nayles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;e body &thorn;eroff es so
mykill and so lang &thorn;at, whare it hase gane in &thorn;e sand, it es lyke as men had drawen a grete tree &thorn;are. In &thorn;at
wilderness also er many o&thorn;er maners of wilde bestez, and namely olyfauntes. And in &thorn;at ile es a grete
mountayne, and euen abouen on &thorn;e toppe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">in mydd place of the mounte, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. So Odoric, "in medio montis"; but one MS. reads "in &hellip; cacumine."</NOTE> &thorn;eroff es a grete lowgh full of water. And men of &thorn;at cuntree saise
&thorn;at Adam and Eue wepid apon &thorn;at hill a hundreth &yogh;ere efter &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware dryfen oute of Paradys, and of &thorn;aire
teeres &thorn;at &thorn;ai weped was &thorn;at water gaderd. In &thorn;e grund of &thorn;at lac er funden faire precious stanes; and aboute
&thorn;at lowgh growes grete plentee of redez, amanges whilk er many cocodrilles and o&thorn;er diuerse nedders dwelland,
and &thorn;are er in &thorn;e lowgh hors iles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> eels; grete water leches, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of wonderfull greteness. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at ile anes in &thorn;e &yogh;ere giffez all &thorn;e
pouer folk of &thorn;e land lefe for to gang in to &thorn;e lac and gader &thorn;am precious stanes for almous and for &thorn;e lufe of
Adam and Eue Godd; and &thorn;er es ilk a &yogh;ere fun ynew of &thorn;a precious stanes. &THORN;is &thorn;ouer folk when &thorn;ai ga in to
&thorn;is lowgh for to gader &thorn;e precious stanes, &thorn;ai enoynt &thorn;am all ouer with &thorn;e ius of &thorn;e fruyt &thorn;at es called lymons,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">lyche smale pesen, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, "pesen" being over an erasure.</NOTE>
and &thorn;an &thorn;ai drede noght &thorn;e cocodrilles ne &thorn;e o&thorn;er <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">venymous vermyn</SUPPLIED>.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">The bottom of the leaf is torn away at this point. The missing words here and below are supplied as far as possible, with the help of <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e water of &thorn;is <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">lowghe renneth
<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio">flowynge and ebbynge</SUPPLIED> downe <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">a syde of &thorn;e mountayne. And</SUPPLIED> by <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">that ryuer er perles and</SUPPLIED> many precious
stanes fun. &THORN;ai say in &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;at nedders and o&thorn;er venymous bestez of &thorn;at cuntree duse na diseese to na
straungers ne pilgrimes &thorn;at passez thurgh &thorn;e land, bot all anely til men of &thorn;e same cuntree and &thorn;aim &thorn;at dwellez
nere. Also &thorn;are <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">er</SUPPLIED> in &thorn;at ile wylde geesse with twa heuedes; and &thorn;are er whyte wolfes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">lyouns alle white, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> als grete of body as
oxen, and many o&thorn;er diuerse bestes. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e see whilk es aboute &thorn;is ile and o&thorn;er iles
aboute it semez so hye abouen &thorn;e land &thorn;at it es lyke to men &thorn;at behaldez it as it hang in &thorn;e aere and schuld fall
doune alssone and couer all &thorn;e erthe; and &thorn;at es a wonder thing, as &thorn;e prophete saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Mirabiles elaciones
maris</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Ps. xcii. 4.</NOTE></SEG> &thorn;at es to say, "Wonderfull er &thorn;e rysings of &thorn;e see."</P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.22" N="22" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.23">
<PB N="99">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[How men knowen be the ydole &yogh;if the sike schall dye or non; of folk of dyuerse schap and merueylously disfigured; and of the monkes that &yogh;euen hire releef to babewynes, apes and marmesettes, and to other bestes.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.99.4" CORRESP="Cot.132.19">FRA &thorn;is ile men wendez by see toward &thorn;e southe to ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;e whilk es called Dundeya, and it es a
large ile and a mykill. In &thorn;is ile dwellez a maner of folk &thorn;at es of euill condiciouns, for &thorn;e fader etez
&thorn;e son and &thorn;e son &thorn;e fader, &thorn;e husband his wyf and &thorn;e wyf hir husband. For, if it fall &thorn;at a mannes
fader be seke, &thorn;e sonne gase to &thorn;e preste of &thorn;e lawe and praies him &thorn;at he will ask &thorn;aire godd, whilk es a
<MILESTONE N="83" UNIT="folio">mawmet, whedir his fader sall dye of &thorn;at sekeness. And &thorn;an &thorn;e preste and &thorn;e seke mannez sonne knelez before
&thorn;e <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">mawmet deuoutely</SUPPLIED> and askes him wheder <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">&thorn;e seke man schall liue or</SUPPLIED> die. And &thorn;e fende <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">&thorn;at is within &thorn;e
mawmet answeres &thorn;at he schall not die at &thorn;at tyme, and showes</SUPPLIED> &thorn;am medecynes for to hele him with;
and &thorn;an &thorn;e son turnez hame to &thorn;e fader and duse til him as he was teched before vntil he be hale. And,
if he say &thorn;at he schall dye, &thorn;e preste and &thorn;e son and &thorn;e wyf of &thorn;e seke man commez till him and castez a clath
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">putten here hondes ("main" for "pain"), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
on his mouth and stoppez his wynde, and so &thorn;ai slae him. And, when he es deed, &thorn;ai take his body and hewes
it in small pecez and callez all his frendez togyder, and all &thorn;e mynstralles &thorn;at may be geten, and makes &thorn;am a
sollempne feste and etes &thorn;e deed mannes body. And, when &thorn;ai hafe eten all &thorn;e flesch, &thorn;ai gader all &thorn;e banes
togyder and grafez &thorn;am on &thorn;aire maner with grete sollempnitee and lowd sang. And &thorn;us duse ilke frende till
o&thorn;er; and, if it be swa &thorn;at any man &thorn;at es sibbe vnto &thorn;e deed withhald him fra &thorn;is feste and commez no&yogh;t to &thorn;e
sollempnitee, all &thorn;e kynreden will reproue him as of a notable blame, and neuer efter &thorn;at sall he be accountid
amanges his frendez. &THORN;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ai ete &thorn;e flesch of &thorn;aire frende by cause &thorn;at wormes schuld no&yogh;t ete him in
&thorn;e erthe, and for to delyuer him of &thorn;e grete payne &thorn;at his saule suld suffer, if wormes gnew him in &thorn;e erthe.
&THORN;ai say also, when &thorn;ai fynd his flesch leen by cause of lang sekeness, &thorn;at it ware a grete synne to suffer him liffe
langer or to suffer payne withouten cause. And, if &thorn;ai fynd his flesch fatte, &thorn;ai say &thorn;ai hafe done wele &thorn;at &thorn;ai
hafe slaen him so sone and sent him to paradys and sufferd him no&yogh;t overlang be tourmentid in &thorn;is werld. &THORN;e

<PB N="100">
<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio">kyng of &thorn;at land es a grete lord and a myghty, and he hase vnder him liiii. iles mykill and large; and in ilkane
of &thorn;am es a coround kyng, &thorn;e whilk er all obeyand till him.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.100.3" CORRESP="Cot.133.28">And in &thorn;ase iles er many maners of folk of diuerse condiciouns. In ane of &thorn;am es a maner of folk of grete
stature, as &thorn;ai ware geauntz, horribill and foule to &thorn;e sight; and &thorn;ai hafe bot ane egh, and &thorn;at es in myddes &thorn;e
forheued. &THORN;ai ete rawe flesch and rawe fisch. In ano&thorn;er ile er foule men of figure withouten heuedes, and &thorn;ai
hafe eghen in ayther schulder ane; and &thorn;aire
<NOTE N="1" RESP="GW">and &thorn;aire&mdash;schulders, omitted in the printed text of <ABBR>C</ABBR>., but contained in the MS, in much the same form as here given.</NOTE> mouthes er round schapen, lyke a hors scho, ymiddes &thorn;aire
brestez. In ane o&thorn;er ile er men withouten heuedes; and &thorn;aire eghen and &thorn;aire mouthes er behind in &thorn;aire
schulders. In ano&thorn;er ile es a maner of folk &thorn;at hase a platte face, withouten nese or eghen; bot &thorn;ai hafe twa
smale holes in steed of eghen, and &thorn;ai hafe a platte mouth, lippless. In ano&thorn;er ile er foule men &thorn;at hase &thorn;e
ouer lippe so grete &thorn;at, when &thorn;ai slepe in &thorn;e sonne, &thorn;ai couer all &thorn;e visage with &thorn;at lippe. In ano&thorn;er ile er folk
of lytill stature, as &thorn;ai ware dwerghes; and &thorn;ai er sumwhat mare &thorn;an pigmez. &THORN;ai hafe na mouth; bot &thorn;ai hafe
in steed of &thorn;aire mouth a lytill hole, and &thorn;erfore, when &thorn;ai schall ete, &thorn;am behoues souke it with a rede or a pype.
Tunges hafe &thorn;ai nane; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai speke no&yogh;t, but hizssez and makez signes as mounkes duse, ilke ane till o&thorn;er,
and ilkane of &thorn;am wate wele what o&thorn;er menez. In ano&thorn;er ile er folk whas eres er so syde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at han grete eres and longe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. For "syde," meaning "long" (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> A.S. s&iacute;d), see above, p. 69.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ai hing doune
<MILESTONE N="84" UNIT="folio">to &thorn;e kneesse. In ano&thorn;er ile er folk &thorn;at hase fete lyke hors, and on &thorn;aim &thorn;ai will rynne so swythe &thorn;at &thorn;ai will
owertake wylde bestes and sla &thorn;am to &thorn;aire mete thurgh swyftnes of fote. In ano&thorn;er ile er folk whilke gase on
&thorn;aire hend and on &thorn;aire fete, as &thorn;ai ware foure foted bestez; and &thorn;ai er rowgh and will clymbe in to treesse als
lightly as &thorn;ai ware apes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">And &thorn;ei ben alle skynned and fedred, and &thorn;ei wole lepen als lightly in to trees and fro tree to tree as it were squyrelles or apes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;are es ano&thorn;er ile whare folk er &thorn;at er bathe men and wymmen, and hase members
of bathe &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e tother, and ilkane of &thorn;am hase a pappe on &thorn;e ta syde. And, when &thorn;ai vse &thorn;e member
of man, &thorn;ai get childer; and, when &thorn;ai vse &thorn;e membre of womman, &thorn;ai bere childer. Ano&thorn;er ile &thorn;er es whare
&thorn;e folk gase on &thorn;aire kneesse wonderfully, and it semez as &thorn;ai schuld fall at ilke a passe; and &thorn;ai hafe on ayther
fote viii. taasse.</SEG> &YOGH;it es &thorn;er
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">&yogh;it es &thorn;er &hellip; schuld dye, not in French text, nor in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> ano&thorn;er ile whare &thorn;e folke has bot a fote, and &thorn;at fote es so brade &thorn;at it will couer
all &thorn;e body and owmbre it fra &thorn;e sonne. Apon &thorn;is fote will &thorn;ai rynne so fast &thorn;at it es <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">wonder</SUPPLIED> to see. Also &thorn;er es
ano&thorn;er ile whare &thorn;e folk liffez all with &thorn;e sauour of a maner of apple; and, if &thorn;ai tharned
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> were deprived of.</NOTE> &thorn;at sauour, alssone &thorn;ai
schuld dye. Many o&thorn;er maner of folk &thorn;er er in o&thorn;er iles &thorn;er aboutes, whilk ware to lang to tell all.</P>

<PB N="101">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.101.1" CORRESP="Cot.135.2">For to ga fra &thorn;ise iles by see toward &thorn;e este many day iournez men fyndes a grete kyngdom, &thorn;e whilk es
called Mancy. And it es in Inde &thorn;e mare; and it es &thorn;e best land and maste lykand and plentifousest of all
<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio">gudes &thorn;at es in &thorn;e power of man. In &thorn;is land dwelles many Cristen men with Sarzenes, for it es a grete land
and a gude. And &thorn;er er &thorn;erin ma &thorn;an ii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> of noble citeez, withouten o&thorn;er gude townes. And &thorn;e land of Inde es
&thorn;e maste plentifous land of folk &thorn;at es owerwhare, by cause of &thorn;e grete commoditez &thorn;at it has &thorn;erin. In &thorn;at land
es na beggar, ne na pouer man. And &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at land er ri&yogh;t faire, outetaken &thorn;at &thorn;ai er pale of colour. And
&thorn;e men of &thorn;at land has schyre berdes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">thynne berdes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> with few hares in &thorn;am; for a man schall vnnethes fynd in ane of &thorn;aire
berdes l. hares. &THORN;ai er few, here a hare and &thorn;are a hare, as it es in &thorn;e berde of a lebard or of a catte, and &thorn;a
harez er ri&yogh;t lang. In &thorn;at land er &thorn;e fairest wymmen &thorn;at er in any land be&yogh;ond &thorn;e see; and &thorn;erfore sum callez
&thorn;at land Albany, by cause &thorn;at &thorn;e folk &thorn;at wonnes &thorn;erin er so white.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.101.11" CORRESP="Cot.135.21">&THORN;e first citee of &thorn;is land, and &thorn;e next &thorn;e see, es called Latoryn; and it es mare &thorn;an Parisch. And thurgh
&thorn;is citee rynnez a grete water, hable for to bere schippes; and it rynnez into &thorn;e see a lytill fra &thorn;e citee, &thorn;at es to
say a day iournee. &THORN;are es na citee in &thorn;e werld better ordayned, ne ma schippes langand to, ne better ne larger
and stranger hauen hase &thorn;an &thorn;is citee. All &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at citee and of &thorn;e cuntree aboute wirschepez mawmetes.
&THORN;are er all maner of fewles gretter by &thorn;e half &thorn;an &thorn;ai er in &thorn;is cuntree.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">In &thorn;at contree ben double sithes [more briddes than ben] here, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. The words in brackets are only in the [1725] printed text, the MS. having a lacuna. See the French text.</NOTE> &THORN;are er geesse all whyte, als grete
as swannez in &thorn;is cuntree; and &thorn;ai hafe on &thorn;aire heuedes a reed spotte euen round. &THORN;are es grete plentee and
<MILESTONE N="85" UNIT="folio">grete cheep of all maner of vitaile, and also grete plentee of nedders, of whilke &thorn;ai make grete festes and delicious
metes. For, if a man make a grete feste and had giffen all &thorn;e best metes &thorn;at myght be geten owerwhare and
he gyffe &thorn;am na nedders, he has na thank of all his feste.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.101.20" CORRESP="Cot.136.1">&THORN;are er many o&thorn;er faire citees in &thorn;is land, and grete plentee of vitaile; and &thorn;are er also many kirkez and
housez of religioun efter &thorn;aire lawe. And in &thorn;a kirkes er grete ydoles, as &thorn;ai were geauntz, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai giffe
mete and drink vnto on festiual days apon &thorn;is wyse. &THORN;ai bring before &thorn;am metes als hate as &thorn;ai come fra &thorn;e
fire, and &thorn;ai late &thorn;e smoke of &thorn;am ascend vp towardes &thorn;e ydoles, and &thorn;an &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ai er fedd wele
ynoghe; and, when &thorn;ai hafe so done, &thorn;e men of religioun etez &thorn;e metes. In &thorn;is cuntree er whyte hennes
withouten fethers, bot &thorn;ai hafe whyte woll on &thorn;am, as scepe hase in oure cuntree. Wymmen of &thorn;at cuntree
&thorn;at er weddid
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&thorn;at ben vnmaryed &hellip; to ben knowen for vnmaryed, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. See [commentary].</NOTE> beres crownes apon &thorn;aire heuedes, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may be knawen by forby &thorn;aim &thorn;at er vnweddid. In

<PB N="102">
&thorn;is land &thorn;ai take a beste &thorn;at es called Loyres, and &thorn;ai teche it to ga in to waters and viuers, and alssone he
bringes oute grete fischez, als many and as oft as &thorn;ai will.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.102.3" CORRESP="Cot.136.21">Fra &thorn;eine men gase by land many day iournez til ano&thorn;er citee &thorn;at es called Cassay, &thorn;e whilk es &thorn;e maste
citee of &thorn;e werld; and it es als mykill at say as &thorn;e Cytee of Heuen. &THORN;is citee es of l. myle vmgang, and &thorn;er es
<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio">wonder mykill folk &thorn;erin.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">in so moche &thorn;at in on hous men maken x. housholdes, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is citee hase xii. grete &yogh;ates; and before ilke a &yogh;ate, as it ware a three myle or
foure, es a grete toune and a gude. &THORN;is citee es bigge on &thorn;e same manere &thorn;at Venice es bigged; and &thorn;er er
&thorn;erin xii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> brigges and ma. And on ilke a brigg es a gude toure at ayther end, and men of armes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">wardeynes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in &thorn;am for to
kepe &thorn;e toune agayne &thorn;e Grete Caan, for it marchez apon his land. And apon a syde of &thorn;e citee rynnes a grete
ryuer endlang &thorn;e citee. And &thorn;are dwellez many Cristen men and many marchandes of diuerse naciouns, for &thorn;e
cuntree es wonder plentifous and gude and full of all maner of ricches. &THORN;are growes wonder gude wyne,
whilke &thorn;ai call Bygon; and it es ri&yogh;t myghty wyne and lykand
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">gentylle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e drinkyng. In &thorn;is citee was &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;at
land wont to dwell; and &thorn;are es a hous of Cristen freres.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.102.13" CORRESP="Cot.137.5">Fra &thorn;is citee may men ride in schippe or in bate by &thorn;at riuer
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">solacynge and disportyne hem, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> till ane abbay of mounkes a lytill fra &thorn;e citee;
and &thorn;ai er wonder religious after &thorn;aire lawe. In &thorn;at abbay es a grete gardyne and a faire, and &thorn;are growez
&thorn;erin many treesse of diuerse kyndes. And in &thorn;at gardyne er many diuerse bestez, as marmusetes, apes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">apes, marmozettes, babewynes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. Odoric has "symi&aelig;, catti, maymones."</NOTE> and
o&thorn;er many vntil iii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> or iiii<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. And, when &thorn;e couent hase eten, a munke takez &thorn;e relefe and berez it to &thorn;e
gardyn; and he knyllez a lytill bell of siluer
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">and he smytethe on the gardyn &yogh;ate with a clyket of syluer, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at he hase in his hand, and &thorn;an commez oute all &thorn;ise bestez till
<MILESTONE N="86" UNIT="folio">him of &thorn;aire clapers.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> burrows; used by Chaucer of cronies, "that comyn out of her clapers" (<HI REND="i">Rom. of Rose</HI>, 1405).</NOTE> And he mase &thorn;am to sitt on rawe and delez &thorn;am &thorn;is relefe in faire siluer vessell ouer gylt,
and &thorn;ai ete it. And when &thorn;ai hafe done, he knyllez &thorn;e bell agayne, and &thorn;ai ga &thorn;are &thorn;ai come fra. &THORN;ir mounkes
saise &thorn;at &thorn;ase bestez whilk er faire and gentill er saules of lordes and gentillmen,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">soules of worthi men, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;ase bestes whilk er no&yogh;t
so er saules of o&thorn;er men.
<NOTE N="9" RESP="GW">soules of pore men and of rude comouns, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ai say and affermes &thorn;at &thorn;e saules of men, when &thorn;ai passe oute of &thorn;e bodys,
entrez in to &thorn;ase bestez; and &thorn;at es fully &thorn;aire belefe, and &thorn;er may na man turne &thorn;am fra &thorn;at opinioun. &THORN;e
saules of grete men, &thorn;ai say, entrez in to gentill bestez and faire bestez, and &thorn;e saules of meen men entrez in to
foule bestez; and &thorn;erfore giffe &thorn;ai &thorn;aim mete and almous for &thorn;e lufe of Godd. I asked &thorn;e mounk &thorn;at delt &thorn;e

<PB N="103">
almous, if it had no&yogh;t bene better to hafe giffen &thorn;at relefe to pouer men &thorn;an to &thorn;ase bestez, and he answerd and
said &thorn;at in &thorn;at cuntree es na pouer man and, if &thorn;er ware, &yogh;it it ware mare almous to giffe it to &thorn;ase saules &thorn;at
suffers &thorn;aire penaunce &thorn;are and may ga na ferrere to get &thorn;aire mete &thorn;an to &thorn;e pouer &thorn;at hase
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;at hase &hellip; liffing, om. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;aire witte and
can and may laboure and get &thorn;aire liffing. &THORN;ir ilke bestez take &thorn;ai when &thorn;ai er &yogh;ung and bringez &thorn;am vpp and
vsez &thorn;am to comme to take &thorn;e forsaid almous. Many o&thorn;er meruailes sawe I in &thorn;at cuntre, &thorn;e whilk at &thorn;is tyme
I speke no&yogh;t of, by cause of schortyng of my buke.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.103.7" CORRESP="Cot.138.3">Fra &thorn;is citee men gase for&thorn;ermare in &thorn;is land vi. day iournez and commez to ano&thorn;er grete cite, &thorn;e whilk es
<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio">called Chibense. &THORN;is citee es xx. myle aboute &thorn;e walles; and within &thorn;e citee er lx. brigges faire and gude, all of
stane, wele and curiously wroght. In &thorn;is citee was first &thorn;e see of &thorn;e kyng of Mancy, for it es a faire citee
and a gude.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.103.11" CORRESP="Cot.138.9">Fra &thorn;eine men gase ouer a grete riuer, &thorn;e whilk es called Dalay; and it es &thorn;e fairest and &thorn;e grettest riuer in
&thorn;e werld of fresch water, for it es in &thorn;e narowest place &thorn;erof mare &thorn;an foure myle brade. And &thorn;an men
entres agayne in to &thorn;e Grete Caan land. &THORN;is ilke riuer of Dalay rynnez thurgh &thorn;e middes of &thorn;e land of &thorn;e
Pigmens, whilk er men of litill stature, for &thorn;ai er bot iii. span lang; bot &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t faire and wele proporciound
of &thorn;aire mykill. &THORN;ai er weddid when &thorn;ai er a half &yogh;ere alde and getez childer; and &thorn;ai liffe comounly vii. &yogh;ere or
viii.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">vi. or vii., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, if &thorn;ai liffe ix.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">viii., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &yogh;ere, &thorn;ai er halden wonder alde folke amanges &thorn;am. &THORN;ise smale men wirkez wonder
wele silk and bombe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">gold, syluer, cotoun, sylk, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and swilke o&thorn;er sutill werkes, &yogh;a mare sutilly &thorn;an o&thorn;er men. And &thorn;ai feight with craanes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">with the bryddes of the contree, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
comounly, and hase allway were with &thorn;am; and, when &thorn;ai may sla any of &thorn;am, &thorn;ai ete &thorn;aim. &THORN;ai trauaile no&yogh;t
aboute telyng of land ne o&thorn;er grete laboures; bot &thorn;ai hafe amanges &thorn;am men of oure stature, &thorn;e whilk telez &thorn;e
land and dightez vynes and duse all o&thorn;er grete laboures &thorn;at er nedefull to &thorn;am. And &thorn;ise smale men hase als
<MILESTONE N="87" UNIT="folio">grete scorne at &thorn;e grete men and wonders als mykill of &thorn;am as we wald do of geauntz amanges vs. In &thorn;at land
es a gude citee amanges o&thorn;er, wharin dwellez grete multitude of &thorn;ir smale men. And amanges &thorn;aim dwellez
myklll men also and men of comoun stature, &thorn;e whilk, if &thorn;ai get childer, when &thorn;ai er borne &thorn;ai er smale as &thorn;e
childer of &thorn;e Pigmenz er; for &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e cuntree es swilk &thorn;at &thorn;are er nane engendred &thorn;erin bot swilk smale
thinges. &THORN;is citee gers &thorn;e Grete Caan kepe wonder wele, for he es lord &thorn;eroff. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at
&thorn;ir Pigmenz, if all &thorn;ai be lytill, &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t resonable after &thorn;aire elde, and wonder sutill of witte and can discerne
betwix gude and euill.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.103.28" CORRESP="Cot.139.2">Fra &thorn;is cite men gase thurgh &thorn;e forsaid cuntree by many citeez and tounes till &thorn;ai comme to a citee &thorn;at es

<PB N="104">
called Iamcaly; and it es a faire citee and a riche. &THORN;ider commez marchauntz fra diuerse landes for to by all
maner of marchandys. &THORN;is citee &yogh;eldez &yogh;erely to &thorn;e Grete Caan, as citesenez &thorn;eroff talde me,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">as &thorn;ei of &thorn;e cytee seyn, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> l. thousand
comacyes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">cumantz, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of florenes of gold. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at a comacy contenes x<HI REND="sup">m</HI> florenes; and so &thorn;e somme
&thorn;at &thorn;is citee &yogh;eldez &yogh;erely commez to fyue hundreth thowsand florenez of gold. &THORN;e kyng of &thorn;at land es a grete
lord and a myghty, bot he es subget to &thorn;e Grete Caan; and he has vnder him xii. grete princes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">prouynces, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;at land
es a gude custom vsed in ilke a gude toune. For, if a man will make a feste till his frendez, &thorn;are er in ilk a
gude toune certayne innes grete and faire; and &thorn;an he &thorn;at schall make &thorn;e feste commez to &thorn;e hostiller and saise,
<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio">"Puruay me in &thorn;ine inne for so many men," and he tellez him &thorn;e nowmer of &thorn;e men, and what maner of metes
he will hafe, and what he will spend. And &thorn;an &thorn;is hostiller gase and ordaynez all maner of thinges &thorn;at er
nedefull, so &thorn;at &thorn;are lakkes na thing; and he ordaynez mykill better &thorn;arfore &thorn;an he &thorn;at makez &thorn;e feste schuld
do in his awen hous.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.104.12" CORRESP="Cot.139.25">Foure myle fra &thorn;e citee of Iamcaly, toward &thorn;e heued of &thorn;e riuer of Dalay, es ano&thorn;er citee, &thorn;at es called
Menke. In &thorn;e whilk citee es a grete nauee of schippez, and &thorn;ai er all whyte as snawe of kynde of &thorn;e wodde
&thorn;at &thorn;ai er made off. And &thorn;ai er made as it ware grete houses, with hallez and chaumbres and o&thorn;er esementz.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.104.15" CORRESP="Cot.139.31">Fra &thorn;eine men gase by many tounes of &thorn;at cuntre to ano&thorn;er citee &thorn;at es called Lanteryn; and it es fra
Menke viii. day iournez. &THORN;is citee standez apon a grete riuer &thorn;at es called Caremoran, or Caromosan; and
it rynnez thurgh &thorn;e cuntree of Cathay. And oft tymez it duse grete harme to &thorn;e cuntre by ouerflowyng,
when it es grete.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.23" N="23" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.24">
<PB N="105">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the Grete Chane of Chatay; of the rialtee of his palays, and how he sitt at mete; and of the grete nombre of officeres that seruen hym.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.105.4" CORRESP="Cot.140.3">THE land of Catay es a grete cuntree, faire and gude and riche and full of gude marchandyse. And
&thorn;ider commez marchauntz ilk a &yogh;ere for to fecche spicery and o&thorn;er maner of marchandys mare
comounly &thorn;an till o&thorn;er cuntrees. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at marchandes &thorn;at commez fra Venice
or Geen, or o&thorn;er placez of Lumbardy or Romany, &thorn;ai trauaile by see and by land xi. monethes or xii. are &thorn;ai
<MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="folio">comme to Catay, whilk es &thorn;e cheeffe rewme of &thorn;e Grete Caan.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR> omits a passage here which is thus given in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (f. 89): "Fro Cathay go men toward the est be many iorneyes, and &thorn;an men fynden a gode cytee betwene &thorn;eise o&thorn;ere, &thorn;at men clepen Sugarmago; &thorn;at cytee is on of the beste stored of sylk and o&thorn;er marchandises &thorn;at is in the world. After go men &yogh;it to ano&thorn;er old cytee toward &thorn;e est, and it es in the prouynce of Cathay. And besyde &thorn;at cytee the men of Tartarye," <HI REND="i">etc.</HI></NOTE></SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.105.8" CORRESP="Cot.140.16">And toward &thorn;e este es ane alde citee, and nere
to &thorn;at citee &thorn;e Tartarenes has made ano&thorn;er citee, whilk &thorn;ai call Gaydon. &THORN;is citee hase xii. &yogh;atez, and euer
betwix a &yogh;ate and ano&thorn;er es a myle, and so all &thorn;e vmgang of &thorn;is citee es xx. myle and foure. In &thorn;is citee es
&thorn;e sege and &thorn;e see of &thorn;e Grete Caan in a ri&yogh;t faire palays, of whilk &thorn;e walles aboute er twa myle and mare; and
within &thorn;ase wallez er many o&thorn;er faire palays. And in &thorn;e gardyn of &thorn;e grete palays es a hill, apon whilk es
ano&thorn;er palays, a faire and a riche; &thorn;er es no&yogh;t swilk ano&thorn;er in all &thorn;e werld. And all aboute &thorn;e palays and &thorn;e
hill er many treesse, berand diuerse maners of fruyt; and withouten &thorn;aim er depe dykes and brade, and
withouten &thorn;aim er many vyuers and stankes, whare on er many fewles of riuer, as swannes and cranes, herouns,
butours and mawlardes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">wylde gees and gandres and wylde dokes and swannes and heirouns, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and swilk o&thorn;er. Withouten &thorn;aim also er all maner of wylde bestez of wenery, as
hertez and hyndez, bukk and da, and rae, and many o&thorn;er. And, ay when &thorn;e Grete Caan will hafe his disporte
in ryuaying or huntyng, he may wylde fewle slayne with hawkes and dere slaen with hundes or o&thorn;er gynnez and
passe no&yogh;t his chaumbre. &THORN;is palays with his see er wonder faire and grete; and &thorn;e hall of &thorn;at palays es richely

<PB N="106">
dight. For within &thorn;e hall er xxiiii. pilers of gold; and all &thorn;e walles er couerd with reed skynnes of bestez, &thorn;at
er called Panters. And &thorn;ai er wonder faire bestez and wele smelland, and by cause of &thorn;e gude smell of &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio">skynnes &thorn;er may na wikked aer comme &thorn;erin. &THORN;ase skynnes er als reed as any blude, and so faire schynand
agayne &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at men may vnnethes luke on &thorn;am or behald &thorn;am for grete bri&yogh;tness. &THORN;e folk of &thorn;at cuntree
wirschepez &thorn;at beste, whare &thorn;ai see it,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">whan &thorn;ei meeten hem first at morwe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for &thorn;e grete vertu and &thorn;e swete sauour &thorn;at commez &thorn;eroff; and &thorn;ai praise
&thorn;e skynne &thorn;eroff als mykill as it ware of fyne gold. In &thorn;e midward of &thorn;e palays es made ane ascensory
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">mountour, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. ascensorium, Harl. MS. 175.</NOTE> for &thorn;e
Grete Caan, enourned with gold and precious stanes; and at &thorn;e foure corners er made foure dragouns of gold.
And &thorn;is ascensory es couerd abouen with clathez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">large nettes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of silk, barred ouerthwert with gold and siluer, and many
grete precious stanes er hingand aboute it. And vnder &thorn;e ascensory er cundytes full of drink, &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at er of
&thorn;e emperours courte drynk off; and be syde &thorn;e cundytes er vessell sett of gold, &thorn;at men may drink off when
&thorn;ai will. &THORN;is hall es nobilly and wirschepfully arayd and ordaynd in all thinges. First, vp at &thorn;e hie deesse,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">at the chief of the halle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
euen in &thorn;e middes, es ordaind &thorn;e trone for &thorn;e emperour, whare he sittes at his meet, wele hye fra &thorn;e pament.
His table, on whilk he etez, es made of precious stanes sett in fyne gold, and it es wele bordured aboute with
fyne gold sette full of precious stanes. And &thorn;e greece, whare he gase vp till his trone, es all of precious stanes,
endentid in gold.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">medled with gold, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And at &thorn;e left syde of his trone es &thorn;e seete of his first wyf, a gree lawer &thorn;an his trone; and
it es of iasper, with sydes of fyne gold sett full of precious stanes, and hir burde es of iasper bordurde with
gold sett full of precious stanes. &THORN;e seet of his secund wyf es a gree lawer &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;er; and bathe hir seet and
<MILESTONE N="89" UNIT="folio">hir burde es enourned wirschipfully as &thorn;e to&thorn;er es. &THORN;e seet also of &thorn;e thrid wyf and hir table er a gree lawer
&thorn;an &thorn;e secund. For he hase euermare three wyfes with him, whare so euer he ryde, ferre or nere. Next his
thridd wyf apon &thorn;e same syde sittez o&thorn;er ladys of &thorn;e emperoure kynne, ilkane a gree lawer &thorn;an o&thorn;er, efter &thorn;ai er
nere of blude to &thorn;e emperour. All &thorn;e wymmen of &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;at er weddid hase standand on &thorn;aire heuedes as
it ware a mannez fote, made of gold and precious stanes and pacok fethers &thorn;at er schynand curiousely and wele
dight, in takennyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai er vnder mannez subieccioun; and &thorn;ai &thorn;at er no&yogh;t weddid hase nane swilke. Apon
&thorn;e ri&yogh;t hand of &thorn;e emperour sittez his eldest sonn, &thorn;at schall regne after him, a grece lawer &thorn;an his fader. His
seet and his borde es araid in all thing as &thorn;e empericez es. And &thorn;an sittez o&thorn;er lordes of &thorn;e emperoure kynne,
ilkane as &thorn;ai er of degree, as ladys duse on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde. And ilkane of &thorn;am has a burde by him self, and
ri&yogh;t so has &thorn;e ladys; and &thorn;ai er ow&thorn;er of iasper or of cristall or of amatist or of <FOREIGN LANG="lat">lignum aloes</FOREIGN>, whilk commez

<PB N="107">
oute of Paradys, or of euour.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">In <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, as in the French text, this is the description of the emperor's table only.</NOTE> And all &thorn;ir burdez er bordured aboute with gold sett full of precious stanes, so
&thorn;at &thorn;er es nane of &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne er worthe a grete tresoure. Vnder &thorn;e emperour table at his fete sittez foure
clerkes, &thorn;at wrytez all &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at he spekez at his mete, wheder &thorn;ai be gude or ill. For all &thorn;at euer he saise
behoues be halden and done in dede; for his worde may no&yogh;t be agayne called for na thing.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.107.5" CORRESP="Cot.143.2">&THORN;are er broght furth apon solempne days before &thorn;e emperoure tablez of gold, faire and grete, in &thorn;e whilk
standez pacokes of gold and many o&thorn;er maners of fewles of gold, curiousely and sutilly wro&yogh;t.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">richely wrought and enameled, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ir fewles
er so wonderfully made by craft of man &thorn;at it semez as &thorn;ai leped and daunsed and bett with &thorn;aire wengez and
playd &thorn;am on o&thorn;er diuerse wyse; and it es ri&yogh;t wonderfull to &thorn;e sight, how &thorn;at swilk thinges may be done. By
what craft &thorn;ai moue so, can I no&yogh;t say; bot a thing wate I wele, &thorn;at &thorn;at folk er wonder sutell of witte towchand
any thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai will do, forby any o&thorn;er folk of &thorn;e werld. For &thorn;ai passe all &thorn;e naciouns of &thorn;e werld in suteltee
of witte, wheder it touche ill or gude; and &thorn;at knawez &thorn;aim self wele. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ai luke with
twa eghen and Cristen men with ane; for &thorn;ai hald Cristen men maste sutell and wys after &thorn;aim selfen. Folk of
o&thorn;er naciouns &thorn;ai say er blynd withouten eghen, as ynentes kunnyng and wirking. I bisied me gretely for to
wit and persayfe by what craft &thorn;ir forsaid thinges ware done; bot &thorn;e mayster of &thorn;e werk sayd me &thorn;at he was so
boun by vowe til his godd &thorn;at he myght schew &thorn;at craft to na man bot till his eldest sonne. Abouen &thorn;e
emperour table and aboute a grete party of &thorn;e hall es made a grete vyne of fyne gold; and it es wonder
curiousely wro&yogh;t with many braunchez and grapez lyke vnto grapez of vynes growand, of whilk sum er whyte,
<MILESTONE N="90" UNIT="folio">sum &yogh;alow, sum reed, sum blakk, sum grene. All &thorn;ase &thorn;at are reed er made of rubies or cremas or alabauncez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">of grenaz and of alabaundynes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>;
&thorn;e whyte er made of cristall or of berill
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">of berylle and of iris, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; &thorn;e &yogh;alow er made of topazes or crisolytez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">of perydos and of crisolytes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, after "emeraudes."</NOTE>; &thorn;e grene of emeraudez;
&thorn;e blak of onichyns or geraudes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">garantez, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;is vyne es &thorn;us made of precious stanes so properly and so curiousely
&thorn;at it semez as it ware a vyne growand.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">a verry vyne, berynge kyndely grapes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.107.22" CORRESP="Cot.143.32">And before the emperoure table standez grete lordes and barouns for to serue the emperoure; and nane of
&thorn;aim er so hardy to speke worde, bot if &thorn;e emperour speke first to &thorn;aim, oute taken minstralles &thorn;at singez him
sanges, or saise him gestes, or tellez iapez or bourdez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">gestes or o&thorn;er desportez, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for solace of &thorn;e emperour. All &thorn;e vessell &thorn;at er serued in
to his hall or his chaumbre, and namely at his awen burde or at burdez &thorn;are grete lordes sittez, er of iasper or of
cristall or of amatistes or of fyne gold. And all &thorn;aire coppes er of smaragdez or of saphires, of topacez or of

<PB N="108">
o&thorn;er precious stanes. Vessell of siluer make &thorn;ai nane, ne settez na prys by siluer. For &thorn;ai will now&thorn;er ete ne
drink of &thorn;e vessell &thorn;at er made &thorn;eroff; bot &thorn;ai make &thorn;eroff grecez, pilers and pamentes to halles and chaumbres.
Before &thorn;e hall dure standez certayne lordes and many o&thorn;er knyghtes for to kepe &thorn;at nane entre in at &thorn;e dure bot
&thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour will, oless &thorn;an he be of &thorn;e houshald or a mynstrall; o&thorn;er dare &thorn;er nane comme nere.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.108.5" CORRESP="Cot.144.15">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at my felawes and I ware dwelland sodeours with &thorn;e Grete Caan xvi. monethes
<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio">agaynes &thorn;e kyng of Mancy, for &thorn;ai ware at were when we ware &thorn;are. And &thorn;e cause of oure dwellyng with him
was for &thorn;at we desired gretely to see his grete nobillay and &thorn;e state and &thorn;e ordinaunce of his courte, and &thorn;e grete
excellence of his ricches, to wit wheder it ware swilk as we had herd tell before. And sikerly we fand it mare
riche and noble &thorn;an we herd say &thorn;eroff; and we schuld neuer haf trowed it, if we had no&yogh;t sene it with oure eghen.
&THORN;are es na swilk courte here in &thorn;is land. For kynges and lordes in &thorn;ir parties haldes als fewe men in &thorn;aire
courtes as &thorn;ai may
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">han folk of certeyn nombre, als &thorn;ei may suffise, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; bot &thorn;e Grete Caan hase ilke a day in his courte at his coste folk withouten nowmer. Bot
&yogh;e sall vnderstand &thorn;at mete and drynk es mare honestly araid in oure cuntree &thorn;an it es &thorn;are; and also in &thorn;is
cuntree men sittez mare honestly at &thorn;e mete &thorn;an &thorn;ai do &thorn;are. For all &thorn;e comouns of his courte hase &thorn;aire mete
laid on &thorn;aire kneesse, when &thorn;ai ete, withouten any clathe or towail, and for &thorn;e maste party &thorn;ai ete flesche,
withouten breed, of all maner of bestez; and, when &thorn;ai hafe eten, &thorn;ai wype &thorn;aire hend on &thorn;aire skirtez. And
&thorn;ai ete bot anes on &thorn;e day. &THORN;is es &thorn;e aray and &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e comouns of &thorn;e courte of &thorn;e Grete Caan. Bot &thorn;e
aray of him self and o&thorn;er lordes &thorn;at sittez with him es nobill and reall, passand all erthely mennez.</SEG> For sikerly
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">For sikerly &hellip; leue on, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
vnder &thorn;e firmament es no&yogh;t so grete a lorde ne sa riche ne na so myghty as es &thorn;e Grete Caan of Tartre. No&yogh;t
<MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="folio">Prestre Iohn &thorn;at es emperour of Inde &thorn;e less and &thorn;e mare, ne &thorn;e sowdan of Babiloyn, ne &thorn;e emperoure of Pers, ne
nan o&thorn;er may be made comparisoun off till him. Certez it es mykill harme &thorn;at he ne ware a Cristen man; and
no&yogh;t for&thorn;i he will gladly here speke of Godd and suffer Cristen men dwell in his empire. For na man es
forboden in his land to trowe in what lawe &thorn;at him list leue on. <SEG ID="Eg.108.22" CORRESP="Cot.144.37">And if all sum men perauenture will no&yogh;t
trowe me of &thorn;is &thorn;at I hafe said, and will say it es bot truflez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">holden it for fable, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at I tell of &thorn;e noblay and &thorn;e grete excellence and
ricches of &thorn;e Grete Caan and of his courte and &thorn;e multitude of men &thorn;erin &thorn;at I spakk off before, I recke no&yogh;t
mykill. Bot he &thorn;at will trowe it, trowe it; and he &thorn;at will no&yogh;t, lefe. For I will neuer &thorn;e latter tell sum what &thorn;at
I sawe with myne eghen of him and of his folk and of &thorn;e ordinaunce of his courte, wheder &thorn;ai will trowe it or &thorn;ai nil.
Neuer&thorn;eles I wate wele &thorn;at, and any had bene &thorn;are or in cuntrez &thorn;at marchez &thorn;er apon, if all he had no&yogh;t bene
in his courte, he schuld hafe herd of his noblay and his excellence so mykill &thorn;at he schuld lightly trowe me of
&thorn;at &thorn;at I hafe said. And &thorn;erfore I will no&yogh;t lette &thorn;at ne I will tell thinges &thorn;at I knawe wele er sothe for &thorn;aim
&thorn;at knawez &thorn;am no&yogh;t ne will no&yogh;t trowe &thorn;am. Now will I tell &yogh;ow mare of &thorn;e Grete Caan and of his state and
his ordinaunce, when he will passe oute of a cuntree in to ano&thorn;er, and when he makes his grete festez.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.24" N="24" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.25">
<PB N="109">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXIV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Wherfore he is clept the Grete Chane; of the style of his lettres; and of the superscripcion abowten his grete seall and his pryuee seall.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.109.4" CORRESP="Cot.145.18">BOT first will I tell &yogh;ow why he es called Grete Caan. &YOGH;e schal vnderstand &thorn;at all &thorn;e werld was
<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio">fordone thurgh Noe flude, oute taken a few menyee, &thorn;at es to say Noe and his wyf, his sonnes and
&thorn;aire wyfes. For Noe had three sonnes Sem, Cham and Iaphet. Cham was he &thorn;at sawe his fader
priuee membres naked, as he lay and sleped, and went till his bre&thorn;er and schewed &thorn;aim &thorn;am in scorne; and
&thorn;erfore his fader efterward, when he wist, gaf him his malisoun. Bot Iaphet went bakward till his fader and
couerd his priuee membres. &THORN;ir three sonnes of Noe after &thorn;e diluuy parted amanges &thorn;am all &thorn;e erthe. Seem,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Seem, over an erasure</NOTE>
by cause he was &thorn;e eldest bro&thorn;er, chose
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Cham for his crueltee toke, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>, following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Royal 20 B. x">R</ABBR> literally both here and below.</NOTE> &thorn;e best party and &thorn;e grettest, whilk es toward &thorn;e este, and it es called
Asy. Cham
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Cham, over an erasure.</NOTE> tuke Affryk, and Iaphet tuke Europe. Cham was &thorn;e my&yogh;tiest of &thorn;ir bre&thorn;er and &thorn;e ricchest; and
of him come many generaciouns ma &thorn;an of his o&thorn;er bre&thorn;er. Of ane of his sonnez &thorn;at hight Chus come
Nemproth &thorn;e geaunt, &thorn;e whilk was &thorn;e first king &thorn;at euer was; and he began to bigg &thorn;e toure of Babilon. In
whas tyme &thorn;er come many fendez in liknes of men and lay by wymmen of his kynreden and gatt on &thorn;am geauntz
and o&thorn;er monstres of horrible figure, sum withouten heuedes, sum with hund heuedes, and many o&thorn;er disfigured
and misschapen men. Of &thorn;e kynreden also of Cham come &thorn;e payenes and diuerse maner of men of &thorn;e iles of
Inde. And for he &thorn;is Cham was so myghty &thorn;at na man myght agayne stand him, he gert call himself Goddes
sonne and lorde of all &thorn;e werld. And &thorn;erfore saise sum men &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour of Tartare gert call him Cham,
<MILESTONE N="92" UNIT="folio">for he es halden &thorn;e maste excellent emperour of &thorn;e werld and occupies &thorn;e same land &thorn;at he was lorde off. And
of Sem, as &thorn;ai say, come &thorn;e Sarezenes; and of Iaphet &thorn;e folk of Israel and we &thorn;at dwellez in Europe. &THORN;is es
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">And &thorn;ough &thorn;at wee duellen in Europe, this is, <HI REND="i">etc</HI>., <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e
opinioun of &thorn;e Sarzenes and of &thorn;e Samaritanes; and &thorn;us made &thorn;ai me at vnderstand, ay till I come to Inde; and,
fra I come &thorn;are, I knewe wele &thorn;at it was o&thorn;erwise. Neuer&thorn;eles it es sothe &thorn;at &thorn;e folk of Tartre come of &thorn;e

<PB N="110">
kynreden of Cham, and all &thorn;ase &thorn;at dwellez in Asy &thorn;e mare. Bot &thorn;e emperour of Cathay hat Caan and no&yogh;t
Cham, and for &thorn;is skill.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.110.3" CORRESP="Cot.146.25">It es no&yogh;t &yogh;it gane viii<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> &yogh;ere sen all &thorn;e folk of Tartre was in subieccioun and thrall till o&thorn;er naciouns aboute
&thorn;am, and ware made hirdmen and kepers of bestez. Bot amanges &thorn;am ware vii. principall kynredens; of whilk
&thorn;e cheeffe kynreden and &thorn;e maste worthy was called Tartre, &thorn;e secund was called Tangut, &thorn;e third Eurac, &thorn;e
ferthe Valair, &thorn;e fyft Semok, &thorn;e sext Menchy, &thorn;e seuent Tobak. Now it befell so, &thorn;at in &thorn;e first kynreden was
ane alde man, &thorn;e whilk was in his tyme a wyght man and a hardy, bot he was no&yogh;t ryche; and his name was
Chaanguys. &THORN;is man lay on a nyght in his bedd, and &thorn;er came til him in a visioun a knyght all whyte armed,
sittand apon a whyte hors, &thorn;e whilk said vntil him, "Caan," quod he, "slepez &thorn;ou?" And he answerd and said,
"Nay." "Godd," quod he, "&thorn;at es all myghty, sent me to &thorn;e, to schew &thorn;e his will. His will es &thorn;at &thorn;ou say to
<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e seuen kynredens, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schall be &thorn;aire emperour. And &thorn;ou schall conquere and wynne all &thorn;e landes &thorn;at er
about &yogh;ow; and &thorn;ai
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;ei &thorn;at marchen (<HI REND="i">sc.</HI> border) vpon &yogh;ou, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> schall be in &yogh;oure subieccioun, as &yogh;e hafe bene in &thorn;aires. For &thorn;is es &thorn;e will of Godd all
myghty." Apon &thorn;e morue he went to &thorn;e vii. kynredens and talde &thorn;am his visioun, and &thorn;ai scorned him and held
him a fule; and he went fra &thorn;am schamed and confused. And on &thorn;e nyght next folowand &thorn;e same whyte knyght
appered to &thorn;e vii. kynredens and bad &thorn;am on Goddes behalf &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld make Chaanguys &thorn;aire emperour, for
he schuld delyuer &thorn;aim oute of &thorn;e subieccioun of o&thorn;er naciouns and conquere and wynne many rewmes. And
apon &thorn;e morue &thorn;ai made Chaanguys &thorn;aire emperour by comoun ascent, and sett him in a chaier and didd him all
&thorn;e wirschepe and reuerence &thorn;at &thorn;ai myght, and called him Chaan, as &thorn;e whyt knyght called him before. And,
when he was chosen on &thorn;is wyse and made emperour, he tho&yogh;t he wald proue &thorn;aire trewth and bowsoumness,
whe&thorn;er he myght seurly trist in &thorn;am or no&yogh;t; and he made many statutez and lawes, whilk &thorn;ai call Ysachan. &THORN;e
first statute was &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld be obedient to Godd all myghty and trowe &thorn;at he schuld delyuer &thorn;am oute of all
thraldom, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld call apon him in all &thorn;aire nede. Ano&thorn;er statute was &thorn;at all men &thorn;at myght bere
armes schuld be armed and be nowmbred, and to ilk ten schuld be a mayster, and to ilk xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> a maister, and to ilk
hundreth a maister, and to ilk thowsand a maister, and to ilk ten thousand a maister, and to ilk xx<HI REND="sup">m</HI> a maister.
And after &thorn;is he comaunded to all &thorn;e grettest and &thorn;e ricchest of &thorn;e vii. kynredens &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld forsake all &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="93" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ai had in heritage and lordschepe, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld fra &thorn;eine forward hald &thorn;am payd of &thorn;at he wald gyffe
&thorn;am of his grace; and &thorn;ai did so. Also he bad &thorn;at ilkane of &thorn;am schuld bring his son before him and slae his

<PB N="111">
awen son with his awen handes and smyte off his heued; and &thorn;ai did so, withouten any tariing. And when he
sawe &thorn;ai made na lettyng of &thorn;at he bad &thorn;am do, &thorn;an he bad &thorn;am folowe his banere.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">to make hem redy and to sewen his banere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;an he wan all &thorn;e
landes aboute him and made &thorn;am subiettes till him.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.111.4" CORRESP="Cot.148.12">Afterwardes it befell on a day &thorn;at &thorn;e Chaan rade with a lytill cumpany of men to see &thorn;e landes &thorn;at he had
wonnen; and euen sudaynly he mette with a grete multitude of his enmys. And he, as a doghty man, for to
giffe his men ensaumple and will to feight, went baldely before all his men apon his enmys; and &thorn;are was he
smyten doune of his hors and his hors slaen. And, when his men sawe him at &thorn;e erthe, &thorn;ai wend he had bene
deed and fledd away, and &thorn;aire enmys folowed &thorn;am and wist no&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;at was &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at was so smyten fra his
hors. And, when Chaan sawe his enmys ware ferre fra him, he went til a wodde &thorn;at was nere besyde and hidd
him in a thikk busk. And, when &thorn;e enmys ware commen agayne fra &thorn;e chace, &thorn;ai went to seke in &thorn;e wodde, if
any ware hidd &thorn;erin, and &thorn;ai fand many and slewe &thorn;am ilkane. So it fell &thorn;at &thorn;ai come nere &thorn;e place whare &thorn;e
kyng was hidd and sawe a fewle sitte apon a tree vnder &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e king lay in hidels; and &thorn;at fewle men callez
<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio">ane owle. And, when &thorn;ai sawe &thorn;at fewle sitte so still, ilk ane of &thorn;am said till o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;are was na man. And
so &thorn;ai went &thorn;aire way; and &thorn;us was &thorn;e kyng saued fra deed and went away on &thorn;e nyght and come to his men.
And, when &thorn;ai sawe &thorn;aire lord on lyfe, &thorn;ai ware wonder gladd and thanked allmy&yogh;ty Godd and &thorn;e forsaid bridd
&thorn;at had saued &thorn;aire lord fra &thorn;e deed and delyuerd him oute of &thorn;e handes of his enmys. And euer sen &thorn;at tyme
men of &thorn;at cuntree has done grete wirschepe to &thorn;at fewle forby all o&thorn;er fewles, and luffez it so mykill &thorn;at, wha
so may get a fether &thorn;eroff, he kepez it wirschepfully, as it ware a relyque, and beres it on his heued with grete
reuerence, supposing to be blissed &thorn;erby and delyuerd fra all maner of perils. Afterwardes &thorn;e emperour Chaan
assembled all his men and rade apon his enmys and destruyd &thorn;am to &thorn;e vtterest.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.111.21" CORRESP="Cot.149.10">And, when he had wonnen all &thorn;e landes aboute him vnto &thorn;e mount Belyan, &thorn;e white knyght appered to him
agayne and said vntil him, "Chaan, &thorn;e will of Godd es &thorn;at &thorn;ou passe &thorn;e mount Belyan, and &thorn;are schall &thorn;ou
conquere &thorn;at land and many o&thorn;er and make &thorn;am subiettes vnto &thorn;ine empire. And, for &thorn;ou sall fynd na gude
passage &thorn;ider, ga to &thorn;e mount Belyan, &thorn;e whilk es apon &thorn;e see syde, and knele &thorn;are nyne sythes agayne &thorn;e este
in &thorn;e wirschepe of Godd allmyghty, and he sall schew &thorn;e a way how &thorn;ou schall passe." And &thorn;e Chaan did as
he badd; and, alsone as he come &thorn;are, &thorn;e see, &thorn;at before bette apon &thorn;e mount, withdrewe it and schewed a faire

<PB N="112">
<MILESTONE N="94" UNIT="folio">way of ix. fote brade betwene &thorn;e mount and &thorn;e see. And so passed he and all his men and conquerd all &thorn;e land
of Cathay, whilk es &thorn;e maste land of &thorn;e werld. And by cause of &thorn;ir ix. knelings and ix. fote of way &thorn;e Chaan
and &thorn;e men of Tartre haldez &thorn;e nowmer of ix. in grete wirschepe. And &thorn;erfore, when any man makez a presand
of horsez or of fewles, or of bowes, or of arowes, or of any o&thorn;er thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai vse to send to &thorn;e emperour, if &thorn;ai
make &thorn;at presand of &thorn;e forsaid nowmer, &thorn;ai sall hafe mare thank &thorn;eroff, and mare acceptable sall it be to &thorn;e
emperour &thorn;an if he gafe him a hundreth falde so mykill in o&thorn;er nowmer. For &thorn;am think &thorn;e nowmer of nyne &thorn;e
halyest nowmer &thorn;at es, by cause &thorn;e messangere of Godd expressed &thorn;at nowmer so specially.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.112.8" CORRESP="Cot.149.35">Qwhen &thorn;e Grete Chaan had conquerd and wonnen &thorn;e land of Chatay, and many o&thorn;er landes had putte
ynder his subieccioun, he fell greeffe seke and feled wele &thorn;at he myght no&yogh;t couer of &thorn;at sekeness, bot &thorn;at him
most nedez dye &thorn;eroff. And &thorn;an he gert call byfore him his xii. sonnes, and bad &thorn;at ilkane of &thorn;am schuld bring
him ane arowe; and &thorn;ai did so. And he bad &thorn;am fast togyder with three bandez, and &thorn;ai did as he bad &thorn;am.
And, when &thorn;ai ware so bunden, he bad his eldest son &thorn;at he schuld breke &thorn;am so bunden togyder; and he
assayd, and my&yogh;t no&yogh;t breke &thorn;am. And &thorn;an he bad ano&thorn;er of his sonnez ga to and breke &thorn;am, and he myght
no&yogh;t. &THORN;thorn;us he bad til xi. of his sonnez, bot nane of &thorn;am myght breke &thorn;e arowes whils &thorn;ai ware so bunden togyder.
<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio">At &thorn;e last he said till his &yogh;ungest son, "Son," quod he, "ga and louse &yogh;one arowes, ilkane fra o&thorn;er, and breke
&thorn;am ilkane by &thorn;am self"; and he did as he bad and brakk &thorn;am ilkane after o&thorn;er. And &thorn;an &thorn;e kyng asked his
o&thorn;er sonnez, why &thorn;ai myght no&yogh;t breke &thorn;am; and &thorn;ai answerd agayne &thorn;at, for &thorn;ai ware so fast bunden togyder, &thorn;ai
my&yogh;t no&yogh;t breke &thorn;aim. &THORN;an answerd &thorn;e emperour, "How my&yogh;t &yogh;our &yogh;ungest bro&thorn;er breke &thorn;am so lightly and so
wele?" "For &thorn;ai ware lowsed," quod &thorn;ai, "and twynned ilkane fra o&thorn;er." "Right so," quod &thorn;aire fader,
"will it fare of &yogh;ou. For, als lang as &yogh;e er knytt togyder with &thorn;ir three bandes, &thorn;at es to say, of lufe and lewtee
and of accorde, &thorn;er may na man of &thorn;is werld stryfe ne disese &yogh;ow; bot, alssone as &thorn;e knotte is lowsed of &thorn;ir
bandes, &thorn;at es to say, alssone as &yogh;e er diuised and stryfez ilkane with o&thorn;er, alssone &yogh;e schall be confused and
schent and destruyd. And, if &yogh;e luffe stedfastly togyder, &yogh;e schall be lordes of all naciouns." And, when he
had teched his sonnes on &thorn;is wyse and had ordayned for his empire thurgh &thorn;e counsaile of &thorn;e grete lordes of his
rewme, sone after he dyed. And after him regned Cichota his eldest sonne and was called Chaan, as his fader was.
And his o&thorn;er bre&thorn;er went furth and conquerd many landes and rewmes, euen vnto Pruysse and Russy; and ilkane
of &thorn;am gert call him Chaan. Bot all ware &thorn;ai subiettes to &thorn;e eldest bro&thorn;er; and &thorn;erfore was he called &thorn;e Grete
Chaan, and all his successours after him. After Cichota regned his eldest bro&thorn;er Guys Chaan; and after him
regned Mango Caan, &thorn;e whilk was baptized and worthed till a worthy and a deuote Cristen man and a gude. He
<MILESTONE N="95" UNIT="folio">graunt his lettres of perpetuele peess till all Cristen men for to wonne in his rewme, and sent his bro&thorn;er Halaon

<PB N="113">
with a grete oste for to wynne &thorn;e Haly Land oute of &thorn;e Sarzenes handes in to Cristen mennez handes, and for to
destruy Machomete lawe, and also for to take Calaphes of Baldac, &thorn;at was emperour and lord ower &thorn;e Sarzenes.
Halaon went furth and tuke Calaphes and fand with him grete plentee of tresoure, so grete &thorn;at him tho&yogh;t &thorn;are
schuld no&yogh;t hafe bene mykils mare in all &thorn;e werld as was funn with him.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">men fownden him of so highe worschipe, &thorn;at in alle &thorn;e remenant of &thorn;e world ne myghte a man fynde a more reuerent man, ne highere in worschipe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;an Halaon said vntill him,
"Qwhy," quod he, "wald &thorn;ou no&yogh;t wage men ynew with &thorn;i tresoure for to agaynstand me and defend &thorn;i land?"
And he answerd and said, "I had men ynew of myne awen," quod he. And &thorn;an said Halaon, "&THORN;ou was &thorn;e
Godd of &thorn;e Sarzenes, and Godd hase na mister of mete ne drink
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">it is conuenyent to a god to ete no mete, &thorn;at is mortalle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schall neuer for vs hafe mete
ne drink, bot ete, if &thorn;ou will, &thorn;i precious stanes and &thorn;i tresoure, &thorn;at &thorn;ou gaderd so fast togyder and luffed so
mykill." And &thorn;an he spered him in amanges his tresour withouten mete or drink; and so he died for hunger
and for thrist. He, &thorn;is ilk Halaon, conquerd and wan all &thorn;e Haly Land in to Cristen men handes. In &thorn;e meen
tyme &thorn;e Grete Caan died; and for&thorn;i &thorn;e iournee chaunged efter to &thorn;e werse.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and &thorn;at was gret sorwe and losse to alle cristen men, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> After Mango &thorn;e gude regned
ano&thorn;er &thorn;at hight Chebysa and was called Caan; and he was a gude Cristen man also, and regned xlii. &yogh;ere. He
<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio">foundid a gude citee and a grete in &thorn;e kyngdom of Chatay, &thorn;e whilk es called Iong; and it es mare &thorn;an Rome.
Ano&thorn;er Caan regned after him, and he renayed &thorn;e Cristen lawe and become a Sarzene,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">a payneme, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and all &thorn;e Caanes after
him vnto &thorn;is tyme.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.113.16" CORRESP="Cot.151.27">And wit &yogh;e wele &thorn;at &thorn;e rewme of Chatay es mare &thorn;an any rewme in &thorn;is werld; and so es he &thorn;at es Grete
Caan &thorn;e grettest kyng of all o&thorn;er kynges and ricchest of gold and all maner of tresoure and of grettest astate.
&THORN;e style of his lettres es &thorn;is, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Caan, filius dei excelsi, omnium vniversam terram colencium summus imperator
et dominus dominancium</Q>, &thorn;at es to say "Chaan, Goddes son all myghty, and &thorn;e souerayne emperour of all &thorn;ase
&thorn;at tillez &thorn;e erthe and lord of all lordes." &THORN;e circumscripsioun of his grete seel es &thorn;is, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Deus in celo, Caan super
terram, eius fortitudo. Omnium hominum imperatoris sigillum</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "Godd in heuen, and Caan apon
erthe, his strenth. &THORN;e seel of &thorn;e emperour of all men." And &thorn;e wrytyng aboute his priuee [seel] es &thorn;is, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Dei
fortitudo. Omnium hominum imperatoris sigillum</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "&THORN;e strenth of Godd. Seel of &thorn;e emperoure of
all men." &THORN;is emperour and all &thorn;e folk of his land, &thorn;of &thorn;ai be na Cristen men, neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai trowe in grete Godd,
&thorn;at made heuen and erthe; and, when &thorn;ai will manace any man, &thorn;ai say on &thorn;is wyse, "Godd wate &thorn;at I schall
do &thorn;e ane euill turne."</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.25" N="25" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.26">
<PB N="114">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the gouernance of the Grete Chanes court, and whan he maketh solempne festes; of his philosophres; and of his array, whan he rideth be the contre.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.114.4" CORRESP="Cot.152.7">HERE hafe I talde &yogh;ow why he es called &thorn;e Grete Caan, and now will I tell &yogh;ow of &thorn;e aray and &thorn;e
<MILESTONE N="96" UNIT="folio">gouernaunce of his courte, when he makez grete festez; and &thorn;at es principally at foure tymes in &thorn;e
&yogh;ere. &THORN;e first es at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e Grete Caan was borne; &thorn;e secund es at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he was
presented in to &thorn;aire tempill, &thorn;e whilk es called Moseak, whare he was circumcised; &thorn;e o&thorn;er twa festez er of
&thorn;aire mawmet.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">ydoles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e first of &thorn;am es at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;aire mawmet was first sett in trone in &thorn;aire temple; and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er es at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;aire mawmet began first to speke and giffe answere and to do myracles. O&thorn;er festez
makez no&yogh;t &thorn;e emperour so sollemply, bot if it be at &thorn;e weddinges of his sonnez. At ilkane of &thorn;ir festez es
wonder grete multitude of folk gaderd; and &thorn;ai er all wele arayd and ordaynd by thowsands, hundreths and
vintaynes, and ilkane wate what he schall do and bisily tentez till &thorn;aire officez, &thorn;at &thorn;are be na defawt funn.
First er ordaynd iiii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> riche barouns and myghty, for to hafe &thorn;e gouernaunce and &thorn;e ordinaunce of &thorn;e feste and to
serue &thorn;e emperour. And all &thorn;ir barouns has corouns of gold apon &thorn;aire heuedes wele dight with precious
stanes and perle; and &thorn;ai er cledd in clathez of gold and cammaca and swilk o&thorn;er, and &thorn;ai er als riche as &thorn;ai
may be made.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and alle &thorn;o robes ben orfrayed alle abouten, and dubbed fulle of precious stones and of grete oryent perles, fulle richely, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ai may wele hafe swilk clathes, for &thorn;ai er of lesse prys &thorn;are &thorn;an wollen clathez er here.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">ben gretter chep &thorn;ere a gret del &thorn;an ben clothes of wolle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> [French texts]).</NOTE>
And &thorn;ir festez er made in tentes made of clathes of gold or of tartarene or camaca; and &thorn;ai er so curiousely made
<MILESTONE N="96b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at na man may ymagyn mare curious. &THORN;ir foure thowsand barouns er departed in foure companys; and ilk a
company es cledd in a suyt by &thorn;am self of a colour diuerse fra &thorn;e o&thorn;er companys. &THORN;e first
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">This description is more literally rendered in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> company es of
dukes, erles, markysez and amyrals; and &thorn;ai er cledd in clathez of gold and of silk of grene colour, &thorn;e secund
of reed colour, &thorn;e thrid of blew colour, &thorn;e ferthe of &yogh;alow colour. And &thorn;aire garmentz er all so curiousely and

<PB N="115">
so craftily ebrowded and dight with gold and precious stanez and perle &thorn;at, what man of oure land as had ane
swilk, men my&yogh;t sauely say he ware na pure man; for gold and precious stanes es of mykill gretter prys here &thorn;an
it es &thorn;are.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">And whan &thorn;ei ben &thorn;us apparaylled, &thorn;ei gon, ii. and ii. togedre, fulle ordynatly before the emperour, withouten speche of ony woord, saf only enclynynge to him, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And ilkane of &thorn;ir barouns beres before him a table of iaspre, or of euour, or of cristall; and before
&thorn;aim gase mynstrallez, playand on diuerse instrumentes of music. And, when &thorn;e first thowsand es passed and
hase done &thorn;aire seruys, &thorn;ai draw &thorn;am o syde; and &thorn;an commez &thorn;e secund thowsand, and &thorn;an &thorn;e thridd, and so &thorn;e
ferthe, and duse &thorn;aire seruise as &thorn;e first thowsand didd. And nane of &thorn;am spekez a worde; and &thorn;us &thorn;ai ga
aboute &thorn;e hall.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.115.8" CORRESP="Cot.153.36">At a syde of &thorn;e emperour table sittez many philosophers and grete clerkez of diuerse sciencez, sum of
astronomy, sum of nigromancy, sum of geomancy, sum of pyromancy, sum of ydromancy, and many swilk o&thorn;er
sciencez. And sum has before &thorn;am astrolabres of gold, sum speres
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> spheres; speres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of precious stanes, sum &thorn;e scalpe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">brayn panne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of a deed
man, sum vessell of gold full of hate coles, sum vessell of gold with water and wyne and oile. Sum also has
<MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="folio">orlogez wonder craftily made, sum vessell of gold full of sand, and o&thorn;er of &thorn;am diuerse instrumentes occordand
for &thorn;aire science. And at certayne houres, when &thorn;ai see tyme, &thorn;ai say to men &thorn;at standez before &thorn;am, "Makez
now peesse"; and &thorn;an ane of &thorn;ase men saise to all &thorn;e hall with a lowd voice, "Non. peesse." And &thorn;an saise
ane of &thorn;e philosophers, "Now ilk man do reuerence and howghe him to &thorn;e emperour, whilk es Goddes sonne
and lord of all &thorn;e werld, for now es tyme." And &thorn;an ilk man enclynez his heued toward &thorn;e erthe; and &thorn;an
saise &thorn;e philosopher to &thorn;am, "Liftez vp &yogh;otire heuedes agayne." And at ano&thorn;er houre saise ano&thorn;er philosopher,
"Ilk man putte his lytill fynger in his ere"; and &thorn;ai do so. And at ano&thorn;er houre saise ano&thorn;er philosopher,
"Ilke man lay his hand before his mouth"; and &thorn;ai do so. And sone after ano&thorn;er philosopher biddes ilk man
lay his hand apon his heued; and &thorn;ai do so. And &thorn;us ilk houre &thorn;ir philosopheres biddez diuerse thinges; and
&thorn;ai say &thorn;ase thinges hase grete betaknyngs.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">han dyuerse significaciouns, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And I ast priuely what &thorn;ise thinges myght bemene; and ane of
&thorn;e philosophers said &thorn;at &thorn;e enclynyng of &thorn;e heued &thorn;at tyme betaknez &thorn;at all &thorn;ase &thorn;at louted &thorn;an schall be
obedient and trew to &thorn;e emperour, so &thorn;at for na giftez ne for na hetyng &thorn;ai schall neuer be fals ne traytours to
him. And puttyng of &thorn;e fynger in &thorn;e ere bemenez &thorn;at nane of &thorn;ase schall here ill be spoken of &thorn;e emperour,
now&thorn;er of fader ne bro&thorn;er, sibbe ne fremmed, &thorn;at ne he schall schew it to &thorn;e emperoure, or to his counsail. &THORN;e
<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio">laying of &thorn;e hand before his mouth bemenez &thorn;at nane of &thorn;am sall speke euill of &thorn;e emperour. And on &thorn;e same
wyse of all the o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;at &thorn;ai bidd do, &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe grete betakenyng. And &yogh;e schall ynderstand &thorn;at

<PB N="116">
men dyghtez ne makez na thing to &thorn;e emperour, &thorn;at es to say now&thorn;er clathez, mete, ne drink, ne nane o&thorn;er thing,
bot at certayne tyme when &thorn;e philosophers tellez, &thorn;e whilk thurgh &thorn;aire science and calculacioun aspiez and
considerez certayne houres couable for to do swilk thingez. And, if any man begynne were agayne &thorn;e emperour
in any cuntree, alssone &thorn;e philosophers knawez it and tellez &thorn;e emperour and his counsaile, and he sendez his
oste &thorn;ider to restreyne &thorn;e malice of his enmys.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.116.6" CORRESP="Cot.155.14">Qwhen &thorn;e philosophers hase bidden all thinges &thorn;at langes to &thorn;am for to hidd, &thorn;an &thorn;e mynstrallez begynnez to
do &thorn;aire melodys agayn, ilkane after o&thorn;er. And, when &thorn;ai hafe done &thorn;aire mynstralcy a grete while, &thorn;an ane of
&thorn;e emperoures officers gase vp apon a stage, richely made and curiously, and criez with a lowde voiee, "Peesse,"
and &thorn;an er all men still. And &thorn;an all &thorn;ase &thorn;at er of &thorn;e emperour kynne gase and araiez &thorn;am wele and richely in
clathez of gold, and ilkane of &thorn;am commez with many whyte hors wele araied and richely on &thorn;e best maner &thorn;at
&thorn;ai may. And &thorn;an saise &thorn;e steward of &thorn;e courte &thorn;at lord and &thorn;at lorde, and neuens &thorn;aire names, "Comme and
<MILESTONE N="98" UNIT="folio">do reuerence to &thorn;e emperour of all &thorn;e werld." And &thorn;us he neuens &thorn;am all on rawe, ilkane in &thorn;aire degree;
and &thorn;an commez ilkane of &thorn;am after oper before &thorn;e emperoure and presendez him whyte horsez in &thorn;e noumer of
nyne.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">presenten the white hors to the emperour and &thorn;an gon hire wey, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And efter &thorn;aim commez grete barounes and presandez him with sum iowell or sum o&thorn;er riche gyft, ilk
ane after his degree aschez.
<NOTE RESP="DR" N="2">Warner's note here reads: "So MS., with doubtful sense; after &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben of estate, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>." Yet in his Glossary (p. xlv), evidently prepared later, he renders <HI REND="i">aschez</HI> as "requires," and the phrase <HI REND="i">after his degree aschez</HI> as "according to his rank." He also includes a footnote (p. xlv) explaining, "In the note to p. 116, l. 10 [commentary], I have inexcusably taken this word to mean 'ashes'." See MED <HI REND="b">asken</HI> v., 6: "Of things: to require as appropriate or necessary; require, demand, call for."</NOTE> And, when &thorn;ai hafe all on &thorn;is wyse made &thorn;aire presandez to &thorn;e emperoure, &thorn;an
makez prelatez of &thorn;aire lawe &thorn;aire presandez. And efterwardes &thorn;e cheeffe prelate giffez a grete benysoun,
sayand ane orisoun of &thorn;aire lawe. And &thorn;an begynnez &thorn;e mynstralles &thorn;aire melody agayne. And, when &thorn;ai hafe
made mynstralcy a whyle, &thorn;ai er bidden be still, and &thorn;an men bringez before &thorn;e emperour lyouns, lebardes and
o&thorn;er maner of bestez and briddez and fischez and nedders, for to do wirschepe to &thorn;e emperoure; for &thorn;ai say all
thing &thorn;at has lyf schall do wirschepe to &thorn;e emperour and be obedient to him. And &thorn;an commez iugillours and
enchantours and dose many meruailes; for &thorn;ai make to comme in &thorn;e aere as it semez &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e mone to do
him reuerence, whilk schynes so bright &thorn;at men may no&yogh;t behald &thorn;am. And seyne &thorn;ai make so grete myrknes
&thorn;at it semez nyght; and efterwardes &thorn;ai make &thorn;e light to appere agayne. And &thorn;an &thorn;ai make damysels to comme
in carolland, as men thinkes &thorn;at seez. Seyne &thorn;ai make o&thorn;er damysels to comme in, bringand cowpez of gold full
of meere
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> mare's; mylk of dyuerse bestes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> mylk, and proffers lordes and ladys to drink off. And after &thorn;is &thorn;ai make knyghtes to iust in &thorn;e aere wele

<PB N="117">
<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio">armed; and &thorn;ai smyte so sammen with &thorn;aire speres &thorn;at &thorn;e trunschouns of &thorn;am flyes aboute all &thorn;e tablez in hall.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and &thorn;ei rennen togidre a gret raundoun, and &thorn;ei frusschen togidere fulle fiercely, and &thorn;ei breken here speres so rudely &thorn;at the tronchouns flen in sprotes and peces alle aboute &thorn;e halle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And, when &thorn;is es done, &thorn;ai make hertez and wylde bares comme and hundez persuand &thorn;am. &THORN;ise and many
o&thorn;er meruailes &thorn;ai do, ay to &thorn;e emperour hafe eten.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.117.4" CORRESP="Cot.156.32">&THORN;s emperour, &thorn;at es called &thorn;e Grete Caan, hase many men kepand
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">kepand, erased.</NOTE> in his courte, as I said before, and
mynstralles to &thorn;e nowmer of xiii. comacies. I talde &yogh;ow before how mykill a comacye contenez. Bot &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at all &thorn;ir mynstrallez dwellez no&yogh;t continuelly in the emperours courte, bot what mynstrall so
commez before him, of what nacioun so euer he be, he es ressayued in his courte and his name writen. And
&thorn;erfore, whare so euer he go fra &thorn;at tyme furward, he claymez him self for ane of his mynstralles, and &thorn;erfore es
&thorn;are sa grete nowmer of &thorn;am. He hase also xv. comaciez of men ordaynd for no&yogh;t elles bot for to kepe fewles
of diuerse kyndes, as gerfawcouns, gentill fawcouns, laneres, sagres, sperhawkes, nyghtgales syngand, and papeiays
spekand. He hase also a thowsand olyfauntes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and also of wylke bestes, as of olifauntz, tame and othere, babewynes, apes, marmesettes, and o&thorn;ere dyuerse bestes, the mountance of xv. cumancz of &yogh;omen, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And he <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">hase</SUPPLIED>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">hase, om. MS., with "haues" interlined later.</NOTE> many phisiciones, of whilk cc. er Cristen men,
and xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> Sarzenes; bot he traistez maste in Cristen men.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">And of phisicyens Cristene he hath cc.; and of leches &thorn;at ben Cristene he hath cc. and x., and of leches and phisicyens &thorn;at ben Sarrazines xx., but he trusteth more in the Cristene leches &thorn;an in the Sarazines, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;are er also in his courte many barouns and o&thorn;er
officers &thorn;at er cristend and conuerted to Cristen faith thurgh preching of gude Cristen men &thorn;at dwellez &thorn;are;
bot &thorn;er er many &thorn;at will no&yogh;t be aknawen, ne late men wit &thorn;at &thorn;ai er Cristen men.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.117.15" CORRESP="Cot.157.24">&THORN;is emperour may dispend als mykill as him list spend, for he makez na monee bot ow&thorn;er of lether, or of
papire, or of barkez of treesse.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">or of barkez of treesse, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, when &thorn;is monee es waxen alde, and &thorn;e prynte &thorn;eroff defaced by cause of
vsyng, it es bro&yogh;t to &thorn;e kynges tresoury, and his tresourer giffez new for alde. &THORN;is monee es prynted on bathe
&thorn;e sydes, as monee es of o&thorn;er cuntreez, and it <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">gase</SUPPLIED>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">gase, om. MS., with "gos" interlined later.</NOTE> thurgh all &thorn;e Grete Caan landes. For &thorn;ai make na monee
&thorn;are of gold ne siluer, when it es broght &thorn;ider fra o&thorn;er landes by diuerse naciouns, bot &thorn;e emperour gers
enourae his palace &thorn;erwith and gers make &thorn;eroff o&thorn;er necessaries at his awen list. In his chaumbre on a piler
of gold es a ruby and a charbuncle, ayther of a fote lang
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">of half a fote long, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;is charbunele lightnez all &thorn;e chaumbre on &thorn;e
nyght. He hase also many o&thorn;er precious stanes and rubies in his chaumbre; bot &thorn;ir twa er &thorn;e grettest and
maste precious of all o&thorn;er.</SEG></P>

<PB N="118">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.118.1" CORRESP="Cot.158.7">&THORN;e Grete Caan dwellez in somer in a citee toward &thorn;e north, &thorn;at es called Saduz, whare &thorn;e aer es ri&yogh;t calde;
and in wynter he dwellez in &thorn;e citee of Camalach, whare &thorn;e aer es ri&yogh;t hate. Bot &thorn;e place whare he es
comounly dwelland es at Gaydoun,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Gaydo or in Iong, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> whare &thorn;e aer es atemperee after &thorn;e qualitee of &thorn;at cuntree. Neuer&thorn;eles til
men of &thorn;is cuntree it ware ouer hate. And, when &thorn;is Grete Caan schall ryde fra a cuntree to ano&thorn;er, &thorn;are er
ordaynd foure ostez for him, ri&yogh;t grete of folk, of whilk ane oste wendez before him a day iournee. And &thorn;is oste
liggez ilke ane nyght whare &thorn;e emperour schall ligg on &thorn;e morue; and &thorn;are er all things fun redy puruayd &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;am nedez. In &thorn;at oste er fyfty comacy of men, what of hors men, what of fote men; and ilke a comacy
contenez x<HI REND="sup">m</HI>, as I talde &yogh;ow before. Ano&thorn;er oste es on his ri&yogh;t syde, as it ware half a day iournee fra him, and
&thorn;e thridd on his left syde als ferre fra him. And &thorn;e ferthe commez bebind him, as it ware ane arow draght;
and in &thorn;at oste er ma men &thorn;an in &thorn;e o&thorn;er three. Ilkane of &thorn;ir ostez hase &thorn;aire iourneez limited; and &thorn;are &thorn;er
&thorn;ai. schall luge ilk a nyght, &thorn;ai schall fynd before &thorn;am redily puruayd all maner of thinges &thorn;at er necessary to &thorn;am.
And, if it hapne &thorn;at any man of &thorn;ir ostea dye by &thorn;e way, alssone &thorn;ai putte ano&thorn;er in his steed, &thorn;at &thorn;e forsaid
noumer be all way keped hale.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.118.14" CORRESP="Cot.158.35">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e Grete Caan rydez neuernare apon a hors, bot if he ryde till any place with
a priuee mene&yogh;ee. Bot be rydez in a chariot with foure whelez; and &thorn;erapon es a chaumbre made of a tree &thorn;at
men callez <FOREIGN LANG="lat">lignum aloes</FOREIGN>, &thorn;e whilk commez oute of Paradys terrestre at certayne tymes with fludes &thorn;at rynnez
oute of Paradys. And by cause of &thorn;e kynde of tree &thorn;at it es made off &thorn;is chaumbre es of noble smell; and it es
couerd all ouer within with plates of gold sett full of precious stanes. And foure olyfauntes and foure whyte
stedez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">grete destreres alle white, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> trapped with riche clathez drawez &thorn;is chariot. And fyfe or sex grete lordes in riche apparaile rydez
aboute &thorn;e chariot, so &thorn;at na man schall come nere him bot lordes, o less &thorn;an be call any man till him. And
<MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="folio">abouen on &thorn;at chaumbre in a lytill caban sittez men with foure or fyue gerfawcouns,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">ben sett vpon a perche iiii. or v. or vi. gerfacouns, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at, if &thorn;ai fynd any wilde
fewle by &thorn;e way as &thorn;ai ryde, &thorn;ai may late &thorn;am flie for to make &thorn;e emperoure gammen. And before &thorn;is chariot
rsydez na man nere it by a bowe schote, bot &thorn;ir forsaid lordes. And on &thorn;e same aray of chariotes and of men er
&thorn;e empericez ledd thurgh &thorn;e cuntree, ilkane of &thorn;am by &thorn;am self; bot &thorn;ai haue nower nere so many men in &thorn;aire
hostez as &thorn;e emperoure hase. Also &thorn;e eldest sonne of &thorn;e emperour rydez by ano&thorn;er way in his chariot on &thorn;e

<PB N="119">
same aray, with a grete multitude of folk. For &thorn;are es so mykill peple in &thorn;at land &thorn;at it es wonder to see.
Sum tyme it fallez, when &thorn;ai wende no&yogh;t ferre, &thorn;at &thorn;e empericez and &thorn;e em erours childer wendez togyder in a
company, and &thorn;aire men menged owerheued; neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ai er departid in foure ostez, as I said before.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.119.4" CORRESP="Cot.160.1">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e land of &thorn;e Grete Caan es diuided in xii. prouincez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> has here the sentence "ilkane &hellip; withouten nowmer" (below, l. 26) and otherwise follows the French text.</NOTE>;</SEG> and <SEG ID="Eg.119.4b" CORRESP="Cot.160.4">in ilk a prouince
es a kyng reall. And &thorn;ase kynges hase o&thorn;er smaler kynges vnder &thorn;aim, and all &thorn;ase kynges er subiectes to &thorn;e
Grete Caan, whas empire es so large &thorn;at a man wende &thorn;e vmgang &thorn;eroff by water and by land in vii. &yogh;ere. For
&thorn;er many grete desertes thurgh whilk men most nedez passe, in &thorn;e whilk men schall fynd now&thorn;er citee ne
towne. Bot &thorn;er er in certaynez placez comoun ostriez ordaynd, whare trauaillyng men may fynd all thinges &thorn;at
er nedefull to &thorn;am in &thorn;aire iournee. And &thorn;er es a wondefull custom in &thorn;at land, bot it es ri&yogh;t profitable. For,
<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio">when any tythings er herd in &thorn;e cuntree, and namely &thorn;at er noyouse or any thing agaynes &thorn;e emperour, he schall
hafe worde within a day and a nyght, if all it be ferre &thorn;eine, &thorn;a three day iourneez or foure. For he has all way
embassatours and messangers in ilk a prouince aboute him, &thorn;e whilk, alssone as any rumour begynnez to ryse
&thorn;at touchez &thorn;e emperour, &thorn;ai take dromedarys or o&thorn;er horsez &thorn;at &thorn;ai can gett and in all &thorn;e haste &thorn;at &thorn;ai may &thorn;ai
prike till ane of &thorn;ir forsaid ostriez. And when &thorn;ai comme nere it, &thorn;ai blawe in a horne, and &thorn;e messangers &thorn;at
er &thorn;are when &thorn;ai here &thorn;e horne, knawez wele &thorn;at &thorn;er es sum tythings to bere to &thorn;e emperour and makez redy
&thorn;aire dromedaries or &thorn;aire horsez for to bere &thorn;e lettres with &thorn;e tythings furth till ano&thorn;er ostrie. And &thorn;are do
&thorn;ai on &thorn;e same wyse, and &thorn;us &thorn;ai do fra ostrie to ostrie till &thorn;ai comme at &thorn;e emperour; and on &thorn;is wise hase &thorn;e
emperour within a schort while all &thorn;e tythings &thorn;at er in any cuntree aboute him. And on &thorn;e same wyse es it of
&thorn;e emperour curroures, when &thorn;er es any hasty tythings for to make. For ilke a curroure hase a lang corde full
of belles, when he commez with &thorn;e emperouse lettres nere any of &thorn;ir forsaid ostriez, by &thorn;e ringyng of &thorn;e
belles &thorn;e currour &thorn;at es ordaynd for to be &thorn;are knawez wele &thorn;at &thorn;are commez lettres for to be borne hastily to
&thorn;e emperour and he makez redy for to ga. And, when &thorn;e to&thorn;er commez, he delyuers &thorn;is currour &thorn;e lettres, and
him self restez him &thorn;are, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er rynnez furth in all &thorn;e haste he may till &thorn;e thridd ostrie and restez him &thorn;are,
as &thorn;e to&thorn;er didd; and &thorn;us &thorn;ai do do fra ostrie to ostrie to &thorn;ai comme at &thorn;e emperour. &THORN;ir curroures er called in
&thorn;aire langage Chidibo, &thorn;at es als mykill at say in &thorn;aire langage as messangere.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.119.26" CORRESP="Cot.160.3">Ilkane of &thorn;ir forsaid twelfe prouincez hase &thorn;erin twa thowsand citeez and ma, and townes withouten
nowmer.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.119.27" CORRESP="Cot.161.8">Also, when &thorn;is emperour rydez thurgh any citee or toune, ilke man makez a fyre before his dore
whare &thorn;e emperour schall comme, and &thorn;ai caste &thorn;erin encense or o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;at may giffe gude smell to &thorn;e
emperour. And, if Cristen men of religioun dwell nere whare he schall passe, as &thorn;ai do in many citeez in &thorn;at

<PB N="120">
land, &thorn;ai go agayn him with procession with crosse and haly water, syngand with a hye voice, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Veni, Creator
spiritus</Q>. And, when he seez &thorn;am comme, he commaundez &thorn;e lordes &thorn;at rydez nere him to make way &thorn;at &thorn;a
men of religioun may comme to him. And, alssone as he seez &thorn;e crosse, he doffez his hatte,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">his galaoth, &thorn;at sitte syt vpon his hede, in manere of a chapelet, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. [DR: "sitte" should be omitted.]</NOTE> whilke es made
full richely with perlez and precious stanes, and &thorn;ai say &thorn;are &thorn;at &thorn;at hat es worthe a kyngdom. And &thorn;an he
lowtez deuotely to &thorn;e crosse; and &thorn;e prelate of &thorn;ase religious men saise twa orisouns before him and giffez him
benysoun with &thorn;e crosse, and be lowtes to &thorn;e benisoun full deuotely. And &thorn;an &thorn;at same prelate giffez him sum
maner of fruyt, as appels or peres or swilk o&thorn;er, to &thorn;e nowmer of nyne on a plate of gold. For the maner es
swilk &thorn;are &thorn;at na straunge man schall comme before &thorn;e emperour bot if he giffe him sum thing, after &thorn;e alde
lawe &thorn;at saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Nemo apparebit in conspectu meo vacuus</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">Non apparebis, etc.</HI>, Exod. xxiii. 15.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Na man comme in my sight tome hand."
And &thorn;an ga &thorn;ai hame agayne to &thorn;aire place.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and &thorn;anne the Emperour seyth to the religious men, &thorn;at &thorn;ei withdrawe hem a&yogh;en, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne be not hurt ne harmed of the gret multytude of hors &thorn;at comen behynde him, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And on &thorn;is same maner dose men of religioun &thorn;at dwelles whare &thorn;e
emperice asid &thorn;e emperour eldest sonne commes.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.120.12" CORRESP="Cot.162.4">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at all &thorn;ir men &thorn;at er in &thorn;e forsaid ostez of &thorn;e Grete Caan, of his wyfes and of his
eldest sonne er no&yogh;t all way dwelland in his courte; bot, ay when &thorn;ai er bidden go with him, &thorn;ai er redy at his
comaundement, and, when &thorn;e iournee es done, &thorn;ai wende hame agayne to &thorn;aire awen howsez, all safe &thorn;a &thorn;at er
of &thorn;e emperour courte, and &thorn;at es a grete nowmer, &thorn;e whilk er ordaynd for to serue &thorn;e emperour and his wyfez
and his childer, and for gouernaunce of &thorn;e courte. For &thorn;are er contynuelly with him in his courte l. thowsand
men at hors and cc. thowsand fote men, withouten diuerse ministres
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">mynstrelles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e palace and withouten &thorn;ase also &thorn;at er
ordaynd for to kepe certayne wylde bestez and fewles of diuerse kyndez, whilk I spakk of before.</SEG> <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW" SOURCE="Cot">Vndre
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">This passage, omitted in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>, is given from <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
the firmament is not so gret a lord, ne so mighty, ne so riche, as is the Grete Chane; nought Prestre Iohan,
&thorn;at is emperour of the highe Ynde, ne the sowdan of Babyloyne, ne the emperour of Persye. Alle &thorn;eise ne
ben not in comparisoun to the Grete Chane, nou&thorn;er of myght ne of noblesse, ne of ryaltee, ne of ricehesse
for in alle &thorn;eise he passeth alle erthely princes. Wherfore it is gret harm &thorn;at he beleueth not feithfully in God.
And natheles he wil gladly here speke of God, and he suffreth wel &thorn;at Cristene men dwelle in his lordschipe and
&thorn;at men of his feith ben made Cristene men, &yogh;if &thorn;ai wile, &thorn;urgh out alle his contree; for he defendeth no man to
bolde no lawe other &thorn;an him lyketh.</SUPPLIED></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.120.26" CORRESP="Cot.162.29">In &thorn;e land of &thorn;e Grete Caan has ilk man als many wyfes as him list, for sum hase c., sum xl., sum ma, sum
less. And &thorn;ai wedd &thorn;are &thorn;aire sibbe wymmen, all safe moders and doghters and sisters; half sisters of &thorn;er fader
syde wedd &thorn;ai, bot no&yogh;t of &thorn;er moder syde. Also &thorn;ai wedd &thorn;e wyfez of &thorn;aire bre&thorn;er, when &thorn;ai er deed, and
&thorn;aire stepdames efter &thorn;e deed of &thorn;aire faders.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.26" N="26" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.27">
<PB N="121">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXVI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the lawe and the customs of the Tartarienes duellynge in Chatay; and how that men don, whan the Emperour schal dye; and how he schal be chosen.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.121.4" CORRESP="Cot.163.1">THAI vse wyde garments in &thorn;ase parties withouten pelure
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">furroures, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;ai er of purpure or of tartarene or
chamelet.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and &thorn;ei ben clothed with precious clothes of Tartarye and of clothes of gold, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ai er open at &thorn;e sydes and laced togyder with lacez of silke. And sum vsez
garmentz of pelour,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">pylches, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;e bare turned outeward; budes vsez &thorn;am nane. And on &thorn;is same maner er
wymmen of &thorn;at cuntree cledd, so &thorn;at vnnethes may men knawe &thorn;e tane forby to&thorn;er, outaken &thorn;at wymmen &thorn;at er
<MILESTONE N="102" UNIT="folio">wedded beres takyns on &thorn;aire heueds, as I talde &yogh;ow before. &THORN;iare wyfez dwellez no&yogh;t togyder, bot ilkane of
&thorn;am by &thorn;am self; and &thorn;aire hushandes gase now till ane of &thorn;am now till ano&thorn;er, as him list. &THORN;aire housez er
made of stikkes, aad &thorn;ai er rounde and hase bot a wyndowe, whare at &thorn;e light commez in and &thorn;e reke gase oute
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and also &thorn;at serueth for delyuerance of smoke, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>;
and &thorn;e thakk of &thorn;am and &thorn;e walles er of filtre, and &thorn;e dores also.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">and the helynge of here houses and the wowes and dores ben alle of wode, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And, when &thorn;ai ga to &thorn;e were, &thorn;ai cary &thorn;aire
housez with &thorn;am apon cartes, as men in o&thorn;er cuntreez duse tentes and pafeliouns. And &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire fyre in
myddes of &thorn;ir housez. &THORN;ai hafe grete plentee of all maner of bestes, oute taken of swyne; and &thorn;at es for &thorn;ai
brede nane.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">bryngen non forth, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;ai trowe all in a Godd, &thorn;at made all thing; bot neuer&thorn;eles &yogh;it hafe &thorn;ai mawmets of gold and of
siluer, of filtre and of clathe, to &thorn;e whilke &thorn;ai offer &thorn;e first mylke of &thorn;aire bestez and &thorn;e first of &thorn;aire mete and
&thorn;aire drink before &thorn;ai ete or drink any &thorn;eroff. And sum tyme &thorn;ai offer to &thorn;am horsez and o&thorn;er diuerse bestez.
Godd of kynde call &thorn;ai Yroga; and, what name so euer &thorn;e emperour hase, &thorn;ai eke &thorn;erto Caan. &THORN;at tyme &thorn;at I
was &thorn;are &thorn;e emperour name was Thyak, and &thorn;ai called him Thyak Caan. And his eldest sonne hight Theophue,
and, when be schal be made emperour, he schal be called Theophue Caan. &THORN;e emperour had &thorn;at tyme o&thorn;er
twelfe sonnes withouten Theophue, of whilk ane hight Cunnyt, ano&thorn;er Ordu, &thorn;e thridd Chahadoy, &thorn;e ferthe
Burgu, &thorn;e fyft Vengu, &thorn;e sext Nachaly, &thorn;e seuent Cadu, &thorn;e viii. Syban, &thorn;e ix. Creten, &thorn;e x. Balac, &thorn;e xi. Babilan,

<PB N="122">
<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio">and &thorn;e xii. Carygan. And he had three wyfes, of whilk &thorn;e first and &thorn;e principall was Prestre Iohn doghter, and
scho was called Serioth Caan; &thorn;e secund hight Borach Caan, and &thorn;e thridd Charauk Caan.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.122.3" CORRESP="Cot.164.9">&THORN;e men of &thorn;at cuntree begynnez all &thorn;at &thorn;ai do in &thorn;e newe mone, and wirschepez it mykill; and &thorn;ai do grete
wirschepe also to &thorn;e sonne, and mase many knelinges &thorn;erto. And &thorn;ai ryde comounly withouten spurres; bot &thorn;ai
hase ow&thorn;er in &thorn;aire hand a whippe or a wand or sum o&thorn;er thing for to cacche
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">chacen with, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;aire horsez with. &THORN;ai hald it a
grete synne to putte a knyffe in &thorn;e fire, or to take oute flessch of a potte or a caldron with a knyffe, or to smyte
a hors with a brydle, or to breek a bane with ano&thorn;er, or to cast mylke or any o&thorn;er liquor &thorn;at men may drynke
apon &thorn;e erthe.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">or for to take and sle lytil children, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;e maste synne &thorn;at man may do, &thorn;ai say, es to pisse in &thorn;aire housez whare &thorn;ai dwell. And
he &thorn;at pissez &thorn;are and &thorn;ai may wit it, &thorn;ai will slae him; and &thorn;at place &thorn;at a man has pissed in bose be halowed
or elles dare na man entre in to it. And of &thorn;ir s&yogh;nnes bus &thorn;am schryfe &thorn;am to &thorn;e prestes of &thorn;ire lawe; and,
when &thorn;ai er schrifen, &thorn;ai giffe a grete sonme of monee for to bye oute &thorn;aire penaunce withall. And, when &thorn;ai
hafe &thorn;us boght &thorn;aire penaunce, &thorn;ai schall passe thurgh a fyre to make &thorn;am clene of &thorn;aire synnes. And on &thorn;e
same maner a messanger, when be bringez a presand to &thorn;e emperour, he schall passe thurgh a fyre with &thorn;e
presand &thorn;at he bringez for to make it clene, so &thorn;at he bring na venym ne o&thorn;er thing for to grefe &thorn;e emperour.
What man amanges &thorn;aim &thorn;at es taken in avowtry, or womman ow&thorn;er, &thorn;ai slayne, and all
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and who &thorn;at steieth ony thing, anon &thorn;ei sle him, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> thefez and robbours &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="103" UNIT="folio">er taynted &thorn;eroff. All &thorn;e men and &thorn;e wymmen of &thorn;at land er gude archers; and als gude werrayours er &thorn;e
wymmen as &thorn;e men, and als fast will &thorn;ai rynne. And &thorn;ai do all maner of craftez, &thorn;at es to say talyour craft and
sowter craft and swilk o&thorn;er. Bot namely &thorn;ai vse to dryue &thorn;e ploghe and &thorn;e cart and &thorn;e wayne; and &thorn;ai er
wri&yogh;tes, als wele as men, and makes housez and all o&thorn;er necessaries, out takne howes and arowes and o&thorn;er
wapnez, &thorn;e whilke men all anely makez. Wymmen &thorn;are vsez breke, als wele as men. All &thorn;e folk of &thorn;at land
er wonder obedient to &thorn;aire soueraynes, and &thorn;ai feight neuermare amanges &thorn;am self; ne &thorn;ai er na thefez ne na
robbours, bot ilke ane of &thorn;am lufez o&thorn;er and wirschepez o&thorn;er. &THORN;ai vse no&yogh;t comounly to do reuerence ne
wirschepe to straunge men, if all &thorn;ai be men of grete astate. &THORN;ai ete hundes and lyouns, meres and foolez, mys
and ratouns, and all o&thorn;er bestez grete and smale, oute takne swyne and bestez &thorn;at ware forbedd in &thorn;e alde lawe.
And &thorn;ai ete all &thorn;at commez of &thorn;e beste, safe &thorn;e dung. And &thorn;ai ete ri&yogh;t lytill breed, bot if it be in lordez courtes.

<PB N="123">
And in many placez &thorn;ai hafe now&thorn;er peise ne wortes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">nou&thorn;er pssen ne benes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> ne o&thorn;er maner of potagez; bot in for &thorn;aire potage &thorn;ai vse
broth and sothen flesch. For &thorn;ai ete nerehand nane o&thorn;er mete bot flesch and &thorn;e broth &thorn;eroff. And, when &thorn;ai
hafe eten, &thorn;ai wype &thorn;aire hend on &thorn;aire clathez vnhonestly; for &thorn;ai vse now&thorn;er burde clath ne sawnape,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">non naperye, ne towaylles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> bot anely
in lordez howsez. And also, when &thorn;ai hafe eten, &thorn;ai putte &thorn;aire dischez and &thorn;aire dublers agayne vnwesched in
&thorn;e pottez or &thorn;e caldrouns with &thorn;e flesch &thorn;at &thorn;ai lefe, ay till <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;ai</SUPPLIED> will ete eftsones. And riche men drinkez mylk
<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio">of meeres and of camels and assez and o&thorn;er bestez; and of &thorn;at mylke will &thorn;ai be ri&yogh;t drunken. &THORN;ai hafe also
ano&thorn;er maner of drinke made of water and hony; for in &thorn;at cuntree es na wyne, and namely amanges comouns,
for &thorn;ai lede bot a wreched lyf. &THORN;ai ete bot anes on &thorn;e day, and at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ai ete ri&yogh;t litill. For a man of &thorn;is
cuntree etez mare on a day &thorn;an twa of &thorn;aim on three days. And, if a messanger comme oute of a straunge
cuntree vnto &thorn;e emperour, be schall hafe na mete &thorn;are bot anes on &thorn;e day and ri&yogh;t lytill &thorn;at anes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.123.11" CORRESP="Cot.166.3">Qwhen &thorn;ai ga to were, &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;am ri&yogh;t warly and wysely, and duse all &thorn;e bisynes &thorn;at &thorn;ai may to conquere
and wynne and ouercomme &thorn;aire enmys. And ilke ane of &thorn;ame beres with him twa bowes or three, and many
arowes and a grete ax. And &thorn;e gentils hase schorte swerdez scharpe on ta syde; and &thorn;ai hafe platez made of
coerbuille
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">quyrboylle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and helmes of &thorn;e same on &thorn;aire heuedes and trappour to &thorn;aire hors. And he &thorn;at fleez in bataile, &thorn;ai
slee him. When &thorn;ai ensege a castell or a walled toune, &thorn;ai behete &thorn;aim &thorn;at er enseged so faire proffers &thorn;at it es
wonder; for &thorn;ai will graunt &thorn;am what sum euer &thorn;ai asch. Bot, als sone as &thorn;ai hafe &yogh;olden &thorn;am, &thorn;ai slae &thorn;am and
cuttez off &thorn;aire eres and layes &thorn;am in vynegre for to sowce and makez of &thorn;aim a dayntee meet for grete lordes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and sowcen hem in vynegre, and &thorn;ereof &thorn;ei maken gret seruyse for lordes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And it es &thorn;aire entent and &thorn;aire purpose
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Alle here lust and alle here ymaginacioun is, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> to bring all landes in &thorn;aire subieccioun. For &thorn;ai say &thorn;aire prophecy
tellez &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;ai schall be ouercommen with schotte of archers, and &thorn;at &thorn;ase men sall turne &thorn;am to &thorn;aire
lawe. Bot &thorn;ai wate no&yogh;t what men &thorn;ai schall be, and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai suffer all maner of nacions dwell amanges &thorn;am
<MILESTONE N="104" UNIT="folio">and men of all maner of lawes and sectez withouten any lettyng. &THORN;is folk, when &thorn;ai will make &thorn;aire ydoles or &thorn;e
ymage of any of &thorn;aire frendez for to hafe &thorn;am in mynde euermare, &thorn;ai make &thorn;am naked; for &thorn;ai say &thorn;at trew lufe
hase na couering, ne &thorn;are schuld na man luffe a creature for &thorn;e bewtee withouten, bot all anely for affeccioun of
&thorn;e persoun and for &thorn;e gude vertuz &thorn;at &thorn;e body es enourned with of kynde.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">of nature, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> It es grete peril to pursue &thorn;e
Tartarenes, when &thorn;ai flee oute of bataill; for &thorn;ai will schote behind &thorn;am fleand and slae men als wele as before

<PB N="124">
&thorn;am. When &thorn;ai schall feight, &thorn;ai hald &thorn;am so nere togyder and so thrang
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">wille schokken hem togidre in a plomp, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at, whare &thorn;er er xx<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men, sum men
wald suppose &thorn;er ware no&yogh;t x<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. &THORN;ai conquere o&thorn;er landes wele and mannfully, bot, <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">when</SUPPLIED> &thorn;ai hafe conquered
&thorn;am, &thorn;ai kepe &thorn;am no&yogh;t wele. &THORN;ai lufe better to ligg in &thorn;e felde in tentez &thorn;an ow&thorn;er <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">in</SUPPLIED> tounes or in castelles.
&THORN;ai commend bot lytill any men witte bot &thorn;aire awen. Amanges &thorn;aim es oile of
<NOTE N="2">de, MS</NOTE> olyfe of grete valu, for &thorn;ai say
it es soueraynly medecinale. All &thorn;e Tartarenes hase smale eghen and lytill berdes and thynne.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">not thikke hered, but schiere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ai er
cumounly fals, for &thorn;ai hald na thing &thorn;at &thorn;ai hete. &THORN;ai may wele suffere penaunce and discese and hardness of
trauaile, forby all o&thorn;er folk; for &thorn;ai lered it at hame in &thorn;er awen cuntree, whare &thorn;ai liffe with grete wricchedness
and scantness.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.124.9" CORRESP="Cot.167.14">Qwen any of &thorn;am schall dye, &thorn;ai stikke a spere by him in &thorn;e erthe; and, when he drawez nere to &thorn;e deed,
<MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio">ilke man fleez oute of &thorn;e hous ay till he be deed; and, when he es deed, &thorn;ai bere him in to &thorn;e felde and puttez
him in &thorn;e erthe. And, when &thorn;e emperour es deed, &thorn;ai sett him in a chaier in &thorn;e middes of his tent; and &thorn;ai
sette before him a table couerd with a clathe, and &thorn;ai sette &thorn;er apon breed and flesch and o&thorn;er metez and a
coupe full of mere mylke. And &thorn;ai sette by him a mere with hir foole and a hors sadled and brydled; and &thorn;ai
lay apon &thorn;e hors als mykill gold and siluer as he may bere.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and &thorn;ei putten abouten him gret plentee of stree, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And be syde &thorn;is tente &thorn;ai make a grete grafe, and
puttez &thorn;erin &thorn;e tent with &thorn;e emperour and all &thorn;e o&thorn;er thinges and grauez &thorn;am togyder. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at, when
he commez to &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld, he schall no&yogh;t be withouten a hous, hors, gold ne siluer; and &thorn;e meere, &thorn;ai say,
schall giffe him mylke for to drink and bring him furth many horsez, so &thorn;at he be wele stored in &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld
of all thing &thorn;at him nedez. For &thorn;ai trowe &thorn;at, when &thorn;ai er deed, &thorn;ai schall in ano&thorn;er werld ete and drinke and
hafe dalyaunce with wymmen, as &thorn;ai hafe here. And fra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour be layd in &thorn;e erthe na man
schall be so hardy to speke of him in presence of any of his frendez.</SEG> <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW" SOURCE="Cot">And &yogh;it
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">And &yogh;it &hellip; was here, from <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>; omitted in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>.</NOTE> natheles somtyme falleth of
manye &thorn;at thei maken hem to ben entered preuylly be nyghte in wylde places, and putten a&yogh;en the grasse ouer
&thorn;e pytt for to growe; or elle men coueren the pytt with grauell and sond, &thorn;at no man schall perceyue where ne
knowe where the pytt is, to &thorn;at entent &thorn;at neuer after none of his frendes schull han mynde ne remembrance
of him. And &thorn;anne &thorn;ai seyn &thorn;at he is ravissht in to ano&thorn;er world, where he is a gretter lord &thorn;an he was here.</SUPPLIED></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.124.25" CORRESP="Cot.168.7">And, when &thorn;is emperoure es deed and grauen in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at I talde &yogh;ow before, &thorn;e seuen kynredens
gaders &thorn;am togyder and chesez his sonne or &thorn;e next of his blude for to be emperour. And &thorn;ai say on &thorn;is wyse,
"We will and we pray and we ordayne &thorn;at &thorn;ou be oure emperour and oure souerayne lorde." And &thorn;an he
answers and saise, "Will &yogh;e be obeyaunt vnto my comaundementes in all thinges &thorn;at I bidd &yogh;ow do withouten

<PB N="125">
any agaynsaying?" And &thorn;ai say agayne, all with a voice, "We will." And he saise to &thorn;aim, "Wit &yogh;e &thorn;an &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="105" UNIT="folio">fra heyne forward my worde sall be of als grete strenth, and als scharpe and scherand, as my swerde." And
&thorn;an es he sette apon a blak filtre,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> felt; a blak stede, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> with &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai lift him vppe and settez him in his trone and corounes him.
And &thorn;an all &thorn;e citeez and gude tounes of &thorn;at land sendez him presandes; and he schall hafe at &thorn;at tytne three
score cartefulles and ma of gold and siluer, withouten iowels and gold and precious stanes &thorn;at grete lordes
giffez him, &thorn;e whilk passez mannez estimacioun, and also withouten horsz and clathez of gold and cammaca and
tartarene withouten nowmer.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.27" N="27" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.28">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXVII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the roialme of Tharse and the londes and kyngdoms towardes the septentrional parties, in comynge down from the lond of Chathay.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.125.11" CORRESP="Cot.169.1">THIS land of Catay es in Asie &thorn;e depe, and it marchez toward &thorn;e west apon &thorn;e kyngdom of Tarse, whare
off ane of &thorn;e three kynges &thorn;at soght oure Lorde in Bethleem was kyng sum tyme. And all &thorn;a &thorn;at er
commen of his lynage er Cristen. In &thorn;e land of Tarse &thorn;ai ete neuermare na flesch ne drinkez na
wyne. On &thorn;is syde &thorn;at rewme, towardes &thorn;e west, es &thorn;e land of Turquesten; and it lastez toward &thorn;e west vnto &thorn;e
kyngdom of Persy and toward &thorn;e north vnto &thorn;e kyngdom of Corasme. In &thorn;e cuntree of Turquesten er bot few
citeez, and &thorn;e best citee &thorn;eroff es called Eceozar. &THORN;are er large pastures and mykill, bot &thorn;er es bot lytill corne;
and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e comouns of &thorn;at land er all hird men and lyez &thorn;eroute in logez and drinkez a maner of drink
made of water and hony.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">a maner ale made of hony, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.125.19" CORRESP="Cot.169.16">On &thorn;is syde &thorn;at land es &thorn;e land of Corasme, &thorn;e whilk es a plentifous cuntree and a gude, bot &thorn;er es na wyne.
<MILESTONE N="105b" UNIT="folio">And it hase on &thorn;e este syde a grete deserte, &thorn;at lastes mare &thorn;an c. day iourneez. &THORN;e best citee of &thorn;at land es
called Corasme, and after it es &thorn;e land called. Folk of &thorn;at cuntree er gude werrayours and ri&yogh;t hardy. On &thorn;is

<PB N="126">
syde es &thorn;e land of Comany, oute of &thorn;e whilk ware putte a folk &thorn;at er in Grece and er called Comany. And it
es ane of &thorn;e grete kyngdommes of &thorn;e werld, bot it es no&yogh;t all inhabit; for in a place of &thorn;at land it <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">es</SUPPLIED> so calde,
and in ano&thorn;er party so hate, &thorn;at &thorn;are tnay na man dwell in &thorn;am. And &thorn;er es so grete plentee of fliez in &thorn;at land
&thorn;at men wate neuer whare &thorn;ai may turne &thorn;am. In &thorn;at land also er bot few treesse berand fruyt.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">is but lytille arberye ne trees &thorn;at beren frute ne o&thorn;ere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And in &thorn;at
land men liggez in tentes and in loogez and driez bestez dung and brynnez for defaute of fewaile.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.126.6" CORRESP="Cot.169.32">&THORN;is land comez dounward toward Pruys and Ruscy. And thurgh &thorn;is land rynnez &thorn;e riuer of Ethill, whilk
es ane of &thorn;e grete riuers of &thorn;e werld; and it es sum tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere so hard frosen &thorn;at men fyghtes &thorn;erapon in
grete batailes
<NOTE N="2">bailes, MS</NOTE> on horsez and on fote ma &thorn;an a c<HI REND="sup">m</HI> at anes. And a lytill fra &thorn;at ryuer es &thorn;e grete see Oceean,
&thorn;at &thorn;ai call Maure. And betwene &thorn;aim twa liggez &thorn;e maste parte of &thorn;e land of Corasme. And toward &thorn;e heued
of &thorn;at land es &thorn;e mount Caspye.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> Caucasus.</NOTE> And betwene &thorn;at mount and &thorn;e grete <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">see</SUPPLIED> of Maure es a strayte way and
straite passage to ga toward Inde. And &thorn;erfore kyng Alysaundre gert make &thorn;are a citee, &thorn;at was called
<MILESTONE N="106" UNIT="folio">Alysaundre, to kepe &thorn;e cuntree, &thorn;at na man schuld passe &thorn;are bot if he had leue; bot now es &thorn;at citee called
<NAME>Porte de fer</NAME>.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">the &yogh;ate of hell (<HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> "d'enfer," for "de fer"), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e principall citee of Comany es called Sarak or Sarachy. And &thorn;is es ane of &thorn;e ways to ga in
to Inde. Bot by &thorn;is way may no&yogh;t many men ga, bot if it be in wynter; and &thorn;is passage es called Berhent.
Ano&thorn;er way &thorn;er es for to ga <CORR SIC="thurgh" RESP="GW">fra</CORR>
<NOTE RESP="DR" N="5">Warner's note here reads: "thurgh, corrected to 'fra.'" It's not clear to me who made this, or the next, correction; I've treated them as editorial.</NOTE> &thorn;e land of Turquesten <CORR SIC="and thurgh" RESP="GW">thurgh</CORR>
<NOTE RESP="DR" N="6">Warner's note here reads: "and thurgh, corr. to 'thurgh.'" It's not clear to me who made this, or the preceding, correction; I've treated them as editorial.</NOTE> Persy; bot in &thorn;at way schall men ga many
iourneez thurgh wilderness. &THORN;e thridd way es to ga fra Comany by &thorn;e grete see Occean and thurgh &thorn;e kyngdom
of Abcaz. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at all &thorn;ise kyngdommes and landes vnto Pruysse and Ruscy er halden of
&thorn;e Grete Caan of Catay, and many o&thorn;er &thorn;at marchez on &thorn;am. And &thorn;erfore he es a grete lord of my&yogh;t
and of landes.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.28" N="28" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.29">
<PB N="127">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXVIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the emperour of Persye; and of the lond of derknesse; and of other kyngdomes that belongen to the Grete Cane, and other londes of his vnto the see of Grece.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.127.4" CORRESP="Cot.171.1">HERE hafe I talde &yogh;ow of landes and kyngdommes toward &thorn;e north, to comme doune fra &thorn;e land of Catay
vnto &thorn;e landes of Pruysse and Ruscy, whare Cristen men dwellez; and now will I tell &yogh;ow of o&thorn;er
landes and kyngdommes in commyng doune fra Catay to &thorn;e see of Grece toward Cristen land on
to&thorn;ar syde. And for als mykill as, next &thorn;e Grete Caan of Catay and Prestre Iohn &thorn;e emperoure of Inde, &thorn;e
emperour of Perse es &thorn;e grettest londe, &thorn;ertore I will first speke of him and of his kyngdom. And &yogh;e schall
vnderstand &thorn;at he has twa kyngdommes, of whilk ane begynnez estward at &thorn;e kyngdom of Turquesten and it
lastez westward to &thorn;e ryuer of Phison, &thorn;e whilk es ane of &thorn;e foure fludez &thorn;at commez oute of Paradyse. And
<MILESTONE N="106b" UNIT="folio">toward &thorn;e north it lastez to &thorn;e see of Caspye; and southward it lastez to &thorn;e desertes of Inde. And &thorn;is land es
gude and plentifous, and mykill folk &thorn;erin and many citeez. Bot twa principall citeez of &thorn;at land er called
Bactria aad Seormegraunt. &THORN;e to&thorn;er kyngdomme lastez fra &thorn;e ryuer of Phisoun toward &thorn;e west vnto &thorn;e land of
Medy and Ermony &thorn;e mare, and toward &thorn;e north vnto &thorn;e see of Caspy, and southward to &thorn;e land of Inde. And
&thorn;is es a plentifous cuntree and a gude. And &thorn;are er &thorn;arin three principall citeez, &thorn;at es to say Nessabon,
Saphaon, and Sarmassane.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.127.17" CORRESP="Cot.171.26">And &thorn;an es &thorn;e land of Ennony, &thorn;e whilk was sum tyme diuided in foure kyngdommes. &THORN;is es a grete land
and a plentifous and gude. And it begynnes at Perse and lastez toward &thorn;e west on lenth vnto &thorn;e land of
Turky; and on brede it lastez fra &thorn;e citee of Alisaundre, &thorn;at now es called <NAME>Porte de Fer</NAME>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&yogh;ate of Helle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> vnto &thorn;e land of
Medy. In &thorn;is land of Ermony er many faire citeez, bot Taurisius es maste of name.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.127.21" CORRESP="Cot.172.4">&THORN;an es &thorn;e land of Medie, &thorn;e whilk es ri&yogh;t lang, bot no&yogh;t full brade. And it begynnez estward at &thorn;e land of
Perse and Inde &thorn;e less, and lastez westward to &thorn;e kyngdom of Caldee, and northward to Lytill Ermony. In &thorn;is
land of Medy er many grete hilles and lytill playne. And &thorn;are dwellez Sarzenes and ano&thorn;er maner of folk, &thorn;at
men callez Cordynes. &THORN;e principall citeez of &thorn;at land er called Seras and Kermen.</SEG></P>

<PB N="128">
<MILESTONE N="107" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.128.1" CORRESP="Cot.172.13">And &thorn;an next es &thorn;e kyngdom of Georgy, &thorn;e whilk begynnez estward at a grete hill &thorn;at es called Abior. In
&thorn;is land dwellez many diuerse naciouns; and &thorn;is land es called Halamo. And it lastez vnto Turky and to &thorn;e
grete see; and southeward it marchez apon Ermony &thorn;e mare. In &thorn;is land er twa cuntreez; &thorn;e tane es called
Georgy and &thorn;e to&thorn;er Abcaz. And ay&thorn;er of &thorn;am has a kyng, and bathe er &thorn;ai Cristen; bot &thorn;e kyng of Georgee
es vnder &thorn;e subieccion of &thorn;e Grete Caan. Bot &thorn;e kyng of Abeaz es subiecte till na man, for his land es ri&yogh;t
strang of &thorn;e self and &thorn;erfore he defendez him wele agayne all men.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.128.7" CORRESP="Cot.172.27">In &thorn;is land of Abcaz es a grete meruaile; for &thorn;are es a cuntree &thorn;e whilk es nere three day iourneez vmgang,
and it es called Hamson. And &thorn;at cuntree es couerd all ouer with mirkness,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">derkness, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> so &thorn;at men &thorn;at er withouten may
<SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">no&yogh;t</SUPPLIED> see anything
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">any, erased, and "no" interlined.</NOTE> &thorn;erin; and &thorn;er dare na man ga in to &thorn;at cuntree for &thorn;e mirkness. And neuer&thorn;eles men &thorn;at
dwellez in &thorn;e cuntree nere aboute it saise &thorn;at &thorn;ai may sum tyme here &thorn;erin &thorn;e voice of men, and horsez nye, and
cokkes crawe, and &thorn;areby wate &thorn;ai wele &thorn;at sum maner of men dwellez &thorn;are, bot &thorn;ai wate no&yogh;t whatkyn men
&thorn;ai er. And &thorn;ai say alsso &thorn;at &thorn;is mirkness come thurgh myracle of Godd, &thorn;at he schewed &thorn;are for Cristen men;
and &thorn;at fynd &thorn;ai writen in alde storyes amanges o&thorn;er wonders and meruailes. For are was sum tyme a wikked
tiraunt &thorn;at was emperour of &thorn;e land of Perse, and he was called Taures. &THORN;is emperour persued Cristen men in
his tyme, all &thorn;at ware within his empyre; and he went aboute ferre and nere with a grete oste for to destruy
<MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;am, or elles to gerre &thorn;am make sacrifice to his mawmetz. And in &thorn;at cuntree dwelled many Cristen men, &thorn;e
whilk forsuke all &thorn;aire gudes and &thorn;aire ricchess and fledd by cause of &thorn;e persecucioun of &thorn;at tiraunt, and wald
hafe gane in to Grece. And, when &thorn;ai ware all gadred sammen in a faire playne, &thorn;e whilk es called Megon, &thorn;e
emperour &thorn;at was warned of &thorn;aire fleyng lay before &thorn;am with his oste for to fall apon &thorn;am and sla &thorn;am. And,
when &thorn;e Cristen men sawe &thorn;am com to &thorn;am wardes, &thorn;ai ware ri&yogh;t ferde, and &thorn;ai sette &thorn;am all apon &thorn;aire kneesse
and besoght Godd to helpe &thorn;am and saue &thorn;am fra &thorn;aire enmys. And alssone come a thikke mirkness and
vmbelapped &thorn;e emperour and all his oste, so &thorn;at &thorn;ai my&yogh;t nower go away; and so dwell &thorn;ai &yogh;et in &thorn;at mirkness
and euermare schall.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and so schulle &thorn;ei euermore abyden in &thorn;at derknesse tille the day of dome be the myracle of God, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;e Cristen men went whare &thorn;ai wald; and &thorn;erfore may &thorn;ai say with &thorn;e prophete
Dauid on &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">A Domino factum est istud et est mirabile in oculis nostris</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Ps. cxvii. 23. <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> omits the English translation as usual.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Of oure Lorde
es &thorn;is done, and it es wonderfull io oure sight." And me think &thorn;at &thorn;is miracle and swilke o&thorn;er schuld stirre
Cristen men to be mare deuote ynentez Godd &thorn;an &thorn;ai er now on days
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">&thorn;an ony other men of ony other secte, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for withouten doute, ware ne &thorn;er ware
so mykill wikkednes and syn amanges Cristen men, &thorn;ai schuld be lordes of all &thorn;e werld and soueraynes. For
Godd es euermare redy for to succoure and helpe his lele seruandes, &thorn;at seruez him duely with a clene hert, so

<PB N="129">
&thorn;at he will send &thorn;am &thorn;e ouerhand of &thorn;aire enmys, as &thorn;e prophete saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quomodo persequebatur vnus mille, et
<MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="folio">duo fugarent decem milla</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Deut. xxxii. 30, with "persequatur" and "fugent" (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text).</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Ane of &thorn;i trewe seruandes pursued a thousand mescreauntes
<NOTE N="2"></NOTE>, and twa
chaced x<HI REND="sup">m</HI>." And Dauid saise on &thorn;is wyse, "On &thorn;ine a syde sall fall a thowsand, and on &thorn;ine o&thorn;er syde x<HI REND="sup">m</HI>."
And how &thorn;is may be he tellez efterward in Haly Wrytte, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quia manus Domini fecit hoc</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "For
&thorn;e myght of oure Lorde Godd duse all &thorn;is."
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">And oure Lord him self seyth (Ps. lxxx. 15), be &thorn;e prophetes mouth, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text), adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;us it may appertely be proued &thorn;at, and we will be gude
men, oure enmys may no&yogh;t agayne stand vs.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">enduren a&yogh;enst vs, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Oute of &thorn;is land commez a riuer &thorn;at by certayne taknez schewez
hat men dwellez &thorn;erin; neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;are dare na man comme &thorn;erin.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.129.8" CORRESP="Cot.174.6">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at in &thorn;ir forsaid rewmes of Georgy and Abcaz and of Ermony &thorn;e less er dwelland
gude Cristen men and deuote. For &thorn;ai schryue &thorn;am ilke a woke
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">ones or twyes in the woke, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and er howseld; and sum of &thorn;am er schryuen
and howseld ilke a day. And
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">And so do wee not on this half, alle be it &thorn;at seynt Poul commandeth it, seyenge, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text). Thei kepen &thorn;at commandement, but wee ne kepen it not, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. The passage quoted is not from St. Paul.</NOTE> in &thorn;is &thorn;ai schewe mare deuocioun &thorn;an we do, &thorn;at er vnnethez anez in a &yogh;ere
schryfen and howseld.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.129.12" CORRESP="Cot.174.14">Next &thorn;is land es &thorn;e rewlm of Turky, &thorn;e whilk marchez apon Grete Ermony. And &thorn;are in er many
cuntreez, as Lycony, Saure, Capadoce, Bryke, Quificion, Pytan and Geneth. In ilkane of &thorn;ir cuntreez er
many citeez faire and gude. &THORN;is land of Turky lastez to &thorn;e citee of Sakara, &thorn;e whilke standes apon &thorn;e Grekez
see; and also it marchez apon Surry, &thorn;e whilke es a grete cuntree and a gude, as I talde &yogh;ow before. Also
<MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio">amanges &thorn;ir forsaid landes towardes Inde es &thorn;e land of Caldee, &thorn;e whilk lastez fra &thorn;e hilles of Caldee estward
vnto &thorn;e citee of Niniue, &thorn;at standez apon &thorn;e riuer of Tygre, on lenth; and on brede it begynnez northward at
&thorn;e citee of Maraga and lastez southward to &thorn;e grete see Occian. &THORN;e land of Caldee es a playne cuntree, and
&thorn;are bot few riuers &thorn;erin.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.129.20" CORRESP="Cot.174.28">And next &thorn;e land of Caldee es &thorn;e land of Mesopotamy, &thorn;e whilk begynnez estward at &thorn;e riuer of Tygre at a
citee &thorn;at men callez Mosell, and it lastez westward to &thorn;e riuer of Eufrates at a citee &thorn;at men callez Rochays;
and on brede it lastez fra &thorn;e mountez of Ermony vnto &thorn;e desertez of Inde &thorn;e lesse. And it es a playne cuntree
and a gude and plentifous, and few riuers &thorn;erin. And twa hie mountaynez er &thorn;erin,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">It hath (il y a) but ii. mountaynes in &thorn;at contree, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of whilk &thorn;e tane es called
Symar and &thorn;e to&thorn;er Lyson. And it marchez to &thorn;e land of Caldee.</SEG></P>

<PB N="130">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.130.1" CORRESP="Cot.175.1">And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at Ethiopie marchez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&yogh;it &thorn;ere is toward the parties meridionales many contrees and many regyouns, as the lond of Ethiope &thorn;at marcheth, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> estward to &thorn;e grete deserte, westward to &thorn;e land of
Numidy, southward to Mauritane, and northward to &thorn;e Reed See. And Mauritane lastez fra &thorn;e hillez of
Ethiopie vnto Liby &thorn;e hye; and it liggez on lenth endlang &thorn;e grete see Occeane southward, and northward it
marchez apon Numidy and Liby &thorn;e hie. In Namidy dwellez Cristen men; and it marchez apon &thorn;ir forsaid landez
and to &thorn;c deserte of Egipte, of whilk I spak before. And &thorn;an es Liby, &thorn;e hie and &thorn;e lawe, &thorn;e whilk commez
<MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="folio">doune toward &thorn;e Spaynisch see. In &thorn;e whilk cuntree er many diuerse folk and diuerse naciouns. Here hafe I
talde &yogh;ow of many cuntreez &thorn;at er on &thorn;is syde of &thorn;e grete kyngdom of Catay, of &thorn;e whilk many er obeischaunt
to &thorn;e Grete Caan.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.29" N="29" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.30">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXIX</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the contrees and yles that ben be&yogh;onde the lond of Cathay, and of the frutes there; and of xxii. kynges enclosed within the mountaynes.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.130.12" CORRESP="Cot.175.20">AND now will I tell &yogh;ow of landes and cuntreez and iles &thorn;at er be&yogh;ond &thorn;e land of Cathay. And &thorn;arfore
he &thorn;at will ga fra Cathay til Inde &thorn;e less and &thorn;e mare,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">toward the highe Ynde and toward Bacharye, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> he schall <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">ga</SUPPLIED> thurgh a kyngdom &thorn;at es called
Cadhilhe, &thorn;e whilk es a grete land. And &thorn;are growez a maner of fruyte grete as gourdes; and, when
it es rype, &thorn;ai open it and fyndez &thorn;erin a beste with flesch and blude and bane, and it es lyke to a lytill lambe
withouten wolle. And men of &thorn;at cuntree etez &thorn;at beste, and &thorn;e fruyt also. And &thorn;at es a grete meruaile.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Of &thorn;at frute I haue eten, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
Neuer&thorn;eles I said &thorn;am &thorn;at me thoght it na grete meruaile, for in my cuntree I said &thorn;am ware treesse berand a
fruyte &thorn;at becommez briddez flyand, &thorn;e whilk men callez Bernakes, and &thorn;er es gude mete of &thorn;am; and &thorn;ase &thorn;at
fallez in &thorn;e water liffez and fliez furth, and &thorn;ase &thorn;at fallez on &thorn;e land dyez. And, when I had talde &thorn;am &thorn;is, &thorn;ai

<PB N="131">
meruailed &thorn;am gretely &thorn;eroff. In &thorn;is land also er grete appils of noble smell and noble sauour; and men may
fynd of &thorn;am on a clustre c. and ma, and &thorn;e lefez of &thorn;e treez er twa fote lang and sum langre. And in &thorn;at
cuntree er treesse berand gariofiez and nute mugez and grete nuttez of Inde and o&thorn;er diuerse spiceriez. And
&thorn;are er vynes &thorn;at beres so grete bobbes of grapez &thorn;at a wyght man may vnnethez bere ane of &thorn;am.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.131.5" CORRESP="Cot.176.18">In &thorn;is same land er &thorn;e hillez of Caspy, whilk men callez Vber. And amang &thorn;ase hilles er &thorn;e Iewes of &thorn;e
ten kynredens enclosed, whilk men callez Gog and Magog; and &thorn;ai may comme oute at na syde. For kyng
Alysaundre chaced &thorn;am &thorn;ider, for he wend to hafe enclosed &thorn;am &thorn;are thurgh wirking of man; and, when he
sawe &thorn;at he myght no&yogh;t, he praid to Godd &thorn;at he wald fulfill &thorn;at he had begon. And, if all he ware a haythen
man, Godd of his speciall grace herd his praier and closed &thorn;a hilles sammen, &thorn;e whilk er so grete and so heghe
&thorn;at na man may passe &thorn;am. And on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde <CORR SIC="est" RESP="GW">es</CORR>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">est (the "est" of the French text), MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e see of Caspye; bot
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Now may sum men asken, "Sith &thorn;at the see is on &thorn;at o syde, wherfore go &thorn;ei not out on the see syde, for to go where &thorn;at hem lyketh?" But to &thorn;is questioun I schal annswere, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on &thorn;at syde may &thorn;ai no&yogh;t wynne
oute for &thorn;is cause, for &thorn;at see commez vp oute of &thorn;e erthe vnder &thorn;e forsaid hillez and rynne on &thorn;e ta syde &thorn;e
cuntree thurgh a grete deserte and fra &thorn;eine it lastez to &thorn;e land of Perse. And if all it be called a see,
neuer&thorn;eles it es nane, bot it es a lake, &thorn;e grettest in &thorn;e werld. And if all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at er enclosed &thorn;are myght, and
&thorn;ai wald, passe ouer &thorn;at see by schippe, neuer &thorn;e latter &thorn;ai wate no&yogh;t whare &thorn;ai myght aryfe, and also &thorn;ai schuld
no&yogh;t vnderstand &thorn;er langage. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes has now na land of &thorn;aire awen to dwell in
in all &thorn;e werld, bot anely amang &thorn;ir hilles. And &yogh;it &thorn;ai pay tribute &thorn;arfore to the quene of Amazoun, and scho
<MILESTONE N="110" UNIT="folio">gers &thorn;ase forsaid hilles wonder wele be keped, &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;asse no&yogh;t oute ouer &thorn;am to &thorn;aire awen cuntree, &thorn;e whilk
marchez apon &thorn;ase hillez. And no&yogh;t for&thorn;i sum tyme it happens &thorn;at sum of &thorn;am clymbez ouer &thorn;ase hilles and
gase oute, bot &thorn;are may na grete nowmer of &thorn;am clymbe ouer &thorn;am togyder by cause of &thorn;e grete height of &thorn;am
and &thorn;e ill clymbyng. And &thorn;are es nan o&thorn;er passage oute, bot at a narowe stie,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">a litill issue, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk was made thurgh
sleight and wirking of men. And &thorn;at passage es bot foure myle lang, and &thorn;an es &thorn;are a grete deserte, whare men
may fynd na water ne na dwellyng for men, by cause of dragouns and nedders and o&thorn;er venymous bestez, so &thorn;at
na man may passe &thorn;are away, bot if it be in &thorn;e wynter. And &thorn;is strayte passage call &thorn;ai &thorn;are Clyrem; and &thorn;e
qwene of Amazoun gers kepe it wele, as I said before. And, if it hapne &thorn;at any of &thorn;am passe oute, &thorn;ai can speke

<PB N="132">
na langage bot Ebrew, ne &thorn;ai no&yogh;t speke with o&thorn;er men, when &thorn;ai comme amang &thorn;am. And men in &thorn;e cuntree
&thorn;are nere saise &thorn;at in &thorn;e tyme of Antecriste &thorn;ir Iewes schall comme oute and do mykill harme to Cristen men.
And &thorn;erfore all &thorn;e Iews &thorn;at dwellez in diuerse partys of &thorn;e werld lerez for to speke Hebrew, for &thorn;ai trowe &thorn;at
&thorn;ir Iewes &thorn;at er enclosed amanges &thorn;e hillez schall comme oute and schall knawe &thorn;am by &thorn;aire speche &thorn;at &thorn;ai er
Iews as &thorn;ai er. And &thorn;an schall &thorn;ai lede &thorn;am in to Cristendom for to destruy Cristen men. For &thorn;ir Iews saise
&thorn;ai knawe by &thorn;aire prophecys &thorn;at &thorn;e Iews &thorn;at er closed amanges &thorn;e hilles sall comme oute and Cristen men
<MILESTONE N="110b" UNIT="folio">schall be vnder &thorn;aim, as &thorn;ai hafe bene vnder Cristen men. And if &yogh;e will wit how &thorn;ai schall fynd a place for to
wynne oute at, I schall tell &yogh;owe, after &thorn;at I hafe herd say before tymes. In &thorn;e tyme of Antecriste a foxe schal
make his den
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">make &thorn;ere his trayne and mynen an hole, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e same place whare kyng Alysaundre gert make &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;ase hillez, when he enclosed &thorn;is
forsaid folk. And so lang sall &thorn;is fox wirk in &thorn;e erthe &thorn;at at &thorn;e last he schall comme oute amang &thorn;is folk; and,
when &thorn;ai see him, &thorn;ai schall hafe grete meruaile of him, for &thorn;ai sawe neuer are na swllke beste. Neuer&thorn;eles
&thorn;ai hafe all maner of o&thorn;er bestez, owt taken &thorn;e fox, amanges &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai sall hafe so grete meruaile of &thorn;is fox
&thorn;at &thorn;ai sall chace him hider and &thorn;ider; and so lang sall &thorn;ai pursue him &thorn;at at &thorn;e last &thorn;ai schall dryfe him to &thorn;e
hole whare be come oute. And &thorn;an schall &thorn;ai grafe after him so lang vnto &thorn;ai comme to &thorn;e &yogh;ates &thorn;at Alysaundre
gert stoppe with grete stanes and syment, and &thorn;ai schall breke &thorn;ise &yogh;atez and so sall &thorn;ai fynd &thorn;e passage oute.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.132.16" CORRESP="Cot.178.24">Fra &thorn;is land men sall ga to &thorn;e land of Bachary, whare er many wikked men and fell. In &thorn;is land er treesse
&thorn;at berez wolle, as it ware of schepe, of whilke &thorn;ai make clathe. In &thorn;is land also er many ypotams, &thorn;at dwellez
sun tyme apon land and sum tyme on &thorn;e water; and &thorn;ai er half man and halfe hors. And &thorn;ai ete men whare so
&thorn;ai may get &thorn;am, na mete gladlier. And in &thorn;at land er many griffouns, ma &thorn;an in any cuntree elles. And sum
<MILESTONE N="111" UNIT="folio">men saise &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe &thorn;e schappe of ane egle before, and behind &thorn;e schappe of a lyoun; and sikerly &thorn;ai say
sothe. Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;e griffoun es mare and stranger &thorn;an viii. lyouns of &thorn;ise cuntreez, and gretter and stalworther
&thorn;an a hundreth egles. For certaynely he will bere til his nest flyand a grete hors and a man apon him,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">Cf.</HI> French text, note 17; a gret hors &yogh;if he may fynde him at the poynt or ii. oxen, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI>, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> or twa
oxen &yogh;oked togyder, as &thorn;ai ga sammen at &thorn;e plogh. For he has nailes apon his fete als grete and als lang as
&thorn;ai ware oxen hornes, bot &thorn;ai er wonder scharpe. And of &thorn;ase nailes men makez coppez for to drink off, as we
do of &thorn;e hornes of bugles; and of &thorn;e bakkez of his fethers
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and of hire ribbes and of the pennes of hire wenges, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;ai make strang bowes for to schote with.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.132.26" CORRESP="Cot.179.12">Fra &thorn;e land of Bachary men gase many day iourneez to &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn, &thorn;at es emperour of Inde;
and his land es called &thorn;e Ile of Pentoxere.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.30" N="30" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.31">
<PB N="133">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXX</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the ryalle estate of Prestre John and of a riche man that made a merueyllous castelle and cleped it Paradys; and of his sotyltee.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.133.4" CORRESP="Cot.179.16">THIS emperour Prestre Iohn has many diuerse cuntreez vnder his empire, in &thorn;e whilk er many noble
citeez and faire tounes and many iles grete and large. For &thorn;is land of Inde es departed in iles by
cause of &thorn;e grete fludez &thorn;at commez oute of Paradys and rynnez thurgh his land and departez it. And
also in &thorn;e see he has many grete iles. &THORN;e principal citee of &thorn;e ile of Pentoxore es called Nise; and &thorn;are es &thorn;e
emperour see, and &thorn;erfore it es a noble citee and a riche. Prestre Iohn has vnder him many kynges and many
diuerse folk; and his land es gude and riche, bot no&yogh;t so riche as &thorn;e land of &thorn;e Grete Caan of Cathay. For
marchands commez no&yogh;t so mykill to &thorn;at land as to &thorn;e land of Cathay, for it ware to lang way. And also
<MILESTONE N="111b" UNIT="folio">marchandes may fynd in &thorn;e ile of Cathay all &thorn;at <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;ai</SUPPLIED> hafe nede of, as spicery, clathes of gold, and o&thorn;er riche
thinges; and &thorn;ai lette also for to ga &thorn;ider by cause of lang way and grete periles in &thorn;e see.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">And &thorn;erfore, alle be it &thorn;at men han greter chep in the yle of Prestre Iohn, natheles men dreden the longe weye and the grete periles in the see in &thorn;o partyes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> For &thorn;er er in many
placez in &thorn;e see grete roches of &thorn;e stane &thorn;at es called Adamaunt, &thorn;e whilk of his awen kynde drawez to him
yrne; and, for &thorn;er schuld passe na schippes &thorn;at had nayles of yrne &thorn;are away by cause of &thorn;e forsaid stane, for
he schuld drawe &thorn;am till him, &thorn;arfore &thorn;ai dare no&yogh;t wende &thorn;ider. &THORN;e schippes of &thorn;at cuntree er all made of wode
and nane yrne. I was ane tyme in &thorn;at see, and I sawe as it had bene ane ile of treesse and bruschez growand;
and &thorn;e schippe men talde me &thorn;at all &thorn;at was of grete schippes &thorn;at &thorn;e roche of &thorn;e adamand had gert dwell &thorn;are,
and of diuerse thinges &thorn;at ware in &thorn;e schippez ware &thorn;ase treesse and &thorn;ase brusches sprungen. And
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">and of the rotenesse and o&thorn;er thing, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for &thorn;ir
perils and swilke o&thorn;er, and also for &thorn;e lang way, &thorn;ai wende to Cathay.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">and &thorn;erfore dur not the marchauntes passen &thorn;ere, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei knowen wel the passages, or elle &thorn;at &thorn;ei han gode lodes men, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI> (following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Royal 20 B. x">R</ABBR>), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &yogh;it Cathay es no&yogh;t so nere &thorn;at ne &thorn;aim
behoues fra Venice or fra Ieen or o&thorn;er placez of Lumbardy be in trauaillyng by see and by land xi. monethes
or xii. are &thorn;ai may wynne to &thorn;e land of Catay. And &yogh;it es &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn mykill ferrer by many a day
iournee. And marchandes &thorn;at wendez &thorn;ider wendez thurgh &thorn;e land of Perse and commez to a citee &thorn;at men

<PB N="134">
callez Hermes, for a philosopher &thorn;at men called Hermes foundid it. And &thorn;an &thorn;ai passe ane arme of &thorn;e see and
<MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="folio">commez to ano&thorn;er citee &thorn;at es called Soboth or Colach; and &thorn;are fynd &thorn;ai all maner of marchandyse, and
papeiays als grete plentee as es in oure cuntree of larkes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">gees (<HI REND="i">i.e.</HI> "owes," for "alowes"), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;is cuntree es lytill qwheet or barly, and &thorn;erfore
&thorn;ai ete milet and rysz, hony and milk and chese and o&thorn;er maner of fruytes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">ryzs and hony and mylk and chese and frute, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And fra &thorn;eine may marchandes
passe suerly ynogh, if &thorn;am list.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.134.5" CORRESP="Cot.182.17">In &thorn;at
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">In &thorn;at &hellip; three taas, repeated lower down, in its proper place according to the French text and <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> land er many papeiais, &thorn;i whilk &thorn;ai call in &thorn;aire langage Psitakes; and
&thorn;ai speke of &thorn;aire awen kynde als properly as a man. And &thorn;ase &thorn;at spekez wele has lang tunges and large, and
apon ayther fote fyfe taas; and &thorn;ai &thorn;at spekez no&yogh;t or elles lytill hase bot three taas.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.134.8" CORRESP="Cot.180.35">&THORN;is ilk reall kyng Prestre Iohn and &thorn;e Grete Caan of Tartary er euermare alyed togyder thurgh mariage; for
ayther of &thorn;am weddez o&thorn;ir doghter or o&thorn;er sister. In &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn er grete plentee of preciouse stanes
of diuerse kyndez, sum of &thorn;am so grete and so large &thorn;at &thorn;ai make of &thorn;am vessell, as dischez, dublers, coppes,
and many o&thorn;er thinges &thorn;at lang ware to tell.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.134.12" CORRESP="Cot.181.7">Now will I speke of sum of &thorn;e principall iles of Prestre Iohn land, and of &thorn;e realtee of his state and what
lawe and belefe he and his pople haldez. &THORN;is emperour Prestre Iohn es a Cristen man, and &thorn;e maste party of
of his land also, if all it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe no&yogh;t all &thorn;e articles of oure beleue so clerely as we hafe. no&yogh;t for&thorn;i
&thorn;ai trowe in Godd, Fader and Son and Haly Gaste; and full deuote men &thorn;ai er and trewe ilkane til o&thorn;er, and
<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;are es now&thorn;er with &thorn;am fraude ne gyle.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">and &thorn;ei sette not be no barettes, ne by cawteles, ne of no disceytes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is emperour hase vnder his subieccioun lxxii. prouinces; and in ilk
ane of <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;am</SUPPLIED> es a kyng. And &thorn;ase kynges hase o&thorn;er kynges vnder &thorn;aim, and all er &thorn;ai tributaries to &thorn;e
emperour Prestre Ionn. In &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn er many meruailes. Bot amanges o&thorn;er &thorn;are es a grete see
all of grauell and sande, and na drope of water &thorn;erin. And it ebbez and flowes as &thorn;e grete see duse in o&thorn;er
cuntreez with grete wawes, and neuermare standez still withouten mouyng. &THORN;at see may na man passe, now&thorn;er
by schippe ne o&thorn;er wyse; and &thorn;erfore it es vnknawen till any man whatkyn land or cuntree es on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde
of &thorn;at see. And, &thorn;of &thorn;er be na water in &thorn;at see, neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;are es grete plentee of gude fischez taken by &thorn;e see
bankes; and &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t sauoury in &thorn;e mouth,</SEG> bot &thorn;ai er of o&thorn;er schappe &thorn;an fischez er of o&thorn;er waters.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">and &thorn;ei ben of right goode tast and delicyous to mannes mete, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> I Iohn
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">I Iohn &hellip; es soth, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
Maundeuill ete of &thorn;am, and &thorn;arfore trowez it for sikerly it es soth.</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.134.25" CORRESP="Cot.181.29">And three day iournez fra &thorn;at see er grete hilles, oute of &thorn;e whilk commez a grete riuer &thorn;at commez fra
Paradise; and it es full of preciouse stanes, and na drope of water. And it rynnez with grete wawes thurgh
wilderness in to &thorn;e Grauelly See, and &thorn;an er &thorn;ai na mare sene. And &thorn;is riuer rynnez ilke woke three days so fast

<PB N="135">
&thorn;at na man dare com &thorn;arin; bot all &thorn;e o&thorn;er days may men gang in to it, when &thorn;ai will, and gader of &thorn;e precious
stanes. And by&yogh;ond &thorn;at riuer toward &thorn;e wilderness es a grete playne amanges hilles, all sandy and grauelly, in
<MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e whilk playne er treesse as it semez, &thorn;e whilk at &thorn;e sonne rysing begynnez to growe and a fruyte to spring oute
of &thorn;am; and &thorn;ai growe so vnto it be midday, and &thorn;an begynne &thorn;ai to dwyne and turne agayne in to &thorn;e erthe, so
&thorn;at by &thorn;e sonne be sette &thorn;er es na&thorn;ing sene of &thorn;am, and &thorn;us &thorn;ai fare ilke a day. Bot of &thorn;is fruyt dare na man ete
ne negh it, for it semez as it ware a fantom and a dessayuable thing to &thorn;e sight.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">but no man dar taken of &thorn;at frute, for it is a thing of fayrye, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;is es halden a meruailous
thing, and so it may wele.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.135.8" CORRESP="Cot.182.13">And in &thorn;e forsaid wildernes er many wylde men with hornes apon &thorn;aire heueds; and &thorn;ai dwelle in wodes as
beste: and speke: no&yogh;t, bot gruntils as swyne duse. Also in sum wodes of &thorn;at land er wylde hundes, &thorn;at neuer
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;at neuer &hellip; cuntree, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. After this follows in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> the passage about "popegayes."</NOTE>
will com to man mare &thorn;an foxez will do in &thorn;is cuntree.</SEG> <SEG ID="Eg.135.10" CORRESP="Cot.182.17a">And &thorn;are er fewles also spekand of &thorn;aire awen kynde;
and &thorn;ai will hails
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">saluen, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> men &thorn;at com thurgh &thorn;e desertez, spekand als openly as &thorn;ai ware men. &THORN;ir fewles hase large
tungez and on ayther of &thorn;aire fete v. nayles. And &thorn;are er o&thorn;er &thorn;at has bot three nayles on ayther fote, and &thorn;ai
speke no&yogh;t so wele ne so openly.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">for &thorn;ei cone not but cryen, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;ir fewles call &thorn;ai &thorn;are Psitakes, as I said before.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.135.14" CORRESP="Cot.182.24">&THORN;is ilke grete kyng and emperour Prestre Iohn, when he wendez to bataile agaynes his enmys, he hase na
banere borne before him, bot in steed of baner &thorn;are er borne before him three crosses of fyne gold, &thorn;e whilk er
grete and hie and wele dyght with preciouse stanes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">and euery of &thorn;o crosses ben sett in a chariot, fulle richely arrayed, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And to &thorn;e kepyng of ilke a crosse er ordaynd and assigned
x<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men of armes and ma &thorn;an a hundreth thousand men on fote, on &thorn;e same maner as men kepez a baner or a
<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio">standard in bataile in o&thorn;er placez. And &thorn;is nowmer of men es all way assigned to &thorn;e keping of &thorn;e forsaid crossez
ay when &thorn;e emperour wendez to bataile, withouten &thorn;e principall oste and withouten certayne lordes and &thorn;aire
men &thorn;at er ordaynd for to be in his awen bataile, and also withouten certayne scales &thorn;at er ordaynd for forraying.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">and this nombre of folk is withouten the pryncypalle hoost and withouten wenges ordeynd for the bataylle, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And, when he rydes in tyme of peesse with his priuee men&yogh;ee, &thorn;ar es borne before him a crosse of tree, withouten
gold or paynture or precious stanes, in remembraunce of Cristez passioun &thorn;at he sufferd on a crosse of tree. Also
he hase borne before him a plate of gold full of erthe, in taken &thorn;at for all his grete noblay and his lordschepe he
come fra erthe and intill erthe sall he turne. And &thorn;er es borne before him anoper vessell full of gold and of
iowailes and precious stanes, as rubies, dyamaundes, saphires, emeraudes, topazes, crisolites and o&thorn;er many, in
taknyag of his grete noblay, lordschepe and myght.</SEG></P>

<PB N="136">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.136.1" CORRESP="Cot.183.7">Now will I tell &yogh;ow the aray of Prestre Iohnes palays, &thorn;e whilk es comounly
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">He duellethe comounly, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> at &thorn;e citee of Suse. And
&thorn;at palays es so riche, so delitable and so noble, &thorn;at it es wonder to tell. For abouen &thorn;e principall toure er twa
pomelles of gold; and in ayther of &thorn;aim er twa charbuncles grete and faire, &thorn;e whilk schynez ri&yogh;t clere apon &thorn;e
nyght. And &thorn;e principall &yogh;ates of &thorn;e palays er of precious stanes, &thorn;at men calles sardones, and &thorn;e barrez of
&thorn;am er of euour; and &thorn;e wyndows of &thorn;e hall and &thorn;e chaumbres er of cristall. And all &thorn;e tables on whilk &thorn;ai ete
er of emeraudes, amatistes and sum of gold, sett full of precious stanes; and &thorn;e pilers &thorn;at beres &thorn;e tablez er of
<MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e same maner of precious stanes. And &thorn;e grecez,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">degrees, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> on whilk &thorn;e emperour gase vp to his trone whare he sittez
at &thorn;e mete, er ane of oniche, ano&thorn;er of cristall, ano&thorn;er of iaspre, ano&thorn;er of amatist, ano&thorn;er of sardone, ano&thorn;er of
corall
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">corneline, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;e hiest gree, whare on he settez his fete at &thorn;e mete, es of crisolytez. And all &thorn;ir greez er bordurde
with fyne gold, frette full of perle and o&thorn;er precious stanes aboute &thorn;e sydez and &thorn;e endez. And &thorn;e sydes of his
trone er of smaragdes,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">emeraudes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> bordured with fyne gold, sett full of precious stanes. &THORN;e pileres in his chaumbre er of
fyne gold, sett full of precious stanes, of whilk many er charbunclez &thorn;at giffez grete light on nyghtez; and &yogh;it
neuer &thorn;e latter he hase ilk a nyght brynnand in his chaumbre xii. vessell
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">a vessell, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of cristall full of bawme, to giffe gude
smell and swete and to dryfe away wikked aere. And &thorn;e fourme of his bedd es all of saphires, wele bunden
with gold, for to make him to slepe wele and for to destruy lichery; for he will no&yogh;t lye by his wyfez, bot at
foure certayne tymez in &thorn;e &yogh;ere,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">after the iiii, cesouns, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;an all anely for to gete childre.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.136.17" CORRESP="Cot.184.4">&THORN;is emperour hase also ano&thorn;er palays, riche and noble, in &thorn;e citee of Nise, and &thorn;are he suggeournes when
him list; bot &thorn;e aer es no&yogh;t so gude &thorn;are ne so halesome as it es at Suse. Thurgh oute all &thorn;e land of Prestre
Iohn &thorn;ai ete bot anez on &thorn;e day, as &thorn;ai do in &thorn;e courte of &thorn;e Grete Caan. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at Prestre
Iohn hase ilk a day in his courte etand ma &thorn;an xxx<HI REND="sup">m</HI> of folke, withouten commers and gangers; bot now&thorn;er xxx<HI REND="sup">m</HI>
<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;are ne in &thorn;e courte of &thorn;e Grete Caan spendez so mykill mete on a day as xii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> in oure cuntree. &THORN;is emperour
hase also euermare vii. kyngez in his courte, for to serue him; and, when &thorn;ai hafe serued him a moneth, &thorn;ai
wende hame and o&thorn;er vii. kynges commez and seruez ano&thorn;er moneth. And with &thorn;a kinges seruez all way lxxii. dukez
and ccclx. erles, and many o&thorn;er lordez and knyghtes. And ilke a day &thorn;are etez in his courte ii. ercebischopes
and xx. bischopes. And &thorn;e Patriarch of sayn Thomas es &thorn;are as it ware pape. All ersbischopes and bischopes
and abbotes &thorn;are er kynngez and
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">And euerych of &thorn;eise grete lordes knowen wel ynow the attendance of hire seruyce. The on is mayster of his houshold, <HI REND="i">etc.</HI> (literally following <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Royal 20 B. x">R</ABBR>), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> grete lordes of feez. And ilkane of &thorn;am hase sum office in &thorn;e emperour courte;
for a kyng es porter, ano&thorn;er hawler, ano&thorn;er chaumberlayne, ano&thorn;er steward of howshalde, ano&thorn;er buteler,

<PB N="137">
ano&thorn;er sewer, ano&thorn;er marschall, and so furth of all o&thorn;er officez &thorn;at langes till his courte; and &thorn;erfore es he full
richely serued and wirschipfully. His land lastez on brede foure monethes iournez; and on lenth it es withouten
mesure.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;at is to seyne, alle the yles vnder erthe &thorn;at wee supposen to ben vnder vs, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG> Trowez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">Trowez &hellip; for to tell, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> all &thorn;is, for sikerly I sawe it with myne eghen and mykill mare &thorn;an I hafe talde &yogh;ow. For my
felaws and I ware dwelland with him in his courte a lang tyme and saw all &thorn;is &thorn;at I hafe talde &yogh;ow and mykill
mare &thorn;an I hafe layser for to tell.</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.137.6" CORRESP="Cot.184.32">Besyde &thorn;e ile of Pentoxore, &thorn;e whilk es Prestre Iohnez, es ano&thorn;er ile bathe lang and brade, &thorn;e whilk es
called Mulstorak; and it es vnder &thorn;e lordschepe of Prestre Iohn. In &thorn;is ile es grete plentee of all maner of
<MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="folio">gudes and ricchess. And in &thorn;at land was sum tyme a riche man &thorn;at was called Catolonabes, and he was a grete
man and a wonder wyly. And he had a faire castell and a strang, standand apon a hill, and he gert make aboute
it strang wallez and hie. And within &thorn;ase wallez be gert make a faire gardyn and plant &thorn;erin all maner of treez
berand diuevse fruytz. He gert plant &thorn;erin also all maner of erbez of gude smell and &thorn;at bare faire floures.
&THORN;are ware also in &thorn;at gardyne many faire welles, and besyde &thorn;aim ware many faire halles and chaumbres, paynted
with gold and azure wele and curiousely with diuerse storys, and with diuerse maners of briddes, &thorn;e whilk semed
as &thorn;ai sang and turned by engyne as &thorn;ai had bene all quikke. He putte also in &thorn;at gardyne all maner of fewles
&thorn;at he myght get, and all maner of bestez &thorn;at he myght fynd, to make a man solace and disporte. And he putte
also in to &thorn;at gardyne faire damysellz within &thorn;e elde of xv. &yogh;ere, &thorn;e fairest &thorn;at he my&yogh;t fynd, and knafe childre
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">&yogh;onge striplynges, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
of &thorn;e same elde; and &thorn;ai ware all cledd in clathes of gold. And &thorn;ase he said ware aungelles. Also he gert
make in &thorn;e forsaid gardyn three faire welles of precious stanes, closed aboute with iasper and cristall, wele
bunden with gold, and o&thorn;er precious stanes. And he gert make cundytes vnder &thorn;e erthe, so &thorn;at, when he wald,
ane of &thorn;ir wellez ran of wyne, ano&thorn;er of mylke, ano&thorn;er of hony, thurgh &thorn;ir forsaid cundytes. And &thorn;is place
called he Paradys. And, when any &yogh;ung bachelere of &thorn;e cuntree come to him, he ledd him in to &thorn;is Paradys and
<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio">schewed him all &thorn;ise forsaid thingez. And he had diuerse mynstralles priuely in hye toure &thorn;at &thorn;ai myght no&yogh;t be
sene, playand on diuerse instrumentez of music. And he said &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware Goddes aungelles, and &thorn;at &thorn;at was
Paradys &thorn;at Godd graunted to &thorn;ase &thorn;at he lufes, sayand on &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Dabo vobis terram fluentem lac et mel</Q>, &thorn;at
es to say, "I sall giffe to &yogh;ow land flowande mylke and hony." And &thorn;an &thorn;is ryche man gafe to &thorn;ise men a maner
of drinke, of whilke &thorn;ai ware drunken alssone; and &thorn;an &thorn;ai ware mare blinded &thorn;an &thorn;ai ware before, and wend
&thorn;ai had bene in full blisse. And he said &thorn;am &thorn;at, if &thorn;ai wald putte &thorn;aim in iuperdy of deed for his sake, when

<PB N="138">
&thorn;ai ware deed, &thorn;ai schuld com in to his Paradys and &thorn;ai schuld euermare be of &thorn;e elde of &thorn;e forsaid damyselles
and &thorn;ai schuld euermare dwell with &thorn;am and haue lyking and dalyaunce of &thorn;am and euermare be maydens, and
after a certayne tyme he schuld putte &thorn;am in a fairer Paradys, whare &thorn;ai schuld see Godd in his maiestee and in
his blisse and ioy. And &thorn;an &thorn;ai graunted at do all &thorn;at he wald bidd &thorn;am do. And &thorn;an he bad &thorn;am ga to swilk a
place and sla swilke a lorde or man of &thorn;e cuntree whilk was his enmy, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld hafe na drede, for, if
&thorn;ai ware deed, &thorn;ai schuld be putte in to &thorn;at Paradys. And &thorn;us gert he sla many lordes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">And &thorn;us wenten many dyuerse lusty bacheleres for to sle grete lordes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e cuntree; and also
many of &thorn;ise men ware slaen in hope to hafe &thorn;is Paradys &thorn;at he hight &thorn;am. And &thorn;us he venged him on his
<MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="folio">enmys thurgh &thorn;is dessayte. And when lordes and riche men of &thorn;e cuntree persayued &thorn;is malice and wyle of
him, &thorn;is Catolonabes, &thorn;ai gadred &thorn;am togyder and assailed &thorn;is castell, and slew Catolonabes, and destruyd all his
ricchess and faire thinges &thorn;at ware in his Paradys, and kest doune his castell; and &yogh;it er &thorn;e welles &thorn;are and sum
other thinges, bot na ricchess. It es no&yogh;t lang sen it was destruyd.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.31" N="31" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.30">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXXI</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the deueles hede in the Valeye Perilous; and of the customes of folk in dyuerse yles that ben abounten in the lordschipe of Prestre John.</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.138.15" CORRESP="Cot.187.1">A LYTILL fra &thorn;at place toward &thorn;e water of Phison es a grete meruaile. For &thorn;are es a vale betwene twa
hilles &thorn;at es foure myle lang; and sum men callez it &thorn;e Vale of Enchaunting, sum &thorn;e Vale of Deuilles,
and sum &thorn;e Vale Perillous. In &thorn;is vale er oft tymes herd many tempestes and voices vggly and hidous,
bathe on nyghtes and on days. And sum tyme &thorn;er es herd noyse as it ware of trumppes and tawburez and of
nakers, as it ware at festez of grete lordez. &THORN;is vale es full of deuilles and all way hase bene; and men saise in &thorn;at
cuntree &thorn;at &thorn;are es ane entree to hell. In &thorn;is vale es mykill gold and siluer; and for to gete &thorn;eroff &thorn;are commez

<PB N="139">
many men, bathe Cristen and haythen, and entres in to &thorn;at vale. Bot &thorn;are commez bot fewe oute agayne, and namely
of mescreauntes
<NOTE N="1"></NOTE>, for all &thorn;ase &thorn;at gase &thorn;ider by cause of couetise er strangled with deuills and fordone. In myddes
of &thorn;e vale vnder a roche es schewed openly &thorn;e heued and &thorn;e visage of a deuill, ri&yogh;t hidous and dredefull to see;
and &thorn;er es na thing sene &thorn;eroff bot &thorn;e heed fra &thorn;e schulders vpward. And &thorn;er es na man in &thorn;is werld, Cristen ne
<MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio">o&thorn;er, &thorn;at ne he schuld hafe grete drede to behald it, it es so horrible and so foule. And he behaldez ilke man so
scharpely and so felly, and his eghen er so fast stirrand and sprenkland as fyre, and be chaungez so oft his
countenaunce, and oute of his mouthe and his neese commez so grete plentee of fyre of diuerse colours with so
grete stynk, &thorn;at na man may suffere it. Bot all way gude Cristen men, &thorn;at er stable in &thorn;e faith, may ga in to &thorn;at
valay withouten grete harme, if &thorn;ai be clene schriffen and blisse &thorn;am with &thorn;e taken of &thorn;e Crosse; for &thorn;an schall
deuils no&yogh;t dere &thorn;am. And if all &thorn;ai eschape withouten harme of body, neuer&thorn;eless &thorn;ai eschape no&yogh;t withouten
grete drede; for fendez apparez to &thorn;am openly and manacez &thorn;am and fliez vp and doune in &thorn;e aer with grete
thunders and leuennynges and hidous tempestez, &thorn;at mykill drede schall &thorn;ai hafe, &thorn;at &thorn;are furth passez als well
gude men as euill, supposand &thorn;at Godd for &thorn;aire alde synnes will perchaunce take wreke on &thorn;am and vengeaunce.
My felawes and I, when we come nere &thorn;at valay and herd speke &thorn;eroff, sum of vs kest in oure hertes to putte vs
all halely in &thorn;e mercy of Godd to passe thurgh &thorn;at valay and sum forsuke it and said &thorn;ai wald no&yogh;t putte &thorn;am in
&thorn;at perill. And &thorn;are was in oure company twa frere meneours of Lumbardy, &thorn;at said &thorn;ai wald ga thurgh &thorn;at
valay, if we wald go with &thorn;am; and so, thurgh comforth of &thorn;ire wordes and &thorn;e excitacioun of &thorn;aim, we schrafe
vs clene and herd messe and comound vs and went in to &thorn;e valay, xiiii. felawes sammen. Bot at &thorn;e commyng
<MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="folio">oute we ware bot ix. We wist neuere what worthed of &thorn;e remenaunt, whedir &thorn;ai ware lost or &thorn;ai turned agayne;
bot we sawe &thorn;am na mare; twa of &thorn;am ware Grekez, and three ware Spanyols. Oure o&thorn;er felawes &thorn;at wald no&yogh;t
passe &thorn;e Valay Perillous went aboute by ano&thorn;er way for to mete vs. And my felawes and I went thurgh &thorn;e valay,
and sawe many meruailous thingez and gold and siluer and precious stanes and many o&thorn;er iowels on ilke a syde
vs, as vs thoght; bot whedir it ware as it semed, or it was bot fantasy, I wate no&yogh;t. Bot for &thorn;e drede &thorn;at we
had, and also for it schuld no&yogh;t lette oure deuocioun, we wald lay hand on na thing &thorn;at we sawe; for we ware
mare deuote &thorn;an &thorn;an euer we ware before or efter, for ferdeness of deuils &thorn;at appered till vs in diuerse figures
and for &thorn;e multitude of deed men bodys &thorn;at lay &thorn;are in oure way. For if twa kynges with &thorn;ire ostez had

<PB N="140">
foghten togider and &thorn;e maste parte of bathe &thorn;e sydez had bene slaen, &thorn;er schuld no&yogh;t hafe bene so grete noumer
of deed bodys as was &thorn;are. And, when I sawe so many bodys ligg &thorn;are, I had grete meruaile because &thorn;ai ware
so hale withouten corrupcioun, and so fresch as &thorn;ai had bene euen new deed. Bot I dare no&yogh;t say &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware all
verray bodys &thorn;at I sawe in &thorn;at valay, bot I trowe &thorn;at fendez gert &thorn;are seme so many bodys for to fere vs with;
for it es no&yogh;t semely &thorn;at so grete a multitude of folk schuld verrayly hafe bene deed &thorn;are so fresch withouten
stynk or corrupcioun. And many of &thorn;ase bodys &thorn;at I sawe &thorn;are semed in clething of Cristen men; bot I trowe
<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio">full wele &thorn;at &thorn;ai come &thorn;ider for couetise of gold and o&thorn;er iowels &thorn;at er in &thorn;at valay, or for fals hert myght no&yogh;t
bere &thorn;e grete drede and fere &thorn;at &thorn;ai had for &thorn;e horrible si&yogh;tes &thorn;at &thorn;ai sawe. And I do &yogh;ow to witte &thorn;at we ware
oft tymes striken doune to &thorn;e erthe with grete hidous blastez of wind and of thouner and o&thorn;er tempestez; bot
thurgh &thorn;e grace of Almyghty Godd we passed thurgh &thorn;at valay hale and sounde.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.14011" CORRESP="Cot.189.22">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;at valay es a grete ile, whare &thorn;e folk &thorn;at wonnez &thorn;erin er als mykill of stature as &thorn;ai ware geauntes
of xxviii. or of xxx. fote lang. Clathez hafe &thorn;ai nane to were, bot skynnez of bestez, whare with &thorn;ai couer &thorn;aire
bodys. Breed ete &thorn;ai nane; bot &thorn;ai ete raw flesh and drinkez mylke, for &thorn;are es grete plentee of bestez.
Housez hafe &thorn;ai nane to dwell in; and &thorn;ai will gladlyer ete mannez flesch &thorn;an any o&thorn;er. &THORN;is ile dare na
pilgrim come in ne nere it, &thorn;aire thankes; for, if &thorn;ai see a schippe in &thorn;e see with men &thorn;erin, &thorn;ai will wade in to
see for to take &thorn;e men to &thorn;aire men. And men talde vs &thorn;at &thorn;are es ano&thorn;er ile be&yogh;ond &thorn;at, whare geauntz er,
mykill mare &thorn;an &thorn;ir, for sum of &thorn;am er fyfty fote lang, sum sexty.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">summe of xlv. fote or of l. fote long, and as somme men seyn, summe of l. cubytes long, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> I had na will to see &thorn;am, for &thorn;er may na
man com in to &thorn;at ile &thorn;at ne he schall alssone be strangled with &thorn;a monstres. In &thorn;ase iles amang &thorn;a geauntz er
schepe als mykill as oxen, bot &thorn;e woll of &thorn;am es grete and sture.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">&thorn;ei beren gret wolle and rough, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Of &thorn;ir schepe hafe I oft sene; and sum men
<MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="folio">hase oft tymes sene of &thorn;ir geauntz take men in &thorn;e see and com to land with twa in &thorn;e ta hand and twa in &thorn;e
to&thorn;er, etand of &thorn;aire flesch rawe.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">etynge hem goynge, all rawe and all quyk, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.140.22" CORRESP="Cot.190.11">&THORN;are
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">The paragraph in the French text (and in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>) omitted here will be found lower down.</NOTE> es ano&thorn;er faire ile and a gude and full of folk, whare &thorn;e maner es swilk &thorn;at, when a womman es new
wedded, scho sall no&yogh;t &thorn;e first nyght lye with hir hushand, bot with ano&thorn;er &yogh;ung man, &thorn;at sall assay hir &thorn;at nyght
and hafe hir maydenhede, takand on &thorn;e morue a certayne monee for his trauaile. And &thorn;are er ordaynd in ilke
a toune certayne &yogh;ung men for to do &thorn;at seruise, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai call Gadlibiriens, &thorn;at es to say, "Foles despaired."
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">Cadeberiz, &thorn;at is to seyne the Foles of Wanhope, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And &thorn;ai say &thorn;are and affermes for sothe &thorn;at it es a full perilous thing to take &thorn;e maydenhede of a mayden; for,

<PB N="141">
as &thorn;ai say, wha so duse, puttez him self in perill of dede. And, if &thorn;e husband of &thorn;e womman fynd hir mayden on
&thorn;e nyght next suand (for perauenture he &thorn;at schuld hafe had hir maydenhede was drunkyn, or for any o&thorn;er skille
did no&yogh;t his deuere to &thorn;e womman), &thorn;an hir hushand sall hafe his actioun agaynes him before &thorn;e iusticez of &thorn;e
land, als fortherly as he had bene aboute for to slae him. Bot after &thorn;e first nyght &thorn;at &thorn;ase wymmen er so
defouled &thorn;ai er kepid so straitely &thorn;at &thorn;ai schall no&yogh;t speke ne com in company of &thorn;ase men.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;at &thorn;ei ben not so hardy to speke with no man, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> I asked &thorn;am what
was &thorn;e cause and &thorn;e skill &thorn;at swilke a custom was vsed &thorn;are. And &thorn;ai talde me &thorn;at in alde tyme sum men ware
deed in &thorn;at cuntree thurgh &thorn;e defloracioun of maydens, for &thorn;ai had within &thorn;am nedders, &thorn;at taanged &thorn;e husbands
<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio">on &thorn;e &yogh;erdez in &thorn;e wymmen bodys; and so ware many men slayne, and &thorn;erfore vsed &thorn;ai &thorn;are &thorn;at custom to make
o&thorn;er men to assay &thorn;e passage before &thorn;ai putted &thorn;am self to &thorn;at auenture.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.141.10" CORRESP="Cot.190.6">Ano&thorn;er ile
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">See above, p. 140, note 4.</NOTE> &thorn;er es southward
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">toward &thorn;e north, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in &thorn;e grete see Occian, whare in er wikked wymmen and fell, &thorn;at in &thorn;aire
eghen has precious stanes growand. And &thorn;ai er of swilke a kynde &thorn;at, if &thorn;ai luke apon a man with ane irous
will,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">with wrathe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> thurgh &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;a stanes &thorn;ai sla him with &thorn;aire lukyng, as &thorn;e basilisc duse.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.141.13" CORRESP="Cot.191.1">Nere &thorn;at ile es ano&thorn;er ile, whare wymmen makez mykill sorowe when &thorn;aire childer er borne, and mykill ioy
when &thorn;at &thorn;ai er deed, and callez &thorn;aire frendez and makez feste and takez &thorn;e deed childe and castez it in a grete
fyre and brynnez it. And wymmen also &thorn;at luffed &thorn;aire husbandez wele, when &thorn;ai er deed, &thorn;ai putte &thorn;am self in
to &thorn;e fire with &thorn;aire childer for to brynne. And it es &thorn;aire opinioun &thorn;are &thorn;at on &thorn;at wise &thorn;ai er purged thurgh &thorn;e
fire, so &thorn;at na corrupcioun neuer efter sall com of &thorn;am, bot, purged and clene of all vice and alkyn deformitee,
&thorn;ai sall passe to &thorn;aire hushandes in &thorn;e to&thorn;er werld. &THORN;e cause why &thorn;ai wepe and makez sorow at &thorn;e birth of &thorn;aire
childer and makez ioy when &thorn;ai dye es for, when &thorn;ai er borne in to &thorn;is werld, &thorn;ai com to sorow and to trauaile,
and, when &thorn;ai dye, &thorn;ai go to &thorn;e ioy of Paradys, whare riuers er of mylke and hony and plentee of all maner of
gudes and lyf withouten sorowe. In &thorn;is ile es euermare &thorn;e kyng made by eleccioun; and &thorn;ai chese no&yogh;t &thorn;e
ricchest man ne &thorn;e nobilest, bot him &thorn;at es best of condiciouns and maste rightwys and trewe &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire
<MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="folio">kyng. And also &thorn;ai luke &thorn;at he be ane aunciene man and no&yogh;t &yogh;ung of age.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">of gret age, and &thorn;at he haue no children, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> In &thorn;at ile also er wonder rightwise
iuggez; for &thorn;ai do resoun and trewth to ilke man, als wele to pouer as to riche, and demez ilke man efter his
trespas and no&yogh;t after his state ne his degree. &THORN;e king also may do na man to deed withouten &thorn;e counsaile and
&thorn;e ascent of all his baronage. And, if it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng do a trespasse, as sla a man or swilke ano&thorn;er notable
thing, he schall be deed &thorn;erfore. Bot he schall no&yogh;t be slaen with mannez hand, bot &thorn;ai schall forbede &thorn;at na
man be so hardy to make him company, ne speke with him, ne com to him, ne giffe him mete ne drink; and so

<PB N="142">
for euen pure nede and hunger and thrist and sorow &thorn;at he schall hafe in his hert he schall dye.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">and so schall he dye in myschef, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;are es nane
spared &thorn;at es taken with a trespas, now&thorn;er for ricches, ne hie state, ne dignite, ne for hie blude, ne for na maner
of gift, &thorn;at ne ilke man schall hafe after his werkes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.142.4" CORRESP="Cot.192.1">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;is ile es ano&thorn;er ile in &thorn;e see, whare es grete plentee of folk. And &thorn;ai ete neuermare flesch of
hares, ne of hennes, ne of geezsse; and no&yogh;t for&thorn;i &thorn;ai hafe many of &thorn;am and bringez vp many of &thorn;am all anely for
&thorn;aire solace and for &thorn;e sight of &thorn;am. Bot &thorn;ai ete flesch of o&thorn;er bestez and drinkez mylke. In &thorn;is ile &thorn;ai wedd
&thorn;aire awen doghter and &thorn;er sisters and &thorn;er sibbe wymmen, and dwellez togyder in a hous ten or twelf or ma.
<MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio">And ilke mannez wyf sall be comoun till o&thorn;er &thorn;at wonnez &thorn;are; and ilkane of &thorn;am takez o&thorn;er wyfez, ane a
nyght, ano&thorn;er ano&thorn;er nyght. And, when any of &thorn;ir wyfes beres a childe, it sall be giffen to him &thorn;at first lay by
hir &thorn;at es &thorn;e moder
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">sche may &yogh;eue it to what man &thorn;at sche list &thorn;at hath companyed with hire, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and so es &thorn;er nane &thorn;at wate whe&thorn;er &thorn;e childe be his or ano&thorn;er mannez. And, if a man
say to &thorn;am &thorn;at on &thorn;is wise may <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">&thorn;ai</SUPPLIED>
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">om. MS.; &yogh;ou, inserted later.</NOTE> fader ano&thorn;er mannez childe, &thorn;ai answere agayne &thorn;at so duse o&thorn;er
men &thorn;aires.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.142.13" CORRESP="Cot.192.16">In &thorn;at cuntree and thurgh oute all Inde es grete plentee of cocodrilles; and it es a maner of neddere lang
of body, as I talde &yogh;owe before. And on nyghtes it es in waters, and on days in &thorn;e erthe in creuicez or in
craggez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">roches and in caues, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and in wynter ete &thorn;ai na mete, bot liggez as &thorn;ai ware half deed.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">as in a drem, as don &thorn;e serpentes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;is nedder will sla men and deuoure
&thorn;am; and, when he etez, he mouez &thorn;e ouer chaft
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">&thorn;e ouer jowe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>. For "chafte" see <HI REND="i">Cursor Mundi</HI>, l. 1073, "wit &thorn;e chafte ban of a ded has (<HI REND="i">sc.</HI> ass)."</NOTE> and no&yogh;t &thorn;e neder, and he has na tung. In &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;ai
sawe ilke &yogh;ere a maner of sede, and it growez vp in smale bruschez; and of &thorn;aim &thorn;ai gader boumbe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">cotoun, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in grete
quantitee. &THORN;are es also a maner of tree, &thorn;e whilk es so hard and so strang &thorn;at, if a man brynne it and couer &thorn;e
coles &thorn;eroff with aschez, &thorn;ai will hald in quikk a twelfmonth and mare. &THORN;is tree hase wonder many leefes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">as the gynypre hath, adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And
&thorn;er er sum treez &thorn;at will now&thorn;er brynne ne rote. &THORN;are er also hesils
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">note trees, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at berez nuttez as grete as a mannez
heued. &THORN;are er
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">&thorn;are er &hellip; cuntreez, in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text) forming part of the passage on cotton (boumbe) higher up.</NOTE> treez &thorn;at berez cotoun; and so es &thorn;are in many o&thorn;er cuntreez. And &thorn;are er bestez whilk &thorn;ai
call orafles; and in Araby &thorn;ai call &thorn;am gyrfauntz. And it es a faire beste, wele dappled, of &thorn;e height of a grete
<MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="folio">stede or hier; and his nekk es xx. cubites lang, and his crupoun and his taile er lyk to a hert. And he may wele
ynogh stand on &thorn;e erthe and luke ouer a hie hous. In &thorn;at cuntree also er many cameliouns,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="11">camles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e whilk es a lytill

<PB N="143">
beste of &thorn;e mykilnes of a raa
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">a goot &thorn;at is wylde, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and it now&thorn;er etez ne drinkez, bot gase all way with &thorn;e mouth open, for it liffez
with &thorn;e aer. And it chaungez oft &thorn;e colour in all maner of colours, safe white and reed, for nowe it will be of a
colour, and sodaynely of ano&thorn;er. <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW" SOURCE="cot">&THORN;ere
<NOTE N="2">From <ABBR>C</ABBR>.; omitted in <ABBR>E</ABBR>.</NOTE> ben also in &thorn;at contree passynge grete serpentes, summe of vi<HI REND="sup">xx</HI> fote
long, and &thorn;ai ben of dyuerse coloures, as rayed, rede, grene and &yogh;alowe, blewe and blake, and all spekelede.</SUPPLIED>
&THORN;are er also nedderes with cambez on &thorn;aire heeds, as it ware a cokk; and &thorn;ai er of foure fote
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">a iiii. fadme (<HI REND="i">sc.</HI> fathom), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> lang or mare,
and gase on fete nerehand vprightes. And &thorn;ai er comounly dwelland in rochez and cragges and hillez. And
&thorn;ai er euermare gapand, redy for to schote &thorn;aire venym.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">And &thorn;ei han all wey the throte open, of whens &thorn;ei droppen venym all weys, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;er er also wilde swyne, als grete as oxen and
dappeld and spotted, as it ware founez of daes. <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">And
<NOTE N="5">From <ABBR>C</ABBR>., omitted in <ABBR>E</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;ere ben also vrchounes als grete as wylde swyn here;
wee clepen hem <NAME>Porcz de Spyne</NAME>.</SUPPLIED> And &thorn;are er lyouns all whyte, grete and strang. And &thorn;are er also o&thorn;er
maner of bestez, als grete as stedez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">als grete and more gretter &thorn;an is a destrere, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;ai er called Louherans, and sum
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">and sum &hellip; Toutes, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> callez &thorn;am Toutez, and sum
Odenthos. &THORN;ai hafe blak heuedes and three hornes euen in &thorn;e frunt, als scharpe as any swerde; and &thorn;e bodys
of &thorn;am er &yogh;alow.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">sclendre, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;ai er wonder cruell bestez, and &thorn;ai chace and slaez &thorn;e olyfaunt. &THORN;are es also o&thorn;er
maner of bestez noyand and fell, of &thorn;e mykilnes of beres; and &thorn;aire heuedes er lyke bare
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> boar; han the hed lych a bore, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> heueds. &THORN;ai hafe sex
fete, and on ilk a fote er twa nailes, grete and lang and scharpe. And of body &thorn;ai er lyke vnto beres, bot &thorn;aire
<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio">tailes er lyke lyoun tailes. &THORN;are er also ratouns mare &thorn;an
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="10">myse als grete as houndes, and &yogh;alowe myse als grete as ravenes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> hundes; and geessez all reed, oute taken &thorn;e heued
and &thorn;e nekk, &thorn;e whilk er blakk, and &thorn;ai er mykill mare &thorn;an oure geezse. &THORN;are er also many o&thorn;er maner
of bestez in &thorn;at cuntree and in cuntreez &thorn;are aboute, of whilke it ware to lang to tell all the kyndez and &thorn;e
schappez.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.32" N="32" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.33">
<PB N="144">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXXII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the godenesse of the folk of the yle of Bragman; of Kyng Alisandre; and wherfore the Emperour of Ynde is clept Prestre John.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.144.4" CORRESP="Cot.194.6">BE&YOGH;OND &thorn;is ile es ano&thorn;er ile gude and grete and full of folk; and &thorn;ai er gude folk and trewe and of
gude faith and gude lyf after &thorn;e maner of &thorn;aire conuersacioun. And if all it be swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai er na Cristen
men, no&yogh;t for&thorn;i by lawe of kynde &thorn;ai liffe a commendable lyf, and er folk of gude vertuz and fleez all
vicez and synne and malice, and &thorn;ai kepe wele &thorn;e ten commaundementz. For &thorn;ai er now&thorn;er proude, ne couetous,
ne licherous, ne glotouns; and &thorn;ai do noght to ano&thorn;er man bot as &thorn;ai wald ware done to &thorn;aitn self. &THORN;ai sette
no&yogh;t by ricchesse of &thorn;is werld, ne by hafyng of erthely gudes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">&thorn;ei &yogh;if no charge of aveer ne of ricchesse, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;ai make na lesyngs, ne sweres nane athes for
nathing, bot symply saise it es or it es no&yogh;t; for &thorn;ai say he &thorn;at sweres es aboute to begile his neghboure. &THORN;is
ile &thorn;at &thorn;is folk dwellez in es called &thorn;e ile of Bragmans; and sum men callez it &thorn;e Land of Fayth. And thurgh
&thorn;is ile rynnez a grete riuer, &thorn;e whilk es called Thebe. And generally all &thorn;e men of &thorn;at ile and of o&thorn;er iles &thorn;arby
er trewer and ri&yogh;twiser &thorn;an er in o&thorn;er cuntreez. In &thorn;is ile er na thefez, ne men murthereres, ne commoun
wymmen, ne lyers, ne beggers; bot &thorn;ai er als clene men of conuersacioun and als gude as &thorn;ai ware men of
<MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="folio">religioun. And, for als mykill as &thorn;ai er so trew folk and so gude, &thorn;er es neuermare in &thorn;at cuntree now&thorn;er thunner
ne leuenyng, haile ne snawe, ne o&thorn;er tempestez of ill weders; ne hunger, ne pestilence, ne were, ne o&thorn;er
tribulaciouns commez &thorn;are nane amanges &thorn;am, as duse amanges vs because of oure synne. And &thorn;erfore it semez
&thorn;at Godd luffez &thorn;am wele and es wele payd of &thorn;aire liffyng and of &thorn;aire fayth. &THORN;ai trowe in Godd &thorn;at made all
thing, and him &thorn;ai wirschepe at all &thorn;aire myght; and all erthely thingez &thorn;ai sette at no&yogh;t. And &thorn;ai liffe so
temperately and so soberly in meet and drink &thorn;at &thorn;ai er &thorn;e langest liffand folk of &thorn;e werld; and many of &thorn;aim
diez for pure elde withouten sekeness, when &thorn;e kynde failez.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">whan nature fayleth hem for elde, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE></SEG></P>

<PB N="145">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.145.1" CORRESP="Cot.195.11">Qwhen Alysaunder &thorn;e conquerour reyned and conquerde all &thorn;e werld, in &thorn;at tyme he come by &thorn;at ile and
sent his lettres to &thorn;aim &thorn;at dwelled in &thorn;at ile and said &thorn;at he wald com and destruy &thorn;aire land, bot if &thorn;ai wald
be vnder his subieccioun, as o&thorn;ir landes ware. And &thorn;ai wrate lettres agayne till him in &thorn;is maner: "Qwhat thing
myght suffice to &thorn;at man, to wham all &thorn;e werld may no&yogh;t suffice? &THORN;ou schall fynd na thing with vs wharfore
&thorn;ou schuld werray apon vs; for we hafe na ricchesse of &thorn;is werld, ne nane couetez for to hafe. All &thorn;e placez
of oure land and all oure gudes mobill and vnmobill er commoun till ilke man. All oure ricches &thorn;at we hafe es
oure meet and oure drink, wharwith we sustene oure bodys; oure tresoure es peess and accorde and luffe &thorn;at es
amanges vs. In steed of aray of oure bodys we vse a vile clathe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">a sely lityll clout, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> for to couer with oure caytiff carayne. Oure
<MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio">wyfez also er no&yogh;t proudely ne richely arayd to plesing of oure eghen, for we hald awilk enournement grete foly
to putte to &thorn;e wricched body mare bewtee &thorn;an Godd has kyndely giffen it; oure wyfez couetez na mare bewtee
&thorn;an kynde has giffen &thorn;am. Oure land seruez vs of twa thinges, &thorn;at es to say of oure lyfelade, whilk we liffe
with, and of sepulture, when we er deed. And ay to &thorn;is tyme hafe we bene in peess, of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ou will now
dispoile vs and disherit vs. A kyng we hafe amanges vs, no&yogh;t for to do right to any man, for amanges vs na man
duse wrang till o&thorn;er bot all anely to lere vs to be obedient. Iuggez nedez vs nane to hafe amanges vs, for nane
of vs duse till o&thorn;er bot as he wald ware done till him. For&thorn;i fra vs may &thorn;ou refe na thing bot peess, &thorn;e whilk
hase ay vnto &thorn;is tyme bene amanges vs." And, when kynge Alysaunder had sene &thorn;ir lettres and redd &thorn;am, him
thoght in his hert &thorn;at it ware grete harme and grete vnmannhede to grefe swilk folk or truble &thorn;am; and he
graunt &thorn;am suertee of peess, and bad &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld continue furth &thorn;aire gude maners and vse &thorn;aire gude
custommes withouten drede hauyng of him, for he schuld no&yogh;t dere &thorn;am.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.145.20" CORRESP="Cot.196.12">Nere be syde &thorn;at ile es ano&thorn;er ile &thorn;at men callez Oxidrace, and ano&thorn;er &thorn;at es called Gynoscriphe, whare
for &thorn;e maste party &thorn;ai hald &thorn;e maneres of &thorn;e Bragmans, liffand innocently in lewtee and in luffe and charitee ilk
ane till oper; and &thorn;ai ga euermare naked. In to &thorn;ir iles come Alysaunder &thorn;e conquerour; and, fra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at
<MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="folio">he sawe &thorn;aire conuersacioun and &thorn;aire lewtee and luffe ilkane till o&thorn;er, he said he wald noght grefe &thorn;am, bot
bad &thorn;am <SUPPLIED REASON="scribal omission" RESP="GW">ask</SUPPLIED> of him what so &thorn;ai wald, and he schuld graunt &thorn;am. And &thorn;ai answerd and sayd &thorn;at werldly
ricchesse wald &thorn;ai nane asche ne hafe, bot all anely meet and drink wharwith &thorn;e feble body myght be susteynd.
For &thorn;e gudez and &thorn;e ricches of &thorn;is werld, quod &thorn;ai, er no&yogh;t lastand bot dessayuable. Bot and he myght giffe
&thorn;am thinges &thorn;at ware aylastand and no&yogh;t dedly,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">but &yogh;if it were in his powere to make hem immortall, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;an wald &thorn;ai thank him mykill. &THORN;e kyng answerd &thorn;am and
sayd &thorn;at &thorn;at my&yogh;t he no&yogh;t do, for he was dedly
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> mortal; mortell, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> him self, als wele as &thorn;ai. "Qwhare to &thorn;an," quod &thorn;ai, "gaders

<PB N="146">
&thorn;ou &thorn;e ricches of &thorn;is werld, &thorn;at er transitory and may no&yogh;t last; bot, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou will or no&yogh;t, &thorn;ai schall leve
<NOTE N="1">leve, <ABBR>C</ABBR>., om. <ABBR>E</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e
or elles &thorn;ou &thorn;aim, as it has befallen to &thorn;aim &thorn;at ware before &thorn;e. And oute of &thorn;is werld schall &thorn;ou bere na
thing with &thorn;e, bot naked as &thorn;ou come hider sall &thorn;ou passe heyne, and &thorn;i flesch sall turne agayne to erthe &thorn;at &thorn;ou
was made off. And &thorn;erfore schuld &thorn;ou think &thorn;at na thing may last euermare, bot Godd &thorn;at made all &thorn;e
werld. And &yogh;it, no&yogh;t hafand reward
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> regard.</NOTE> hereto, &thorn;ou ert so presumptuous and so proude &thorn;at, ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ou ware Godd,
&thorn;ou wald make all &thorn;e werld subiecte vnto &thorn;e, and &thorn;ou knawez no&yogh;t &thorn;e terme of &thorn;i lyf ne &thorn;e day ne &thorn;e houre."
When Alisaundre had herd &thorn;ir wordes and swilke o&thorn;er, he had grete wondre &thorn;eroff and was gretely compuncte
and went fra &thorn;am and did &thorn;am na disese. And if all it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ise maner of folk hafe no&yogh;t &thorn;e articles of oure
<MILESTONE N="122b" UNIT="folio">beleue, neuer&thorn;eles I trowe &thorn;at for &thorn;aire gude fayth &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe of kynde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">for hire gude feyth naturell, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;aire gude entent Godd luffez &thorn;am
wele and haldez him wele payd of &thorn;aire liffing, as he did of Iob, &thorn;e whilke was a payen, and no&yogh;t for&thorn;i his dedez
ware acceptable to Godd as of his leel seruandes. And if all &thorn;are be many diuerse lawes and diuerse sectez in
&thorn;e werld, neuer &thorn;e latter I trowe &thorn;at Godd euermare luffez wele all &thorn;ase &thorn;at luffez him in sothefastness and
seruez him mekely and trewly and settez no&yogh;t by &thorn;e vayne glory of &thorn;e werld, as &thorn;is folke duse and as Iob did.
And &thorn;erfore said oure Lord by &thorn;e prophete Ysai,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Hosea viii. 12, but with "scribam."</NOTE> <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Ponam eis multiplices leges meas</Q>, &thorn;at es to say, "I schall putte
to &thorn;aim my lawes manyfalde."
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">And also in another place <HI REND="i">Qui totum, etc.</HI> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text), adds <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And also in &thorn;e Gospell he saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Alias oues habeo, que non sunt ex hoc ouili</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">John x. 16.</NOTE>
&thorn;at es to say, "I hafe o&thorn;er schepe, whilk er no&yogh;t of &thorn;is falde," as if he said, "O&thorn;er seruandes I hafe &thorn;an er vnder
Cristen lawe." And hereto accordes &thorn;e visioun &thorn;at was schewed to saynt Petre in &thorn;e citee of Iaffe, how ane
aungell come fra heuen and broght with him all maner of bestez and neddres and fewles, and bad him take and
eet; and sayne Petre answerd and said, "I ete neuer of vnclene bestez." And &thorn;e aungell said agayne to him, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Quod
Deus mundauit, tu ne immundum dixeris</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="7">Acts x. 15.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "Call &thorn;ou no&yogh;t vnclene &thorn;at &thorn;at Godd hase clensed." &THORN;is
was done in takyn
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="8">altered to "taknyng," with "sould no&yogh;t" in the margin, before "despise."</NOTE> &thorn;at men despise na men for &thorn;e diuersetee of &thorn;aire lawes. For we wate no&yogh;t wham Godd
<MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="folio">luffez ne wham he hatez; and &thorn;erfore,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="9">And for &thorn;at ensample, whan men seyn <HI REND="i">De profundis</HI>, &thorn;ei seyn it in comoun and in generall with &thorn;e Cristene, <HI REND="i">pro animabus, &amp;c.</HI> (<HI REND="i">cf.</HI> French text), <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> when I pray for &thorn;e deed and sayse my <TITLE LANG="lat">De profundis</TITLE>, I say it for all
Cristen saules and also for all &thorn;e saulez &thorn;at er to be prayd fore. And of &thorn;is folk I say &thorn;us mykill, &thorn;at I trowe
&thorn;ai er full acceptable to Godd, &thorn;ai er so trew and so gude. And &thorn;are er many prophetez amanges &thorn;am and hase
bene of alde tyme; for in &thorn;ir iles was sum tyme &thorn;e incarnacioun of Criste prophecied, how he schuld be borne
of a mayden, &yogh;a iii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> &yogh;ere and mare before &thorn;e tyme of his incarnacioun. And &thorn;ai trowe wele &thorn;e incarnacioun of
Criste; bot &thorn;ai knawe no&yogh;t &thorn;e maner of his passioun.</SEG></P>

<PB N="147">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.147.1" CORRESP="Cot.198.6">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;ir iles es ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;at es called Pytan, whare &thorn;e folk now&thorn;er tillez ne sawez na land, ne now&thorn;er
etes ne drinkez. And neuer&thorn;eless &thorn;ai er ri&yogh;t faire folk and wele coloured and wele schapen after &thorn;e stature &thorn;at
&thorn;ai er off; for &thorn;ai er lytill, lyke dwerghs, sum what mare &thorn;an &thorn;e pigmens. &THORN;is folk liffes with &thorn;e smell of wylde
appels &thorn;at growez &thorn;are; and, if &thorn;ai gang owere ferre fra hame, &thorn;ai take with &thorn;am of &thorn;ase appels, for alssone as
&thorn;ai forga &thorn;e smell of &thorn;am &thorn;ai dye. &THORN;is folk es no&yogh;t full resonable, bot ri&yogh;t symple and as it ware bestez.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.147.7" CORRESP="Cot.198.16">&THORN;are nere es ano&thorn;er ile, whare &thorn;e folk er all full of fe&thorn;ers and rugh,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">ben all skynned rough heer, as a rough best, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> oute taken &thorn;e visage and &thorn;e palmez of
&thorn;e hend. &THORN;ise men gase als wele apon
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">vnder, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;e water as apon &thorn;e land; and &thorn;ai ete flesh and fisch rae. In &thorn;is ile es
a grete riuere &thorn;e brede of twa myle; and it es called Wymare.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">a ii. myle and an half of brede, &thorn;at is clept Buemare, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Be&yogh;ond
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">This sentence is translated literally in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;at riuer es a grete wilderness, as men
talde me, for I sawe it no&yogh;t ne come no&yogh;t be&yogh;ond &thorn;e riuere. Bot men &thorn;at dwellez nere &thorn;e riuer talde vs &thorn;at in
<MILESTONE N="123b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ase desertes er &thorn;e treesse of &thorn;e Sonne and &thorn;e Mone, whilk spakk till kyng Alisaunder and talde him of his deed.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> death; dethe, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>
And men saise &thorn;at folke &thorn;at kepez &thorn;a treesse etes of &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;am and of &thorn;e baume &thorn;at growez &thorn;are and &thorn;ai
liffe iiii<HI REND="sup">c</HI> &yogh;ere or fyfe thurgh &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;at fruyt and of &thorn;at baume. For &thorn;are growez grete plentee of baume
and nowere whare elles &thorn;at I couthe here off, oute taken in Egipte besyde Babiloyne, as I talde &yogh;owe before.
My felawes and I wald fayne hafe gane &thorn;ider; bot, as men talde vs, a hundreth thousand men of armes schuld
vnnethez passe &thorn;at wilderness because of &thorn;e grete multitude of wilde bestez &thorn;at er in &thorn;at wilderness, as dragouns
and diuerse maners of nedders and o&thorn;er rauyschand bestez, &thorn;at slaez and deuourez all &thorn;at &thorn;ai may get. In &thorn;is
forsaid ile er many olyfauntz all whyt and sum all blewe and of o&thorn;er colour withouten nowmer; &thorn;are er also
many unicornes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="6">white olifantes withouten nombre and of vnycornes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and lyouns and many o&thorn;er hidous bestez. Many o&thorn;er iles &thorn;er er in &thorn;e lordschepe of Prestre
Iohn, and many meruailez and also mykill ricches and nobillay of tresour and precious stane and o&thorn;er iowailes,
&thorn;e whllk ware ower lang to tell.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.147.21" CORRESP="Cot.199.9">Now will I tell &yogh;ow why &thorn;is emperour es called Prestre Iohn. &THORN;are was sum time ane emperour in &thorn;at land
whilk was a noble prince and a do&yogh;ty; and he had many knyghtez with him &thorn;at ware cristned, as he hase &thorn;at
now es emperour &thorn;are. And on a tyme &thorn;is emperour thoght &thorn;at he wald see &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e seruice in Cristen
<MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio">kirkez. And &thorn;at tyme occupied Cristen men many cuntreez toward &thorn;ase partiez, &thorn;at es to say, Turky, Surry,
Tartary, Ierusalem, Palestyne, Araby, Halope and all Egipte. And so it fell &thorn;at &thorn;is emperour and a Cristen
knyght with him come in to a kirke in Egipte apon a Seterday in Whisson woke, when &thorn;e bischope gaffe ordres.

<PB N="148">
And &thorn;e emperour beheld &thorn;e seruice and &thorn;e maner of &thorn;e makyng of prestez, how sollempnely and how bisily and
deuotely &thorn;ai ware ordaynd. And &thorn;an he asked &thorn;e knyght &thorn;at was with him what maner of folk &thorn;ase ware &thorn;at
ware so ordayned and what &thorn;ai hight; and he said &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware prestez. And &thorn;an &thorn;e emperour said he wald na
mare be called kyng ne emperour bot preste, and also he wald hafe &thorn;e name of &thorn;e first preste &thorn;at come oute of
&thorn;e kirke. So it fell &thorn;at &thorn;e first preste &thorn;at come first oute of &thorn;e kirke hight Iohn; and &thorn;arfore &thorn;at emperour and
all o&thorn;er emperoures seyne hase bene called Prestre John, &thorn;at es als mykill at say as Preste Iohn. In &thorn;e land of
Prestre Iohn er many gude Cristen men and wele liffand, and men of gude fayth and of gude lawe, and namely
of men of &thorn;e same cuntree. And &thorn;ai hafe prestez amanges &thorn;am &thorn;at singez &thorn;am messez; bot &thorn;ai make &thorn;e
sacrement of leuaynd breed, as &thorn;e Grekez dose. And also &thorn;ai say no&yogh;t &thorn;aire messez in all thingez as oure prestez
duse; bot &thorn;ai say all anely &thorn;e <TITLE LANG="lat">Pater Noster</TITLE> and &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e consecracioun with whilk &thorn;e sacrement es made,
as sayne Tbomas &thorn;e apostill taght &thorn;am in alde tyme. Bot of &thorn;e ordynauncez and addiciouns of &thorn;e courte of
<MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio">Rome whilk oure prestez vsez can &thorn;ai no&yogh;t.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.33" N="33" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.34">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXXIII</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the hilles of gold that pissemyres kepen; and of the iiii. flodes that comen from Paradys terrestre.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.148.15" CORRESP="Cot.200.5">TOWARD &thorn;e este fra &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn es ane ile mykill and large and gude, &thorn;e whilk es called
Taprobane. And in &thorn;at ile es a noble king and a riche, whilk es subiecte vnto Prestre Iohn. &THORN;is
kyng es chosen by eleccioun. In &thorn;is ile er twa someres and twa wyntres in a &yogh;ere, and heruest also
twys in &thorn;e &yogh;ere. And all &thorn;e tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere er &thorn;aire gardynes flurisched and &thorn;aire mydews grene. In &thorn;is ile es
gude folk dwelland and resonable; and &thorn;er er many gude Cristen men amangez &thorn;am &thorn;at er so riche &thorn;at &thorn;ai knawe
nane end of &thorn;aire gudes. In alde tyme, when men went fra &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn vnto &thorn;is forsaid ile, &thorn;ai vsed
swilk maner of schippez &thorn;at &thorn;aim behoued nedez be in sayling &thorn;ider xx. dayes
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">xxiii. dayes or more, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; bot in swilke maner of schippes
as men vsez nowe men may saile it in seuen days. And as &thorn;ai saile &thorn;ai may oft tymez see &thorn;e ground of &thorn;e see in
diuerse placez, for it es no&yogh;t full depe.</SEG></P>

<PB N="149">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.149.1" CORRESP="Cot.200.19">Nere &thorn;is ile toward este er twa iles, of whilk &thorn;e tane es called Oriell and &thorn;e to&thorn;er Arget; in &thorn;ir twa iles
all &thorn;e erthe es full of myne of gold and siluer. And &thorn;ai er anentz &thorn;e Reed See, whare it entrez in to &thorn;e grete
see Occean. In &thorn;ase iles may men see nerehand na sternes schynand, bot ane &thorn;at &thorn;ai call Canapos; ne &thorn;e
moone may no&yogh;t be sene &thorn;ere, bot in &thorn;e secund quartere. In &thorn;e forsaid ile of Taprobane er grete hilles of gold,
&thorn;e whilk pissemyres kepez bisily and pures &thorn;e gold and disseuerez &thorn;e fyne gold fra &thorn;e vnfyne. And &thorn;ase
<MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="folio">pissemyres er als grete as hundes er here, so &thorn;at na man dare com nere &thorn;ese hilles for drede &thorn;at &thorn;ase pissemyres
schuld assaile &thorn;am; no&yogh;t for&thorn;i men getez of &thorn;at gold by sleyghtez. For &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e pissemyres es &thorn;at, when
&thorn;e wedir es hate, &thorn;ai will hyde &thorn;am in &thorn;e erthe fra vndrun of &thorn;e day til efter noone; and &thorn;an &thorn;e men of &thorn;at
cuntree commez with camelles and dromedaries and horsese, and chargez &thorn;am with of &thorn;at gold, and gase away
&thorn;erwith are &thorn;e mowres
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> mires; pissemyres, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> com oute of &thorn;aire holes. O&thorn;er tymes of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, when &thorn;e wedir es no&yogh;t hate ne mowres
hydez &thorn;aim no&yogh;t in &thorn;e erthe, &thorn;ai vse ano&thorn;er wyle for to get &thorn;is gold with. For &thorn;ai take meres &thorn;at hase &yogh;ung
fooles and lays apon ayther syde of &thorn;ir meres a tome vessell
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">voyde vesselles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> and &thorn;e mouth vpward trayland nere &thorn;e erthe and
latez &thorn;am furth arely at morne to &thorn;aire pasture aboute &thorn;e hillez whare &thorn;e gold es and haldez &thorn;e foolez at hame.
And &thorn;an &thorn;ir pissemyres, when &thorn;ai see &thorn;e toome vessellez, &thorn;ai ga and fillez &thorn;am with gold; for it es &thorn;e kynde
of &thorn;e pissemyre to lefe na thing void besyde &thorn;am, now&thorn;er hole ne creuice ne nano&thorn;er thing &thorn;at ne &thorn;ai will fill it.
And when men trowez &thorn;at &thorn;e meres er full charged with &thorn;e gold, &thorn;ai late &thorn;e fooles furth, &thorn;e whilk nyez after
&thorn;aire moderes, and &thorn;an &thorn;e meres herez &thorn;aire foolez nye and hiez &thorn;am fast to &thorn;am wele charged with gold. And
on &thorn;is wyse &thorn;ai get grete plentee of &thorn;is gold; for &thorn;e pissemyres will wele suffer all maner of bestez besyde
&thorn;am bot man.</SEG></P>
<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio">
<P>Be&yogh;ond &thorn;ir ilez
<NOTE RESP="DR" N="3">The following long passage about the island of Thule and a miracle of St. Thomas of Canterbury (Be&yogh;ond &thorn;ir ilez &hellip; ferrest end of &thorn;e werld) is unique to <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Egerton 1982">E</ABBR>. Warner does not include it in the body of his text, printing it instead in his commentary (p. 220).</NOTE> toward &thorn;e este es &yogh;it ano&thorn;er ile, &thorn;at es called Tile; and it es &thorn;e ferrest ile of &thorn;e werld inhabited with men. Of &thorn;is ile spekez the poete and saise, <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Tibi seruiet vltima Tile</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Virgil, Georg. i. 30.</NOTE> "To &thorn;e," he saise, "sall serue Tile, &thorn;e ferrest ile of the werld." At &thorn;e &yogh;onder syde of &thorn;is ile toward &thorn;e est rynnez a grete water, be&yogh;ond &thorn;e whilk es no&yogh;t bot waste land and wildernes. In &thorn;at wildernes es na thing dwelland bot dragouns and o&thorn;er wilde bestez, cruell and fell. Oute of &thorn;is ilke wildernes &thorn;are was sum tyme wont for to com ilke a &yogh;ere owere &thorn;e grete water in to &thorn;is forsaid ile a grete multitude of cruell bestez, &thorn;e whilk did mykill harme are &thorn;ai went agayne. Fore &thorn;ai wald sum &yogh;ere wiry i<HI REND="sup">m</HI> men and wymmen and sum tyme ma. And &thorn;ir bestez ware schapen on &thorn;is wise. Behind &thorn;ai ware schapen lyke horsez, and all &thorn;e for&thorn;ermare party was lyke vnto lyouns. And &thorn;ir bestez ware so cruell and so swift of fote &thorn;at &thorn;er my&yogh;t na man flee fra &thorn;am, ne agaynstand &thorn;am. Bot &thorn;e commyng of &thorn;ir bestez in to &thorn;is ile was restreyned by a myracle of sayn Thomas of Caunterbiry, so &thorn;at sen &thorn;at tyme hiderward &thorn;er come nane of &thorn;ase bestez on &thorn;is syde &thorn;at water. And &thorn;is myracle will I tell &yogh;ow after &thorn;at I hafe herd and sene writen in diuerse bukes. &THORN;are was on a tyme a Cristen kyng of &thorn;at ile, as &thorn;er es &yogh;it. So it fell &thorn;at &thorn;is kyng was greeffe seke and was lyke as he schuld hafe died within &thorn;e thridd day. And it hapned &thorn;at &thorn;e ercebischepe of &thorn;e land was &thorn;are with &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at same tyme, and he enioyned all men &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld fast &thorn;a three days and pray deuotely vnto Godd &thorn;at he wald [grant] &thorn;am &thorn;at grace &thorn;at &thorn;aire kyng myght liffe and hafe his hele ay till his son and his ayre ware of elde, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;at tyme was bot a &yogh;ung childe and no&yogh;t hable ne sufficeaunt for to gouern &thorn;e rewme. &THORN;ai fasted and &thorn;ai prayed, bot &thorn;e kyng mendid no&yogh;t, bot his sekeness encressed ay mare and mare till all men wend he had bene euen at &thorn;e dying. And, as he lay in transing and now&thorn;ermyght speke ne fully vnderstand what o&thorn;er men said aboute him, sayn Thomas of Caunterbiry appered vntill him. And he held furth his hand to &thorn;e kyng as he was dyand and blissed him with &thorn;e takne of &thorn;e Crosse, and bad &thorn;at he schuld no&yogh;t drede him. And &thorn;an alssone &thorn;e kyng began to gader his spiritz agayne and answerd to sayne Thomas, "Lord," quod he, "now &thorn;at I see &thorn;is glorious takne of lyf with whilk &thorn;ou hase blissed me, I hafe na drede. Bot I beseke &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou will tell me what &thorn;ou ert, &thorn;at &thorn;us has comforthed me in my nede." "I was," quod he, "sum tyme arcebischope of &thorn;e citee of Caunterbiry in Bretayne &thorn;e mare, wham &thorn;e kyng of &thorn;at land ouercommen with wikked counsaile, gert wrangwisely do to deed. And now &thorn;ou seez me here, in &thorn;e same fourme and &thorn;e same stature &thorn;at I was in &thorn;e werld liffand, for to bring &thorn;e hele and for &thorn;e mynde of me schuld be had in &thorn;i rewme to &thorn;e wirschippe and louyng of oure Saueour. And also&thorn;ase cruell bestez &thorn;at ware wont ilke a &yogh;ere for to comme owere &thorn;e riuer in to &thorn;i land and deuoured &thorn;i men schall neuer fra &thorn;is tyme forward comme on &thorn;is syde of &thorn;e water. And &thorn;at all &thorn;is &thorn;at I hete &thorn;e es soth, I giffe &thorn;e &thorn;is takne &thorn;at, what tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou gers make a kirk in &thorn;i rewme in mynde of me, alssone as &thorn;e first stane es layd in &thorn;e grund &thorn;eroff &thorn;ou schal be all hale." And, when he had said &thorn;ir wordez, he vanyscht away, and &thorn;e kyng reuertid oute of tanssing and talde &thorn;am all his vision; and &thorn;ai ware wonder ioyfull and fayne. And &thorn;anne &thorn;e king commaundid &thorn;am &thorn;at in all &thorn;e haste &thorn;ai myght &thorn;ai schuld gegynne to bigg a kirk in &thorn;e wirschepe of sayne Thomas. And arely on &thorn;e morue &thorn;ai hyred mazsouns and beganne to bigg &thorn;is kirk. And, alssone as &thorn;e ercebischope had layd &thorn;e first stane, &thorn;e kyng rase oute of his bedd als hale as euer he was and went and helped &thorn;am for to wirk with his awen handes. And afterward he sent vnto Caunterbiry of &thorn;e grettest lordes of his rewme with riche giftes and noble of gold and precious stanes to wirschepe with and enourne &thorn;e schryne of &thorn;is haly martir. And &thorn;ase lordes talde &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware twa &yogh;ere and mare are &thorn;ai myght wynne til Caunterbiry fra &thorn;aire awen cuntree, what for &thorn;e lang way and what for &thorn;e empediment &thorn;at &thorn;ai had by cause of waters and wikked wedirs. Here may &yogh;e see how glorious &thorn;is martir es in heuen, whas vertuz Godd wald publisch and schew in &thorn;e ferrest end of &thorn;e werld.</P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.149.20" CORRESP="Cot.201.26">Be&yogh;ond &thorn;ir ilez &thorn;at I hafe talde &yogh;ow off and &thorn;e desertez of &thorn;e lordschepe of Prestre Iohn, to ga euen est, es
na land inhabited, as I said before, bot wastez and wildernessez and grete rochez and mountaynes and a myrk
land, whare na man may see, nyght ne day, as men of &thorn;as cuntreez talde vs.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="5">as &thorn;ei of the contree seyn, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And &thorn;at mirk land and &thorn;ase
desertez laste ri&yogh;t to Paradyse terrestre, whare in Adam and Eue ware putte; bot &thorn;ai ware &thorn;are bot a lytill
while. And &thorn;at place es toward &thorn;e este at &thorn;e &thorn;e begynnyng of &thorn;e erthe. Bot &thorn;at es no&yogh;t oure este, whare &thorn;e sonne
risez till vs; for, when &thorn;e sonne risez in &thorn;ase cuntreez, &thorn;an es it midnyght in oure cuntree, because of &thorn;e

<PB N="150">
roundness of &thorn;e erthe. For, as I said before, Godd made &thorn;e erthe all rounde in myddez of &thorn;e firmament. Bot
&thorn;e hillez and &thorn;e valays &thorn;at er now on &thorn;e erthe er no&yogh;t bot of Noe flude, thurgh &thorn;e whilk &thorn;e tendre erthe was
remowed fra his place and &thorn;are become a valay, and &thorn;e hard erthe habade still and &thorn;are er now hilles.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.150.4" CORRESP="Cot.202.10">Off Paradys can I no&yogh;t speke properly, for I hafe no&yogh;t bene &thorn;are; and &thorn;at forthinkez me.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">It is fer be&yogh;onde; and &thorn;at forthinketh (<HI REND="i">sc.</HI> repenteth) me; and also I was not worthi, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> Bot als mykill
as I hafe herd of wyse men and men of credence of &thorn;ase cuntreez, I will tell &yogh;ow. Paradys terrestre, as men
saise, es &thorn;e hiest land of &thorn;e werld; and it es so hye &thorn;at it touchez nere to &thorn;e cercle of &thorn;e moone. For it es so
hye &thorn;at Noe flode myght no&yogh;t com &thorn;erto whilk flude couerd all &thorn;e erthe bot it. Paradys es closed all aboute
<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio">with a wall; bot whare off &thorn;e wall es made, can na man tell. It es all mosse begrowen and couerd so with
mossse and with bruschez &thorn;at men may see na stane, ne no&yogh;t elles wharoff a wall schuld be made. &THORN;e walle of
Paradys strechez fra &thorn;e south toward &thorn;e north; and &thorn;er es nane entree open in to it, because of fire euermare
brynnand, &thorn;e whilk es called &thorn;e flawmand swerde &thorn;at Godd ordaynd &thorn;are before &thorn;e entree, for na man
schuld entre.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.150.13" CORRESP="Cot.202.28">In &thorn;e middes of Paradys es a well oute of &thorn;e whilke &thorn;er commez foure flodez, &thorn;at rynnez thurgh diuerse
landez. &THORN;ir flodez sinkez doune in to &thorn;e erthe within Paradyse and rynnez so vnder &thorn;e erthe many a myle, and
afterwardes comme &thorn;ai vp agayne oute of &thorn;e erthe in ferre cuntreez. &THORN;e first of &thorn;ir flodez es called Physon or
Ganges, springez
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">springez &hellip; Orcobares, with more of this description of the four rivers, not in French text or <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> vp in Inde vnder &thorn;e hilles of Orcobares, and rynnez esteward thurgh Inde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Ynde or Emlak, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> in to &thorn;e grete see
Occeane. In &thorn;at riuer er many precious stanes and grete plentee of &thorn;e tree &thorn;at es called <FOREIGN LANG="lat">lignum aloes</FOREIGN>, and
mykill grauell of gold. &THORN;is riuer es called Phison by cause many waters gaders sammen and fallez intill it, for
Phison es als mykill at say as Gadering.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Assemblee, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> It es also called Ganges for a kyng &thorn;at was in Inde, &thorn;e whilke men
called Gangaras; and for it rynnez thurgh his land it was called Ganges. &THORN;is riuer es in sum place clere, in sum
place trubly, in sum place hate, in sum place calde. &THORN;e secund riuer es called Nilus or Gyon; and it risez vp
<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio">oute of &thorn;e erthe a lytill fra &thorn;e mount Atlant. And no&yogh;t ferr &thorn;eine it sinkez doune agayne in to &thorn;e erthe and
rynnez so vnder &thorn;e erthe till it comme at &thorn;e Reed See bank, and &thorn;are it risez vp agayne oute of &thorn;e erthe and
rynnes all aboute Ethiopy, and so thurgh Egipt ay till it com at Grete Alexandre, and &thorn;are it rynnez in to
see Mediterrany. &THORN;is riuer es euermare trublee and &thorn;erfore es it called Gyon; for Gyon es als mykill at say
as Trublee. &THORN;e thridd riuer es called Tigris, &thorn;at es to say Fast Rynnand; for it es ane of &thorn;e swythest rynnand

<PB N="151">
waters of &thorn;e werld. And it es called Tigris after a beste &thorn;at has &thorn;e same name, and it es &thorn;e swiftest beste of
fote of &thorn;e werld. &THORN;is riuer begynnez in Ermony &thorn;e grete vnder &thorn;e mounte of Parchoatra and rinnez so thurgh
Ermony and Asy toward &thorn;e south, and so turnez in to &thorn;e see Mediterrany. &THORN;e ferthe riuer es called Eufrates,
&thorn;at es als mykill at say as Wele Berand; for &thorn;are growez many gude thingez apon &thorn;at riuer. &THORN;at riuer rynnez
thurgh Medy, Ermony and Perse. And men saise &thorn;are &thorn;at all &thorn;e fresch waters of &thorn;e werld takez &thorn;aire begynnyng
of &thorn;e forsaid well &thorn;at springez vp in Paradys.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.151.7" CORRESP="Cot.203.20">And &yogh;e schall wele vnderstand &thorn;at na man liffand may ga to Paradys. For by land may na man ga &thorn;ider by
cause of wilde bestez &thorn;at er in &thorn;e wilderness and for hillez and roches, whilk na man may passe, and also for
mirk placez, of whilk &thorn;er er many &thorn;are. By water also may na man passe &thorn;ider, for
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">for the water renneth so rudely and so scharpely, because &thorn;at it cometh doun so outrageously from the high places abouen, &thorn;at it renneth in so grete wawes &thorn;at no schipp may not rowe ne seyle a&yogh;enes it. And the water roreth so, and maketh so huge noyse and so gret tempest, &thorn;at no man may here o&thorn;er in the schippe, &thorn;ough he cryede with all the craft &thorn;at he cowde in the hieste voys &thorn;at he myghte, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &thorn;as riuers commez with so
grete a course and so grete a birre and wawes &thorn;at na schippe may ga ne saile agayne &thorn;am. &THORN;are es also so grete
<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio">noyse of waters &thorn;at a man may no&yogh;t here ano&thorn;er, crie he neuer so hie. Many grete lordes has usayd diuerse
tymes to passe by &thorn;ase riuers to Paradys, bot &thorn;ai myght no&yogh;t spede of &thorn;aire iournee; for sum of &thorn;am died for
weryness of rowyng and ower trauaillyng, sum wex blind and sum deeff for &thorn;e noise of &thorn;e waters, and sum ware
drouned by violence of &thorn;e wawes of &thorn;e waters. And so &thorn;er may na man, as I said before, wynne &thorn;ider, bot
thurgh speciall grace of Godd. And &thorn;erfore of &thorn;at place can I tell &yogh;owe na mare; bot I will turne agayne and
tell &yogh;ow of thingez &thorn;at I hafe sene in iles and landes of &thorn;e lordschepe of Prestre Iohn, &thorn;e whilk as vntill vs er
vnder &thorn;e erthe.</SEG></P></DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="chapter" ID="Eg.Ch.34" N="34" CORRESP="Cot.Ch.35">
<PB N="152">
<HEAD TYPE="numeral-editorial">CHAPTER XXXIV</HEAD>

<HEAD TYPE="CotMS">[Of the customs of kynges and othere that dwellen in the yles costynge to Prestre Johnes lond; and of the worschipe that the sone doth to the fader, whan he is dede.]</HEAD>

<P><SEG ID="Eg.152.4" CORRESP="Cot.204.8">OTHER iles &thorn;are er, wha so wald pursue &thorn;am, by &thorn;e whilk men myght ga all aboute &thorn;e erthe, wha so had
grace of Godd to hald &thorn;e ri&yogh;t way, and com ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e same cuntreez &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware off and come fra, and
so ga all aboute &thorn;e erthe, as I hafe sayd before, by processe of tyme. Bot for it schuld be a lang tyme are
&thorn;at vaiage ware made, and also so many perils of tymez fallez to men &thorn;at passez thurgh straunge cuntreez bathe by
water and by land, and semely ware to fall to men &thorn;at wald make &thorn;at vayage, &thorn;erfore few men assays &thorn;at passage;
and neuer&thorn;eles &yogh;it myght it be done wele ynogh thurgh Goddes grace. Bot men lefes &thorn;at passage and turnez
agayne fra &thorn;ir forsaid iles by o&thorn;er iles costayand &thorn;e land of Prestre Iohn and iles &thorn;at er of his lordschepe. And
<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio">in commyng so, &thorn;ai comme till ane ile &thorn;at men callez Casson; and &thorn;at ile es nere lx. day iournez lang and mare
&thorn;an l. on brede. And it es &thorn;e best ile in &thorn;ase parties, safe Cathay; and, if marchandes come &thorn;ider als comounly
as &thorn;ai do to Cathay, it schuld be better &thorn;an Cathay. For citeez and gude tounes er &thorn;are so thikk &thorn;at, when a
man gase oute of a citee, he seez alssone ano&thorn;er citee or a gude toune before him on what syde so he turne him.
&THORN;is ile es full and plentifous of all maner of spicery and of all maner of o&thorn;er gudez, and namely &thorn;at partenez to
mannez lyflade; and &thorn;are er many grete woddez full of chestaynes.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> chestnuts; chesteynes, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e king of &thorn;is ile es full riche and myghty,
and he haldez his land of &thorn;e Grete Caan of Cathay; for &thorn;at es ane of &thorn;e xii. prouineez &thorn;at &thorn;e Grete Caan has
vnder him withouten his awen land and o&thorn;er smale iles, as I talde &yogh;ow before. Fra &thorn;is ile men commez til
ano&thorn;er ile &thorn;at men callez Ryboth or Gyboth; and &thorn;at es also vnder &thorn;e Grete Caan. &THORN;is es a gude land and a
plentifous of corne, of wyne, and of many o&thorn;er thingez. Men of &thorn;is land hase na housez to dwell in, bot &thorn;ai
dwell all in tentez made of blakk filtre.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2"><HI REND="i">sc.</HI> felt; blak ferne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> &THORN;e principall citee of &thorn;at land es walled aboute with blakk stanes and
whyte; and all &thorn;e stretez er paued with swilk maner of stanes. And in &thorn;at citee es na man so hardy to schedd
blude, now&thorn;er of man ne of beste, for lufe of a mawmet &thorn;at es wirschipped &thorn;are. In &thorn;is citee dwellez &thorn;e pape

<PB N="153">
<MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio">of &thorn;aire lawe, wham &thorn;ai call Lobassi. And he giffez all &thorn;e digniteez and beneficez &thorn;at fallez to &thorn;aire mawmetes;
and all &thorn;e prestez and ministres of ydoles er obedient to him as oure prestez er till oure pape.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.153.3" CORRESP="Cot.205.22">In &thorn;is ile &thorn;ai hafe a custom thurgh oute all &thorn;e land &thorn;at, when any mannez fader es deed and his son will do
him wirschepe, he sendez after all his kynredyn and his gude frendez, prestez of &thorn;aire lawe, minstralles and
many o&thorn;er; and &thorn;ai bere &thorn;e body to a hill with grete sollempnytee and grete myrth. And, when it es &thorn;are, &thorn;e
grettest prelate smytet off &thorn;e deed mannez heued and lays it apon a grete plater of siluer, or of gold if he be a
riche man, and giffez it to his son. And &thorn;an all his frendez singez and saise many orisouns, and &thorn;an &thorn;e prestez
and religious men of &thorn;aire lawe hewez &thorn;e body all in smale pecez and saise many orisouns. And fewles of &thorn;e
cuntree, &thorn;at knawez &thorn;e custom commez &thorn;ider and houers abouue &thorn;am, as vowltures, egles, rauyns, and o&thorn;er
fewlez of rauyne; and &thorn;e prestez castez &thorn;is flesch to &thorn;am, and &thorn;ai bere it a lytill &thorn;eine and etez it. And &thorn;an,
ri&yogh;t as prestez in oure cuntree syngez for saulez <TITLE LANG="lat">Subuenite, sancti Dei</TITLE>, so &thorn;ase prestez &thorn;are singez with a hie
voice on &thorn;aire langage on &thorn;is wyse "Takez tent now and seez how gude a man &thorn;is was, wham &thorn;e aungelles of
Godd commez to fecche and bere in to Paradys." And &thorn;an thinkes &thorn;e sonne and and his frendez &thorn;at his fader es
gretely wirschipped, when fewles hase &thorn;us eten him. And ay &thorn;e ma fewles &thorn;ar commez, &thorn;e mare ioy hase all
his frendez, and &thorn;e mare think &thorn;am &thorn;e deed man es wirschipt. And &thorn;an wendez &thorn;e sonne hame and takez with
<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio">him all his frendez aad makez &thorn;am a grete feste; and ilke ane of &thorn;am tellez till o&thorn;er in &thorn;aire myrth how &thorn;are
come x. fewles, &thorn;are xvi., &thorn;are xx., ri&yogh;t as it ware to &thorn;am grete cause of myrth. And &thorn;e sonne gers sethe his
fader heued, and &thorn;e flesch &thorn;eroff he partez amang his speciale frendez, ilke man a lytill, for a dayntee.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">in stede of entremesse, or a sukkarke, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> And of
&thorn;e scalpe
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">brayn panne, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e heued he gers make him a coppe, and &thorn;eroff he drinkez all his lyf tyme in remembraunce
of his fader.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.153.21" CORRESP="Cot.206.28">Fra &thorn;is land for to comme hiderward thurgh &thorn;e land of &thorn;i Grete Caan x. day iournez es ane o&thorn;er gude ile,
whare off &thorn;are es a riche king and a myghty. And in &thorn;at ile &thorn;are es a lord amanges o&thorn;er &thorn;at es wounder riche;
and &yogh;it he es now&thorn;er prince, ne duke, ne erle. Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;are haldez many a man &thorn;aire landes of him, and he
es a lorde of grete ricchess. For he has ilke a &yogh;ere broght till him ccc<HI REND="sup">m</HI> hors lade of corne and als many of ryess.
And &thorn;is lorde ledez a meruailous lif. For he has fyfty damyselles &thorn;at seruez him ilk a day at his mete and his

<PB N="154">
bedd, and dose what he will. And, when he sittez at &thorn;e mete, &thorn;ai bring him mete and euermare fyfe meessez
togyder: and in &thorn;e bringyng &thorn;ai sing a faire sang. And &thorn;ai schere his mete before him and puttez it in his
mouth, as he ware a childe; for he scherez nane ne touchez nane with his handez, bot haldez &thorn;am before him on
&thorn;e table. For he has so lang nayles on his fyngers &thorn;at he may hald na thing with &thorn;am. And &thorn;at es a grete
noblay in &thorn;at cuntree and a grete wirschepe to hafe so lang nayles. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai late &thorn;aire nayles growe
<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio">als lang as &thorn;ai may and cuttez &thorn;am no&yogh;t. And sum latez &thorn;am growe so lang to &thorn;ai growe all aboute &thorn;aire hend;
and &thorn;at think &thorn;aim es a grete noblay and a grete gentry. And &thorn;e gentry of wymmen &thorn;are es to hafe smale fete;
and &thorn;erfore alssone as &thorn;ai er borne, &thorn;ai bynd &thorn;aire fete so straite &thorn;at &thorn;ai may no&yogh;t waxe so grete as &thorn;ai schuld.
&THORN;ir forsaid damyselles, als lang as &thorn;aire lorde es sittand at &thorn;e mete, er nerehand all way singand; and, when he
has eten ynogh of &thorn;e first course, &thorn;ai bring before him o&thorn;er fyfe meessez, syngand as &thorn;ai didd before. And &thorn;us
&thorn;ai do ay, till &thorn;e end of &thorn;e mete. And on &thorn;is wise ledez &thorn;is lorde his lyfe by alde custom of his auncestres, &thorn;e
whilk custum on &thorn;e same wyse his successoures will vse. And &thorn;us &thorn;ai make &thorn;aire godd of &thorn;aire wambe, so &thorn;at
na worthyness ne doghtyness &thorn;ai vse, bot all anely liffez in lust and lyking of &thorn;e flesch, as a swyne fedd in stye.
&THORN;is riche man also hase a full faire palays and riche, whare he dwellez, of whilke &thorn;e walle es twa myle vmgang.
And &thorn;erin er many faire gardynes; and all &thorn;e pament of hallez and chaumbres er of gold and siluer. And in
myddes of ane of &thorn;e gardynez es a lytill hill, whare apon es a lytil palace made with toures and pynnacles
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">is a lytill mountayne, where &thorn;ere is a lityll medewe, and in &thorn;at medewe is a lityll toothill, with toures and pynacles, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE> all of
gold; and &thorn;are in will he sitt oft for to disporte him and take &thorn;e aer, for it es made for no&yogh;t elles.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.154.18" CORRESP="Cot.208.5">Fra &thorn;is land men commez thurgh &thorn;e land of &thorn;e Grete Caan, of &thorn;e whilk I talde &yogh;ow before and &thorn;erfore it
<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio">nedez no&yogh;t to reherce it here agayne. And &yogh;e schall vnderstand &thorn;at in all &thorn;ir landes, rewmes and naciouns,
outaken &thorn;ase &thorn;at er inhabited with vnresonable men, es na folk &thorn;at ne &thorn;ai hald sum articlez of oure beleue. If
all &thorn;ai be of diuerse lawes and diuerse trowyngs, &thorn;ai hafe sum gude poyntes of oure trowth. And generally &thorn;ai
trowe in Godd &thorn;at made &thorn;e werld, and him call &thorn;ai Godd of Kynde
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">God of Nature, <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR>.</NOTE>; and &thorn;us es &thorn;e prophecy verified &thorn;at saise,
<Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Et metuent eum omnes fines terre</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="3">Ps. lxvi. 8.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "And all &thorn;e endes of &thorn;e erthe schall drede him." And in
ano&thorn;er place <Q TYPE="citation" LANG="lat">Omnes gentes seruient ei</Q>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="4">Ps. lxxi. 11.</NOTE> &thorn;at es to say, "All folk schall serue him." Bot &thorn;ai can no&yogh;t properly
speke of Godd, and namely of &thorn;e Trinytee, by cause &thorn;ai hafe na teching. &THORN;ai can no&yogh;t of &thorn;e Sonne, ne of &thorn;e

<PB N="155">
Haly Gaste; bot &thorn;ai can speke wele of &thorn;e <TITLE>Bible</TITLE> and specially of &thorn;e buke of Genesis and o&thorn;er bukes of Moises,
and sum tyme of &thorn;e xii. Prophetez sayinges. And &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;ase creatures &thorn;at &thorn;ai wirschippe er na goddes,
bot &thorn;ai wirschippe &thorn;am for &thorn;e grete vertuz &thorn;at er in &thorn;am, whilk &thorn;ai say may no&yogh;t be withouten speciall grace of
Godd. And of ydoles and simulacres &thorn;ai say &thorn;at &thorn;er es na folk &thorn;at &thorn;ai ne hafe simulacres; and &thorn;at say &thorn;ai
principally for &thorn;ai see Cristen men hafe crucifixez and ymages of oure Lady and of o&thorn;er sayntes and do wirschepe
to &thorn;am. Bot &thorn;ai wate no&yogh;t &thorn;at we wirschepe no&yogh;t &thorn;ase ymagez of stane or of tree for &thorn;am self, bot in remembraunce
of &thorn;e sayntz for whaim &thorn;ai er made; for, ri&yogh;t as letterure and bukez techez clerkes, so ymagez and payntures
<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio">techez lawd men to wirschepe &thorn;e sayntes for whaim &thorn;ai er made. &THORN;ai say also &thorn;at aungelles spekez to &thorn;am in
&thorn;aire mawmetes and dose miracles. And &thorn;ai say sothe, for &thorn;ai hafe ane aungell within &thorn;am; bot &thorn;ar er twa
maner of aungelles, &thorn;at es at say ane gude, ano&thorn;er ill, as men of Grece saise, Chaco and Calo. Chaco es &thorn;e ill
aungell and Calo es &thorn;e gude. Bot &thorn;at es na gude aungell &thorn;at es in &thorn;e mawmetz, bot ane ill, &thorn;at es to say a fende
&thorn;at answeres &thorn;am and tellez &thorn;am many thinges, for to dessayfe &thorn;am with and for to mayntene &thorn;am in &thorn;aire
mawmetry and &thorn;aire errour.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.155.14" CORRESP="Cot.209.9">&THORN;are
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">These concluding paragraphs are more literally rendered in <ABBR EXPAN="British Library MS Cotton Titus C. xvi">C</ABBR> than here. See [commentary].</NOTE> er many o&thorn;er cuntrcez and o&thorn;er meruailes whilk I hafe no&yogh;t sene, and &thorn;erfore I can no&yogh;t speke
properly of &thorn;am; and also in cuntreez whare I hafe bene er many meruailes of whilk I speke no&yogh;t, for it ware
owere lang to tell. And also I will tell na mare of meruailes &thorn;at er &thorn;are, so &thorn;at o&thorn;er men &thorn;at wendez &thorn;ider may
fynd many new thingez to speke off, whilk I hafe no&yogh;t spoken off. For many men hase grete lykyng and desyre
for to here new thinges; and &thorn;erfore will I now ceesse of tellyng of diuerse thingez &thorn;at I sawe in &thorn;ase cuntreez,
so &thorn;at &thorn;ase &thorn;at couetez to visit &thorn;ase cuntrez may fynd new thinges ynewe to tell off for solace and recreacioun of
&thorn;aim &thorn;at lykez to here &thorn;am.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.155.21" CORRESP="Cot.210.19">And I, IOHN MAWNDEUILL, knyght, &thorn;at went oute of my cuntree and passed &thorn;e see &thorn;e &yogh;ere of oure Lord
Ihesu Criste m<HI REND="sup">l</HI>cccxxxii, and hase passed thurgh many landes, cuntreez and iles, and hase bene at many
<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio">wirschipfull iourneez and dedez of armez with worthy men, if all I be vnwor&thorn;i, and now am commen to rest, as
man discomfitt for age and trauaile and febilness of body &thorn;at constraynez me &thorn;arto, and for o&thorn;er certayne causez,
I hafe compiled &thorn;is buke and writen it, as it coome to my mynde, in &thorn;e &yogh;ere of oure Lord Ihesu Criste m<HI REND="sup">l</HI>ccclxvi,
&thorn;at es for to say in &thorn;e foure and thrittyde &yogh;ere efter &thorn;at I departed oute of &thorn;is land and tuke my way &thorn;iderward.</SEG></P>

<PB N="156">
<P><SEG ID="Eg.156.1" CORRESP="Cot.209.31">And for als mykill as many men trowez no&yogh;t bot &thorn;at at &thorn;ai see with &thorn;aire eghen, or &thorn;at &thorn;ai may consayue
with &thorn;aire awen kyndely wittes, &thorn;erfore I made my way in my commyng hamward vnto Rome to schew my
buke till oure haly fader &thorn;e Pape.
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="1">Pape, erased and rewritten, MS.; and so below, l. 8.</NOTE> And I tald him &thorn;e meruailes whilk I had sene in diuerse cuntreez, so &thorn;at he
with his wyse counsaile wald examyne it with diuerse folke &thorn;at er in Rome, for &thorn;are er euermare dwelland men
of all naciouns of&thorn;i werld. And a lytill <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">after</SUPPLIED>,
<NOTE RESP="GW" N="2">This word and portions of a few others at the edge of the leaf have been cut away.</NOTE> when he and his wyse counsaile had examynde it all thurgh, he
said to me for certayne &thorn;at all was soth &thorn;at was &thorn;erin. For <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">he</SUPPLIED> said &thorn;at he had a buke of Latyn &thorn;at con<SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">teyned</SUPPLIED>
all &thorn;at and mykill mare, after whilk buke <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">the <TITLE LANG="lat">Mappa</TITLE></SUPPLIED> <TITLE LANG="lat">Mundi</TITLE> es made; and &thorn;at buke he schewed m<SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">e. And</SUPPLIED>
&thorn;erfore oure haly fader &thorn;e Pape hase ratified <SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">and</SUPPLIED> confermed my buke in all poyntes.</SEG></P>
<P><SEG ID="Eg.156.9" CORRESP="Cot.210.34">Qwh<SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">erfore</SUPPLIED> I pray til all &thorn;ase &thorn;at redez &thorn;is Buke or heres it redd, &thorn;at &thorn;ai will pray for me, and I schall
<MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio">p<SUPPLIED REASON="ms damage" RESP="GW">ray</SUPPLIED> for &thorn;aim. And all &thorn;ase &thorn;at saise for me deuotely a <TITLE LANG="lat">Pater Noster</TITLE> and ane <TITLE LANG="lat">Aue</TITLE>, &thorn;at Godd forgife me my
synnez, he graunt &thorn;am parte of all my pilgrimage and all o&thorn;er gude dedis &thorn;at I hafe done or may do in tyme
commyng vnto my lyfez end. And I, in &thorn;at in me es, makez &thorn;am parceneres of &thorn;am, prayand to Godd, of wham
all grace commez, &thorn;at he fulfill with his grace all &thorn;ase &thorn;at &thorn;is buke redez or heres, and saue &thorn;am and kepe &thorn;am
in body and saule, and after &thorn;is lyf bring &thorn;am to &thorn;e cuntree whare ioy es and endles rest and peesse with outen
end. Amen.</SEG></P>
<TRAILER>HERE ENDEZ &THORN;E BUKE OF JOHN MAUNDEUILE.</TRAILER></DIV1></BODY></TEXT></TEI.2>
